<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TV COMMERCIAL: EASING A WOMAN'S FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H., Mass.)  (See also BAUER-COMMERCIAL) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a look at a 60-second TV commercial that former Sen.
Bill Bradley, who is running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, began showing in Iowa, New Hampshire and the Boston
area this week.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: The Kaplan Thaler Group and MacWilliams, Cosgrove,
Smith, Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The commercial opens with white letters on a
black background that say, ``Someone who listens.'' It then shows,
in succession, head shots of Maureen Drumm, a Philadelphia mother
of three, her husband, Christopher, and Bradley. Mrs. Drumm is
seated on a sofa, holding her infant daughter, flanked by her
husband and their eldest daughter. A relaxed Bradley sits
cross-legged in a chair, with a piano and fireplace behind him. The
spot closes with the words, ``It can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: Maureen Drumm: I really believe that thanks to Sen.
Bradley my third daughter is alive today, because he took the time
to care.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley: She was actually afraid that the child would die
because she would be pushed out of the hospital in 24 hours or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Drumm: The insurance companies had instituted a
policy of 24 hours postpartum care.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Drumm: I wanted to ensure that I was guaranteed that I
would be in the hospital long enough that she wouldn't be
experiencing the problems that my first child experienced. So I
said to my husband, ``I'm going to call Sen. Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley: I knew the people were on my side, so even if the
insurance companies and HMOs were against me, that we could win.
Forty-eight hours should be a minimum. Introduced a bill. Passed a
law. Made 48 hours a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Drumm: That's the type of man I want in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Bradley was the main sponsor of a law enacted in 1996
requiring health insurance companies to cover at least 48 hours of
hospital care for new mothers. However, Vice President Al Gore's
campaign has criticized Ms. Drumm's contention that her third
daughter is alive today because of Bradley _ a claim the Bradley
campaign also featured in a commercial released last week _ as
hyperbolic. Though this new commercial expands on Ms. Drumm's
complicated story, it still does not entirely explain the
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Drumm, 34, said that ``I would not have had
the courage to go through another pregnancy'' without the 48-hour
law because her first two daughters both developed serious
complications more than 24 hours after delivery. Her insurance
company covered an extended hospital stay for her first child, but
it told her in 1995 that it would limit coverage to 24 hours for
her second child. So she called Bradley's Senate office, and he
brought her to testify before a Senate committee. Soon after, her
insurer agreed to cover 48 hours of hospital care for her second
daughter. Then in 1996, the 48-hour bill passed, giving her the
confidence, she said, to become pregnant for a third time, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The commercial tries to show Bradley _ whom the Gore
camp has criticized as being ineffective in the Senate _ as a
no-nonsense legislator who gets things done. And in saying that he
had to fight insurance companies and HMOs to get the bill passed,
Bradley suggests that he will have the courage to take on
entrenched special interests in Washington, a central theme of his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the real aim of the commercial seems to be to woo female
voters, who support Gore in significantly higher numbers, polls
show. That may be the reason Bradley has focused on the 48-hour
bill in his first advertisements rather than the major proposal of
his campaign: a contentious plan to extend health insurance to
almost all Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
