<HEADLINE>
SHAQ KEEPS GOING, AND GOING, AND GOING ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first month of the season is nearly over, and
the gaudy stats Shaquille O'Neal is posting show no signs of
dipping into mortal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Not the points, not the rebounds, and certainly not the minutes
played.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has pushed O'Neal to the limits _ he averaged
almost 44 minutes per game in the five games prior to Friday's _
and O'Neal has responded. During that five-game span, he was more
dominant than ever _ 37.4 points, 16.0 rebounds, 4.0 assists and
4.8 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is undaunted by the marathon, and Jackson believes he's
playing better in part because he doesn't take long breaks on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting him sit too long, because I think he does cool
off and loses his feel for the game,'' Jackson said. ``We just
said, let's see if we can't refocus and somehow get your energy
back there. That's been the difference, because he's always been a
good starter. He really started games good and somehow ran out of
energy in the course of games. Right now, he's sustaining the
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the reason for that, oddly, might be those much-discussed
extra pounds O'Neal added this offseason. O'Neal reported at 345
pounds, which he chalked up to a muscle-building program, and that
strength has helped him endure the nightly beatings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so. I am stronger,'' he said, then quipped, ``and I've
been on my Krispy Kreme diet all summer. I'm feeling pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said the only toll has been on his legs, which have
required a little extra massaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel it on game day, but on certain days it's kind of
hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his recent streak of dominance, O'Neal said it's not
necessarily the best string he's played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did better in elementary school,'' he said ``I was averaging
50 in elementary. And they were going, `He's not 10. I want to see
his birth certificate.' For real. That's a true story.''
</P>
<P>
   As for O'Neal's minutes, Jackson said he'll look to play him 40
a night, unless the Los Angeles Lakers have a big fourth-quarter
lead, which has been a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make him lose weight,'' Jackson joked.
</P>
<P>
   Milestone: A.C. Green played in his 1,042nd consecutive game to
break the professional basketball record, earning a standing
ovation from the Staples Center crowd. Green tied former
record-holder Ron Boone on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, now a Utah Jazz broadcaster, put together his streak over
13 seasons of ABA and NBA play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
