<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TOPS KENTUCKY TO WIN PRESEASON NIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the tourists crowding midtown Manhattan could not
get good seats to see ``Cats'' on Broadway Friday night, they had
another option for feline-titled entertainment in the same general
area.
</P>
<P>
   Two college teams nicknamed Wildcats _ Kentucky and Arizona _
played for the championship of the Preseason National Invitation
Tournament in Madison Square Garden. Plenty of seats were available
as only 12,560 customers attended.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, a 63-51 winner, improved its record to 4-0. Kentucky
fell to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is ranked No. 8 in the nation and Kentucky is No. 11.
Kentucky led by as many as seven points in the first half, but
Arizona held a four-point advantage at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona gradually built its lead to a comfortable level during
the second half, using the speed and shooting of Jason Gardner and
Gilbert Arenas, the guards.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona lead peaked at 16 points with about three minutes
remaining as coach Lute Olson's team began to dominate in almost
every aspect of play.
</P>
<P>
   Arenas led Arizona in scoring with 20 points. Gardner had 10.
Richard Jefferson, a forward, had 15 points and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   For Kentucky, Tayshaun Prince had 18 points and Desmond Allison
12.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona outrebounded Kentucky, 43-37. Arenas had five steals and
Gardner four as Arizona dominated in this category by 15-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason has told me all along he can play like a veteran,''
Olson said. ``Gilbert is only 17 and he doesn't realize there's any
pressure. We're going to try to keep him from finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson reflected on the array of strength in the Arizona
attack. ``We have so many different weapons that can beat you on a
given day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a pretty game by both teams,'' coach Tubby Smith of
Kentucky said. ``But it was a slugfest for a while from a defensive
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that his team shot only 35.6 percent from the field,
Smith found fault with Jamaal Magloire, the senior center, who
scored only four points and was 1 for 5 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamaal has jump shots and he was missing them for the second
night in a row,'' Smith said. ``We didn't capitalize on easy
attempts.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Kentucky was intimidated by the inside game of Arizona
center Loren Woods, who had eight points and seven rebounds but no
blocked shots because not that many were taken in his presence.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona reached this year's final by beating Notre Dame on
Wednesday night before Kentucky eliminated Maryland. In Friday
night's consolation game, Maryland improved its record to 4-1 with
a 72-67 victory over Notre Dame (3-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's championship game was close and intense from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Arizona had a 29-25 lead despite trailing twice by
seven points midway through the first half.
</P>
<P>
   At intermission, the only player scoring in double figures was
Arizona's Arenas, who had 13 points on 4-of-6 field-goal shooting,
including 1 for 2 from 3-point range. He also had four steals.
</P>
<P>
   Prince led Kentucky scorers with nine points.
</P>
<P>
   In the consolation game, Maryland took its first lead just nine
seconds into the game on a dunk off a rebound by Lonny Baxter, a
sophomore forward who led his team with 17 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Notre Dame cut Maryland's 18-point second-half lead to one
point with two minutes left and kept things interesting until the
final horn.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's Juan Dixon secured the victory by making two free
throws with 19.3 seconds left. The sophomore Troy Murphy,
impressive again at power forward, led Notre Dame with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Williams, the head coach of Maryland, said the Notre Dame
comeback was the result of his team's not working plays low to the
basket and back out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had to work hard for that win,'' Williams said.
``We're a young team and we're learning how to play. A lot of
people didn't think we could win this year, losing three guys to
the pros and Terrell Stokes, our starting point guard for three
years. We have to prove to ourselves and to our fans that we can
win. This certainly was big tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
