<HEADLINE>
THE RANGERS' LONG SEASON IS FEELING LONGER AND LONGER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ If you threw out the second period Friday night,
the New York Rangers played a competitive game. But that's like
saying discount the first two months of the season and the Rangers
have the makings of a good team.
</P>
<P>
   Without their captain, Brian Leetch, who will be out for six to
eight weeks with a broken right arm, the Rangers were buried, 6-2,
by the Florida Panthers. The Panthers scored four consecutive
second-period goals, and five unanswered goals in all, to break a
1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Rangers feel they have an excuse in the absence of
Leetch, their best player, but there is no excuse for the way the
Rangers have begun the season. And no one in the organization _
from Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, to
Neil Smith, the team president and general manager, to coach John
Muckler to the team's high-priced core of veteran players _ is
exempt from blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody stepped up tonight,'' Muckler said. ``Nobody stepped up
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers supposedly play better away from home, but even with
a 6-3 victory in Tampa on Wednesday (their best performance of the
season), the Rangers ended their four-game road trip 1-3-0 with a
regulation tie. Over their last 15 games, the Rangers are 3-10-2
with that regulation tie. Through 23 games they are 7-13-3.
</P>
<P>
   Every shot they took Friday night _ 41, a season high _ seemed
aimed directly at Florida goalie Trevor Kidd's body. Every one
except the wrist shot that rookie defenseman Kim Johnsson snapped
from the top of the left circle off Kidd's catching glove 19
minutes 37 seconds into the first period that gave the Rangers a
1-1 tie heading into the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bottom dropped out before Alexandre Daigle scored with
3:15 left in the game to make it 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played without Leetch, Todd Harvey (knee), Manny
Malhotra (ankle), Tim Taylor (rib cartilage) and Stephane Quintal
(concussion). So, Muckler was forced to dress three inexperienced
defensemen, Johnsson, Jason Doig and Terry Virtue. Valery Kamensky
(forearm) was playing for the first time since Oct. 24 and just the
seventh time this season _ and the rust showed before Muckler took
him off Petr Nedved's top line and left him on the bench to start
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   That still does not explain what happened to the Rangers during
their second-period collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go brain-dead for a certain period of time,'' John MacLean
said. ``And we pay for it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, who were humiliated at home, 6-1, by the
Philadelphia Flyers on Wednesday, drove Mike Richter from the net
at 2:55 of the second by scoring a pair of goals _ one by Radek
Dvorak, the other by Ray Whitney _ 95 seconds apart early in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure, who had assisted on Florida's first goal (by
Jaroslav Spacek at 11:38 of the first period), set up Dvorak's
tie-breaking goal with a cross-ice pass to Viktor Kozlov. Richter
was able to make the save, but Dvorak batted the rebound straight
out of the air off his backhand past Richter for a 2-1 lead.
Whitney's goal came off a scramble in front with Richter lying on
his back in the crease. And it was 3-1 Florida, and Kirk McLean was
on his way in to replace Richter.
</P>
<P>
   A malfunction caused the scoreboard to read 5-1. That would be
the case soon enough. Kozlov scored on the power play at 11:49,
shortly after Theo Fleury had taken a penalty four seconds after
one to Daigle had expired. Scott Mellanby scored 27 seconds after
Kozlov, and it was truly 5-1. Maybe the scoreboard operator was
prescient. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bure fooled McLean with a wrister from the slot at 5:02 of the
third to give the Panthers a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we'd see Pavel Bure take off, we tried to play the
same way: fancy hockey,'' Mathieu Schneider said. ``There aren't
too many Pavel Bures in the league. We certainly don't have one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
