<HEADLINE>
BAUER TV COMMERCIAL: REACHING IN TWO DIRECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (See also BRADLEY-COMMERCIAL) 
(rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 30-second commercial, ``The American Project,'' is one of
two that the Republican presidential campaign of Gary L. Bauer will
begin showing Saturday in Iowa, which has a caucus in late January.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Edmonds Associates, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The commercial begins with an image of the statue
of Abraham Lincoln inside the Lincoln Memorial in Washington and
then replaces that with a picture of the outside of the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the gates in front of a churchyard, which slowly open,
and then to a copy of the Emancipation Proclamation, with which
President Lincoln freed the slaves in the rebellious southern
states. Next come three smiling children, one of them black, then a
woman pushing a stroller in front of the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The camera pulls back to show that Bauer, who has been talking
all along, is there outside the memorial, too. Now Bauer speaks
directly to the camera. As he continues talking, he leans down
beside the baby in the stroller.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial ends with a Bauer for president logo, including
the slogan ``Advancing America's Values.''
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: ``Throughout history, our greatest presidents understood
that America is about expanding the circle of human rights and
dignity, from freedom of religion to the emancipation of slaves,
from civil rights to equal opportunities for women. I'm Gary Bauer.
For 20 years I've fought to extend to unborn children the most
basic of human rights. I won't stop until every one of God's
children is welcomed into the world and protected by law.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Bauer deftly reaches in two directions with this
advertisement. He appeals to the religious conservatives with whom
he is most popular by plainly stating his ardent, unyielding stand
against abortion. At the same time, he frames his argument for that
position in terms that are not religious, and thus seemingly tries
to avoid having other Republican voters pigeonhole him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his verbal and visual references to blacks and women
seem to move him toward a different end of the political spectrum _
a place closer to the center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
