 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ The grim, unyielding men from the
remote poles of Ulster politics were still getting adjusted to
being seated side by side around a dining room table when their
host hit them with another novelty. George Mitchell told a joke at
the expense of his listeners, men with absolutely no history of
enjoying being made fun of. But they laughed. That moment may have
been the opening of the wall that came down in the last few weeks
as the seemingly dead Northern Ireland peace plan has revived. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-POLITICS (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) _ Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad is all but certain to win a parliamentary election
next week, but already, to many people here, he seems like a relic
of the past. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-Y2K (New York) _ Last month, after searching and testing
nearly every computer and microchip in New York City's vast
inventory of technology, city officials took one of the final steps
in a four-year, $300 million effort to prevent any turmoil stemming
from the Year 2000 computer problem. They canvassed every city
agency to identify each jackhammer, bullhorn, tent, chain saw and
portable toilet. They made a list of every city employee who is a
qualified nurse, elevator mechanic, electrician, cook _ even scuba
diver _ so appropriate gear and specialists can quickly be
dispatched should trouble erupt after clocks and computers tick
from 1999 to 2000. The challenge is that despite spending more than
any other city in the world to fight the computer glitch, the
city's technology and emergency management experts say things may
yet go wrong _ and no one can predict exactly which things. By
Andrew C. Revkin and Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY-JOHNSON (Dallas) _ Thirty-six years ago this week, John
F. Kennedy was killed by a sniper's bullet in Dallas, and Lyndon B.
Johnson succeeded at once to the presidency. Time has treated them
differently. Kennedy has been transformed over the years into one
of the great, romantic American heroes, his shortcomings obscured
by tragedy of an early, violent death. For all his achievements,
Johnson is still remembered mainly as the president who presided
over the wretched war in Vietnam, the most loathed in American
history. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TAX-PROTEST (Rye, N.H.) _ A half dozen towns, upset over
higher rates on property taxes they have to pay because of
inequitable school funding, are telling the state they will not pay
the extra money until their challenge to the new taxes is settled.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 28 and map is being sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients)
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-CARE (Undated) _ Results of a survey on expenses in
caring for aging relatives. By Sarah Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STYLE (Stratham, N.H.) _ When George W. Bush is not
reciting memorized lines during an official speech or rendering
careful answers during a formal interview, he is folksy and feisty,
a politician more playful than most of his peers. This disarming
demeanor goes a long way toward explaining the commitment and
confidence of Bush's core Republican supporters. But Bush's looser,
lighter style also contributes, fairly or not, to the questions
that opponents and reporters have raised about his intellectual
maturity. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARISTA-DAVIS (New York) _ At age 66 _ or a whispered 67 _ Clive
Davis is a music man who usually plays it by ear, sensing hits and
nurturing artists like Janis Joplin, Barry Manilow, Whitney Houston
and Sarah McLachlan. But Davis is also a man with an independent
attitude and a passion for the New York-based company he founded.
And that style has drawn him into an epic Clash of the New Releases
(and Leaks) with Arista's corporate parents, BMG Entertainment and
its German owner, Bertelsmann. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   NYGIANT-ZARB-SUIT (Undated) _ A former New York Giants football
star is contending in a lawsuit that Frank Zarb, the chairman of
the organization that runs the Nasdaq Stock Market, cut short his
career in the insurance industry by deceiving him about a $1.23
billion corporate buyout. The case is scheduled for trial on Monday
in the Superior Court of New Jersey. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   SEGA-OUTLOOK (Tokyo) _ Sega Enterprises Inc., the beleaguered
video game company, commits itself to a radical reorientation of
its business aimed at harnessing the power of the Internet. The
maker of the new Dreamcast game system, which competes with Sony
and Nintendo in the multibillion-dollar home videogame industry,
also reveals that its losses in the first half of the fiscal year
were larger than expected. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No staff-written Op-Ed columns for Saturday's New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on the
throat-slash gesture, which has now been banned by the NFL. It is
the latest confrontation between the league and its players over
in-your-face-style celebrations and it probably won't be the last
one. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-RESTORE (Assisi, Italy) _ A look at the remarkable
restoration of the Basilica of St. Francis in Assisi, heavily
damaged in a 1997 earthquake. The church is to reopen on Sunday. By
Elisabetta Povoledo.
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST-MALLORY (Undated) _ Putting yourself in the boots of a
dead stranger to deduce what he thought and did in his final hours
is a detective's technique. But when the death occurred more than
75 years ago in one of the most remote points of the earth, the
task seems nigh impossible. The discovery on May 1 of the frozen
body of George Leigh Mallory high on Mount Everest has revived a
decades-old debate about what happened to Mallory and his young
companion, Andrew Irvine, on June 8, 1924, when they attempted the
first ascent of the world's highest mountain. By Christopher S.
Wren.
</P>
<P>
   FITZGERALD-GATSBY (Undated) _ The publication of the original
novel, ``Trimalchio,'' that F. Scott Fitzgerald based Gatsby on. By
Irwin Molotsky. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Edward Rothstein reviews ``A
Culinary History of Food.''
</P>
<P>
   ILIAD-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Iliad,'' by the Aquila
Theater Company, at Clark Studio Theater. Reviewed by D.J.R.
Bruckner.
</P>
