<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LOUISIANATECH     11-27 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LOUISIANATECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS LOUISIANA TECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Great start. Better finish.
</P>
<P>
   USC went out with gusto Friday night, routing 25th-ranked
Louisiana Tech 45-19 before 45,070 at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the Trojans could just have done something about those
middle five games it lost, this wouldn't have been such a
disappointing season. And maybe USC coach Paul Hackett wouldn't
have hinted at possible staff changes.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the kind of year it has been.
</P>
<P>
   This USC team has a penchant for the unexpected, and Friday
night, that meant shutting down one of the nation's most-explosive
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Much like its 62-7 season-opening victory over Hawaii, USC
dominated the Bulldogs in a game that made its mediocre play in
October only more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans contained Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay to _
get this _ 405 yards passing. It sounds awful, but Rattay is the
NCAA's No. 2 all-time leading passer, and did less damage than
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   He was rarely able to do much inside the 20-yard line, and threw
three interceptions. Rattay also had three touchdown passes, but
one came with 22 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech (8-3) averaged 37 points per game, so this was an
above-average performance by USC's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised we shut them down like we did,'' free safety
David Gibson said. ``He's an exceptional quarterback, but their
receivers weren't that good. I knew our secondary was better than
their receiving corps.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't mean Tech was prepared to give up. Rattay threw 68
passes, the most ever by a quarterback against the Trojans, and
completed 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets maddening to have to face 60, 70 balls,'' cornerback
Kris Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being severely tested by Rattay, USC's secondary, which
included true freshmen Kevin Arbet and Darrell Rideaux, stood firm
against the aerial assault.
</P>
<P>
   Arbet had the play of the game in the third quarter, when he
intercepted a pass and ran 75 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My running back instincts took over,'' Arbet said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crowning moment for Arbet, who entered USC as a walk-on
before being awarded a scholarship just prior to the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was beautiful. I was running with him the whole way,''
said Arbet's stepfather, former USC wide receiver Jeff Simmons.
``Every step.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (6-6) seemed prepared to blow Tech out early,
running up a 21-0 first-quarter lead. On their first possession,
quarterback John Fox hit R. Jay Soward on a 53-yard touchdown pass.
Fox ended his evening by proposing to his girlfriend, Nicole
Barros, on the Coliseum's giant video screen after the game. She
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-yard reverse by Soward set up Chad Morton's 3-yard
touchdown run for a 14-0 lead, and Morton's 17-yard run made it
21-0 barely nine minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rattay completed just 4 of 16 passes in the first quarter but
then got hot, quickly leading Tech to a pair of touchdowns to cut
the lead to 21-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense rattled him early. I thought he looked out of
sorts,'' Hackett said. ``Once he got his rhythm going, you could
see how dangerous he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattay was accurate in the second half, but he threw two
interceptions in the third quarter that were crucial, including
Arbet's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to win, but we didn't expect to hold them to 19
points,'' said Richard, who had an interception. ``(Rattay) was
everything I thought he would be. He could throw the ball. He had a
great arm and was accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a satisfying victory for the Trojans, but not a
satisfying season, and that's why changes could be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett didn't rule out some type of shakeup on the coaching
staff to improve the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give it some thought and figure out how to get
better,'' Hackett said. ``If that involves making changes, so be
it. But I haven't given it a lot of thought. That's what the month
of December will be for.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     11-27 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR USC'S FOX, PRIZE COMES AFTER GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay piled up the
numbers again Friday evening at the Coliseum, setting one record,
nudging another.
</P>
<P>
   But USC quarterback John Fox got the win _ and the girl.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Fox was afraid to compare himself to Rattay. He didn't
want to embarrass the poor guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have killed myself if I tried to pay attention to (how
Rattay was doing), he's so good,'' Fox said after the Trojans beat
the Bulldogs 45-19 despite Rattay's 35-for-68, 405-yard passing
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't worry about trying to match him.'' The USC offense,
he noted, is ``not set up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Fox was just being polite, respectful.
</P>
<P>
   He knew better than anybody that the last act of the USC
football season wasn't about passes attempted and completed.
Football, and life beyond the final gun, require more than a strong
right arm.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, corny as this sounds, it's all about heart. Fox
proved it on the field for the third straight week, his earnest
efficiency and leadership a big reason the Trojans finish this 6-6
season with a three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Then he proved it on the stadium video screen for the remainder
of the crowd to watch.
</P>
<P>
   As USC players celebrated with family and friends on the field
minutes after the game, Fox knelt in front of girlfriend Nicole
Barros and presented her with an engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicole, Will You Marry Me?'' read the video screen.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen fans propose to their sweethearts at a ballgame _ but
a player?
</P>
<P>
   ``She said OK,'' Fox said later in typical understatement.
</P>
<P>
   They kissed as fans cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Fox explained that he'd been planning the stunt for 12 weeks,
making sure it was all right with his coach, with the video crew,
with the NCAA rulebook.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve weeks ago, Fox was a linebacker, at the most improbable
stage of the odyssey that took him from starting quarterback for
nine games as a sophomore to taking nary a snap as a junior and
back.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't have known how perfectly it would all work out.
</P>
<P>
   USC head coach Paul Hackett gave Fox his approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I think it's a fantastic idea. I don't know if you
have the (guts) to do it, but I think it's a fantastic idea,'''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Fox had the (guts).
</P>
<P>
   He made sure Barros' mother was at the game, and asked his
mother to fly in from Nebraska for the occasion. He entrusted Jack
Ward, the trainer emeritus who has been a USC fixture since the
1950s, with holding the ring during the game.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Fox popped the question, nobody was surprised except
Nicole and the 45,070 football fans who shared the couple's
precious moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big surprise. I thought they were just going to show
pictures of the family (on the video screen),'' she said on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said she tried to pull away as she realized what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on, hold on, let me get through this thing the way I've
been planning it for 12 weeks,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   She's a USC student too. They began dating at Centennial High in
Corona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made my dream come true,'' Fox said. ``She's
definitely the one for me. To have my whole team behind me and
congratulating me... it was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the whole team was behind him. It has been behind him
ever since he reclaimed the starting quarterback job from Mike Van
Raaphorst following the fourth of USC's five straight losses.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't put up stats like Rattay's. Fifteen completions and
148 yards in the loss to Arizona State; 12 and 117 to beat
Washington State; 17 and 216 to beat UCLA last week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he went 11 for 20 for 137 yards, 53 of them to R. Jay
Soward for the game's first touchdown. He didn't make mistakes,
though; a second-quarter interception marked his first turnover in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know he's been the catalyst through the last three
weeks,'' Hackett said. ``I was just hoping for John that we would
win this one and win it big.''
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be Rattay's big night _ the nation's most
prolific passer facing a USC secondary missing the injured Antuan
Simmons and starting two freshmen and a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   And Rattay did show off, to the extent his fumble-fingered
receivers and the resolute young Trojans would allow. His 68
attempts were the most ever against USC and his 35 completions were
the most against USC since Oregon State's Erik Wilhelm had 37 in
1988 and his 405 passing yards were the most against USC since
UCLA's Tommy Maddox had 409 in 1990. His 113th, 114th and 115th
touchdown passes placed him second to BYU's Ty Detmer (121) in NCAA
history.
</P>
<P>
   There will be other nights for Rattay. He'll go high in April's
NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Fox might have played his last football game. He's been training
to become an elementary-school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Who would you rather have been Friday night?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
