<HEADLINE>
CHANGES AWAIT AS USC LOOKS TO NEXT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC may make changes in its coaching staff,
something coach Paul Hackett did not rule out Friday night, but the
Trojans seem assured of changing some players' roles for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, it seems likely defensive end Kori Dickerson will
move to tight end for spring practice. Another likely switch is
moving linebacker Sultan Abdul-Malik back to his original position
of defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik had two sacks against Louisiana Tech, but those came
when he lined up as a defensive end. He was generally ineffective
as an outside linebacker this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bittersweet end: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward started out fast,
with a 53-yard touchdown reception, two runs for 46 yards and two
punt returns for 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But he became ill at halftime and was forced to watch the second
half from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappointing year for him as it related to us, but
he'll have another day,'' Hackett said. ``He was totally exhausted.
It's been a tough year for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward finished his career with 25 plays of 40 yards or longer,
and 32 touchdowns, including 23 on receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking change: Hackett benched kicker David Newbury after he
missed a 46-yard attempt and replaced him with David Bell, who made
a 38-yard field goal and was 2 for 2 on conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen enough,'' Hackett said. ``I'm very disappointed in
the punting and kicking performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury finished 11 of 20 on field goals this season.
</P>
<P>
   Iron man: Offensive tackle Travis Claridge started his 48th
consecutive game to become the first USC lineman of the post-World
War II era to start every game in his career from the day he set
foot on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Other USC linemen have started every game but with the benefit
of a redshirt year.
</P>
<P>
   Up the charts: Tailback Chad Morton finished his career as USC's
eighth all-time rusher with 2,511 yards. His 1,141 yards this
season placed him 18th on the Trojans' single-season list.
</P>
<P>
   No coincidence: USC went 3-0 in its final three games and also
rushed for more than 200 yards in each of those contests.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery set: Linebacker Markus Steele said he will have surgery
on his left shoulder Dec. 14 to repair loose tissue that has
bothered him the second part of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Out of line: Two starters on the offensive line, guard Donta
Kendrick (flu) and center Eric Denmon (ankle), did not play.
</P>
<P>
   Alma mater: Former Louisiana Tech quarterback and current NFL
analyst Terry Bradshaw attended the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
