<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     11-27 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY, RIDEAUX PROVIDE HOPE FOR FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC will begin the new century with a streak.
</P>
<P>
   And for once, it's a good streak. The losing streaks against
Notre Dame and UCLA have been terminated, and no longer will USC
trail them around campus like a piece of toilet paper stuck on
their shoe. USC will break into the 2000s with a modest three-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Considering USC's vagaries in the '90s, no one should take a
three-game winning streak for granted. Since the end of the 1992
season, USC has managed only two longer winning streaks, five in
the middle of 1994 and six to start 1995.
</P>
<P>
   No one's going to count Friday's 45-19 win over Louisiana Tech,
a scruffy team with an annoying offense, as fashionably as last
week's win over UCLA. But it beats losing to TCU in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a nice momentum swing for us,'' Trojan coach
Paul Hackett said after Tim Rattay's 68-pass assault. ``In a lot of
ways, it's a lot better than last year even though we went to a
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This obviously wasn't a bowl game. But winning our last three
and beating UCLA was very positive for our young guys. A number of
them looked me in the eye after the game and said `next year,
coach, next year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two of those young players eyeballing Hackett were Kareem Kelly
and Darrell Rideaux, the former Long Beach Poly standouts who
contributed much more to USC's season as true freshman than anyone
could have reasonably expected.
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux finished his season with starts in the last two games
and 27 of his 34 tackles in USC's last four games. After what he
called a bad game against the Bruins, he was an active and
effective corner against Tech's five-receiver sets Friday. He had
seven tackles, and all of Tech's big plays came against the other
side of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I played well (against UCLA). I had to regroup
against a quality quarterback and an offense that can shake you
up,' said Rideaux. ``I called my high school coaches (Poly
assistants Don Norford and Charles Clinton) this week for
reassurance.''
</P>
<P>
   They reminded him that when in doubt, he can always rely on his
technique. As a 5-9 corner often giving away four-to-six inches to
receivers, technique is what Rideaux has to rely on. But now he
knows what the college game is about, and few young athletes seem
to enjoy the learning process as much as Rideaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great learning experience,'' Rideaux said. ``I
obviously have a lot more to work on. I need to work on my
strength. But what I have now is game experience, experience
playing under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like tonight, you work and learn to get better. But you
grow up against UCLA. There's a locker room full of young players
who grew up last week, guys who will come back next season as
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly actually had more rushing attempts (two reverses) than
receptions (one) Friday as USC's offense stayed on the ground to
keep Rattay off the field. But the wide receiver finishes the year
with 54 catches, 902 yards (both USC freshman records) and a lock
on freshman All-American honors.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had five catches or more in seven games this season and
four games with 100 or more receiving yards, topped by a nine
catch, 170-yard effort against Cal. With R. Jay Soward and Windrell
Hayes departing, Kelly will become USC's go-to receiver in '00.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming in that I would be used a little,'' said Kelly.
``We unfortunately had a few injuries and I had the chance to play
a lot more than I expected. It feels good to contribute. That's
what you want to do as a freshman, contribute any way you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't focus on any hype (about next year). I have to get
better. There are a lot of things I have to polish -- my routes, my
speed, my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting stronger and better won't nearly be as difficult for
Rideaux and Kelly as learning to deal with losses. Six Trojan
losses in '99 matched or exceeded their losses in multiyear high
school careers.
</P>
<P>
   Rideaux became a starter at Poly as a ninth grader and left with
a 49-6 career record. In three seasons, Kelly was 36-5, and he
suffered just two losses in his last 36 games between 1996 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from winning every game to losing six in a season,
that's a (downer),'' said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a freshman, you're told to be seen and unheard,''
said Rideaux. ``So I watched how the team would respond (to
losses), how no one pointed fingers, how players took their licks,
how the team leaders kept us together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually was kind of exciting. We experienced failure,
learned how to win and grew a lot closer as a team. I learned to
understand my role as a Trojan, and most of the guys here will be
back next season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans lose only two players from their defensive two-deep
lineup Friday. Kelly and fellow freshman receiver Marcell Allmond
will welcome back quarterback Carson Palmer, and while there's no
replacing Chad Morton's heart, Sultan McCullough (79 yards Friday)
is a more than capable runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the opportunity to do some super things,'' said
Rideaux. And without any nagging streaks attached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
