<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX GETS THE WIN, AND THE GIRL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay got the yards, 405 of them
to be exact, when the Bulldogs visited USC in the Coliseum on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the win went to USC senior quarterback John Fox. Oh yeah,
Fox also went home with the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Fox did his part in the 45-19 win over the 25th-ranked Bulldogs
by completing 11 of 20 passes for 137 yards, including a 53-yard
scoring strike to R. Jay Soward at the conclusion of the Trojans'
opening drive. However, his postgame performance was even more
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   With family, friends and teammates gathered nearby on the
Coliseum turf, Fox got down on one knee in the moments following
the game and proposed to his girlfriend, Nicole Barros.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said OK,'' Fox said about 20 minutes later with a smile
still plastered on his face. ``It just made my dream come true. I
just can't explain it. I don't think she knew it was coming. To
have my whole team behind me and congratulating me, it was
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an idea hatched in Fox's mind about the time the Trojans
kicked off the season in Hawaii. And one of the first people he
approached was USC coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said absolutely,'' Hackett said. ``It was one of the best
ideas I had heard of. I didn't know if he had the (guts) to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which took 12 weeks to prepare and was shown on
the Coliseum video board, actually was easy on Fox's nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was something I wanted to do,'' said Fox, who has
been dating Barros for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was going to happen win or lose on Friday. But it
sure made it nicer after the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping for John that we won this one and won it
big,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   When the football season began, it appeared like Fox's largest
contribution to the USC football team during his senior year would
come when he was on one knee as the holder for field goals and PAT
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a 6-foot-4, 220-pound senior who was a Best in the West
selection after playing at Corona Centennial High for former Gahr
coach Steve Silberman, started nine games at quarterback in 1997
when John Robinson was the Trojan coach. However, when Hackett took
over, Fox slid down the depth chart. He moved to tight end during
fall camp last season and entered this year as a backup linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox returned to the quarterback rotation after Carson Palmer
broke his collarbone and Mike Van Raaphorst couldn't lead the team
to victory.
</P>
<P>
   His career ended with three consecutive wins, including the
streak-busting victory over UCLA and the duel with Rattay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy is so good,'' Fox said of Rattay. ``He's gonna go
far. But wins and losses are what counts most.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention getting the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary importance: USC's defensive backfield for much of
Friday consisted of cornerbacks Kris Richard, Darrell Rideaux and
Kevin Arbet and safeties David Gibson and Ifeanyi Ohalete.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you without a score card, that is one sophomore,
two freshmen and two safeties who have been better suited for run
support. And they were facing a quarterback who has thrown for more
yards than all but one player in NCAA history.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive game plan called for pressure early to try and
keep Rattay from getting into a rhythm. The plan worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he looked out of sorts early,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans sacked Rattay three times and pressured him
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand Florida State only sacked him one time,'' Richard
said. ``That says a lot for our defensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattay tied a career high with 68 attempts and completed 35 with
three going for touchdowns. But he also was intercepted a season
high three times, including one returned 75 yards for a touchdown
by Arbet, and was sacked twice by Sultan Abdul-Malik and once by
Aaron Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate giving up big plays,'' said Richard, who along with
Ohalete, had the other interceptions. ``But with 60-70 balls, you
can't stop everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pick and roll: Arbet, a true freshman from Stockton, walked on
at USC but earned a scholarship before fall camp was complete. His
biggest moment was undoubtedly the interception and winding 75-yard
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about that interception return?'' Richard
said. ``I ran behind him and watched him making moves like he was
(O.J. Simpson).''
</P>
<P>
   Arbet said it was simply reverting to his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a running back in high school,'' Arbet said. ``When I
got the ball my running back skills took over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
