<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL SPARKS LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal obviously is getting the hang of
this geometry thing that coach Phil Jackson is teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The results were evident enough in his 30-point, 16-rebound
performance Friday night as he led an easy 103-80 rout of the New
Jersey Nets at Staples Center. Just an example of the virtues of
the triangle offense?
</P>
<P>
   More than that, said the scholarly O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the Pythagorean theory,'' he said. ``Not too many
people know the answer to my game. Quote me on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy enough, but could O'Neal quote the Pythagorean theory?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I never knew it,'' he admitted sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal. The Nets, as O'Neal points out, had no answers
either.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal played the first 41 minutes of the game before finally
taking a breather, and by that time the Nets were dizzy with all
the math lessons _ including O'Neal's 14-for-24 shooting, his four
blocked shots and his season-high seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers led wire to wire for what could be
categorized as a routine victory over a very debilitated, 2-11 Nets
team that could only throw the likes of ancient Michael Cage at
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope its systematic, rather than routine,'' coach Phil
Jackson said. ``Routine connotes boredom or robotic kind of
behavior. We want systematic, we want to grind it out. We want to
have the type of team that can take people to a certain space and
make them pay almost 75 percent of the time (against O'Neal).''
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions in the second quarter, Jackson got what he
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice struggled to a 1-for-7 night, but the Lakers found
alternatives easily against the Nets _ from Ron Harper's
season-high 17 points to 12 points each from Derek Fisher and Rick
Fox. Fisher fought through foul trouble to hit 6 of 7 shots, while
Fox shook off early jitters to hit 5 of 7 and record a rare
double-digit performance from a Lakers reserve.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal played 40-plus minutes for the sixth straight game, but
he didn't have to exert much energy against Cage and Stiff Hall of
Famer Jim McIlvaine. The two Nets centers combined for zero points
while 7-7 Gheorge Muresan stayed on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was never in doubt, but it took until the third
quarter for the Lakers to put the Nets away. And even then, they
had to withstand an 11-point quarter from Johnny Newman.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers opened the second half with a 10-2 run, capped by a
pair of fast-break buckets from Harper, to make it a 17-point game,
57-40.
</P>
<P>
   But before you could say, ``Hello, Newman,'' he had scored seven
straight points. That was enough to wake up the Lakers defense, and
they never let the Nets get within single digits, taking a 73-59
lead into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the Nets (2-11) looked like a team on the rise,
boasting the talented young tandem of Keith Van Horn and Stephon
Marbury. But it's who the Nets are missing that is most glaring.
Center Jayson Williams and guard Kendall Gill are on the injured
list, and Kerry Kittles is active but too hurt to play.
</P>
<P>
   Newman scored 24 points off the bench, but the Nets' stars
struggled. Van Horn shot 5 for 14, finishing with 20 points, and
Marbury was 3 for 16 for 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Shaq intimidated us, particularly with the shots
Stephon likes to get inside the paint,'' Nets coach Don Casey said.
``He's a monster, we were worried about Rice and people like that,
but Shaq clears his ground and the others just feed off him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
