<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Nov. 28:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNIONISTS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Northern
Ireland's biggest Protestant party votes to back a deal opening the
way for Northern Ireland's first genuine power-sharing government
of Protestants and Roman Catholics. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ How Russia, taking a leaf from NATO's
playbook, is managing the flow of information in its latest war in
Chechnya. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-RUSSIA (Istanbul) _ While nearly all of Europe has
condemned the Russian government's military assault in Chechnya,
the Turkish government has remained silent, not wanting to leave
itself open to criticism of its own long war against Kurdish
separatists. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-REBEL (Sigli, Indonesia) _ Abdullah Syafie is waging a
guerrilla war against Indonesia. But who has time to fight when the
foreign news media keep dropping by? By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SCANDAL (Jerusalem) _ Scandal, and lots of it, was what
occupied Israel's attention this week, so much so that one leading
newspaper saw fit to run a full-page scandal guide, with boxes for
every major affair, its suspects, its allegations and the status of
its investigation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-CLERIC-SENTENCE (Undated) _ Iran's most powerful religious
court imposes a five-year jail term and a five-year banishment from
political activity on a Muslim cleric, Abdullah Nouri, who has won
widespread popular support with demands for an end to authoritarian
rule by the country's religious hierarchy. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-REV-MOON (Jardim, Brazil) _ The Rev. Sun Myung Moon, the
78-year-old founder of the Unification Church who has been rebuffed
by the United States and is facing financial troubles in his native
Korea, is seeking to reinvent himself in a sparsely populated
corner of Brazil that he calls ``a new Garden of Eden.'' By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-MEETING (UNdated) _ Why the latest negotiations of the World
Trade Organization, set to begin next Tuesday, are turning into a
free-for-all of protests and demands by special interests ranging
from human rights campaigners to unionists to environmentalists. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-WOMEN (Milwaukee) _ Exclusive. Caseworkers rarely ask
and clients rarely tell, but growing evidence suggests that
disproportionately large numbers of women on welfare were sexually
abused as children, a finding that offers new insight into many of
the so-called hard cases that are an increasing focus of the
national effort to overhaul the welfare system. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Michael Hyatt gained admission to
Stanford's business school and prepared to enroll this fall. During
the summer, however, he took an eight-week job helping a friend who
worked at a small Internet company in Southern California, and when
it ended, Hyatt, 28, was hooked. So he called Stanford to say
thanks anyway: he wouldn't be showing up in Palo Alto after all. As
many of the nation's most talented young workers rush to stake that
claim, business school has suddenly lost some of its luster. That
has had a significant impact on applications to some top schools,
particularly those that tend to attract the entrepreneurially
minded. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-VALET-PARKING (Los Angeles) _ A look at the California
culture of parking. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TALKSHOW-PRIEST (Miami) _ A talk show on the Telemundo
Spanish-language network delves into domestic violence, sex
addiction and other issues common to daytime programming. But
``Padre Alberto'' is different in a big way. The host of the
program is a Roman Catholic priest. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-FOREIGN (Washington) _ An overview of Bradley's broad
philosophy on foreign policy and defense issues, and a preview of
Bradley's first major foreign policy speech of the campaign, which
he will give on Monday. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
