<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KITNA REMEMBERS BARCELONA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They were living across from the beach. One day, three
of the American football players decided, and quite admirably, hey,
we're playing for Barcelona, we ought to check out the big town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' said Jon Kitna, telling this story on himself. ``So we
took the train downtown, but there was nobody around. It was so
quiet, and everything was closed. By the time we figured out it was
siesta, we had to get back. It was a wasted trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna did go back often enough, maybe a dozen times in the four
months he was over there, to catch one of the world's great cities
in full blast. He made the most of his time in Spain, in every way.
He played quarterback in 10 games all over Europe in the spring of
1997, improving enough to qualify for the National Football League
the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback from the Barcelona Dragons now has the second
highest ranking in his conference for the Seattle Seahawks, who
have won eight of their first 10 games. The Seahawks play Tampa Bay
Sunday in terminally sodden Seattle, totally justifying the
existence of the dismal Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to going to Barcelona, Kitna has made a lot of other
adjustments in his life. While at tiny Central Washington
University, he gave up his carousing and sought out a spiritual
rebirth, and now, at 27, he is an exuberant but mature family man.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was mature enough to handle the challenge of playing in a
continent where people are more attuned to low-scoring games in the
real futbol between Barcelona and Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   As a spring training league, NFL Europe is clearly paying
dividends. Ten percent of the players (that is, 176) on the
opening-day NFL rosters had played in Europe, including 20
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the quarterbacks playing significant time are Kurt Warner
of St. Louis, Scott Mitchell and Stoney Case of Baltimore and Damon
Huard of Miami. They all benefited from rules that are altered
slightly (no more than six players rushing at a time) ``to give the
offense an advantage,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want to have a lot of 7-6 games over there,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The formerly tough kid from Tacoma made a stop in the
sophisticated Catalan city of Barcelona after throwing for 99
touchdowns, more than any quarterback in the history of the state,
albeit for a tiny NAIA school up in the outback.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna might have never made it to the NFL except that one of his
teammates, Jamie Christian, is a nephew of Dennis Erickson, who was
beginning what would be a four-year hitch with the Seahawks. The
nephew virtually forced the uncle to conduct a private workout for
Kitna, who earned a free-agent contract to the practice squad in
1996. After that, the Seahawks told Kitna about the Barcelona
Dragons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't force me to go; I could see it was a good idea,''
said Kitna, who had given his wife some hard times in college, and
now that he had settled down, ``I did not want to be away from
Jennifer for four months.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna added: ``But then the coaches told me they were bringing
their wives, and they encouraged the players to bring their wives,
too. I went over first and then my wife joined me. Actually, she
was pregnant when she came over, but we didn't know it. She had her
test in Barcelona.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, so did Kitna, who was the most valuable player in the
38-24 victory over the Rhein Fire in the World Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to tell Jon Kitna that he has a great, great
future,'' blurted his Barcelona coach, Jack Bicknell, formerly of
Boston College, who had once coached another quarterback named Doug
Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna has great loyalty to Erickson for giving him a chance, but
he has prospered under Mike Holmgren, who came over with his two
Super Bowl rings from Green Bay. Holmgren said he might have
underestimated Kitna at first.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback is a long way from Barcelona. And, yes, Kitna
did get back downtown. He and Jennifer walked the Ramblas, the
picturesque boulevard of markets and snacks and chairs and flowers,
where crowds have been strolling for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were so nice to us,'' Kitna recalled. ``We didn't speak
much Spanish and they didn't speak much English, but they took care
of us. Our hotel was in Sitges, right across from the water. It was
great. I'd love to get back there soon.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be too soon. As anybody knows from following the two
most recent Summer Games, Atlanta is not exactly Barcelona.
However, Atlanta is where the Super Bowl happens to be this season.
Kitna would not mind making a detour before any sentimental
journeys back to Barcelona, this time not during siesta.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
