<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-27 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: EGYPTAIR 990 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When EgyptAir Flight 990 went down I thought of writing a column
about the passenger list. I was struck by how many Americans, and
particularly American Jews, were on the flight, sitting alongside
33 elite Egyptian Army officers who had been training in the United
States, as well as a host of other nationalities. I thought back to
the first time I visited Cairo in 1972, when Egypt didn't even have
diplomatic relations with the United States, let alone American or
Jewish tourists. We forget, but for Americans, going to Egypt back
then was almost like visiting North Korea. So it seemed to me this
tragedy underscored how far Egyptian-American and Egyptian-Israeli
relations had actually come since those dark days. While this was
no balm for the victims' families, one hoped their common grief
might bind their countries even more.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Before I had a chance to put those words down on paper,
Egyptians and Americans were back to looking at each other through
their most encrusted, us-vs.-them stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   What triggered the downward spiral were leaks, based on the
cockpit voice recorder, suggesting that an EgyptAir co-pilot,
Gameel el-Batouty, may have deliberately disconnected the plane
from its autopilot and pitched it into a downward spiral, all the
time uttering the Arabic phrase ``tawakilt ala Allah'' _ literally
``I put my faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tawakilt ala Allah'' is not the normal rallying cry of Islamic
extremists. Its standard usage is: ``OK, God. Stand by me now.'' No
matter. All that Americans needed to hear was that the co-pilot had
uttered the word ``Allah,'' and it triggered visions of a maniacal
suicide pilot. It is no surprise that Egyptians get upset at the
thought that Americans believe any Muslim prayer must be the
prelude to killing people.
</P>
<P>
   There was something else going on with Americans. After the
still-not-fully-explained crashes of the TWA and Swissair
jetliners, in nearly the same location that the EgyptAir jet went
down, there was an even more intense desire here to have a clear
explanation for the Flight 990 disaster. It is as if every traveler
was saying, ``Please God, not another unexplained crash.'' It's too
scary to think that our high technology has fatal flaws that we
can't find. So when the crazy co-pilot theory emerged, it was
seized on here with relish and relief.
</P>
<P>
   But Egyptian knees jerked just as quickly. The idea that an
EgyptAir jet or pilot might not have performed up to standard
triggered all the Egyptian insecurities that the world looks down
on Arabs as not quite mastering the Information Revolution.
Egyptian newspapers and pundits quickly slid into shameful
conspiracy theories _ claiming U.S. or Israeli plots to shoot down
the EgyptAir flight. I don't expect the Egyptian government to
control its press. But after 20 years of U.S. aid to Egypt,
approaching $40 billion, I would expect the Egyptian leadership to
be clearly and unambiguously educating the Egyptian public that
America is a friend, not an old, sinister imperialist. Where is the
official Egyptian denunciation of such conspiracy theories? Egypt
is too important and serious a country to resort to such fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   We need a timeout here, in which the U.S. government and the
Egyptian government each prepares its public to accept the idea
that its favored explanation might not be the one science
indicates. Americans may have to accept that there is no conclusive
proof that this was pilot error, suicide or mechanical error. It
may be just one more mysterious reason not to fly.
</P>
<P>
   And the Egyptian leadership needs to prepare its public for the
possibility that the overwhelming evidence may indicate this was a
suicide. It can't afford to let the dominant explanation in Egypt
become the notion that this crash was a U.S. or Israeli plot to
weaken Egypt. ``They have to rebut those arguments head on,'' notes
the University of Maryland Mideast scholar Shibley Telhami,
``otherwise how will Egypt be able to continue to pursue a
pro-American, pro-peace-with-Israel foreign policy?''
</P>
<P>
   I still believe the passenger list of EgyptAir 990 tells us
something good about how far Egyptian-American and even
Egyptian-Israeli relations have come in the last 25 years. But the
mistrust so easily triggered by the inquiry tells us we still have
a long way to go. So, one hopes we can agree quickly on what
happened to the dead in this crash, because there is a lot of work
to be done among the living.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
