<P>
   BIZ-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Michael Hyatt gained admission to
Stanford's business school and prepared to enroll this fall. During
the summer, however, he took an eight-week job helping a friend who
worked at a small Internet company in Southern California, and when
it ended, Hyatt, 28, was hooked. So he called Stanford to say
thanks anyway: he wouldn't be showing up in Palo Alto after all. As
many of the nation's most talented young workers rush to stake that
claim, business school has suddenly lost some of its luster. That
has had a significant impact on applications to some top schools,
particularly those that tend to attract the entrepreneurially
minded. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
