<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-L.A.-PARKING-ART-NYT &LR;      11-27 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-PARKING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY IN LOS ANGELES: VALET PARKING AS BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles A to Z, an encyclopedia of this city's
history and folkways published by the University of California
Press, lists ``automobile'' as ``a feature of the regional culture
so dominant as to defy brief description,'' and that seems a safe
understatement. Here in the region that perfected drive-through
banking, drive-in restaurants and drive-by shootings, people do
almost everything with their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, that is, except park them.
</P>
<P>
   By the millions, Southern Californians routinely leave that task
to others. In a city where the phrase ``service economy'' is taken
for granted, valet parking thrives, and not just at restaurants,
hotels and airports, where the service is increasingly popular
around the country. Here you can leave the keys with Jeeves at
hospitals and minimalls, movie theaters and grocery stores, the
occasional Starbucks and at least one gym, not to mention
practically every fancy private party for 20 people or more. The
Yellow Pages features 45 listings for Parking Attendant Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angelenos are lazy,'' said Chuck Pick, owner of Chuck's
Parking Service, who has been parking cars for 40 years and
provides valet service at special events for his third generation
of Hollywood society. ``No, not lazy,'' Pick quickly amended
himself. ``Service-oriented. But when I ever write a book, it's
going to be how people lose their feet and legs when they go to a
party. Suddenly, they can't walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have women call me up and say, `Oh, I need valets,' and I
say, `Can I ask you a question? Do you walk from Saks to Neiman's?'
And they say, `Sure,' and I say, `Well, why can't you walk across
the street?'''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are so many cars in greater Los Angeles, and
so many neighborhood parking restrictions, that valet parking is
often the most efficient way to cram cars into a limited space.
This is, after all, a city that had more than one car for every two
residents as early as 1925, and where married couples still
invariably arrive at workday movies or restaurant dates in separate
cars, and where the affluent often provide separate station wagons
just for their nannies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have grown to accept and expect it,'' said Herb Citrin,
77, the chairman of Valet Parking Service. Citrin pioneered the
industry here beginning in 1946 when he opened the parking
concession at Lawry's Prime Rib in Beverly Hills, which he still
serves today, along with about 60 other restaurants and hotels like
the Regent Beverly Wilshire, plus the Burbank Airport. Citrin's
business has 1,600 employees, many of them recent Hispanic
immigrants, who earn an average of $6 to $7 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's a major, major necessity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, valet parking is so common that drivers of $70,000
luxury cars who would not entrust them to their own teen-agers
routinely hand them over to complete strangers, and sometimes
assume that restaurants offer the service, even if they do not. At
the Grill in Beverly Hills, the reigning power-lunch place for
agents and moguls, there is no valet stand at lunch, because
parking is so tight at that hour in Beverly Hills that it would
cost the restaurant too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every once in a while, we will have somebody who pulls up,
leaves their car running and goes in and eats lunch,'' said Bob
Spivak, one of the restaurant's founding partners and now president
of its parent company. ``And they come back two hours later and the
car's still sitting there, parked in the driveway with a ticket on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most restaurants charge about $3.50, plus tip, for valet
parking. On the other hand, even nonvalet parking in downtown
office towers can easily cost four to five times as much.
</P>
<P>
   In scores of places, though, valet parking is free for at least
two hours, as it is in several municipal and merchant-sponsored
lots in Beverly Hills. At the Century City Shopping Center, the
sort of place where Betsy Bloomingdale goes to the movies, valet
service is free with a $25 purchase of groceries at Gelson's, an
upscale supermarket. Cedars-Sinai Medical Center has valet service,
and so does the Commons at Calabassas, a giant mall in the suburban
San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always valet park at Macy's men's store,'' said Marcella
Benson, an office manager who was retrieving her gray Jaguar from
the valet stand at the cavernous Beverly Center mall in Los
Angeles, where valet parking is free with store validation. ``It's
convenient, they're trustworthy and no matter where you are in the
mall, you always know how to get back here.'' Besides, Ms. Benson
added: ``I'm all for putting out money. It's good for the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Sports Club/LA, perhaps the city's most luxurious gym,
about 400 of the 1,600 daily visitors use valet parking, at $2.50 a
car, twice the price for self-parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really tried to coin the phrase of an urban country
club,'' said Phil Swain, vice president and director of operations
at the club, where a standard membership runs $1,250 for the
initiation fee and $130 a month in dues. ``It's a popular service,
and members develop relationships with the attendants the way they
do with their trainers. It really adds to that service aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Maureen Sullivan, a former shoe saleswoman to the stars
in Beverly Hills, had the idea of using aspiring actresses for an
all-female parking service, and now her Valettes Ltd., at $21 per
attendant per hour, is a fixture at private parties here. The
attendants dress in black jackets and pink tuxedo shirts and give a
single rose to each car at the end of an event.
</P>
<P>
   ``In L.A., the parking's just gotten worse and worse, especially
in the hills or the canyons,'' Ms. Sullivan said. ``I have a lot of
repeat business.''
</P>
<P>
   At Chuck's, whose attendants wear distinctive royal blue
jackets, Pick is gearing up for his busiest season: 200 parties in
the next two and a half weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nowhere else in the world that I could be making a
living as nice as this, doing what I do,'' said Pick, who began
parking cars at the old Romanoff's restaurant, a movie star haunt
in Beverly Hills, and has parked cars at events for every president
since Kennedy. ``We do it all, whether it's one man or 100,'' he
added. ``We go from birth to death. We did a bris last week and
we're doing two funerals this weekend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
