<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BRITAIN-LETTERS-REVIE     11-27 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LETTERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS HAVE ALWAYS GONE POSTAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(jt) 
 By  SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Before I moved to London, I took a deep breath and read
``Clarissa,'' Samuel Richardson's classic 18th-century novel about
the seduction and ruin of a virtuous young girl. From an
anthropological point of view, what is interesting about
``Clarissa'' is not only that it is more than one million words
long and that reading it demands a peculiarly British form of
stoicism, but also that it is an epistolary novel _ that is, it is
written entirely in the form of letters between its characters.
</P>
<P>
   This is a blizzard of letter-writing _ and at first I thought it
had to do with the habits of the British gentry during the
pre-technology era, or simply with a literary conceit that, while
unusual, is not unknown. (Laclos, of course, used it to great
effect in ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' another cautionary tale
about compromised virtue). But what I didn't realize is that, as
far as letter-writing goes, Britons might well still be living in
the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, my husband and I have carried on a
purely epistolary relationship with our neighbors, Sir and Lady
T----. (They really do have titles; he is a former tobacco
executive who was knighted, as far as I can tell, for the good job
he did in getting people to smoke). These are people with whom we
share a wall and a bit of sidewalk and with whom, in all this time,
we have had perhaps three actual conversations. If you count
``Hello,'' answered by ``Hello,'' as an actual conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs to converse? The relationship, like any, has had
its ups and downs. When we moved in, we got a friendly letter
welcoming us to the neighborhood. When they planned to paint the
front of their house, they sent an apologetic letter alerting us.
</P>
<P>
   When we did some work on our house (having notified them, of
course, in writing), they sent an alarmed letter asking about, if I
remember correctly, the common dry wall and the potentially
creeping damp _ issues that apparently haunt the imaginations of
British homeowners. We replied, soothingly, by letter, and then
sent them a copy of the letter our surveyor sent us, and then they
sent us a letter. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps their conversational reserve had to do with latent
anti-Americanism, I thought. But that couldn't be all of it,
because my husband is as English as they come (although, alas,
without a title). The truth, as I found when I began to make
British friends, is that the British love to write letters.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I had lunch with an English friend. It was a
typical lunch in an inexpensive cafe. We discussed our husbands,
our jobs and our hair, as one does, and then split the check and
went happily on our ways.
</P>
<P>
   When the mail came the next day, I was shocked to discover that
she had sent me a note.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a note thanking me for lunch. What's more, my
friend had apparently gone out and bought an expensive card with a
picture that would mean something specifically to me. She had
mailed it off that very afternoon, at a time of day when all I had
been thinking was: Should I eat this candy bar now, or later?
</P>
<P>
   The letter-writing threatens to get out of hand when it comes to
thank-you notes, as much a part of my life here as feeling
compelled to say, ``Sorry,'' instead of ``Excuse me,'' when someone
knocks into me on the tube. It's hard to keep up. Last year, I
celebrated my birthday with my husband and four other couples. All
the couples brought presents, but the dinner was at our house. So
what to do? Who should thank whom? Inevitably, we all thanked each
other. I sent out four letters, and received four letters. The only
person I didn't send a thank-you note to was my husband, but then
all he did was set the table.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he thought I was rude, anyway. He comes from a family
where, when you have lunch with your parents, your mother writes
you the next day to thank you for coming. Sometimes your father
thanks you in a separate letter. (You write them at the same time,
to thank them for having you). All the important family business is
conveyed by letter _ news of major illness, the first salvo in what
is going to be a drawn-out feud, or even bits of sisterly advice _
and then, in a way I have come to think of as quintessentially
English, it is never discussed face to face.
</P>
<P>
   This has been difficult to get used to. I know I have received
moving letters from my own mother _ most memorably, when the dog
died in 1980 _ but never a thank-you note. My brother and I
sometimes exchange e-mails. But at heart, we're a telephoning kind
of family.
</P>
<P>
   My husband's family is not partial to the telephone,
particularly in the older generation, whose habits are informed by
the shortages and deprivations of World War II. ``Happy Birthday,
darling,'' my mother-in-law once said to my answering machine in
New York, where her son was visiting, speaking as if noxious,
expensive gases were seeping out of the telephone. ``I'm calling
long distance so I have to hang up now.''
</P>
<P>
   Britons can afford to like the mail; they have a first-rate
postal service.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattanites like me are used to a mail service where the
couriers are stayed from the swift completion of their appointed
rounds not by rain or sleet, but by the apparently overwhelming
task of transporting a letter 20 city blocks. Here, 92 percent of
first-class letters _ which are expensive, at 42 cents _ arrive the
day after they are mailed, no matter where in the country they're
going.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does e-mail appear to have yet replaced snail mail. Ten
years ago, the Royal Mail handled 53 million pieces of first- and
second-class mail every day. Today, this has increased to 77
million pieces of mail, with ``social mail'' _ that is, for
non-business purposes _ holding steady at 20 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Mail takes great offense at suggestions that its
service is not exemplary. It was not amused, for instance, at
recent newspaper reports describing how a postcard saying, ``We
have arrived safely and are having a lovely time'' turned up at its
destination some 75 years after it had been sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most irritating things that come up in my
job,'' said Patrick O'Neill, a Royal Mail spokesman, saying that in
most of these cases, the piece of mail in question was never lost,
but had turned up at a yard sale of ancient items and then
re-mailed as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what the postal service would do back home. But
here where the fate of the letter is paramount, the outdated card
was duly delivered. ``We have a legal obligation to deliver any
letter that is put in the mail, even if it doesn't have the right
postage,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
