 By  SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Before I moved to London, I took a deep breath and read
``Clarissa,'' Samuel Richardson's classic 18th-century novel about
the seduction and ruin of a virtuous young girl. From an
anthropological point of view, what is interesting about
``Clarissa'' is not only that it is more than one million words
long and that reading it demands a peculiarly British form of
