</P>
<P>
   But who needs to converse? The relationship, like any, has had
its ups and downs. When we moved in, we got a friendly letter
welcoming us to the neighborhood. When they planned to paint the
front of their house, they sent an apologetic letter alerting us.
</P>
<P>
   When we did some work on our house (having notified them, of
course, in writing), they sent an alarmed letter asking about, if I
remember correctly, the common dry wall and the potentially
creeping damp _ issues that apparently haunt the imaginations of
British homeowners. We replied, soothingly, by letter, and then
sent them a copy of the letter our surveyor sent us, and then they
sent us a letter. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps their conversational reserve had to do with latent
anti-Americanism, I thought. But that couldn't be all of it,
because my husband is as English as they come (although, alas,
without a title). The truth, as I found when I began to make
