<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; var-z
u s BC-FBN-PUNISHMENTS-REVIE     11-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PUNISHMENTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NFL SLASHES NONCONFORMITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(jt) 
 By ALLEN ST. JOHN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quiz time: Which of these football infractions carries with it
the biggest penalty: a) a defensive lineman driving his helmet into
a quarterback's chin, resulting in a concussion, b) a special-teams
player blocking low and blowing out an opponent's knee, sidelining
him for the rest of the season, or c) a wide receiver making a
throat-slashing gesture after he scores a touchdown?
</P>
<P>
   Give up? It's a trick question. In the National Football
League's standard of justice, these offenses all merit equal
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the NFL informed its teams that the new vogue in
celebration after scoring _ players have begun drawing a finger
across their throats, ``Sleepy Hollow'' style _ would henceforth be
flagged with a 15-yard unsportsmanlike conduct penalty and the
possibility of a fine. In a memo, George Young, a league vice
president, said the gesture ``appears to depict an unacceptable act
of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue had simmered early in the season, amid whispers that
the gesture was gang related. But it reached critical mass shortly
after the New York Jets wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson did it this
month on Monday Night Football, and a Boston radio station dubbed
it the ``O.J.''
</P>
<P>
   In a league in which actual violence, from concussions to
fractures, is an integral part of the game, the NFL's sensitivity
on this subject strikes some observers as curious. ``I personally
think it's an overreaction on the part of the league,'' says
Michael Lev, senior editor at Pro Football Weekly. ``The NFL should
have greater concerns than how players celebrate a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging violence with such bans is one thing, but the NFL's
style police have a long history of clamping down on
extracurricular matters. In 1997, pro football's powers-that-be
passed the so-called Emmitt Smith rule, which imposed that same
15-yard penalty for removing a helmet on the field _ effectively
eliminating the face-in-the-camera TD celebration originated by the
Dallas Cowboys' star running back. In seasons past the league
banned ``sack dances'' after the quarterback is tackled, and
``excessive celebration,'' which put the kibosh on choreographed
end-zone rituals like the Ickey Shuffle, named for the Cincinnati
Bengals running back Ickey Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The league's rule book also includes a lengthy section
addressing uniform issues, covering everything from the kind of
towel a quarterback can use, to how a player must wear his socks.
Last season, Minnesota's John Randle was fined a total of $15,000
for wearing too much eye black on two separate occasions, while
last year San Diego cornerback Rodney Harrison was fined $7,500 for
leaving his knees uncovered during a game. (By comparison, Denver's
Bill Romanowski was fined the same amount for spitting on J.J.
Stokes of the 49ers.)
</P>
<P>
   What's the NFL's hidden agenda in keeping its players on such a
tight leash? ome have discerned a racial thread, noting that the
majority of the running backs and receivers who score touchdowns,
and thus are affected by the no-celebration rules, are black.
Others see the issue in economic terms. ``They have a product to
promote and want to market it in an attractive way,'' says Andrew
Zimbalist, an expert on sports economics at Smith College. ``Some
fans think it's obnoxious _ and there might be some racism in that
_ but the NFL doesn't want to turn white fans off.''
</P>
<P>
   In a league in which careers are short, the team salary limit
forces players to move from team to team and only the biggest stars
have guaranteed contracts, the NFL finds it is better for business
to build allegiance to the uniform rather than to individual
players. ``They want players to look the same, to act the same and
be robotic,'' says Lev. Is it any wonder that Tampa Bay's Warren
Sapp calls it the No Fun League?
</P>
<P>
   So as the league's skill position players wonder what they  &UR; can &LR; 
do in the end zone, they might try thinking like an NFL owner.
Perhaps the next time Keyshawn Johnson crosses the goal line he'll
spike the ball, smile through his face mask and trace a dollar sign
on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
