<HEADLINE>
CARROLL HAS ALREADY WON A SEASON PASS FROM KRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Carroll's safe. For now.
</P>
<P>
   There's been a buzz going around the NFL the past week that if
the Patriots lose Sunday in Buffalo, Carroll would be whacked by
owner Bob Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Why Buffalo, I couldn't even guess. But it's out there because
in the past week, two coaches with other teams called your humble
servant to see if there was any validity to the rumor. The answer
is no. Kraft has told friends, when asked, that nothing would ever
happen during the season. That's not his style, and, as every year,
the entire organization will be evaluated when the year is over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russell Robbat, owner of The Palace nightclub in Saugus, Mass.,
on what happened with a group of Patriots Wednesday night:
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Patriot players got into a shouting match. It got loud.
They were trash-talking each other. Before anything could happen,
the other players stepped in. There were no punches thrown. Just a
lot of talk,'' Robbat said. ``I had four of my own security people
on the scene and they asked me what to do. I told them to stay out
of it. I didn't want my guys in the middle of 10 football players.
The two guys who were arguing were buddies again by the end of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Willie McGinest. He put on a class act for
charity up here, and the big story is two guys arguing rather than
McGinest raising $30,000 for charity.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there were others who claimed to be present who dispute
this account, saying there was a fight over money wagered on a pool
game between Vincent Brisby and Lawyer Milloy; that the players
drank heavily; and that one had to be carried out bodily. There
were reports that Terry Glenn was stopped by Walpole police and
issued a ticket at 4 a.m. and was two hours late for practice
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little Did He Know Department: Twenty-four years ago Ed Germano
watched as the fans tore up the field at Fenway Park after the
final out of the seventh game of the World Series with Cincinnati.
When Germano, who was working on the grounds crew, reported to work
the next day, boss Joe Mooney told him to dig up home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field was all torn apart with people taking home patches
of grass. They tried to dig up home plate, but couldn't do it,''
said Germano. ``I got it up with pick ax and asked Joe what to do
with it. He said: `Do anything you want with it.' So I kept it. Had
it in my backyard all these years. All of my kids used it to play
ball in my backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Ed's brother, Michael, a Boston attorney, had an idea:
``Last summer, around All-Star Game time, someone paid over
$100,000 for the ball Carlton Fisk hit for the home run to win Game
6,'' said Michael. ``Then I thought about Ed's home plate. It was
from that same World Series so I thought it had to be worth
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germano family will soon find out how much. The home plate
will be auctioned off next week as part of Lelands' national
``Immortals Auction.''
</P>
<P>
   The home plate is item No. 777, and bidding starts at $3,000.
The family will use the money for college tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' attendance has been off 2,000 fans per game,
compared to last season. At an average price of $50 per ticket,
that's $100,000 per game, which, for 40 home games, would be a $4
million drop in revenue if the trend continues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has to coach wearing a brace on his leg and walking with the
use of a cane. But Mike Westhoff, the Miami Dolphins special teams
coach, is thrilled to be able to coach at all, and says he owes it
all to a Boston doctor, Dr. Henry Mankin of Massachusetts General
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't thank Dr. Mankin enough for what he has done for me,''
said Westhoff. ``This man is a real hero in my book. He has done so
much good, for so many people, it is just incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   As Westhoff tells it, 12 years ago he was coaching on Don
Shula's staff, when his trouble started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jogged a lot and my back started to bother me. They thought
it was sciatic nerve,'' he said. ``I had an operation on my back
(in a Florida hospital) and it went bad. I nearly died on the
table. Luckily, I lived. I continued to have problems. I was
diagnosed as having a malignant tumor on my leg. I went to the
Dana-Farber Institute in Boston. I was told the best work was being
done there, and I had two sisters who lived in the Boston area.
They confirmed the bone tumor. I asked the doctor there: `If you
had to pick a doctor to do this operation, who would it be?' He
said Henry Mankin at Mass. General. That's how we got together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mankin saved Westhoff's leg by removing the piece of bone that
housed the tumor, and replaced it with bone from a cadaver. The
surgery required Mankin to screw all of the parts together.
Westhoff returned to coaching, and what he considered a normal
life. Then Feb. 1, not knowing it at the time, more trouble was
brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell down a ramp, working on my boat,'' he said. ``(Doctors)
thought later I must have had a hairline fracture of the leg, right
near where some of the screws were. A few weeks later, I was
walking through the Houston airport and my leg just snapped. I was
in terrible pain, worst I ever felt, just laying there on the
floor. They rushed me to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. (Wayne) Huizenga (owner of the Dolphins) rushed his
private plane and they flew me right away to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Mankin weaved his magic. He put the leg back
together, and gave Westhoff great news: no sign of any cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, he's asked me to call others who have had
similar problems. And I've been glad to do it,'' he said. ``When we
play up in the New England area, I have some of these people come
to the game as my guest. I enjoy meeting them. I feel like I'm
giving back because I've been so lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking the sideline in the NFL can be dangerous. A lot of
coaches get taken down on plays out of bounds. ``I stay behind the
bench, until it's my time. Fourth down. Kickoff. Punts. All the
situations for special teams. I tell them what to do, and then make
sure I stay out of the line of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a scouting report on Sunday's Patriots-Bills game in
Buffalo from a coach who has played against both of them in the
last month:
</P>
<P>
   ``The matchup of the game is Buffalo trying to run the ball at
the middle of the Patriots' defense,'' he said. ``When they run the
ball effectively inside, they make (Buffalo quarterback Doug)
Flutie a much better quarterback. When he has to pass 40 times,
they lose. Their big back (Antowain) Smith has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, the Patriots have to give (quarterback Drew)
Bledsoe some time to throw. If he gets it, he can hurt the Bills'
secondary. Buffalo usually doesn't blitz a lot, but if they do,
after watching how much trouble New England has had picking it up,
the Patriots could be in for a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
