<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2593 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BIZ-SCHOOL-ART-1165(2     11-27 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SCHOOL-ART-1165(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBA BOOM FADES AS CANDIDATES SEEK INTERNET'S REWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., N.H., Mich., Ill., Pa., N.C., Minn., Wash.,
Iowa)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Hyatt was dutifully following a traditional path for a
future corporate executive. After college, he joined a consulting
firm, where he advised blue-chip companies like AT&AMP;T, General
Motors and IBM. He then applied to a few business schools, gained
admission to Stanford, the most selective of them all, and prepared
to enroll this fall.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, however, he took an eight-week job helping a
friend who worked at a small Internet company in Southern
California, and when it ended, Hyatt, 28, was hooked. So shortly
before he was to sit down to his first finance class, he called
Stanford to say thanks anyway: He wouldn't be showing up in Palo
Alto after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to do this now, before it's too late,'' Hyatt said of
working for an Internet start-up. ``If you wait two years, there's
going to be consolidation in the industry. Right now, you have a
chance to stake out your own claim.''
</P>
<P>
   As many of the United States' most talented young workers rush
to stake that claim, business school has suddenly lost some of its
luster. That has had a significant impact on applications to some
top schools, particularly those that tend to attract the
entrepreneurially minded.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, applications to Stanford, MIT, Dartmouth,
Michigan and the University of California at Berkeley, have dropped
as much as 11 percent. On other elite campuses, like Northwestern
and Carnegie Mellon, applications have leveled off. Some less
prestigious universities have seen steep declines.
</P>
<P>
   More students are also dropping out after the first year of the
two-year MBA program to remain with companies where they worked
over the summer. And driven in part by the generally strong
economy, the number of Americans taking the standardized admissions
test for business school has fallen sharply in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are a significant departure from the attitude toward
the MBA degree earlier in this long economic expansion. For the
past decade, until last spring, applications increased at every
elite school virtually every year, turning the MBA program into one
of the hottest areas of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, many potential students worry that two years is
too long to be studying marketing and operations, and, unlike those
aspiring to be lawyers or doctors, they do not need a degree to
practice their craft.
</P>
<P>
   Much as Bill Gates decided in 1976 that starting a software
company immediately was more important than graduating from Harvard
College, they are eager to get moving. Among the prizes they seek
are the stock options available to the first employees of a
start-up _ even if it means forgoing the six-figure salaries that
MBAs often command.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the eagerness is a broader anxiety shared by many
investors and executives that the current Internet bull market
could be at or very near its peak. That perception is encouraging
companies to go public at a record pace to take advantage of
current valuations, for example, and making stock prices gyrate.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in their 20s and 30s also question whether the ivory
tower is the place to learn about the emerging Internet world.
``There's an urgency that this is happening so fast that you've got
to be in it to really learn it,'' said George Daly, dean of New
York University's Stern School of Business. Applications to NYU
dropped slightly last spring after rising an average of 15 percent
in each of the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   To attract students and recruiters, schools are overhauling
curriculums to offer more Internet courses and even creating majors
devoted to the subject. Some schools have increased advertising
budgets and stepped up their own recruiting to compete with
companies trying to lure skilled workers in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time in their histories, schools are seeing
groups of students who leave after their first year, perhaps
abandoning the $25,000 or so investment many had made in a year of
tuition. Twenty-five of the 765 members of the MBA class of 2000 at
the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School, for example, did
not return this fall, and almost all now work for Internet
start-ups, a spokesman for the school said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, some schools are considering more liberal
leave-of-absence policies, while others, including Pennsylvania and
Northwestern, have dusted off little-used rules to allow students
to take up to five years off.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, said Donald Jacobs, Northwestern's dean for
the past 23 years, ``people are wringing their hands'' about the
departures. Jacobs said he had no problem with students taking time
off and he expected most of them to return eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are no statistics that offer a definitive reason
for the changes, many observers said the Internet was a major
factor. More broadly, a low unemployment rate and an almost
insatiable demand for highly skilled workers in corporate America
has left people who would normally be considering an MBA quite
happy in their current jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators also pointed to demographic factors, noting that
the number of people in their late 20s is shrinking slightly, and
added that the recent MBA boom and the resulting lowered acceptance
rates might be intimidating potential applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the number of Americans taking the standardized
business-school admission test has fallen 17 percent in the last
four years, according to the Graduate Management Admission Council,
which administers the test.
</P>
<P>
   That decline is exaggerated by the fact that the test, in its
new computerized format, is no longer offered on college campuses,
discouraging undergraduates from taking it. Still, top schools
typically consider only applicants with at least two years of work
experience, and the number of test-takers has dropped in almost
every age group since 1995, according to the council.
</P>
<P>
   Not every school has seen interest wane. Fueled by the
six-figure salaries that many graduates fetch and the continued
growth in the number of foreigners who want American business
degrees, applications to some schools are still rising.
</P>
<P>
   Applications to Harvard, for example, rose 5 percent last year,
and at Columbia, where one-third of the student body hails from
other countries, they increased by almost 10 percent. Duke and the
University of Chicago also saw increases.
</P>
<P>
   But at top schools renowned for attracting entrepreneurs and
technology experts _ like Stanford and Berkeley _ the number of
applications fell or was unchanged last spring. Many people who
traditionally apply to those schools now feel an urgent need to
work at an Internet start-up, said Sally Lannin, a former Stanford
administrator and currently the president of MBA Strategies, a
Minnesota-based consulting firm for business-school applicants.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Harvard, Columbia and Chicago _ while turning out
many entrepreneurs as well _ are among the schools that aspiring
investment bankers consider first.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Patty Benson, 26, is one of the nonapplicants. Like Hyatt, she
had been following the usual course for ambitious people who want
to work in corporate America. Ms. Benson majored in economics at
Colby College in Maine, landed a plum job at Bain &AMP; Co. as a
consultant, and started to think about business school. Then the
online explosion interrupted her thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these companies are growing very, very fast,'' Ms. Benson
said. ``I wanted to be in on it.''
</P>
<P>
   So she applied to Internet companies rather than business
schools and ended up moving to Seattle two months ago to work as an
assistant product manager in Amazon.com's books division. ``I love
it,'' she said. Just as she imagines a business school to be, she
added, ``It's filled with a lot of very smart, enthusiastic
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on campuses where applications have declined, school
administrators say their schools continue to thrive. The most
prestigious still admit only about one in eight candidates.
Graduates are snapped up by consulting firms and investment banks _
and, increasingly, Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened competition has forced some more traditional
companies to offer new perquisites, like leaves of absence, in
addition to starting salaries that sometimes reach $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market for MBAs is very exciting,'' Jacobs of Northwestern
said. ``As long as we don't become irrelevant to what's happening
in the marketplace, I think we're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   To stay relevant, schools are quickly creating new courses and
changing lesson plans in existing classes to include Internet
business. Earlier this month, Wharton announced that it was adding
an e-commerce major, effective immediately, with 50 faculty members
teaching courses.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Chicago this fall, two staff members had to
stand outside a 9 a.m. Saturday Internet course on the first few
days of class to prevent students not enrolled from sitting in on
the lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a decline in the number of applications can be a serious
matter for graduate schools, particularly in the MBA world, where
schools compete aggressively with one another. Such a drop can
force admissions officers to be less discriminating in selecting a
class. It also has the potential to lower a school's ranking in
U.S. News &AMP; World Report's influential annual survey and can
require a school to spend more money promoting itself.
</P>
<P>
   Some less elite schools, which are often unknown in other
countries, are faring the worst. At Tulane University,
business-school applications fell more than 40 percent over the
last two years, though the assistant dean for admissions, John
Silbernagel, said he thought the pool was still of similar quality.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Iowa's Henry B. Tippie School of
Management, where applications dropped by more than a quarter last
spring, the acceptance rate rose to 37 percent, from 28 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the school has tripled its advertising budget and
continued a recent push to send more unsolicited mail to people who
take the admissions test, said Mary Spreen, the school's director
of MBA admissions and financial aid. ``It has caused some
concern,'' Ms. Spreen said. ``When you have a larger applicant
pool, you're able to attract a higher-quality class.''
</P>
<P>
   But business school can be a tough sell in the current, frenzied
Internet environment. Many potential students hope to be among a
company's early employees, who typically receive a larger batch of
stock options at a lower price than employees who join later.
</P>
<P>
   When Hyatt left his consulting job, at Mercer Management
Consulting, for a summer stint at Winfire, which designs Internet
software, it had 10 employees. It now has 40. Had he attended
Stanford and joined after graduation, the company would have had
150 employees, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of venture capital even allows some Internet
start-ups to offer high salaries, in addition to options, noted
Hyatt, who said he was making over $100,000 as the director of
product management at Winfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I take my admissions hat off,'' said Marie Mookini, the
director of MBA admissions at Stanford, ``I understand why these
24- and 25-year-old people want to jump feet-first into this
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The changing attitude to the MBA is particularly striking in
Silicon Valley, a new center of U.S. business and yet a place where
business school has suddenly become less popular.
</P>
<P>
   Applications to Berkeley's program dropped by 11 percent last
spring. At Stanford _ where school employees came up with the idea
that led to the creation of Cisco Systems and whose graduates
include top Internet executives like Scott McNealy of Sun
Microsystems _ they fell 6 percent. These days, students worry that
their chances of emulating such titans will decrease if they wait
two years to start work.
</P>
<P>
   With the national unemployment rate at just above 4 percent,
many of the start-ups are also making a big push to keep employees
who have been at their jobs for two to seven years, traditionally a
period of high turnover, Jacques Leger, a human resources
consultant with Watson Wyatt in San Francisco, said. ``Now, with
two years of experience, you're considered a prime candidate with
lots of experience,'' Leger said.
</P>
<P>
   Students notice the difference. ``The opportunity cost of going
to school has gone up dramatically,'' said Cheryl Proctor, a
second-year MBA student at Berkeley and the managing editor of the
student newspaper, who watched some of her classmates quit this
summer while many others work part-time jobs during the school year
to maintain contacts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Proctor herself spent last summer at a small Internet
company in San Francisco that asked her to stay when her internship
ended. ``They made it really tempting,'' she said. But business
school, she added, ``seems like a safe bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many school administrators predict that applications will start
rising again everywhere as the Internet industry matures. One
possible sign of resurgent interest in MBA programs is already
being seen: a small rebound in recent months in the number of
Americans taking the admissions test.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a gold-rush mentality'' to the Internet, said Paul
Danos, dean of the Amos Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth. ``A
lot of potential students will make the wrong decision. Everybody
thinks they're all going to strike it rich, and it's just not going
to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
