<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GUNS-POLICE-HNS &LR;      11-27 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION GROWS TO POLICE AGENCIES' PRACTICE OF SELLING OLD
FIREARMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A growing number of police agencies are abandoning the
practice of selling old and confiscated guns to finance new
firearms after a gun used in a high-profile shooting last summer
was traced to a police department sale.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Bill Owens has recently ordered state troopers to
stop the practice, Illinois Gov. George Ryan is looking for a way
out of a pending weapons trade with a Georgia gun manufacturer, and
police departments around the country are being scrutinized for
their gun deals.
</P>
<P>
   Selling old weapons has long been a common, if little known,
practice for many police departments, particularly those in cities
operating under tight budgets. Departments are frequently able to
reduce the purchase price of large weapon orders by several hundred
thousand dollars through such trade-ins of officers' aging weapons
as well as guns seized from criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Police Department came under criticism last
February when it was revealed that the first city to file a product
liability lawsuit against gun manufacturers also had a contract
pending with gun manufacturer Glock Inc. to trade in 10,000 old
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But an August shooting at a Los Angeles Jewish community center,
where two adults and three children were wounded and a postal
worker was killed, brought such deals under closer scrutiny. A 9 mm
pistol used by confessed shooter Buford Furrow was traced to the
police department in Cosmopolis, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon had been sold to a local gun shop and was not part of
a larger weapons trade, but the incident raised similar questions
among critics. The pistol changed hands several times before it
eventually was sold on consignment at a gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Owens began questioning the gun resale practices of
Colorado troopers after the Los Angeles shooting, and he banned
state police gun sales in September.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said the shootings in Los Angeles and at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., had raised questions about the
accessibility of weapons, including old police guns. He said he
decided that the state of Colorado should not participate in the
weapons ``aftermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Illinois Gov. Ryan is looking for a way to purchase
2,500 guns from Glock Inc. without the trade-in of old guns agreed
to by contract in April. The gun sale would cost the Illinois State
Police slightly less than $300,000 with trade-ins but as much as
$800,000 at full price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hugely sensitive to this whole issue,'' said state
police spokesman Lt. Dave Sanders. There were questions raised
about the trade-in provision at the time the contract was
negotiated, he said, but added, ``It didn't become a huge national
concern until the shooting in Los Angeles in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Glock Vice President Paul Jannuzzo said his company does not
care whether Illinois trades weapons or not, as long as they make
up the full price of the deal in cash. ``If we continue to sell to
(police) departments, it will be more profitable to simply do a
straight deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what it is they're saying,'' Jannuzzo said. ``I
just can't agree with the logic of it. If a criminal wants a
firearm, whether a police department has sold theirs or not is not
going to make that firearm any more available or any less available
to the criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real number of firearms that have been obtained by
criminals in this manner is miniscule,'' Jannuzzo said. ``But they
certainly get more press.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Police Department requires officers to purchase
their own weapons and therefore does not negotiate the kind of
large gun purchases where trade-ins might be used, HPD spokesman
Fred King said. By policy, confiscated handguns are melted down
except for a handful used in training.
</P>
<P>
   The city of St. Louis was recently negotiating a large weapons
purchase with a trade-in component when the president of the board
of police commissioners stopped the deal. An old police weapon
traced to a Washington, D.C., homicide influenced his decision,
police spokeswoman Adella Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course (the trade-ins are) attractive, anything that can cut
your costs,'' Jones said. ``But it (would be) far more costly to
have one of your (old) weapons used in the commission of a crime.
So we just have to use some other way. It's a balancing act.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Police Chief Charles Ramsey vowed earlier this month
to end his department's practice of selling old weapons after The
Washington Post linked police weapons sold over the past decade to
the commission of 107 crimes, including eight homicides.
</P>
<P>
   The International Association of Chiefs of Police adopted a
nonbinding resolution a year ago calling for the mandatory
destruction of police departments' obsolete and confiscated
weapons. A spokesman for the Coalition to Stop Gun Violence said
his organization is interested in pursuing federal legislation to
prevent police agencies from selling or trading obsolete or
confiscated weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. Rep. Rod Blagojevich, D-Ill., has introduced a
bill that would give state and local police agencies access to a
$15 million grant program for police weapons purchases as long as
they agree not to sell their cache of old weapons. The bill is not
expected to be considered until some time next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
