<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING USED TO LOSING  
 A BETTER SHOOT-AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-NOTEBOOK-KINGS) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Either the Houston Rockets have incredible perspective or
they're truly in denial. After dropping to 3-11 on Friday night
after an overtime loss to Portland, their locker room at the Rose
Garden bordered on jovial.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, having missed 8 of 11 shots in his first
meeting with Scottie Pippen (whom Barkley engaged in a verbal
barrage during the off-season) joked with coach Rudy Tomjanovich
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley playfully inquired why Matt Bullard, and not he, took a
potential game-tying 3-pointer in overtime. ``Coach, let me tell
you something, I need that last 3,'' Barkley said. ``Bull? Bull
can't shoot like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the corner of a Rose Garden locker room was Hakeem
Olajuwon, who had pulled his groin early in the game and was
expected to miss the remaining three games of the team's road trip.
He bristled at the notion that his once-proud team had learned to
accept losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you get used to that?'' he said. ``We can't get used
to that. It's not lack of effort. This team goes out every night.
We play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, who has resurrected teams from the grave before,
said: ``I'm not used to something like this. We've been known for
our quick starts. November has been our month. I guess I'm getting
paid back for all that success we've had in the past. You've got to
be humble when you're doing well and you can't get yourself down
too low when things aren't going well. That's life.''
</P>
<P>
   A Better Shoot-Around
</P>
<P>
   Shoot-around practices the morning of a game are one of those
monotonous, required routines players look forward to about as much
as income tax returns and lower back pain. But Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy seems to have found a cure.
</P>
<P>
   During last season's truncated 50-game campaign, Portland began
holding its walk-through one-hour practice three hours before the
game. Dunleavy found that it not only gave players most of the day
to take care of personal business, but it also gave his team a
little edge heading into that evening's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes sense,'' said Brian Grant. ``When you wake up in
the morning, drive to the arena, come home and then go back, it
just seems like your whole day is gone. The concentration level
before a game is much higher, I think. It's little things like that
that make you appreciate playing for this franchise.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CONFESSION-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      11-27 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFESSION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONFESSION 3 YEARS AFTER A LIFE IS TAKEN IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARVEY RICE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONROE, Texas _ Henry Ella Nylander had prayed fervently since
her son was shot to death outside her residence three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been praying for all those years, those three years that
passed, that whoever did it would come over and just say, `I did
it,' and I would not be angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Her prayer was answered with an early morning confession. On
Friday, an acquaintance of her son's was in jail charged with
murder.
</P>
<P>
   And Henry Ella Nylander is not angry.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Alexander Moore, 25, a son by a previous marriage, was
found dead outside her Conroe residence Dec. 23, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Conroe, a city of 40,000, is about 35 miles north of downtown
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A single bullet in his chest claimed his life a month before he
was to return to classes at Texas Southern University in an attempt
to pull his life together. He was, his mother said, finding
direction after a failed marriage and a stint in the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my son was killed, it was something that hurt a lot, but
at the same time, I was not angry,'' said Nylander.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that she wished no harm to come to her son's
killer, ``because the Lord said vengeance was his and he would
repay.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the 51-year-old beautician longed to know who killed
her son and why.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came about 6 a.m. one morning last week when her
doorbell rang.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering who it could be at such an early hour, she said she
felt some force pushing her toward the door. ``It seemed like it
was just for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Regis Stewart, 24, stood outside. Nylander and her husband,
Baldwin, 53, a utility operator, had known Stewart for 10 years. He
had been a childhood friend of the youngest of her four surviving
sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Paul, Mrs. Nylander,'' he said through the door. ``I've
got to tell you something.''
</P>
<P>
   As was her custom, Nylander asked him to come around to the
kitchen window because the front door was difficult to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I killed your son Mike,'' Stewart told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you say?'' she remembers asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I killed your son.'''
</P>
<P>
   She let Stewart in and led him into the den, then roused her
husband, who joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart fell down on his knees and clasped Nylander's feet with
his arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just began to cry and cry, and it was like he was bowing
down before us and having so much pain over what had happened,''
Nylander recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just saying, `I'm sorry, I'm sorry,' over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Would you please forgive me?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I forgave you after it happened and I didn't know who
it was.'''
</P>
<P>
   She turned to her husband and asked him to forgive Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Yeah, I forgive him,' and that was hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin Nylander said his question, after the shock, was, ``Did
you kill before?
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't answer me. I said, `Well, I forgive you,' and he
started crying and my wife started crying.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's forgiveness, however, doesn't mean Stewart won't
face justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked, `What do you want to do?' And he said, `I'll do
anything you want me to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nylander told Stewart to surrender to the police and clear
others who were suspects, and he agreed.
</P>
<P>
   It was then, she said, that he told them why he had killed their
son.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart told them that about two weeks before the slaying, he
and Moore had quarreled at a party because Moore had disparaged
Stewart in front of his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   When someone burglarized Stewart's residence shortly thereafter,
Stewart blamed Moore.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Nylanders that one night, by chance, he saw their
son enter a convenience store next to the Nylanders' residence on
South First Street in Conroe.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, according to the Nylanders, told them he hid in the
Nylanders' yard, then stepped out and shot Moore as he returned
from the store. The bullet struck him in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Friends who had been visiting heard the shot and rushed outside
to find the body.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three years later, Stewart told the Nylanders that he had
to seek their forgiveness. He talked of seeing visions of their son
on every street corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what he said, it was just eating away at him,'' the
victim's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   After his confession, the Nylanders sat and drank coffee for
about two hours with Stewart. Then he left, promising to surrender
to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Nylander said, she saw a dazed-looking Stewart
crossing the street in front of her home about 10 a.m. She sent a
friend to fetch him and phoned the police.
</P>
<P>
   She said a man who identified himself as Stewart's grandfather
arrived at the Nylanders' home shortly after the police arrived.
The grandfather, whose name Nylander did not know, was searching
for Stewart because he had been acting strangely, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His grandfather said, `Paul, what have you done?' and he said,
`I killed Mike.'''
</P>
<P>
   Conroe police read Stewart his rights and arrested him. He was
in the Montgomery County Jail on Friday awaiting arraignment on a
murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   Nylander said that although Stewart seemed to know what he was
doing the first time he came to her house, he was different at his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He was incoherent, babbling about UFOs and about being the
subject of discussion on television programs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said he struggled when police tried to handcuff him, but was
subdued. Police officials familiar with the arrest could not be
reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nylander said she hopes that Stewart will be rehabilitated and
get a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my way, he would get psychological help and not just
be pinned in,'' she said. ``There has to be a reason for people to
turn to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   She does not believe families of victims should seek vengeance.
``Sometimes you can be caught up and be so angry until you miss out
on the blessing from God of peace. And you miss out on helping
these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
