<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-KINGS-NY     11-27 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBBER FINDS NICHE IN KINGS' STARRING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-NOTEBOOK) 
(jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence Funderburke remembers a conversation between him and
Chris Webber in May 1998, days after Webber was dealt to Sacramento
from Washington. Funderburke, one of only several players still on
the Kings' roster from two seasons ago, recalled trying to assuage
Webber's worst fears about playing for a perennial lottery team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of blew me off,'' Funderburke said of their talk.
``And we were really good friends. So I'm like, `Chris, come on.' I
knew he was upset by the trade. I just didn't know how long he
would take to get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Webber plays on a team with the best record in the NBA.
He is laughing as he takes those big, loping strides up the court,
shaking his head as teammates affectionately rub his clean-shaven
pate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night against the Nets at Arco Arena, he became the
first player this season to record double figures in points,
rebounds and assists. This was not your grandfather's
triple-double. Webber dunked maliciously five times, scored 26
points, hauled down 22 rebounds and distributed 10 assists; three
were breathtaking, behind-the-back passes in traffic, passes that
materialized in the hands of cutting teammates for layups and
dunks.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, as Webber gathered his belongings in the locker room
and the Kings had surpassed the 1952-53 Rochester Royals for the
best start in franchise history, Funderburke saw the difference in
a team and a onetime disgruntled teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Sacramento being a blip on the map, a cow town
where no one wanted to play,'' he said. ``Now Chris loves it. He
wants to be here. If you would have asked him that before he came,
he would have said: `Impossible. I don't want to have anything to
do with this place.'
</P>
<P>
   If the transformation of the Kings has been stunning, so too has
the transformation of Webber. The former malcontent who claimed he
would not remain in Sacramento has already intimated that he plans
to sign a contract extension with the club after the millennium. It
has been a long wait, but Webber has found the camaraderie and
contentment he has longed for since his Fab Five days at Michigan
and his formative days at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the Warriors host the 2000 All-Star Game in
February. Asked if a first-ever selection would bring his career
full circle, he said: ``No, because I should have been on the
All-Star team two other years. So no, I don't think by far I'm
playing much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have to redeem any season of me playing. If
anything, people want me to redeem something off the court or
something they heard about. But, play? That's something I'll never
have to redeem or will redeem. Because I give it my all every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber was traded from Golden State before the 1994-95 season
after feuding with coach Don Nelson. He played on a promising
Washington team that self-destructed in 1998. Soon, Webber received
more attention for problems off the court.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Webber was fined $500 for carrying a small
amount of marijuana that was detected by dogs at an airport in San
Juan, P.R. Last December, he was acquitted by a Prince George's
County jury in Maryland on charges of possession of marijuana,
driving under the influence of the drug, resisting arrest and
second-degree assault. He was found guilty of two traffic
violations and a misdemeanor charge during a traffic stop that
could have led to a jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Like another Warrior traded to the East Coast, he was vilified
in the Bay Area after the deal. But unlike Latrell Sprewell, Webber
harbors no resentment toward his first team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a love-hate relationship anymore with me and Golden
State,'' Webber said. ``The coach is not there anymore. There's not
one player there from the era when I was there. They've even
reconstructed the whole gym. It seems like I get love there. I'm
going to get my boos, but I get love there.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber added: ``Don't get me wrong. I would love to be an
All-Star. But I know that sometimes you can play that way and not
be one. So my concentration is on playing and making us win. It's
the first time I've been in a winning position like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning or losing, most players on NBA teams develop bonds
over time. Yet Webber's relationships with his teammates in
Sacramento have been noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to attend the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield rematch
with Jason Williams and a few other teammates earlier this month.
Vlade Divac was in charge of transportation, Webber procured the
tickets and, just like that, the Kings were hanging out in Las
Vegas amid the glitter and gaudiness. During a preseason game in
Detroit, the entire team went out for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it is,'' Webber said. ``If there were more children
on this team, some guys would be baby-sitting them and watching
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago against Houston, Webber was having a miserable
game. But the Kings' bench caught fire and essentially won the
game. Near the end, the starters stood and waved towels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when I play bad, I don't say anything,'' Webber said.
``I'm in my head, fighting myself. This team, it was like our bench
was doing so well and we just went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Funderburke said: ``I look at San Antonio; all the guys on the
team liked each other. From the standpoint of being selfish,
bickering and complaining, there was none of that. We had great
camaraderie last year.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times when you wondered if Webber would ever get it,
understand his potential as a player and realize he could be part
of the solution to his team's problems. Those days appear to be
gone, disappearing faster than Sacramento's lottery picks.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Used to Losing
</P>
<P>
   Either the Houston Rockets have incredible perspective or
they're truly in denial. After dropping to 3-11 on Friday night
after an overtime loss to Portland, their locker room at the Rose
Garden bordered on jovial.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, having missed 8 of 11 shots in his first
meeting with Scottie Pippen (whom Barkley engaged in a verbal
barrage during the off-season) joked with coach Rudy Tomjanovich
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley playfully inquired why Matt Bullard, and not he, took a
potential game-tying 3-pointer in overtime. ``Coach, let me tell
you something, I need that last 3,'' Barkley said. ``Bull? Bull
can't shoot like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the corner of a Rose Garden locker room was Hakeem
Olajuwon, who had pulled his groin early in the game and was
expected to miss the remaining three games of the team's road trip.
He bristled at the notion that his once-proud team had learned to
accept losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you get used to that?'' he said. ``We can't get used
to that. It's not lack of effort. This team goes out every night.
We play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, who has resurrected teams from the grave before,
said: ``I'm not used to something like this. We've been known for
our quick starts. November has been our month. I guess I'm getting
paid back for all that success we've had in the past. You've got to
be humble when you're doing well and you can't get yourself down
too low when things aren't going well. That's life.''
</P>
<P>
   A Better Shoot-Around
</P>
<P>
   Shoot-around practices the morning of a game are one of those
monotonous, required routines players look forward to about as much
as income tax returns and lower back pain. But Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy seems to have found a cure.
</P>
<P>
   During last season's truncated 50-game campaign, Portland began
holding its walk-through one-hour practice three hours before the
game. Dunleavy found that it not only gave players most of the day
to take care of personal business, but it also gave his team a
little edge heading into that evening's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes sense,'' said Brian Grant. ``When you wake up in
the morning, drive to the arena, come home and then go back, it
just seems like your whole day is gone. The concentration level
before a game is much higher, I think. It's little things like that
that make you appreciate playing for this franchise.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
