<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTREDAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOHERTY DELIVERS AN EMOTIONAL RESCUE TO NOTRE DAME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.C., Md. ,  Ariz., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the official blew his whistle for a decision against Notre
Dame, Matt Doherty sprang up in front of the bench and became
airborne with impressive hang time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the highest I've gotten up since my freshman year in
college,'' said Doherty, who played at North Carolina in the 1980s
and is the first-year head coach of the Fighting Irish.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Doherty's shoes landed loudly on the wooden floor at
Madison Square Garden, he seemed to regret his reaction.
Demonstrations such as these, even from veteran coaches, often draw
technical fouls. When Doherty touched down, he immediately turned
away from the referee, who stared at him and walked toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quick, emotional outburst; I got carried away,''
Doherty said. ``So I turned my back. I didn't want him to think I
was being a jerk. I'm not trying to show up the referee.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensing Doherty's state of mind, the official calmly
lectured him as Doherty took his chair, nodding and bowing his head
without speaking. There was no behavioral harm, so no technical
foul. It didn't matter immediately, as Notre Dame lost 72-67 to
Maryland in the consolation game of the preseason National
Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before, in the semifinals, the Irish lost 76-60 to
Arizona, which defeated Kentucky, 63-51, in the championship game
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Doherty's demonstration illustrated the temperament of the
young coach, who is trying to restore the program to NCAA
tournament status after a nine-year absence. Even Dick Vitale,
ESPN's hyper host of hoop hyperbole, said last week that Doherty
was a rather intense fellow.
</P>
<P>
   And Doherty's style may be working. In both defeats in New York,
the Irish played with spirit and a refusal to concede. Their record
is 3-2, compared with 1-4 after five games last season under John
MacLeod. The best player on the team, the sophomore forward Troy
Murphy, is playing impressively and voicing strong opinions about
the program's new direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't give up,'' Murphy said. ``Coach Doherty has
really instilled a lot of toughness that wasn't there. We just
keeping going and we play hard. He really gets us fired up. We
compete. Last year we were losing to smaller teams and now we're
competing with some of the top teams in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As Murphy spoke, his coach joined him at the news conference
table and hugged Murphy's shoulder. Doherty did the same thing
after the previous game. Perhaps these gestures suggested his inner
emotions during a difficult week for his first major road trip.
Minutes before the team left the South Bend, Ind., airport, the
coach's 2-year-old son, Tucker, broke a bone in his leg when he
fell near the departure gate.
</P>
<P>
   The accident kept Doherty at home an extra night and forced his
players to reschedule a Tuesday afternoon practice for Tuesday
night, on the eve of the semifinal. Doherty apologized Friday night
for overworking them and tiring them before facing Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   As for his son, Doherty said: ``He's doing OK &UR; . &LR;  He's in a full
body cast. A kid doesn't understand why he's confined. He can't sit
up. He can't crawl. He can't walk. He can't do anything. The first
time I called, he screamed. The second time I called, he said `Hi,
Daddy.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, 37, is a native of East Meadow on Long Island, and he
played in high school at Holy Trinity in Hicksville before playing
with Michael Jordan at North Carolina under Dean Smith. Before
beginning his coaching career as an assistant, first at Davidson
and then at Kansas, Doherty worked for more than three years as a
bond salesman for Kidder Peabody &AMP; Co. in New York during the
``Bonfire of the Vanities'' era.
</P>
<P>
   In his biography in the school's media guide, Doherty recalled
sleeping with a basketball as a child and getting his first jock
strap before going to his first basketball camp at St. Anthony's
High School in Smithtown. He recalled what it was like to grow up
Irish Catholic in the New York area and how he enjoyed the Knicks
in their championship era.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a Long Islander, he attended Nets games, before they
moved from Nassau County to New Jersey, and he cheered for Julius
Erving, before he moved from Uniondale to Philadelphia. Doherty's
favorite player was Rick Barry, a Long Islander known for a
successful but strident style, a perfectionist mentality and a
penetrating voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to shoot like Dr. J and act like Rick Barry,'' Doherty
said.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday night's game, when another whistle stopped play,
Doherty clenched his fist and shook it and shouted to one of his
players: ``What defense were we in?'' When he got an answer,
Doherty shouted his response. ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   He has wiry silver hair, thick dark eyebrows and the lanky look
of so many college coaches. He said repeatedly last week that he
wanted his players to ``hurt'' when they lost. And he said his team
belonged among the elite of college basketball and expected to get
there soon and that he loved the kids on his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the kind of kids you want to date your daughter,''
Doherty said. ``But, on the court, I want them to be jerks. I want
them to be cocky, arrogant, confident, tough suckers who are going
to battle on the court. Off the court, we can wear our shirts and
ties and be nice kids and go to church.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
