<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-UNIONISTS-57     11-27 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-UNIONISTS-570(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER UNIONISTS OPEN WAY FOR RULING WITH SINN FEIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Opening the way for a new
power-sharing arrangement in Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionist
Party on Saturday approved its leaders entering government with its
sworn rivals from Sinn Fein, the political ally of the Irish
Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark vote sets off a series of steps by the British and
Irish governments to transfer power from London to Belfast within
days, and marked the successful crowning of months of patient
mediation by George Mitchell to salvage the April 1998 peace
settlement for the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clears the stalemate,'' David Trimble, the party leader,
said after the vote, referring to the deadlock over IRA disarmament
that had halted all progress on the peace settlement, and had
deepened concern over Ulster's capacity to rise above its violent
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done our bit,'' he said, adding that the next move was
up to Gerry Adams, president of the overwhelmingly Catholic Sinn
Fein party. ``Now Mr. Adams, it's over to you. We've jumped. You
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact voted on Saturday, the IRA must appoint a
representative on Thursday to the independent commission on
disarmament headed by the retired Canadian general John de
Chastelain, and the actual destruction of weapons must begin by
Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said the vote also endorsed a decision to reconvene the
party council in February to ensure that the promised steps had
been taken.
</P>
<P>
   The clear implication was that if there had been no dismantling
of the IRA arsenal by then, the Ulster Unionists, the province's
largest Protestant party, would use the power it has to dismantle
the new government.
</P>
<P>
   It was another defining moment for the Northern Ireland peace
settlement, a complex effort to wring a lasting peace out of the
polarized political climate of Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, this effort _ designed to end 30 years
of sectarian strife by parceling out authority between the
province's Protestant majority and its Roman Catholic minority _
has had to survive a cliff-hanging series of referendums,
legislative elections and 11th-hour deals.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize winner who had staked his
leadership of the party on Saturday's balloting, emerged with the
backing of 58 percent of delegates _ 480 in favor to 349 against _
enough to ensure the establishment of home rule government in
Belfast next week but not enough to avoid leaving his party deeply
divided. He had hoped for at least 60 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   The steps that bring home rule government to Belfast begin
Monday with the naming of the members of the assembly executive,
which effectively becomes Northern Ireland's cabinet. Under the
power-sharing formula, Trimble will be first minister and Seamus
Mallon of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, the largest
Catholic group, will be his deputy. The 10 other cabinet seats are
apportioned with three to the Ulster Unionists, three to the Social
Democratic Labor Party and two each to Sinn Fein and the Democratic
Unionists of the Rev. Ian Paisley.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the House of Commons in London takes up the bill to
transfer power to Belfast, and, by prearrangement, passes it on
Wednesday. On Thursday, the assembly is to hold its first session
as a fully empowered legislature with the Sinn Fein members Martin
McGuiness and Bairbre de Brun as ministers in the new Northern
Ireland government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the Ulster Unionists, the most powerful voice of Protestant
politics in Northern Ireland, Saturday's vote was a significant
step away from a history of stubborn refusal to participate in
arrangements designed to share power with Catholics. Unionists have
often been caricatured as a clan of obdurate naysayers, and Paul
Bew, professor of politics at Queen's University, said he hoped
their willingness to risk cooperating with their republican
opponents would now ``destroy the crude stereotyping of an entire
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Unionists wish to see Ulster remain part of Britain while
republicans, most of whom are Catholic, want the province to move
toward eventual incorporation into the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three decades, paramilitary groups have risen up
on both sides of the argument, installing in this corner of
Northern Europe a brutish culture of vengeance that has cost the
lives of more than 3,300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Unionism is a political movement with zealous followers that
dates from the days of Protestant domination of power in the North
but has had to adapt to the rise in Catholic influence and the
change in republican tactics from organized violence to political
maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   This shift was shown by the fact that the two men most
responsible for the party's swing toward an approval vote in the
past 10 days of intense lobbying _ Trimble and his deputy, John
Taylor _ were both key players in the wrecking by Protestant forces
of the last attempt at power-sharing government, a short-lived
Stormont administration 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble faced strong opposition to going forward with
participation in the power-sharing government because the decision
represented the abandoning of principle by a party that takes its
principles with almost religious seriousness. Followers objected to
his having dropped the pledge _ known in constantly repeated party
shorthand as ``no guns, no government'' _ that there would have to
be a start to IRA disarmament before members of Sinn Fein could
take up their government seats.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate put a complete brake on progress in July, when the
Ulster Unionists boycotted the session of the assembly at which the
nominations to the executive cabinet were to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments asked Mitchell, the former
U.S. senator who was chairman of the original talks, to return on a
rescue mission. That 11-week effort resulted in a deal, announced
10 days ago, that was put to the Ulster Unionists on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was eagerly anticipated. ``After so many years of
deadlock, the speed with which events are unfolding is
breathtaking,'' The Belfast Telegraph commented in an editorial. It
said that a vote supporting Trimble, which it favored, was ``in our
terms the equivalent of the fall of the Berlin Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Trimble's rival parties wished him success. Reflecting a
new political language of mutual accommodation that was an
achievement of the Mitchell review, Adams told a meeting of his
party in Dublin last week, ``I do not underestimate the
difficulties that have to be overcome in the time ahead, especially
for the Ulster Unionist Party and its leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble argued that in exchange for relaxing their demand for
immediate IRA weapons turnover, the unionists were gaining
self-rule, the right to keep Ulster British as long as its
residents wished it, the end to the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement that
gave Dublin joint authority with Britain in some of the North's
affairs, and the withdrawal of the clauses in the constitution of
the Irish Republic that make a territorial claim on Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   He also argued that by making their move first, the Ulster
Unionists, weary of being blamed for intransigence, were
transferring responsibility for the continuation of the new
government to the republican movement.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to shore up support for a yes vote was a tough one.
Campaigners reported the unsettling and poignant experience of
finding that individuals they were asking to take a chance on Sinn
Fein's word had had friends and family members killed in IRA
attacks in recent years. The paramilitary cease-fires began only
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble was opposed by major figures in the party, including six
of the 10 Ulster Unionists in the British Parliament, who accused
him of ``letting terrorists into government.'' In a comment typical
of the strong feelings of opponents, the Young Ulstermen of the
Upper Bann said the approval vote was ``akin to turkeys voting for
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Paisley, the chief opponent of the peace settlement, told a
meeting of his hard-line Democratic Unionist Party in a Belfast
suburb that Trimble would face a dogged opposition in the new
assembly from his party members and disaffected Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice trembling with fury, he said, ``It is an opposition,
Mr. Trimble, that you have betrayed with your lying and deceit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
