</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VIRGINIA TECH, 11-0 COMPUTES TO SUGAR BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ Frank Beamer is a muddy tennis shoes kind of
guy. His coaching cap is of the truck driver variety _ billed, with
logo, pulled down over his eyes. But the Virginia Tech coach didn't
waste much time on Friday trading in his school's hat for the 1999
Big East champion's crown.
</P>
<P>
   His Hokies had just walloped Boston College, 38-14, and he had
something to say. It was a quiet pronouncement, tossed off as
casually as he tugged the bill of the newly minted championship hat
down to the bridge of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mind if I put my hat on, do you?'' he asked,
searching a classroom in the team's field house as if it were the
coffee lounge off the John Deere showroom. ``I'll tell you what. If
I had a Sugar Bowl hat, I'd put that on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was spoken with the assurance of a man who has survived a
2-9, a 3-8 and a 2-8-1 season. Those stone-cold numbers illustrate
the depths of the experience Beamer lived through during the first
six years of trying to put his alma mater on the college football
map. That sort of data would have choked the Bowl Championship
Series computers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven years, however, Beamer's won-lost-tied ledger
looks as if it was reflected through a fun house mirror. Beamer is
64-19 in that span, now the architect of an 11-0 regular season and
the sideline stalking embodiment of The Serenity Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer can accept the things he cannot change _ even if it means
eight computer services might somehow conspire to leave the Hokies
out of the Sugar Bowl, this year's title match with top-ranked
Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done our talking on the field,'' Beamer said. ``It's
the only thing that has been in our power.''
</P>
<P>
   He has demonstrated the courage to change what the Hokies can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got it rolling now,'' Beamer said. ``This isn't the last
time this is going to happen. We're going to do this again.''
</P>
<P>
   He has obtained the wisdom to know the difference. Or at least
his players act as if they have. ``The best two teams are going to
play at the end of the year,'' linebacker Cory Bird said. ``We're
one of them. If not, we're going to represent the Big East in the
Orange Bowl, where there is still a chance to win a split national
title.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been the Hokies' mantra for the last six weeks and, it
has been backed up by fact as well as faith. Virginia Tech has the
nation's top scoring offense (41.7 points a game), the second-best
scoring defense (10.2 point average) and has outscored its ranked
opponents by 174-31.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer and Virginia Tech's belief can still be proved a heresy,
but it might take some otherworldly circumstances. In the latest
BCS ranking, six computer services have the Hokies ranked ahead of
the 10-1 Nebraska Cornhuskers. At least three, and probably as many
as five, have to flip-flop that assessment for Nebraska to overtake
Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely when one stacks up Friday's games, Virginia
Tech's 24-point victory over the 8-3 Eagles against the
Cornhuskers' 33-30 overtime victory over Colorado. Virginia Tech
presumably charmed, finally, the computers that reward margin of
victory while Nebraska took a deduction for struggling against the
Buffaloes (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   Beamer, 53, is rightly proud of how far he and his team have
come. In those lean years, Hokies boosters gave him credit for
being a Tech-man, but not much as a coach. In 1990, for example, he
refused a pay raise in a show of solidarity with other Virginia
Tech faculty members and staff whose salaries at the time were
frozen by the state. Since then, he and his wife, Cheryl, have
twice donated $50,000 to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Beamer will take his seventh consecutive Hokies team to
a bowl game, he has finally been noticed outside the state.
Officials at Georgia, South Carolina and Clemson approached him in
recent years about vacancies in their programs. His name already
had been mentioned for the Louisiana State job when Gerry DiNardo
was fired in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   If Nebraska thrashes Texas in next week's Big XXII Championship
Game and somehow bumps Virginia Tech from the national title game,
the Hokies remain in position to show up college football's
complicated mathematical formula. If they beat the winner of the
Southeastern Conference championship game _ either Florida or
Alabama _ in the Orange Bowl and Nebraska beats Florida State in
the Sugar, there is a possibility for a split championship. The
Cornhuskers and the Seminoles each would have one loss while the
Hokies would be 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches' poll has agreed to award its national championship
to the winner of the BCS title game, but voters from the news media
in the AP poll are likely to name the undefeated Hokies as the best
team in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Complicated? Not for the coach in the cap and the tennis shoes.
Before he sent his players off to study for final exams and to wait
another week for the final BCS poll numbers, Beamer pulled on the
bill of his Big East championship cap one more time. He asked the
simple question, ``Does anyone in this room think we don't deserve
to be in the Sugar Bowl?''
</P>
<P>
   When no one disagreed, he continued, ``There's something
terribly wrong if we don't get in.''
</P>
<P>
   But then a brighter thought overtook him. ``Like I said,'' he
promised of his burgeoning program. ``I don't think it's the last
time you'll see us in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
