<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GOOD-PHOTOS28-COX     11-27 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-PHOTOS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Less `cheese,' more flash
 &HT;    By Jeff Adams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You know the routine. It's Christmas Eve and Aunt
Maude gets all the family in front of the Christmas tree for the
annual ``Christmas photo.'' It's a familiar photo because it's been
taken each year since you were 4, everyone scrubbed within an inch
of their life, every hair in place, dressed in their best clothes.
Everything has to be just right. If you could manage to forget the
ceremony, you need only go as far as the family album in the
section called ``Christmas.'' There they are, all the Christmas
photos from years past. The same picture with the same people and
the same forced smiles. The only thing that changes is the height
of the kids and the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``Christmas photo'' in front of the tree is fine, then
read no more. If you long for better seasonal photos, then here are
some tips.
</P>
<P>
   _ Candid moments: Taking all of your holiday photos with each
subject staring into the camera makes for some boring images. Take
the group shot for Aunt Maude, but then try to capture the flavor
of the event through candid moments.
</P>
<P>
   A photo of cousin Billy surprised at his new fire truck is a far
better image than Billy staring into the camera with the truck
under his arm. Try to anticipate what will happen so you can be
ready with the camera to take an image. (No fair setting up the
moment again if you didn't get it on film when ithappened.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Slices of life: Zeroing in on elements of an event can be
rewarding. Rather than a photo of the entire living room when
everyone is opening presents, zero in on one person. A tight shot
of each family member is more telling than a overall photo of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   If your camera is equipped with a zoom lens, it's a good time to
use it. It doesn't have to be a long telephoto lens. An 85mm or
105mm lens is great at getting closer and eliminating distracting
background. _ Watch your lighting: Even wonder why the photo of
Maude in front of the living room window always comes out dark? The
problem is called backlighting. The problem with such photos is
that without a flash most cameras with auto exposure will read the
window as very bright and will adjust the exposure accordingly. The
camera doesn't know that you want a photo of Maude and not the
window. There is more light from the window than there is on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   To eliminate the problem, be careful when shooting photos where
a bright light source (window, lamp, etc.) is in the frame. If the
light source can't be avoided, using a flash can help add more
light to the subject and balance the strong backlight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Background, background, background: To paraphrase an old real
estate saying, ``There are only three things important in
photography: background, background and background.'' What will
separate so-so photos from good or great holiday photos is the
background. Because photographs are two-dimensional representations
of a three-dimensional world, most photographers see only the
subject when taking pictures. A telephone pole five feet behind
aunt Maude seems like it is coming out of her head in the
photograph.
</P>
<P>
   _ Picking the right film: Most amateur photographers think that
the faster the film (the higher the ISO) the better. But film
should be matched to the type of photos that are taken. The higher
the ISO, the more expensive the film and the more sensitive it is
to light.
</P>
<P>
   But as the ISO goes up, the quality of the image goes down. A
photo of the front of your house will have better color with 100
ISO film than 400 ISO. Most of the time, image quality and film
speed isn't an issue, because most everyone selects the standard
3-by-5-inch photos that comes with developing film. When a frame is
enlarged to an 8-by-10-inch print or larger, quality becomes more
of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   If most of the images you take are outside in direct or indirect
sunlight, consider using a slower film, such as 100 ISO, because
you have all the light you need. If most of the photos you take are
with a flash, you might try 100 ISO as well because your camera is
providing the necessary lighting. If you are shooting in available
light (without a flash) and some of the time it is dim, you'll need
to use a faster film, such as 400 ISO or higher. The past decade
has seen a dramatic improvement in image quality of high-speed
films. If you want to stop action in dim available light, explore
800 ISO or higher.
</P>
<P>
   _ Above all, have fun taking photos of the last holiday season
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
