<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NORAP28-COX     11-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORAP28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rappers' latest project
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Ronald ``Slim'' and Bryan ``Baby'' Williams grew
up in the inner city, and they say their hearts will always be in
the 'hood.
</P>
<P>
   Their homes are another story.
</P>
<P>
   As the CEOs of Cash Money Records, a rap label that signed a $30
million distribution deal with Universal last year and features
stars Juvenile and B.G., the Williams brothers could afford to live
wherever they wanted. They chose the heart of suburban America: a
high-security, gated golf community called English Turn across the
river from downtown New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Living away from the inner city in an exclusive community has
become a rap status symbol as important as gold teeth, diamond
necklaces, Cadillac SUVs and stretch ``Hummers.'' And status
symbols are a Cash Money trademark. Many of their songs _ including
B.G.'s hit, ``Bling! Bling!'' _ are chiefly a list of what their
newfound wealth can buy: cars, jewelry, helicopters, women, drugs
and booze. Baby recently gave Slim a $350,000 Bentley convertible
for his birthday, and Slim doesn't even drive.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was formed in 1991, Cash Money has produced 30 albums,
many chart toppers earning big bucks for the Williams brothers.
</P>
<P>
   What Slim's status required were rooms with a view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my real estate agent I wanted water and windows,'' said
Slim, who is almost 7 feet tall with a build to suit his name. ``I
was looking for somewhere to get away from the business.''
</P>
<P>
   He got it. His creamy stucco house is tucked far into the quiet
community and sits on a lagoon at the edge of an immaculate Jack
Nicklaus-designed golf course. His brother's house, across a
perfectly manicured cul-de-sac, is beige brick and sits on another
lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   In English Turn, houses range from $300,000 to $3 million and
belong mostly to doctors, lawyers and business owners. The most
famous resident besides the Cash Money executives is New Orleans
Saints football coach Mike Ditka. Baby, who is 28, and Slim, 31,
are not only unusual because of their business; they're also
probably two of the youngest homeowners in the community.
</P>
<P>
   But they're not the first rap moguls to storm the gates of white
privilege. Last year, Master P and the rappers of No Limit Records,
including C-Murder, Mystikal and Snoop Dogg, moved to the Country
Club of the South in Baton Rouge. Their neighbors include former
Gov. Edwin Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   There has been more speculation than actual problems associated
with the culture clash of up-from-the-ghetto rappers mingling with
the country club set. People said Master P, who earned more than
$56 million last year, bought extra houses just so he could get
more parking passes for his friends. And a rumor went around that
Snoop Dogg wanted to build a dog bone-shaped pool. The only real
stir was when Master P and his colleagues in Baton Rouge were
denied memberships at their community's golf club. Their lawyer
accused the club of racism but later backed down from the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of English Turn are automatically members of the golf
club, but none of the Cash Money crew plays golf anyway, Slim said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of both communities call the rappers good neighbors
who are rarely home. The Williams brothers said the only person
they know in the community is the security guard. They spend more
time in the housing projects of uptown New Orleans than in English
Turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't affect my life,'' said Tripp Friedler, a
businessman who lives a few streets down from the Williamses. ``If
I grew up in the projects, I'd live in English Turn. They're good
neighbors. Their houses look better than some of my neighbors'.
I've got some who don't cut the grass and don't keep the house
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedler added English Turn is not exclusively white. He
estimates about 10 percent of the homeowners are black.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses say they want to live in a gated community for
the same reasons as most people: They want a nice place to raise a
family, they want peace and quiet, and they don't want to be
bothered.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another reason. Like B.G.'s hit song says, it's
about ``Bling! Bling!'' Li'l Wayne calls it ``braggin' rights.'' A
teen-ager whose gold teeth say ``CASH MONEY,'' Wayne says he lives
with Baby in English Turn just so he can say he does.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile, 23, Cash Money's most famous rapper, won't say where
he lives, but it's definitely outside the city, on a lake, and far
from the C.J. Peete housing project, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just say I'm where the rich people live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl James, publisher and editor in chief of Rap Sheet, said
rap stars don't move to these communities to thumb their noses at
rich white people. They're simply nice places to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have urban youth who grew up very hard and very
impoverished, and their dream if they make it is to live in the
very best portion of the city,'' he said. ``And that often happens
to be where whites are and where few blacks live.''
</P>
<P>
   But the irony is not lost on James.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gated communities are often for people who want to keep
society out and don't want people coming in,'' he said. Rappers who
make money speaking in profanities, glorifying drug use, casual sex
and violence would seem to be just the sort of ``society'' a gated
community is designed to keep out.
</P>
<P>
   But even if English Turn is their address, Baby and Slim have
not exactly made the community their home. Baby feigns utter
nonchalance about his move to English Turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my house, but it don't mean nothin' to me,'' he said.
``I ain't used to living like that. This is how I'm used to
livin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' is the middle of the C.J. Peete public housing project,
a run-down collection of squat brick buildings where many windows
are broken and most walls are covered in graffiti. The smell of
marijuana and stale beer hangs in the air. Young men walk around in
tough-looking packs.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams brothers and their entire stable of rap artists
were here recently filming a made-for-video movie called ``Baller
Blockin','' due out early next year. It was hard for Elston Howard,
the producer, to tear them away from their old friends long enough
to film scenes.
</P>
<P>
   And while they don't live here, the Cash Money crew gives back
to the community. Slim organized a Thanksgiving dinner for the
needy. Juvenile's next goal is to help out his friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to set them all straight,'' he said, leaning against
his canary yellow Trans Am, one of six cars he owns. ``I don't want
them to have no more financial problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
