<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      11-27 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS IS HOPING TO REWRITE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoons growing up in the hardscrabble railroad
town of Lebanon, Pa., the pro football Kerry Collins watched on
television was almost always hearty and brawny football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked all the traditional teams _ Redskins, Giants, Bears,
Eagles,'' Collins said Friday at his Giants Stadium locker. ``Lots
of history, I just ate it up.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came out of Penn State in 1995 as the nation's top-rated
college quarterback, Collins would often tell reporters in the
weeks before the draft that he longed to be selected by one of the
NFL's older, established franchises.
</P>
<P>
   He instead became the first player in the history of the
expansion Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I was ever comfortable being the guy trying
to make a tradition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, more than four years later, Collins will start his first
game at Giants Stadium against the Arizona Cardinals. He admits
this leaves him with a certain sense of wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting on a Giants helmet and running out of the Giants
Stadium tunnel is not just putting on another helmet and running
out of another football stadium tunnel,'' Collins said. ``It's an
honor. And with everything I've gone through lately, sometimes this
week I've found myself going: `Can you believe this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, like all reserve quarterbacks getting their first
chance to play before the home fans, will likely receive a generous
ovation when he takes the field Sunday. The honeymoon, of course,
will not last past one series if Collins stumbles and the offense
sputters.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment is nice, and it's great that Collins appreciates the
Giants' tradition in this, their 75th season in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But can he fix the Giants' broken offense?
</P>
<P>
   Because if you want to talk about Giants tradition, how about
six consecutive years of dreary, depressing offensive football?
</P>
<P>
   Can the fourth quarterback in the Jim Fassel era make Giants
fans enjoy watching the team when it has the football?
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Collins smiled at just such a question and then asked _
and answered _ one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't promise anything but this,'' he said. ``We will play
fast and quick. Giants fans might know a lot about me, but they
don't know me as a quarterback. And what would I tell them to
expect?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback that runs out on the field won't be the same
one who has run out there any other time in his career,'' Collins
said. ``This is the best prepared I've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a whirlwind week around the Giants, with the urgency a
two-game losing streak brings, the changing of the quarterbacks,
the holiday and the death of Fassel's mother Wednesday night.
Through it all, it's been a week for the whole team to watch
Collins practice.
</P>
<P>
   And it's been action-packed. Not that all of it has been good.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, the wide receivers and running backs kept dropping
passes because Collins delivered the ball with such pace, using a
quick, snapping motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, Kerry isn't even looking at you,'' said running
back Tiki Barber. ``And all of a sudden, the ball is coming right
at your head. You have to always be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, the Giants' ends and backs were catching up to the
football, which is almost always a perfect spiral. Collins, in
football parlance, throws a nice ball _ arching when it needs to
be, usually accurate, sometimes with touch.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest thing Collins has brought is a vitality and
confidence. Excitable and talkative, he is nonetheless commanding
in a football huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is just 26 years old, this is someone who was a
6-foot-5-inch, 15-year-old starting quarterback in high school,
where he played before crowds of 7,000 and more. He was an
all-America quarterback, and days after his 24th birthday he played
in a NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he makes his 51st NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has special talents,'' Fassel said of Collins. ``I hope
that people see the dramatic improvement he's made because he's
doing everything better.''
</P>
<P>
   His receivers with the Giants are certain the Giants' offense
will look different Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every quarterback has his different favorite throws or
favorite areas of the field where he looks first,'' Giants wide
receiver Amani Toomer said. ``So some of the same plays will look
different. Kerry likes putting it up there, I know that. And I like
running under it. And catching it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Patten, a Collins favorite who will replace Joe Jurevicius
Sunday as the team's new third receiver, said: ``He's a gambler. We
ran a two-minute drill in practice today and he hit me for a
touchdown on a post route. Next play, we're back at the 20-yard
line, so you figure something short, right? He threw another
touchdown to Amani on a deep sideline route. That's Kerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins likes to throw deep sideline routes, likes to throw
square-outs and likes to throw to tight end Pete Mitchell and wide
receiver Ike Hilliard in shorter, seam routes over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he has also thrown 67 interceptions in his career and
just 51 touchdowns. In parts of three games for the Giants this
season, he has four fumbles. He is fearless, but he has been
reckless, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry has a high-end ability you can't find in many guys,''
Fassel said. ``But he does have a low end. He isn't going to get
better going up and down like that. But if you can raise the low
end, then the median performance would be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Giants' running game still more of a decoy than a
weapon, it's likely Collins will be airing it out frequently
Sunday. That will take adequate pass protection, something Collins
did not have in his one previous start last month for the Giants.
But his speedy passing motion should help.
</P>
<P>
   And that's one thing Collins has no plans to do: wait around for
something to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting for this, maybe for my whole life,'' he said
Friday. ``And I'm going to let it fly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
