<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PRESS SERVES SCANDAL DU JOUR, IN HEFTY DOLLOPS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note language in last graf.) 
 (jw) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ What do call girls, hit-men and fictitious yeshiva
students have in common with soccer goalies, newspaper publishers
and former political leaders?
</P>
<P>
   That is what Israel wanted to know last week.
</P>
<P>
   A transfer of West Bank land to the Palestinians may be overdue.
Israeli-Vatican relations may be at a low point, and unemployment
may be at a record high.
</P>
<P>
   But it was scandal, and lots of it, that truly occupied the
country's attention.
</P>
<P>
   There was scandal of lust, scandal of greed, scandal of
corruption. There was scandal involving the national soccer team
for losing a key match following alleged pregame visits to a house
of ill repute. There was scandal involving former Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and his wife, Sarah, accused of accepting bribes
and stealing valuable state gifts. And there was yeshiva scandal
aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   So much muck was being raked that the newspaper Yediot Ahronot
even ran a full-page scandal guide on Friday, with boxes for every
major affair, its suspects, its allegations and the status of its
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal of the week? It's hard to choose. It did create
quite a stir when the police took Ofer Nimrodi, publisher of the
newspaper Maariv, into custody on suspicions of plotting to murder
the state witness in his wiretapping trial.
</P>
<P>
   Nimrodi, 43 and a stylish Harvard Business School-educated
member of Israel's wealthy elite, was released from prison this
year after serving several months for illegally tapping the phones
of a panoply of media celebrities, businessmen and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in black, he clasped his manacled hands and looked
woefully at the cameras, through stylish wire-rim glasses, as he
was hustled into magistrate court. He remains in police custody but
charges have apparently not been filed. Nimrodi maintains that he
is being framed by a private detective who used to be in his hire
and is now serving a four-year sentence for his own complicity in
the wiretapping affair.
</P>
<P>
   But, in addition to conspiracy to commit murder, in which he is
suspected of making a down payment to a hit-man, Nimrodi is also
suspected of obstructing justice _ with the assistance of police
officers and lawyers. And on this charge, in particular, there is
one damning image that the Israeli public cannot erase from its
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television broadcast it several weeks ago, when word of
the police investigation first leaked. Israeli television showed a
video clip of Nimrodi alone in a police interrogation room with a
pile of documents. As the camera watched, he tore a piece of paper
from one, put it in his pocket, reconsidered and then stuffed it in
his mouth, chewed it and washed it down with a glass of water.
</P>
<P>
   The Nimrodi affair was Wednesday. On Thursday, five senior
Jerusalem city employees and four architects and building
contractors were arrested in what police believe may be a classic
municipal corruption case. Police suspect that the city workers and
their union chief accepted bribes, including cash and sexual
services, in exchange for awarding building contracts and
disregarding illegal construction.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, though, and in stiff competition for scandal du
jour was a suspected yeshiva money-laundering affair connected to
the corruption case of Aryeh Deri, the former Shas party leader.
Deri was convicted last spring and is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, police questioned a prominent businessman and his
lawyer partner. They are suspected of having laundered more than $2
million through the Itri yeshiva as supposed donations that were
meant to help finance Deri's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases include: the Rabbi Yaakov Chemed affair, in which
the former director of Shas' educational network is under
investigation for financial irregularities in the state-financed
school system; and the Fictitious Yeshivas affair, in which several
employees of the Religious Affairs Ministry are under investigation
for funneling millions of shekels to yeshivas that do not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Netanyahu and his wife, who have been repeatedly
questioned by the police, drags on like a persistent hum in the
background of a noisy society. Netanyahu claims that he is being
harassed by political opponents, and several political officials,
including those who are not in his camp, have criticized the police
for carrying out the investigation so publicly as to humiliate the
former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The case began when a building contractor, Avner Amedi, who has
since turned state's witness, submitted to the prime minister's
office a bill for $100,000 for services performed for the
Netanyahus during his term in office. That provoked an
investigation into suspicions of bribery, suspicions that the
contractor had provided the services free with the expectation of
getting favors in return.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the investigation, the police searched the
Netanyahus' apartment, storage rooms and offices and impounded
boxes they believed to contain valuable gifts to Israel that
belonged to the state, not the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Did the soccer team scandal provide comic relief?
</P>
<P>
   Some were taking it quite seriously. The national soccer
association hired a private company to investigate the claims that
some key team members spent the night before a humiliating 5-0
defeat to Denmark in the company of call girls. Five players on the
team started their own Internet site to battle the ``witch hunt''
against them.
</P>
<P>
   But the British tabloids were calling it ``Whoregate,'' and an
Italian television satire show featured the new Israeli team
uniform: boxer shorts with site-specific holes. And some
tongue-in-cheek Israeli newspaper stories were citing new
scientific research questioning the premise that athletes should
avoid pregame sex to conserve their energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
