<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-REBEL-475&AMP;A     11-27 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-REBEL-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDONESIA, REBEL LEADER GAINS FORUM FOR HIS CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIGLI, Indonesia, _ Abdullah Syafie is waging a guerrilla war
against Indonesia. But who has time to fight when the foreign news
media keep dropping by?
</P>
<P>
   Holstering his pistol and pulling out a tape recorder, Syafie
sat here recently for the latest in a long day of interviews. ``We
are fighting Indonesian colonialism,'' he said in the practiced
cadence of a candidate on the stump. ``We want to restore Aceh to
its status as a kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Syafie is the commander of the Free Aceh Movement, a rebel force
that is fighting for the independence of this devoutly Islamic
province on the far western edge of the Indonesian archipelago. The
guerrillas are one of several groups pushing the Indonesian
government to grant Aceh independence. As the separatist tensions
mount, Aceh is quickly becoming a grave threat to Indonesian unity.
</P>
<P>
   For Syafie, however, the emergence of Aceh as Indonesia's new
flash point merely means that he is no longer fighting in
obscurity. The 47-year-old guerrilla still holes up in a jungle
hide-out 10 miles off the main road to elude Indonesian soldiers.
But with journalists and camera crews pulling up to his thatched
hut all day long, he does not seem well hidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in danger,'' said the commander. ``If we were in
danger, you wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   With roughly 800 armed members, the Free Aceh Movement is hardly
a military machine. But because its troops live in remote villages,
it wields a disproportionate influence on the largely rural
population. For many of Aceh's 4.5 million people, these guerrillas
are the face of the separatist movement.
</P>
<P>
   And that face is a brutal one, the Indonesian military says. The
deputy commander of military operations here, Lt. Col. Iro Suparmo,
said the guerrillas were forcing non-Acehnese people to flee the
province. ``They are using the villagers as weapons in their
struggle,'' he said, ``and it is very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's generals have seized on the Free Aceh Movement as a
justification for Indonesia to impose martial law in the province.
Indonesia's president, Abdurrahman Wahid, has so far resisted,
setting up a potential showdown between the army and the civilian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For Syafie the president's restraint means little. The rebel
leader said Wahid was untrustworthy and represented a government
with no legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have anything to do with Gus Dur,'' said Syafie,
using Wahid's nickname. ``If he were to come up here as a Javanese
person, maybe we could negotiate with him. But as long as he is
president of Indonesia, there is no way we will talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Free Aceh Movement, however, does not entirely speak and act
as one. Political analysts said the movement was split into a
militant faction that spurns compromise with the Indonesian
government, and a political wing that is open to negotiation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The group's roots extend to the 1950s, when Aceh began resisting
the newly established Indonesian republic. In the 1970s, a local
businessman, Hasan di Tiro, organized the group as a military
force. Now 77 and living in Sweden, di Tiro, who rejects
compromise, still exerts influence over group members.
</P>
<P>
   Nasrullah Dahlawy, a spokesman for the political wing of the
movement, said: ``We want to have a dialogue with Gus Dur on one
condition _ it has to be about independence, not autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Syafie said the movement had no need to placate the
government. With separatist tensions flaring up in several parts of
the country, he said, Indonesia was rapidly losing its sense of
nationhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for us to find evidence that Indonesia exists,''
Syafie said. ``People who call themselves Indonesians are having an
identity crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Syafie began his interview, he stood up and strode
to another corner of the hut, in front of the Free Aceh flag _
flanked by guerrillas with automatic weapons. The interview
resumed. The television cameras whirred. Abdullah Syafie was ready
for his close-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
