<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sunday, Nov. 28, have moved:
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REVIEW (Washington) _ They are pouring into Seattle this
weekend in vans and on buses, by air and on foot _ the college
students and the church groups, the environmental activists, the
Teamsters, Ralph Nader, Chinese dissidents and the man who became a
hero in France for defacing a McDonalds. All of them say they are
outraged at the growing power of a group few even heard about five
years ago, the World Trade Organization. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-REVIEW (Washington) _ Fair or unfair, the portrayals of
presidential candidates by the news media, the pundits and the
late-night comics are often exaggerated. But perhaps because these
images are often founded on some truth, they can be impossible for
politicians to overcome. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   AIR-TRAVEL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Here are some of the things that
airline flight attendants have watched passengers lug on board:
Mariachi hats, potted palms, boogie boards, shopping bags brimming
with canned hams, a live duck in a cage, cases of wine,
covered-dish casseroles, multi-tiered wedding cakes, a
three-foot-tall religious statue for lawn display, an automobile
transmission and a freshly severed buck's head with its antlers
poking out of a trash bag. And they're carting a lot more stuff
aboard than ever before. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RACE-REVIEW (Washington) _ At first, the survey results
seemed depressingly familiar: Nearly two-thirds of those who
responded in a poll said they had had a racially-offensive
encounter with a colleague during the 12 previous months. What is
startling about the latest manifestation of divergent racial
perceptions is the setting in which they occurred. This was the
military, an institution that has been held up as the paragon of
racial integration, tolerance and equal opportunity. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Soon after EgyptAir Flight 990
plunged into the Atlantic Ocean, the personal-injury lawyers at R.
Jack Clapp and Associates marshaled their resources and mobilized
their forces. Faster than you can say class-action lawsuit, the
Washington, D.C., firm, which specializes in aviation disasters,
launched EgyptAir990.com _ a Web site that at first blush appears
primarily concerned with helping the bereaved deal with loss, but
on closer examination is all about financial gain. Such on-line
opportunism hardly burnishes the flagging reputation of lawyers. By
David Wallas.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-REVIEW (Undated) _ Once, Internet search sites served
as helpful road maps. With advances in artificial intelligence, one
day they might be brilliant secretaries. But today, they are in a
state of transition, slouching toward the human, growing more
philosophical. Mixing mechanical and personal elements, they have
turned into accidental wisefolk, spiritual advisers and drive-by
psychoanalysts. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-FAMILIES-REVIEW (Washington) _ The White House has often
seemed confining to the wives of the men who lived there. Hillary
Rodham Clinton, seeking power that she did not have to exercise
through her husband, announced last week that she was moving to
Chappaqua, N.Y. Mrs. Clinton is not the first president's wife to
find the White House stifling and to leave a husband rattling
around in the whitewashed old pile on Pennsylvania Avenue. Several
presidential wives sought refuge from the burdens of first
ladyship. By John N. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REVIEW (Timlje, Kosovo) _ The former Kosovo Liberation
Army, which has supposedly transformed itself into a civilian force
with no military or police responsibilities, is not the only
challenge to the authority of the U.N. mission in Kosovo, known as
Unmik; the mission is also undermined by the international civilian
agencies that are supposed to serve it, and by the sheer size and
resources of the NATO-led force here _ 42,000 troops _ whose role
tends to be defined only as peacekeeping. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COMRADE-REVIEW (Undated) _ It was perhaps no surprise that
the latest edition of China's dictionary of record, Cihai (The Sea
of Words), narrowed the definition of the word comrade _ or tongzhi
_ out of everyday life, concluding that it could no longer be
regarded as the greeting among China's citizens. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-REVIEW (Washington) _ A new question has entered the
calculations of those who plan for peace or war in the Middle East:
Would democracies or dictatorships make the best neighbors and
partners in the emerging peace with Israel? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LETTERS-REVIEW (London) _ There remains a place where
letter-writing lives _ England. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
