<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-1060(     11-27 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-TUDJMAN-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROATIA LOOKS TO EUROPE AS LEADER NEARS DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia _ The imminent death of Croatia's founder and
president, Franjo Tudjman, no matter who succeeds him, will take
much of the personal animosity and heat out of the country's
strained relationships with Washington and the European Union,
turning at least a part of the Balkans more firmly westward, senior
Croatian officials and Western diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   The medical status of Tudjman, 77, whose myth is being burnished
by his shaken political party even as he lies incommunicado, was
relegated Saturday by doctors to ``very grave.''
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections now scheduled for Jan. 3 _
elections that a center-left opposition coalition is expected to
win _ Tudjman's ruling Croatian Democratic Union, known here as
HDZ, is trying ``to exploit his disease and death to appeal to the
sentiments of voters,'' said Slaven Letica, a former Tudjman
adviser and political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But Tudjman's death ``will bring good news to Croatia in
political terms,'' Letica said. ``In general, the Croatian people
are tired of authoritarian leaders in this century _ we've already
buried four of them,'' including Josip Broz Tito, the Croat-born
founder of Yugoslavia, whom Tudjman has tried to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   His death is likely also to greatly improve relations with a
Western world that wearied of Tudjman's historical obsessions and
xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman is revered here for his crucial role in creating modern
Croatia in 1991, out of the collapse of the communist federation
founded by Tito. But as a historian and nationalist, Tudjman also
articulated and thus fed the country's paranoia about Western
conspiracies to undermine and destroy the state.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's obsessions included his unorthodox view that few Jews
and Serbs were killed by the Croatian fascist regime, the Ustasha,
during World War II and his conviction that the West wanted to
control Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   His constant lectures to Western diplomats and statesmen about
their injustice to Croatia and their dark designs against it were a
more passionate mirror of similar lectures from the Serbian leader,
Slobodan Milosevic, according to those who have heard both.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tudjman, Croatia has been ostracized much as Milosevic's
Yugoslavia has been. Although Croatia has so far escaped the
economic sanctions imposed on Milosevic, the autocratic, corrupt
and sometimes comedic nature of Tudjman's state, combined with his
repression of independent media and his unwillingness either to
make Bosnia work or to cooperate with the war crimes tribunal in
The Hague have deepened his country's isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia, despite its fervent desire to join Europe, has been
kept from two of the main waiting rooms for integration: NATO's
Partnership for Peace, which even Albania and Kazakhstan have been
allowed to join, and the European Union's program known as Phare,
the French word for beacon, which provides financial and technical
assistance to nearly every other postcommunist country in Central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever else Tudjman's death brings, Croatia has a chance now
to join the main currents of European history,'' said a senior
Foreign Ministry official. ``A democratic Croatia, if it gets help
from the West, can be pivotal to bringing peace, democracy and
stability to the region, including Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   That is also the fervent hope in Washington and Brussels,
Belgium, where officials would love to see a new, more outgoing
president, like the current foreign minister, Mate Granic, who is a
moderate member of the ruling party, and a new Parliament and
government dominated by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real possibility for Croatia to turn from being a
major part of the problem in this part of the world into a success
story and a big part of the solution,'' a senior Western diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   Croatian reality is likely to be more complicated than that.
Tudjman's party, a broad congregation that may fragment after his
death, has not yet picked a possible successor and appears afraid
to be seen to do so while the patriarchal president still breathes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been living in a form of prepolitics,'' said Marinko
Culic of the weekly Feral Tribune who has written a new book,
``Tudjman: The Anatomy of Unenlightened Absolutism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough of men of vision,'' he said. ``But I'm not
convinced the opposition will win. It won't be clear-cut, and I'm
not sure the opposition will hold together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Tudjman's nationalist obsessions ``have been transferred
to the opposition, too,'' Culic said. ``Croatia won't be liberated
so easily from the issues Mr. Tudjman pushed,'' like the
paternalistic and constitutional ties to Bosnia's Croats. ``In part
this will remain a small, closed, xenophobic state, but Croatia
will still find its place in the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Drazen Budisa, the leader of the opposition Social Liberal
party, admitted in an interview that the opposition must protect
its ``nationalist'' front in the election. In May, Budisa refused
to go to Washington to meet officials _ the only one of the six
opposition leaders to stay home _ because of government criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's death ``will define the character of the political
campaign and it will be to the detriment of the opposition,''
Budisa said, especially after a huge state funeral with the
participation of the church. The opposition coalition _ actually
two allied coalitions of six parties in total _ will hang together
nonetheless, he predicted, even though it has also not agreed on a
single presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tudjman's death will improve relations with Washington and the
European Union, too,'' Budisa said. ``But political support for us
from abroad does not give us votes in Croatia. We need to have a
balanced policy. So support us more after we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivica Racan, leader of the Social Democrats, admitted that both
he and Budisa could end up running for the presidency. ``I'm sure
we will hold together,'' he said, although he admitted that there
would be severe competition for limited posts even if the
opposition wins control of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition's eventual rule might be short-lived given the
severe economic problems it would inherit, including a bloated
state sector, recession, $10 billion in foreign debt, a $2-billion
budget deficit for next year and high unemployment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A responsible government would have to increase the public's
pain to begin to restructure the economy, and it is questionable
whether the West, preoccupied with Serbia and Kosovo, would provide
sufficient assistance to ease the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Western officials and diplomats say that Tudjman's
tirades were tedious and deeply annoying. On the issues that
Washington pressed hardest _ democratization, compliance with the
Dayton Accords that ended the Bosnian war in 1995, and the return
of ethnic Serbs to Croatian territory from which they were expelled
that same year _ ``Tudjman was fundamentally opposed to each of
them, and his leadership made progress difficult if not impossible
on all of them,'' a senior Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, he said, in a version confirmed by others, Tudjman
had four constant themes. First, that ``they'' in the West were
opposed to the creation of Croatia, so ``they are punishing us for
our independence and holding us to an unfairly high standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, that ``it's all a plot'' to keep Croatia down, whether
the issue is compliance with the war crimes tribunal, membership in
Partnership for Peace, World Bank reluctance to ignore economic
corruption and mismanagement, or highly critical reports on the
state of human rights by Washington or the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Third, ``They want to keep us in the Balkans and create a new
Yugoslavia and stick us back where we don't belong.''
</P>
<P>
   And fourth, that the country is rife with ``foreign enemies'' _
spies and journalists and aid workers _ who ``are in the pay and in
collaboration with foreigners'' and who ``buy the loyalty of
Croatian trash'' who work with them.
</P>
<P>
   Jagoda Vukusic of the newspaper Novi List said that Tudjman's
death will change the whole tone of Croatian political life. ``I
can imagine the HDZ winning, but still it won't be the same
party,'' she said. ``They have to grow up quickly too and are
trying to become a real party and more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death of Tudjman will be a kind of release for them,
too,'' she said. ``It gives us the possibility of becoming a more
normal, boring country. Ah, to be boring,'' she said. ``I'm waiting
for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
