<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Nov. 28 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3704.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
. &QL; 
COMMUTE-GRIDLOCK (Los Angeles) _ When it opened, the 405 Freeway
was envisioned as a fast path into the burgeoning suburbs of the
West Valley. Now, rush-hour traffic on it averages a
school-zone-esque 25 mph. And the problem will only get worse with
the planned expansion of Los Angeles International Airport. Recent
studies have shown that L.A. traffic is the worst in the nation,
and the interchanges on the 405 Freeway with the 10 and the 101 are
ground-zero for gridlock. New figures show commute times through
those interchanges steadily rising. Are there solutions on the
horizon? By Steve Carney (Will run on the ``n'' California news
wire.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SENIORS (Los Angeles) _ Nursing home residents, even if
frail and in their 90s, can help each other overcome aversion to
computers and revitalize their lives through e-mail and the
Internet, according to experts trying to entice more senior
citizens on line. ``The Internet is a window to life,'' says David
Lansdale, a geriatrics expert from Stanford University. ``It's an
elixir for these people.'' By Dominic Berbeo (Will move on the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1414EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2659 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ONLINE-SENIORS-LADN     11-27 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SENIORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SENIORS ARE USING WEB FOR COMMUNICATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dominic Berbeo  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Older Americans who use the Internet are finding a
new way to reconnect with society and may even be benefiting from
regular doses of mental stimulation, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web these days, one can find anything from true love to a
used car. Many go online to shop, invest or just for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But senior citizens also get the added benefit of increased
community participation, a godsend especially for those unable to
get around easily, said Dr. Gary Small, director of the University
of California, Los Angeles' Center on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's generation is a cyber generation,'' he said. ``The
Internet allows seniors to cross generation lines and get in touch
with younger family members.''
</P>
<P>
   He said many older people are ``cyber phobic'' of fast-paced
computer technology, but going online is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act of learning something new and communicating with
others is definitely beneficial to one's health,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Small cited a study funded by the MacArthur Foundation last year
that showed that keeping the mind active on a daily basis is likely
to lead to more healthy aging. For example, he said, it could help
prevent development of ailments often associated with old age, such
as Alzheimer's disease, a progressive, irreversible disease
characterized by degeneration of the brain cells and often leading
to severe dementia.
</P>
<P>
   SeniorNet, a national nonprofit group based in San Francisco,
focuses on bringing the Internet to people ages 50 and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who aren't on the Internet feel left out of
conversations, even within their own families, because they don't
understand all the lingo,'' said SeniorNet spokeswoman Stacy
Dieter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning how to use this resource is like finding an opening
to the world,'' she said. ``For the disabled, this is a way of
staying in touch with the rest of society without even leaving
their bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization has more than 160 learning centers around the
country, including in Los Angeles, offering low-cost Internet
classes to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter said seniors enjoy theme-based discussion groups in which
one can contact others on given topics, such as finding other
veterans around the world with World War II experiences.
</P>
<P>
   A report released last year by America Online showed that only
22 percent of Internet subscribers were 50 years of age or older.
But a SeniorNet study showed that number to be increasing, with 70
percent of seniors who own a personal computer going online in
1998, compared to only 17 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Elisa Driz of Northridge took a free Internet class at her local
library to go online and communicate with close relatives in
Argentina and Israel without running up huge phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, I waited this long to learn because I was scared
to death and confused,'' said Driz, 66. ``But we just got a
computer, and last week my daughter in Mendoza, Argentina, sent me
photos of my grandchild. It was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was interested mostly in e-mail, but also in
services such as shopping, travel planning and reading
international newspapers online.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably many things that I can do that I don't even
know about yet because I have to learn more,'' she said. ``This is
revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Stanton, 69, is a retired mechanical engineer who volunteers
as a teacher of Internet classes at the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is really going to change the world,'' he said.
``It's like when the printing press was invented. All of a sudden,
more people everywhere are getting more access to information they
couldn't get before.''
</P>
<P>
   And the effects of increased Internet use may go even further.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service is projecting a decrease in first-class
mail by 2004 as more Internet users choose to pay bills online.
</P>
<P>
   Postage on bill payments represented about a third of the total
$101 billion first-class revenue last year, said Postal Service
spokesman Greg Frey.
</P>
<P>
   If revenues are seriously reduced, the agency might be forced to
raise prices to break even, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
