<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TALKSHOW-PRIEST-2TAKE     11-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKSHOW-PRIEST-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH-LANGUAGE NETWORK PRAYS THAT PRIEST BRINGS HIGH RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (Eds: In Cutie, the `e' takes an accent, which cannot be
transmitted to some newspapers.) 
(mk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Standing before an audience of some 100 people in a
half-moon-shaped television studio here, the Rev. Alberto Cutie
bowed his head and asked God ``to illuminate us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask you to help us so we can send a positive message to our
community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer is standard before every taping of ``Padre Alberto,'' a
talk show on the Telemundo Spanish-language network that delves
into domestic violence, incest, sex addiction and other issues
common to daytime programming, but that unlike other shows has a
Roman Catholic priest as its host.
</P>
<P>
   Being a cleric was mainly why Cutie, the 30-year-old
Cuban-American parish vicar of St. Patrick Church in Miami Beach,
was chosen from among 500 candidates to head Telemundo's new fall
lineup in September. Another reason, said Nely Galan, the network's
former president of entertainment and the show's producer, was that
he fit the bill for charisma, progressive views and good looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a combination of being young, boyish and fun, and at
the same time he's an old man _ very soulful,'' said Ms. Galan, who
runs her own production company, Galan Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the show came to Ms. Galan after a spiritual
retreat in Mexico, but she said it was long overdue. Hispanic
people, she said, are more apt to confide in their priest than in a
therapist, and ``talk shows are really like confessionals.''
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for priests as broadcasting stars, most
notably Bishop Fulton Sheen, whose inspirational talks from New
York City beat Milton Berle's comedy hour in ratings on Tuesday
nights in the early years of television. At 4 p.m. on weekdays,
Cutie is up against the popular ``El Show de Cristina'' on rival
Univision, whose host, Cristina Saralegui, has been the reigning
queen of Spanish-language talk shows for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Saralegui, Cutie says no subject is taboo. The show's
advertising slogan is: ``Father Alberto. Open your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know you can say anything before a priest,
and he's not going to get all bent out of shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike his competitor, who mixes up the lofty and
educational with the banal and plain tacky, Cutie said in an
interview that he saw the show as an extension of his ministry, and
his mission as inspiring viewers ``to look for the best in
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah has been doing that in the English-language market, but
no one has done it in the Spanish-language market,'' he said in a
not-so-subtle zinger at Ms. Saralegui, who is also Cuban-American.
``We speak about the human experience. We're not going to exploit
the problems. I want to deal with them in a very dignified manner.
I don't want anybody to see my show and be offended.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's underlying tone, indeed, is serious, if only because
most guests start out their sentences with a respectful ``Father.''
The content can sometimes also be dull because of Cutie's fondness
for asking questions like ``How does it feel?'' and advising
professional help for most problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Father Alberto, who is known in his church for starting
every sermon with a joke, is also prone to interjecting humorous
asides and fanning lively repartee in the ``Open Dialogue'' segment
of the show, where four guests, always including a celebrity,
discuss the subject at hand in the style of the ABC program
``Politically Incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the dialogue can get racy enough to make the host
blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behave, Maria Conchita, there's a Father here,'' he told the
Venezuelan actress Maria Conchita Alonso with nervous laughter
during a show about infidelity that veered into talk about oral
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' she said, contrite.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the show is secular, Cutie offers snippets of Roman
Catholic teachings to dispel any misconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Cutie on domestic violence: ``The church doesn't say you have to
stay with an abusive husband. If there is no respect there is no
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   On homosexuality: ``The church does not reject anyone. Being
homosexual is not a sin because it's something that you don't
choose.'' But he added, ``The practice is another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cutie not only represents a church that is topical and
``present,'' said Mary Ross Agosta, spokeswoman for the Archdiocese
of Miami, but he also comes across as a priest who ``is very
handsome and appears to be very happy'' and may encourage the
vocation in the young. (Telemundo's promotions show him working out
at the gym, playing the guitar, talking to teen-agers on the
beach.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful asset for us,'' Ms. Ross Agosta said of the
show, which archdiocesan officials approved after getting
assurances from Telemundo that neither content nor format would
embarrass the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that now we have a priest on prime-time
afternoon television that can speak about the teachings of the
church,'' she said. ``In a way he's evangelizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Telemundo, meanwhile, prays for high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Telemundo, owned by Sony Pictures Entertainment and Liberty
Media, badly lags in viewership behind Univision, which controls 90
percent of the Spanish-language television market in the nation.
Ratings for ``Padre Alberto'' are up 18 percent from the first show
in September, network officials said. But its share of households
is still a fraction of that of ``El Show de Cristina.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Puerto Rico and reared in Miami since the age of 7,
Cutie said he had no significant television experience except for
narrating and translating the pope's visit to Cuba last year for a
family cable channel. But he was the host of a dance music program
on public radio during his senior year in high school and was what
he calls ``a street D.J.'' from the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   When he was younger, Cutie had envisioned a life as ``a yuppie,
with a wife and 10 children,'' but he got his calling while in high
school. He was ordained a priest four years ago at 26, and was
assistant pastor at St. Clement Church in Fort Lauderdale before
landing at St. Patrick Church last year, where he juggles Masses
and baptisms with twice-a-week tapings of his show.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   (A middle child, he has an older sister who works as a dental
hygienist and a younger sister who is a special education teacher
in Miami-Dade County. His father died in 1992, but his mother is a
regular audience member at the shows, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   As a diocesan priest who took the vows of obedience and celibacy
but not of poverty, Father Alberto is paid a salary by the church
and now by Telemundo, but he declined to say how much he gets for
the show except that ``it's not what they pay a typical talk show
host.'' He has signed a two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Busloads of parishioners from area churches now descend upon
Telemundo every week for ``Padre Alberto'' tapings, many of them
members of St. Patrick Church who praise the show as instructive
and say fame has not changed their priest. Typically at the end of
each show, Father Alberto signs autographs and blesses crucifixes
for a long line of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still jovial, humble, always close to the people,'' said
Miriam Garcia, 60, who has attended St. Patrick for the last four
years and has Cutie as her confessor. ``He's very sure of himself,
and he is very firm in his vocation.''
</P>
<P>
   But one noticeable change has been Father Alberto's hairstyle.
While the network did not pressure him to spice up the show in any
way, he said, Ms. Galan insisted that he abandon his ``Fred
Flintstone look'' _ hair parted in a straight line and brushed to
one side. The more hip alternative involves very short hair brushed
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to be the George Clooney look, but I'm not sure
I like it,'' he said. ``I offer it for the souls in purgatory. I'm
just hoping it goes out of style real fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
