<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Nov. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Seasonable chill will return to the northern Plains and upper
Great Lakes as jet stream winds from the northwest begin to direct
colder air into the northern tier of the nation. A large ocean
storm developing off the Northwest coast will cause a bulge to form
in the jet stream over the Rockies early this week. The result will
be a stronger flow from the northwest across much of the East
leading to more widespread chill, but readings will at their worst
be a few degrees below seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure stretching from North Dakota to Alabama will
circulate progressively colder air into the Northeast. A stiff wind
will enhance the chill in the higher terrain of New England as snow
showers develop from the Tug Hill plateau of western New York to
the White Mountains of New Hampshire. The coast will be bright and
cooler with gusty winds during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant weather is expected in the Southeast with low humidity
and mainly clear skies. Florida will be noticeably drier. Patches
of clouds from the western Dakotas to the Tennessee Valley will
mark the boundary between advancing polar air and a very mild air
mass over the southern Plains and lower Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture associated with a series of jet stream disturbances
will flow into the West Coast states. While mainly high clouds will
be seen in California, Nevada and Utah, lower clouds and some
scattered showers are expected in Washington, northern Idaho and
western Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Green November
</P>
<P>
   No snowflakes were seen in Milwaukee on Saturday, tying the
latest date on record without a trace of snow there. If there are
no flurries in Madison, Wis., on Sunday, the capital city will tie
its record. Farther north, in Green Bay, where there has never been
a November without a flurry, the wait also continues for the first
snowflakes. It has been 35 years since Green Bay has had only a
trace of snow during the 11th month. While it will be cold enough
for snow through Tuesday, odds are against any precipitation in
Wisconsin, delaying winter's arrival until December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
