<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-HOTDOG-PINKS-AR     11-27 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HOTDOG-PINKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S INDULGENT ALTERNATIVE TO HEALTH FOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Consider the chili cheese dog, the trademark
indulgence at Pink's hot dog stand in Hollywood. Dripping with
sweet, smooth chili, wrapped in a slice of American cheese and a
soft bun, of considerable heft and not a little messy, it seems an
unlikely culinary obsession in a city thought preoccupied about
healthy eating.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Pink's has been putting the lie to the city's ahi-tuna and
wheat-grass-juice stereotype as the hot dog stand celebrated its
60th anniversary with a 60-cent hot dog special for an hour each
day over the last two weeks, ending on Friday. The wait for a chili
dog, which normally costs $2.40, stretched for up to four hours
near the corner of Melrose and La Brea avenues. Pink's has been
saluted by Mayor Richard Riordan and actors Erik Estrada and Ruth
Buzzi. Regular customers testify to its place in the firmament of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like them too much,'' said Aaron Spelling, the
producer of television shows including ``Melrose Place'' and
``Beverly Hills 90210,'' as he signed autographs there earlier this
week. ``We only order them three times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   As Spelling spoke, a hopeful screenwriter handed him a script
about ``Desert Storm and Hollywood'' and a head shot. ``We'll read
it and get to you right away,'' he told the man.
</P>
<P>
   So how does an unrepentant symbol of gluttony find firm footing
amid the supposedly cautious Angeleno diners? By offering itself as
an alternative, and by trading on its status as one of the few
dining institutions in a city where so many others _ the Brown
Derby and Chasen's, to name two _ have closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to splurge, you're going to splurge at a place
that really tastes good,'' said Richard Pink, who runs the family
business with his wife, Gloria, and his sister, Beverly. ``There's
got to be a place to balance out the tendency to chase low fat, low
carb. You've got to splurge where the calories count.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a newspaper ad, Pink's parents, Betty and Paul
Pink, bought a portable hot dog cart in 1939 with $50 in borrowed
money, running it on an extension cord to a hardware store one
block away. The stand was expanded in 1946 to a building, which
remains unchanged today. The menu, however, has grown to offer 21
kinds of hot dogs, and now Pink's sells up to 2,000 of them a day _
hot dogs with bacon, hot dogs with guacamole, hot dogs with sour
cream, tomatoes, mustard relish and onions, hot dogs stuffed with
Jalapeno peppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great hot dogs,'' said Ruth Reichl, a former food
critic for The New York Times and The Los Angeles Times, who is now
editor of Gourmet magazine. Ms. Reichl said she once dug through
Pink's trash receptacle to find out what kind of chili the
restaurant used; the owners say it is a family recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as you value healthy eating, people still like to eat
the occasionally sinful thing,'' Ms. Reichl said.
</P>
<P>
   Pink's proximity to the entertainment studios _ Paramount
Pictures and CBS Television City are in the neighborhood _ has made
it a Hollywood institution and a part of the city's fabric.
Autographed glossies of celebrities cover a wall where aspiring
unknowns once hung head shots and phone numbers in the hopes of
being noticed. Pink's hot dogs are standard fare for movie wrap
parties and talk show audiences, and the owners say the actor Orson
Welles holds the record for eating the most dogs in one sitting,
18.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even in Hollywood, a hot dog stand cannot survive on
celebrity business alone. Scott Dinsdale, 35, a financial analyst,
brought three friends for lunch from downtown Los Angeles, a trip
of at least 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's a dietitian,'' Dinsdale said over his lunch tray.
``We're just not going to tell her. There'll definitely be a salad
in my future.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Miller, a 55-year-old dock worker, said he had been
coming for years because he liked the distinctive snap of the
Pink's hot dog casing, combined with the taste of the chili. He
estimates that eating one such dog requires at least 10 napkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is junk food right here,'' Miller said. ``You don't eat
these every day. But it's good junk food.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
