<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BIRD-WATCHERS-ART-735     11-27 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-WATCHERS-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TREAT FOR TWITCHER AND SERIOUS BIRDER ALIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Pa., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIPTOPEKE, Va. _ It was almost as if the golden eagle knew that
the humans clustered far below were bird-watchers. The graceful
raptor flew in closer from the horizon fringe where it had first
been spotted, and teased the gathering near the beachfront by
pausing directly overhead, like a dancer on the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``See how the back part of his wings curve into his body _
that's classic,'' one bird-watcher said amid the group of seven who
stared up as the bird slowly soared above the hawk-watching
platform in Kiptopeke State Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It figures _ we were due for one,'' said another watcher,
while all eyes tracked the imperious visitor as it passed the
rampartlike platform, one of the newest and most prized
bird-watching perches along the Chesapeake coastal migration route.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle glided with the panache of one of creation's truly
self-possessed individuals, all glare and glory highlighted by the
late afternoon sunshine. The birders savored the encounter as a
reward for their long hours of watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time that would have been considered a unique
sighting,'' one of them said, elated at his birder's scope even as
he underlined a paradox of modern bird-watching: So many more
people are becoming involved in birding, and with such a plethora
of high-tech optics and wide-ranging leisure options, that once
rare sightings are becoming ever less rare.
</P>
<P>
   In the extreme, ``listers'' bearing woodland beepers and cell
phones are spotted increasingly in birding circles alerting one
another to the latest flying collectibles. Traditionalists consider
these listers fast-traveling fanatics who superficially amass the
longest possible lists of sighted birds as if they were baseball
cards, never truly appreciating the creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brits call them `twitchers' _ they twitch things off on
their list,'' said Tom Cameron, a lawyer and more studious birder
from Boston. ``The virulent lister isn't interested in looking at a
bird if he's already seen it. `Hey,' you tell him, `there's an
Andean condor on that telephone pole!' And the lister says, `Don't
need it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Patient watchers count more substantive rewards, most notably a
black-browed albatross photographed last February about 60 miles
east of Virginia Beach, an extraordinary sighting a hemisphere away
from home. Then there is the arrival and heartening proliferation
of brown pelicans, first spotted this far north a decade ago and
now nesting in the hundreds in the Chesapeake region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are as many different kinds of bird-watchers as there
are birds,'' said Henry Armistead, a librarian from Philadelphia
who has been birding for 50 of his 59 years, celebrating humans as
much as birds. ``Some people come and don't even raise their
binoculars. Whoever shows up can feel like family.''
</P>
<P>
   The humans were excited on this day at the sighting of a
pink-sided junco, far more rare here than a golden eagle. Far east
of its normal haunts in the Northern Rockies, it was spotted by
Susan Hopkins, a research scientist for the Coastal Virginia
Wildlife Observatory who has been working since Sept. 1 at the
platform.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of an avid community of avocational bird-watchers
who come and go, Ms. Hopkins has been tracking the main birds of
prey on their annual fly-by. Merlins, or pigeon hawks, pass in
great numbers, as do American kestrels, or sparrow hawks, and a
dozen other raptors, like peregrines, sharp-shinned hawks, ospreys
and turkey vultures.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively remote hawk platform and other perches in the
Cape Charles region are increasingly rated as a prime place for
autumnal bird-watching on the East Coast. The birds funnel
southward above the land's edge. Birders call Cape Charles the new
Cape May, comparing it to the New Jersey coastal region that is one
of the United States' focal points for bird-watching.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the Kiptopeke watch is a place of serious
business, as Ms. Hopkins and other scientists run careful seasonal
tallies on the state of the species. They trap, measure and band
some birds while sending data back to central population studies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the watch is a shared joy for the many
nonprofessional birders who stop by, the sharpest of them with
decades of valued experience. ``It's a big sky, and nobody can spot
everything that goes over,'' said Armistead, who writes widely of
his travels in birding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Accipiters are pouring through,'' Armistead exulted in his
journal one early morning last month. ``The hand clickers are
smoking,'' he said of the count by the platform watchers. Across
the years, he chronicles the passing creatures, from marbled
godwits to short-billed dowitchers. He notes birders' seasonal
melancholy, citing how Thomas Hardy's darkling thrush dared ``to
fling his soul upon the growing gloom.''
</P>
<P>
   There is more than birds to Armistead's watch. In his
wanderings, he has been stopped by an armed backwoodsman suspicious
that bird banding was a way to send messages to the communists. The
police stopped him one night in Wilmington, Del., when, intent on a
listening watch for urban nighthawks, he stood alert with his
binoculars heedless of a nearby center of night life. ``It was the
Spirit of '76 Massage Parlor,'' he noted for the record.
</P>
<P>
   Down from the hawk platform, Jamie Cameron, a 27-year-old field
biologist, has been trapping and banding assorted raptors 10 hours
a day, a task that continues from September until December. He
manipulates tethered pigeons and starlings to suddenly move on the
ground and so entices a laserlike swoop from a passing predator.
The strikes are cut short by his concealed net trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goshawks, the epitome of all that is aggressive,'' he said of
his most impressive captive. ``They're the alpha,'' he said, as his
father, Tom, knelt by the wood line, studying the far more exotic
pink-sided junco.
</P>
<P>
   ``A spectacular little bird; I'd watch it for hours,'' said the
senior Cameron. ``And this bird being a race and not a species, the
twitchers aren't interested,'' beamed the birder, ever watchful for
that rampant lister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
