<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SEE BALL CONTROL AS KEY TO BEATING COLTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The last time the New York Jets faced the
Indianapolis Colts, their season seemed all but ended as the final
seconds ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lucas, the last hope at quarterback, was sprawled on the
ground with a sprained ankle, the scoreboard showed a Colts victory
and the standing showed the Jets with a 1-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas had some responsibility for that low point. In his first
career start, with the Jets on the Colts' 3-yard line, he threw a
bad pass that was intercepted and turned into the Colts' winning
field goal in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets no longer are comatose. They have a three-game
winning streak that has pushed their record to 4-6, and they have
worked efficiently within a revised offensive scheme. Now, all they
have to figure out is how to get some more yardage and control the
ball, thus keeping it out of the hands of the dangerous Peyton
Manning and his offensive cast.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells admits he has several ``dilemmas'' as the Jets
prepare to face the Colts again on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   One dilemma:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not overly efficient in the passing game,''
Parcells said, ``the worst thing you can have is a second-and-15.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dilemma:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you tell Ray, `Open it up,' you're looking for trouble,''
Parcells added.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Jets need more offense, they have to keep the
running game going and they need the occasional deep ball from
Lucas. After all, Indianapolis is the highest-scoring team in the
conference with an average of 29.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to control the clock,'' Parcells said. ``That's the
best way we can play right now.'' And they need to do it with left
tackle Jumbo Elliott having back pains and with right tackle a
problem since the rookie Ryan Young is attempting to play after
spraining a knee last week.
</P>
<P>
   This is life without Vinny Testaverde. The Jets were disastrous
offensively until recently. And even during the three-game winning
string, they have not bulldozed defenses; not once all season have
the Jets even scored as many points in one game as the Colts have
been averaging.
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis Martin, who began a four-game stretch of 100-yard
rushing performances with the last Indianapolis game, remains a key
to keeping Lucas from having to open it up. Eventually, though,
Parcells knows that Martin's ability to run will also be dependent
on Lucas' keeping the defense honest _ and that means the threat of
a long ball.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason why Lucas worked overtime on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made him go over the red-zone stuff,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder. In the red zone the Jets are the worst in the
American Football Conference, scoring touchdowns only 36.7 percent
of the time on 30 possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that includes Lucas' misfire at the 3-yard line in
the Jets' and Colts' first meeting. That miscue overshadowed the
remarkable job the defense had done against Manning. It held the
second-year quarterback to his lowest yardage total of the season
(210).
</P>
<P>
   While Manning routinely drills the ball downfield, Lucas'
longest completion has been only 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's missed a couple,'' Parcells said. ``We're working on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this is another of those dilemmas. If you want Lucas to
avoid second-and-long, then he has to complete a first-down pass of
seven or eight yards. But his overall average of yards per attempt
is barely five yards. Still, that number is higher this week
because against the Bills last Sunday he was finally able to
average seven yards a throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've been talking to Ray about _ coming up with
second-and-two and second-and-three,'' Parcells said. ``That makes
it easier for Curtis.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has been running smoothly the last month and had a big
game out of the backfield with seven catches against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Ray adds to the running game is he's a threat,'' Martin
said. ``They don't know if he'll run when he gets back in the
pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jets have not had great success running the ball in
short-yardage situations. They convert barely a third of their
third downs, ranking 21st in the league. The reason Parcells made
that controversial decision to ask Lucas to pass the ball from the
3 against the Colts was simple: The team had been unable to produce
in short-yardage situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been about 20 different guys messing up,'' Parcells said.
``We're spending more time on it every week, and our short yardage
hasn't improved since the bye week.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lucas is approaching the rematch with a positive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a decent feel for the game the first time we played
them,'' he said. ``I know that we definitely have to control the
ball. That comes with experience. We've got to keep the ball out of
Peyton's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he doesn't expect Lucas to be mistake-free. ``As
long as he doesn't make it on the 3-yard line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
