<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHEN-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN REBELS COUNTERATTACK EAST OF BESIEGED CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (See also RUSSIA-CHECHNYA, TURKEY-RUSSIA) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russian artillery continued a savage pounding of
Chechnya's capital, largely reducing the remainder of a city of
250,000 to rubble, Chechen militants said they had staged their
first major counterattack and retaken most of a town in a hilly
region 20 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Lecha Dudayev of Grozny, the capital, quoted survivors of
the bombardment as saying at least 260 civilians _ and possibly as
many as 500 _ had died in shelling that began on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were impossible to verify, as the town's streets
were deserted, and people were huddled in basements, waiting out
the attack. More civilians left Grozny on Saturday for Ingushetia,
Chechnya's neighbor to the west, fleeing in vehicles with white
flags during lulls in the bombing. Ingushetia's interior minister,
Khamzat Gutseriyev, said 1,950 Chechen refugees had entered his
region since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 230,000 Chechen refugees are encamped or housed in
Ingushetia. The Russian news service Interfax said a 6-mile-long
line of cars was waiting to cross the Chechen border Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials denied that civilians had suffered
large losses, telling the Tass news service that their attacks had
been aimed strictly at the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said cannon and aircraft had bombed 35 towns
in the north Caucasus region around Grozny, Chechnya's largest city
until Russian attacks began in September. Government troops have
steadily tightened a ring of armor around the city and claimed
Saturday to have taken hills north of the town that gave them a
bead on some remaining rebel strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic militants who have controlled much of the province
began a counterattack early Saturday on the small town of
Novogroznensky, about 25 miles east of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the western part of the town was reported in flames as a
result of the fighting, in which rebels rained Russian-made Grad
rockets on parts of the town. By midday Saturday, The Associated
Press reported, rebels claimed to have retaken all but the eastern
outskirts of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel soldiers have taken a punishing since the Russian
offensive against Chechnya began in September, in part because the
Russians have relied mostly on air power and artillery to batter
towns into submission rather than subjecting their troops to
guerrilla combat.
</P>
<P>
   The militant leaders have claimed, however, that the battle
would turn their way once Russian troops were forced to move into
towns or to go after rebels in their mountain hideouts _ a new
phase of the war that Russian officials said on Friday that they
were prepared to begin.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, who has been recuperating from a viral
infection at his country home north of Moscow, was briefed on the
operation by telephone Saturday by Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev,
Russian news services reported.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Russian officials reported that they had
secured confessions from five Russian soldiers who fired on a shop
stall on Friday in an Ingushetia town near the Chechen border,
killing a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   According to official accounts, the five had driven to the shop
in an armored personnel carrier seeking to buy vodka, and began
firing after they were unable to buy any. The soldiers were
reported to be drunk at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The military's announcement was the first in the nine-week-long
conflict singling out Russian soldiers for punishment for their
treatment of civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
