<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     11-27 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR RIVERS, A PREDICTION RINGS TRUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  ( Eds:  Adds result of Saturday's game to 5th graf . ) 
(rk) 
 By   HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dialogue came at a delicate time of a player's career, near
its conclusion, which, Doc Rivers believes, explains the revulsion
he had for the job he now loves.
</P>
<P>
   He had just aired out his differences with Pat Riley over his
status with the Knicks when the power coach, out of breath and
finally sensing he couldn't bully the veteran, said: ``You're like
me, stubborn. You'll coach in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, Riles,'' Rivers answered. ``I'm a family guy.
Look at you, all wound up in this. Working 24 hours. You have no
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   What particularly alarmed Rivers was that Riley didn't argue
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Half a decade later, Saturday afternoon, Riley's vision returned
to Madison Square Garden, where, in 2 and a half years as a Knick,
Rivers cultivated a decade's worth of popularity. The Magic lost to
the Knicks, 99-96, but overall, Orlando's gain has been New York's
and New Jersey's loss. In Miami, Riley must have felt like the
world's best-dressed prophet when Rivers was hired as the Doc to
treat the Magic's post-Shaq-and-Penny syndrome last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I had that conversation with Riley, I was reaching
the point where I just wanted to get away from the locker room,''
Rivers said.
</P>
<P>
   He went to San Antonio for a season and a half, where one
playoff run was sabotaged when Dennis Rodman sat on the bench in
his socks. When Rivers' wife became pregnant with their fourth
child, he said ``enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a job as a television analyst. The next year, someone
set fire to the Rivers' home near a San Antonio golf course. The
family was away. R.C. Buford, a Spurs assistant coach and close
friend, happened to be on the course when the house went up. He
raced to the front door, found a way in and asked himself a
question most of us have: What should he save?
</P>
<P>
   ``He got the family photo albums and the videotapes of the
kids,'' Rivers said. ``He went in twice and was going to go in
again when the police said they'd arrest him if he did.''
</P>
<P>
   With friends like that, Rivers reminded himself he didn't need a
coaching job to not have time for them. He had a merry, stress-free
broadcasting life, watching the game continue to devolve into
Riley's ultimate vision of basketball, as a hockey score.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, it made him crazy watching guards walk the ball
up the court, the shot clock ticking, the fans yawning. By last
season, his third in headphones, Rivers found himself, at
courtside, conjuring up alternative game plans. Found himself
coaching along with the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I still had something left on the bench,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He rejected a chance to be Milwaukee's general manager. The
Garden's Dave Checketts had a preliminary chat with him about the
Knicks' GM job, before the friendly bounce of Allan Houston's
runner that saved Jeff Van Gundy's job. The Nets, wasting time
dressed up as Phil Jackson's leverage, could not have done better
than Rivers. But then, Rivers was in a rare position for a black
former player who wasn't a big box-office draw. He had some
leverage himself and was too smart to start at the bottom of the
ladder, set up to fail.
</P>
<P>
   So he signed with Orlando, which promptly jettisoned most of its
disgruntled veteran talent.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Doc, people said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor nothing,'' he said. ``We're not going to be rebuilding
very long, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magic has a bundle of bad teams' first-round draft picks
over the next three years, and salary cap room to kill for. These
are not amenities one should necessarily count on, but, as Rivers
said, Orlando's weather is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league is about recruiting now,'' he said. ``The money's
the same everywhere. And this is where Tiger Woods lives. Ken
Griffey Jr. Wesley Snipes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Snipes? Oh, right. ``White Men Can't Jump.'' And the
Magic, as presently assembled, can't win, except Rivers' team has
managed to hold its own.
</P>
<P>
   His players get to run and he tries not to hustle them. He
admits it is easier to tell the truth to what is, with the
exception of Darrell Armstrong, a bunch of role players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them my opinion and it doesn't have to be their opinion
and they don't have to like it but, so far, they do,'' Rivers said.
``If I had five superstars, I might not be able to coach the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had Latrell Sprewell, he said he would have had to say
that Sprewell didn't handle his return to Golden State too well. He
would have told Sprewell that his values were twisted, that shaking
P.J. Carlesimo's hand would not have been ``selling out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers added, ``But that's none of my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Van Gundy has copped out with the same attitude,
which is what happens when dissent becomes house rule. On a
healthier plane, some people believe Rivers has a chance to lure
Tim Duncan to Orlando next season, based on their relationship when
Rivers was broadcasting Spurs games. This may be a remote
possibility, at best, and the coach, of course, can't comment.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't on television anymore, free to share every who, what,
why and whimsy. He is a coach, his bio listed this season on Page
319 of the NBA register. On the opposite page, you guessed it,
Florida's other main man on the bench. Once again, Rivers is
face-to-face with Riley, who told him this is exactly where he
would end up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
