</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BEARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEA IN CHICAGO IS ALL WORK WITH SOME PLAY
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an experiment of sorts taking place in Chicago, and if
it is successful it could be a blueprint for how NFL head coaches
approach the game in the future. Bears coach Dick Jauron is the one
playing chemist, and so far he has been able to accomplish
something few NFL head coaches ever have: working hard while
simultaneously allowing himself, his staff members and his players
time for their personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept _ being able to succeed in the NFL, and also
spend time with significant others. During the intense NFL season,
in which coaches often work 16- to 18-hour days, it is the family
that often suffers. In a twisted sort of way, the more time a coach
spends in the office, the more he is seen by his peers as a
warrior, no matter what the consequences to a coach's health or his
family life.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil used to work 20-hour days as coach of the
Philadelphia Eagles, and the stress became so unbearable that he
quit football. Vermeil has since lightened up with the St. Louis
Rams, but he still routinely works extremely long days. Kansas City
coach Gunther Cunningham said this year that when he dies, he wants
it to be on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Jauron seems to have drawn a line _ it is a thin one, but a line
nevertheless _ between the maniacal demands of the profession and
the necessity of leading a relatively normal life. Jauron still
works hard, and expects his players and staff to do the same. But
he allows both groups to have a life outside of football. Jauron
figures that if that happens, then everyone involved will be
happier, and thus more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Jauron is speaking from experience. He was a longtime assistant
coach, most notably as the defensive coordinator with the
Jacksonville Jaguars, before getting the Bears job. He also played
eight seasons as a safety in the NFL, five with Detroit and three
with Cincinnati. When doing both jobs, Jauron always noticed how
much better he played or coached when he was allowed time away from
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jauron to me is an all-around person,'' Bears wide receiver
Curtis Conway said. ``I like his style. He knows there's more to
life than just football. I think he's one of those coaches that
knows we have families and knows that sometimes you just want to
get way and relax, because he played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jauron's staff still works those insane football hours on
Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday, getting to the office at 5 a.m. or 6
a.m. and not leaving until 10 that night. But unlike most NFL head
coaches, Jauron encourages his assistants to leave early on
Thursday so that they can spend time with their families. The same
goes on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jauron also asks his players to think about life outside of
football. Once a week during meetings when the team is discussing
its next game, he will stop and ask that they look at the big
picture, both in terms of the football season and their own state
of mind.
</P>
<P>
   If Jauron's positive approach sounds too much like a yoga class,
well, it has not made the team soft. The Bears are still a rough,
hard-working team that has yet to quit a game this season. And
Jauron is still a realist.
</P>
<P>
   While no one has studied the subject, there is a strong belief
among many people in the league that coaches have an extremely high
rate of divorce. One of the most talked-about subjects among
coaching buddies is how this friend or that one is separating from
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, part of Jauron's approach comes from the fact that he does
not want to see his own staff in turmoil. And the Bears' coaches
are extremely family oriented. Jauron and his wife, Gail, have two
daughters, Kay, 14, and Amy, 12. His defensive coordinator has six
children; the offensive coordinator and the linebackers coach each
has five children; the defensive line coach and the running backs
coaches each has four; the wide receivers coach has three; the
tight ends coach has two; and the offensive line coach and special
teams coach have one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to say exactly, but the Bears' coaching staff
probably has one of the largest collective families in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's real good for the staff to be able to get away,''
Jauron said. ``The fact is in our business it's difficult. Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday the staff will be working anywhere from 14 to 16
hours. On Thursday I really do like to get them out of here by 6:30
or 7 o'clock. Friday should be an early day so they have time to
spend with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jauron, so far, has been as tactically minded on the field as he
is compassionate off it. After 12 games his team is 5-7, when in
terms of talent, it is a three-victory group at most. The previous
coach, Dave Wannstedt, went 4-12 each of the last two seasons.
Jauron is 3-3 in the NFC Central, and Wannstedt never finished
above .500 in the division in five years as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Jauron can keep building the Bears, he might become one of
the first coaches in a while to win without wearing out his players
and staff. Maybe it is still a long shot. Maybe NFL coaching is
destined to always be a pressure-cooker job.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe at some point in the next millennium, Jauron's way of
thinking will be the one most coaches follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
