<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-SHARPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 SHARPTON CONDEMNS CRACKDOWN ON HOMELESS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rev. Al Sharpton Saturday denounced Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's recent crackdown on homeless people and called on New
Yorkers to monitor and report police efforts to sweep the homeless
off the streets. Sharpton said he planned to hold an all-night
``tent city'' vigil for the homeless at City Hall Park on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a packed room at a rally at the National Action
Network, his headquarters in Harlem, Sharpton called the arrests a
politically motivated attempt to curry favor with voters after a
brutal attack on a woman in Midtown two weeks ago. He was
surrounded by civil libertarians, clergy, advocates for the
homeless and Cornel West, the Harvard professor who is a leading
scholar of African-American studies and a best-selling author of
books about race in America.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said he would hold the vigil, where participants would
sleep on the grass and sidewalks of City Hall Park, with or without
a permit. He called the mayor's crackdown ``unfair, class-based and
in many ways, race-based,'' adding that New Yorkers had a
responsibility for ``protecting the rights of those who are the new
targets of this mayor, who has gone out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 19, Giuliani said that the homeless had no right to
sleep on the streets, and his police commissioner added that they
could be arrested if they refused shelter. That announcement came
three days after a young woman, Nicole Barrett, was seriously
injured when she was struck from behind with a brick. Investigators
have said they believe the man who attacked her could be homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crackdown was announced, police have arrested more
than 100 homeless people. ``Don't think that this is not an issue
that the mayor is using as a political tool in the Senate race,''
Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also has a policy that forces people out of
shelters if they refuse to work inthe city's workfare program.
</P>
<P>
   West criticized that policy, but he cautioned that the problem
was broader than Giuliani. ``He's just a symptom of something else
going on in this city,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   West said that, increasingly, even as the economy boomed, ``poor
people are being segregated by powerful people like Mayor
Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has defended his efforts to force people in shelters to
work and he has called the removal of homeless people from the
street a compassionate act. He has said his critics feel guilty
about what little they have done about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers said Saturday that if Giuliani really wanted to
help the homeless, he would divert the resources from law
enforcement toward job training and low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani supporters argue that he has done more for the homeless
than his most recent predecessors. The budget for homeless
services, now at $420 million, has been increased $30 million in
the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Those supporters also argue that the Giuliani administration has
put more money into mental health, substance abuse, employment
services and shelter security.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the planned City Hall Park rally do not yet have a
permit and will not be allowed to hold the event without one.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration has been criticized for its
reluctance to issue permits to groups the mayor disagrees with, but
the battle over this rally could become particularly sticky given
that city officials have restricted access to the steps and the
plaza in front of City Hall since August 1998, after the bombings
of American embassies in East Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
