<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT &LR;      11-27 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MANAGED CARE'S FUTURE  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Nov. 28:
</P>
<P>
   The recent decision by UnitedHealth Group, a big managed care
company, to let doctors treat patients without interference might
mark the death of one reviled tactic of managed care. No longer
will United have to approve, in advance, procedures that doctors
have recommended to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors resented the need for such clearance as an intolerable
interference by unqualified outsiders, and patients resented any
denials as cost-saving by the insurance company at the expense of
their health. To United's surprise, the advance approvals were not
even saving any money, so it ended the practice.
</P>
<P>
   But if the managed care companies abandon the requirement for
approval in advance, they will have to come up with effective
alternatives. Two less incendiary options are already available.
Someone needs to put a lid on physician charges. That someone, the
market appears to be saying, should be the physicians themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the first option, doctors operate independent practices,
decide what treatments patients need and submit the bill to
insurance carriers, which pay them at a negotiated rate. United
offers its enrollees a popular version of such coverage, a
``preferred provider organization'' that charges patients a small
fee to visit doctors on a list of participating physicians and a
higher fee to visit non-participating physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of approving doctors' recommendations in advance, United
will now collect data on each doctor's practice patterns over the
year. The data will be used to help doctors adopt their
profession's best practices. But those who habitually resort to
needlessly expensive or inappropriate care will be called to task,
perhaps even dropped from the preferred list. Patients can continue
to use these doctors, but only if they pay higher fees for the
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether preferred provider organizations can hold
down costs with retrospective review. If they cannot, their
premiums will soar.
</P>
<P>
   In the second option, physicians join a large medical group like
the Cleveland Clinic or one of the Kaiser Permanente medical groups
across the country. Such medical groups collect a fixed fee from
insurance carriers for each patient they enroll no matter how much
care is eventually required. Once the fee is paid, the insurance
company bows out because no more of its money is at risk. The
physicians take collective responsibility for treating patients
within their fixed budget.
</P>
<P>
   Medical groups typically pay their physicians a base salary plus
a small bonus tied to the overall financial health of the medical
group. But because the groups are large, ranging from a few hundred
to a few thousand physicians, the decisions of any one doctor
barely affect overall financial performance. No physician, then,
has an incentive to skimp on care. The problem for medical groups
has been learning to manage these complicated financial
arrangements. Many have gone bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   So where will these options leave patients? They can pick
preferred provider organizations with a wide selection of
physicians. But if retrospective review proves ineffective, this
option will become expensive. Or patients can choose a group
practice, where the choice of physicians will be more limited,
although some medical groups permit patients to see physicians
outside the group for extra fees. The lure of group practice will
be low premiums if, as is likely, doctors are better equipped to
discipline themselves than are insurance companies. Another lure is
that doctors working in teams should provide better care than
doctors operating outside the view of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to know whether managed care companies other than
United will also stop screening doctors' decisions in advance. But
if United has bet right, patients everywhere will have managed care
options that free doctors of day-to-day scrutiny by faraway
insurance companies. The market is driving insurance companies to
the sidelines because that is where patients insist they belong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ANDES-ADVENTURE-NYT &LR;      11-27 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDES-ADVENTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDES ADVENTURE RACE NOT FOR FAINT OF HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALICIA AULT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the rest of us lazily reached for the remote this weekend,
200 supertoned athletes from 31 nations continued preparations to
paddle, ride horseback, climb, rappel, schlep, scratch and claw
their way through the Andes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, these just-do-it enthusiasts will depart from the
northern Patagonia town of Bariloche, Argentina, in a 12-day quest
to claim at most $50,000, plus the 1999 Eco-Challenge title and
bragging rights for having completed one of the toughest contests
in adventure racing.
</P>
<P>
   With five disciplines _ riding, canoeing, kayaking, fixed ropes
and orienteering _ the Eco-Challenge is akin to a modern-day
heptathlon. The race's founder, Mark Burnett, says it's an
expedition. In a nutshell, the Challenge, now in its sixth year,
matches teams of four against some of the most demanding terrain on
earth. This year it's 300 miles of rugged Patagonian highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stanley and Livingstone, Lewis and Clark or Thelma and
Louise, Eco-Challenge racers must rely mostly on their wits and
resourcefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about chemistry and character,'' said Burnett, adding
that ``all the great expeditions of our time'' have depended more
upon human dynamics than money or endurance. He has tried to
replicate that spirit. Eco-Challenge racers are not given the
course layout or segment order until four days before the start.
</P>
<P>
   Racers have spent a year in training: scouting terrain and gear,
hitting the weights, learning to rappel off frozen waterfalls. But
the key to finishing, and to winning, will be how they respond to
the teammate downed by dysentery or the snowstorm that socks them
into a glacial cave for a day, or a horse that, despite carrots and
sharp heels in the flank, will not enter a darkened bamboo forest
after an afternoon on the dry, flat pampas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your preparation is really flexibility _ being able to wing it
on the fly,'' said Rebecca Rusch, whose Team Rubicon was undone in
the 1998 Eco-Challenge by bickering over a teammate's inability to
overcome fear and altitude sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Success depends on bonding, teamwork and maturity, Rusch said,
and ``being able to go slow, ask directions and communicate with
your teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Rusch is piloting the Atlas Snowshoes/Rubicon team,
which is made up mostly of women. She is joined by Cathy Sassin and
Robyn Benincasa, two of the best-known female adventure racers. The
fourth member of their team is Ian Adamson, a corporate trainer who
has had first- and second-place finishes in previous Eco-Challenges
and the Raid Gauloises and Hi-Tec adventure races.
</P>
<P>
   Top adventure racers tend to be in their mid-30s to mid-40s. One
American team of 20-somethings dropped out a month before this
year's race, fazed by logistics and the fear factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998s race in Morocco, 32 of 55 teams finished, but
Burnett expects only 20 percent to conquer the expedition this
year. ``Patagonia is known for having some of the worst weather on
earth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Patagonian peninsula acts like a big wind tunnel. Prevailing
winds run west to east, dumping thousands of millimeters of
precipitation on the mountaintops as they rush down to blister the
pampas.
</P>
<P>
   Being wet is a constant for competitors. Competitors will kayak
across 200-square-mile Lake Nahuel Huapi, canoe down a raging river
fed by melt from a record winter snowfall, and trudge across
glaciers as the race meanders through the Lakes District along the
Andean spine of Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold, wet and wind of the world drains the spirit far more
than steamy jungles or dry, hot deserts,'' Burnett said cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are heart-gripping ascents and descents, in which
racers must negotiate an elevation equal to Everest, with much of
the upward trip over rock and glacier at 30- to 80-degree vertical
inclines. Fixed ropes will help climbers teeter over crevasses and
crampon their way up ice falls.
</P>
<P>
   With no ``dark zones'' during the race, competitors can go all
night; 16 hours of daylight will encourage the workaholics.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eco-Challenge has never lost a racer, the danger is
palpable. ``Weather can close in and prevent helicopter access,''
said Adrian Cohen, the race's medical director, ``so it's back to
ground-based rescues over snow and ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hardships, Rusch said, racers always return.
``People forget how bad it was,'' she said, likening the race to
childbirth, ``and then they go back for more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
