<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO CLOSE TO CALL  
 DRUG POLICY IS REVISITED 
NOT QUITE A FULL SLASH
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-NOTEBOOK-BEARS) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at the playoff picture shows that a number of the
divisions are still very tight, and that a few aren't.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFC East: Washington remains the favorite, but Arizona at 4-6
has won two straight games and could create a four-team race.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFC Central: Only 2{ games separate last-place Chicago (5-7)
and first-place Detroit (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   _ NFC West: St. Louis will likely go 8-0 in the division and win
home-field advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ AFC East: Indianapolis has edged in front of Miami and New
England is fading.
</P>
<P>
   _ AFC Central: The race could come down to the
Jacksonville-Tennessee game on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   _ AFC West: Oakland (5-5) and Kansas City (5-5) need miracles to
catch Seattle (8-2).
</P>
<P>
   Drug Policy Is Revisited
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials met with investigators from the office of Sen.
Charles Grassley last week in Washington and told them that players
who failed drug tests in 1995 did not go undisciplined, a league
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, R-Iowa, is chairman of the Senate's Caucus on
International Narcotics Control. He began an inquiry into the
league's drug program following an Aug. 30 article in The New York
Times about the annual meeting of the NFL Players Association in
1995, the year a new drug policy was adopted. In videotapes of the
meeting, a union official says that 16 players who had failed drug
tests under the former policy and should have been suspended were
not suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Since the investigation began, NFL and union officials have said
that there were no improprieties in the drug program, and that the
16 players were disciplined by being monitored under the new drug
policy. On the videotape, however, the union's assistant executive
director, Doug Allen, says that the former policy had a double
standard, many times allowing star players to go unpunished while
other players were disciplined for identical infractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old policy was unfair,'' Allen says on the tapes. ``It
treated players differently if they had the same situation. And it
often depended on how the club felt about you and what kind of
player they thought you were.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Kozeny, a spokeswoman for Grassley, said the investigation
was continuing. The Senate investigators may also speak with union
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Not Quite a Full Slash
</P>
<P>
   When wide receiver Johnnie Morton of the Lions caught a
fourth-quarter pass that clinched Detroit's Thanksgiving Day
victory over the Bears, he raised his hand to his throat and
prepared to make a slashing motion.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the thoughtful intervention of a teammate _ tackle
Barrett Brooks _ Morton quickly lowered his hand.
</P>
<P>
   If he had completed the motion, he could have been penalized 15
yards for unsportsmanlike conduct and fined $2,500 for violating
the NFL's recent edict against the slash gesture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
