<HEADER>
A2705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-COL-EVANGELISM-NYT     11-27 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-EVANGELISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: EVANGELISM HITS THE ROAD TO FIND FLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIDGEFIELD, N.J. _ Has James Chavez, an earnest Jehovah's
Witness, lost his way?
</P>
<P>
   He's wandering the truck lot at the Vince Lombardi rest area on
the New Jersey Turnpike, a Bible in his hand and diesel fumes in
his nose. Shouldn't he be knocking on doors, rousting people from
Barcaloungers and dinner tables to encourage Bible study? After
all, it's a fact of life that if you have a doorbell, sooner or
later it will be rung by a Jehovah's Witness.
</P>
<P>
   But as a barometer of how busy and frenetic life has become,
Jehovah's Witnesses no longer count on finding people at home. They
have new strategies, seeking out people as they shop, go to work
and carry on their daily routines.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez often visits the truck stop on the northern edge of the
turnpike, urging the mud-flap crowd to shift to a higher gear.
Jehovah's Witnesses now try to get the ears of commuters at bus
stops, or joggers on the George Washington Bridge. Sometimes they
do ``toll witnessing,'' a kind of midair spiritual refueling of a
toll taker. ``As soon as we pay a toll, we hand them a tract,''
Chavez explained.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Lux, Chavez's partner the other day, said, ``Sometimes
they have 15 or 30 seconds with no one moving through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jehovah's Witnesses once carried their message almost
exclusively door to door. ``Nowadays,'' Lux said, ``if all you're
doing is knocking on doors, you're not talking to people.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true for sellers of vinyl siding and PTA candy, too, but
imagine if your product is spirituality. If you can't reach people
at home, try getting them to look at their relationship with God
while they're standing on the corner looking for the next New
Jersey Transit bus to the Port Authority terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Pity Chavez trying to spiritually engage a trucker from
California while engines roar around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Sikh,'' the driver told Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sick?'' Chavez yelled back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Sikh,'' the man said again.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed when they got it straightened out. The driver
showed Chavez a religious icon from his dashboard and Chavez found
a tract written in Punjabi.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez was welcomed by a woman sitting high in an idling
Peterbilt rig, smoking a cigarette, with a dog on her lap. He gave
her a pamphlet titled ``When Someone You Love Dies,'' and she
thanked him, saying her father had died recently.
</P>
<P>
   Jehovah's Witnesses like their reputation for eventually finding
everyone. Adhering to a literal reading of the Bible, they believe
they are divinely guided to spread the ``good news'' of the coming
kingdom of God. Lux, 39, who began going door-to-door as a boy in
South Dakota, says he fears that spirituality is being squeezed
from busy lives, making it more important for Jehovah's Witnesses
to find new ways to reach more people.
</P>
<P>
   They are running up against a human mutation of the late 20th
century: an internal caller-ID system that instantaneously sizes up
and disconnects unsolicited pitches, whether they're for fatter
wallets or thinner thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 23, a waiter at an Olive Garden when he's not
``witnessing,'' understands. He said that when first approached by
a Jehovah's Witness while growing up in New York: ``I blew them
off. She told me something about the end of the world. I was messed
up. I was smoking drugs. I didn't want to know about the end of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the second encounter seriously. And the other day, on
Anderson Avenue in Cliffside Park, he stopped a woman rushing by to
offer her a pamphlet titled ``Should You Fear the Apocalypse?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' she said. ``I need a job. Will it give me a
job?''
</P>
<P>
   Jehovah's Witnesses promise nothing, except that they will seek
you out _ even at home. One of the few people to answer Lux's knock
that day was a woman who rushed to the door with a poodle underfoot
and a child in the background. Lux politely said he wanted to
discuss the Bible. Given how harried she was, he might as well have
asked if she wanted to learn to tango. Her weary smile said,
``Maybe sometime, but maybe not with you.''
</P>
<P>
   But her stated excuse was just what Lux expected: ``I just don't
have the time right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
