<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-LABORERS     11-27 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-LABORERS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: MEXICO)  
 LABORERS WANTED, BUT NOT LIVING NEXT DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGVILLE, N.Y. _ Down a slate path, behind a row of hedges
and white vinyl-sided walls, Roberto Tobar Galvez, 24, shares a
small ranch house here with more than a dozen other day laborers
from the state of Hidalgo in central Mexico. Each morning they
gather on street corners in the hopes of being hired for
construction and gardening jobs that can pay $80 to $100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   But if a proposed law takes effect, he might not be here much
longer.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Neighborhood Preservation Act would outlaw dozens
of houses like Galvez's by limiting the number of people who can
legally occupy rentals. And it would give the town of Brookhaven,
which governs the area, the authority to enter homes _ in some
cases without a warrant _ to enforce the code.
</P>
<P>
   The law has touched off an emotional, racially charged conflict
in this eastern Long Island town, where day laborers have become an
increasingly conspicuous fact of life _ newcomers from impoverished
villages in Mexico and Central America in a mostly white hamlet of
15,000. And it has highlighted in stark relief a situation being
repeated across the New York suburbs as Hispanic laborers _ drawn
to boom-era jobs that no one else is taking _ find themselves
valued as workers but not as neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening in many places,'' said Stefan H. Krieger,
the director of the Housing Rights Clinic at Hofstra Law School.
``And behind it all is the lack of affordable housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has taken on a through-the-looking-glass quality:
groups that have long spoken out harshly against immigrants are
suddenly professing concern for their safety in crowded dwellings.
Landlords are rallying to the support of their day-laborer tenants
with impassioned speeches against discrimination. And immigrants'
rights groups and housing advocates alike find themselves opposing
a bill that seeks to improve living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the locals and the new arrivals, who began
coming here about five years ago as construction picked up on
eastern Long Island, have run high from the start. Some homeowners
accuse the newcomers of everything from littering to selling drugs
to molesting women to driving down property values. The immigrants
complain of beatings, harassment and constant taunts. A proposal
that would have banned open-air hiring halls here failed earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now Farmingville is riven by the proposed housing law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's backers call it a safety measure that would protect
renters from landlords who crowd them into unsafe houses. They
point to a series of fires in such houses across Long Island that
have killed several immigrants in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the day laborers and advocacy groups fiercely oppose the
proposal, calling it just another attempt to drive out immigrants.
They say the safety argument is a sham, since the bill places no
limits on the number of people homeowners can crowd into their own
homes and excludes rentals on Fire Island, where time-sharers from
Manhattan pack into beach houses like sardines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the proposed law, each dwelling would have to have at
least 150 square feet of space per occupant, not including kitchens
or bathrooms, and no more than four people could share a bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow the town to inspect rental apartments with
search warrants, by getting the permission of the tenant, ``or at
such other time as may be necessary in an emergency, without
consent of the owner, agent and / or tenant.'' To pay for the new
inspectors, landlords would be required to pay a fee every two
years ranging from $150 for a one-bedroom rental to $550 for one
with five bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Similar laws have been passed in Patchogue and Freeport on Long
Island and Mount Kisco in Westchester County, where building
inspectors and the police join to go on midnight raids. Krieger, of
the housing rights clinic, said that many towns in California had
imposed similar measures. On Long Island, the trend has led
landlords to create their own group, the Coalition of Landlords,
Homeowners and Merchants, to fight what they say are excessive
fines and an infringement upon their rights to use their property
as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Brookhaven proposal, violations would be punishable by
fines and jail time, but there is some confusion as to who would be
held liable. John Jay LaValle, a member of the Brookhaven Town
Council, said at a public hearing this month that it was aimed at
landlords. But advocates for the day laborers say the bill's
language is ambiguous and could be construed to be aimed at not
only landlords but also at renters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would punish people who are already forced to live in bad
conditions,'' said Nadia Marin-Molina, the executive director of
the Workplace Project.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rental bill's staunchest supporters are members of a
civic group called the Sachem Quality of Life Organization.
Margaret Bianculli, the president of the group, which was formerly
known as Farmingville Citizens for Immigration Reform, said that
she began pressuring local officials to crack down on day laborers
in the area after a man made lewd comments to her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rights of foreign nationals are taking precedence over the
rights of citizens,'' she said. ``We came to understand that we
were actually the underdogs; we were actually the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bianculli said that she resented the charges that the
members of her group are racist or xenophobic, adding that she
would have mobilized against the workers on the streets whether
they were Swedes, Germans or Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
