</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-MEDICAID-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SEEKS TRADE-OFF WITH DEMOCRATS TO CUT MEDICAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In secret negotiations, Gov. George Pataki is
pushing his Democratic rivals in the Legislature to cut Medicaid
spending steeply as part of a deal to preserve a program that pays
hospitals billions of dollars to treat uninsured patients and train
doctors, according to people involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.7 billion state program is set to expire at the end of
the year, and Pataki has not said exactly what he plans to do about
it. But Democrats and representatives of the health care workers'
unions privately say that the governor is using the program's
looming expiration to try to force reductions in Medicaid _
across-the-board cuts that he has sought nearly every year in
office, usually without success.
</P>
<P>
   The administration concedes that the two programs have been
linked in private talks in recent weeks, but insists that it has
not made renewal of the subsidies contingent on cutting Medicaid.
The administration also notes that it would not be bothering to
pursue the current negotiations if the other side had not signaled
a willingness to consider the governor's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the parties have indicated that they want to negotiate in
good faith,'' said one official close to the governor. ``We believe
that all the parties have an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The state program of hospital subsidies, the Health Care Reform
Act, is financed through surcharges added to all hospital bills,
inflating medical expenses. Pataki's powerful business allies have
urged him to reduce the charges, contending that employers end up
paying most of them through higher insurance premiums for their
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are enormous: New York's hospitals operate on thin
margins, and would quickly be unable to meet their bills without
the enormous subsidy created by the surcharges. The program also
pays to insure children in tens of thousands of low-income families
who would lose that health coverage if the program is not renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, each side appears prepared to force a standoff
with the Dec. 31 deadline fast approaching. The powerful hospital
workers' unions and their Democratic allies vow to wage political
war against the governor if he makes any move to scale back the
program or greatly reduce state financing for hospitals. But
officials close to Pataki privately say they doubt that he would
suffer any serious political consequences, given his popularity and
the fact that he is not up for re-election until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Reform Act was adopted three years ago as part
of a far-reaching effort to deregulate New York's health care
industry and open it to market forces. For decades, New York had
been one of a handful of states that set the rates that hospitals
could charge for all medical procedures, from an appendectomy to
open-heart surgery. The hospitals had no say in what what to
charge, and insurers had no say in what to pay.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, at Pataki's urging, the state stopped setting
rates. That change introduced an era of fierce competition in which
hospitals were forced to negotiate with powerful insurers over the
price of procedures that now total $16 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   But one element of the old system was retained in an effort to
shield New York's hospitals, many of them economically distressed,
from the full brunt of market forces. The state continued to add
charges to all hospital bills, although the charges are one-third
less than they were under the old system, to provide subsidies to
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The largest part of that money, about $780 million a year, goes
toward reimbursing hospitals for payments they cannot collect from
patients who are usually poor and uninsured. The second-largest
piece, about $540 million annually, goes to teaching hospitals to
train doctors who are just out of medical school. A third piece,
worth about $210 million, was created to provide health coverage
for low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   According to people involved in the negotiations, the governor
is seeking to wring some savings for the state by restraining its
fast-growing Medicaid program. The program, which pays for medical
care for the poor and the elderly, represents the largest part of
the state budget, totaling about $28 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the cuts that Pataki wants is not clear. But
according to people involved in the negotiations, he is at the very
least seeking an extension of a series of Medicaid cuts that are
due to expire on April 1. Those cuts total $1 billion a year in
federal, state and local financing for the program, and the
governor would like to renew them for at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who control the state Assembly have not completely
ruled out Pataki's proposal. But in the end, Democratic leaders are
likely to take their cue from labor groups, most notably the
leaders of 1199, the National Health and Human Service Employees
Union, who say they oppose any reduction in state support for
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has also indicated that he wants to cut the money
used to pay hospitals to train young doctors, though he has not
indicated how much of a cut he wants, according to those involved
in the talks. That proposal is likely to meet with stiff resistance
from Democrats and union leaders, who regard the money as crucial
to the survival of teaching hospitals. Their resolve is most likely
to be strengthened now that Congress has made deep Medicare cuts
for New York's teaching hospitals in the budget it has sent to
President Clinton.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some Republicans have suggested replacing the current funding
source for doctors' training with cash that the state is expected
to receive from last year's settlement of a national lawsuit
against the tobacco industry. But it is not clear whether Pataki
will do that.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has offered some inducements, according to those involved
in the talks. Privately, he has said that he is willing to expand
health care coverage for the poor and the uninsured _ something
that Democrats and union leaders strongly support, though they
would like to use tobacco money for such an initiative. It is not
clear how Pataki intends to do that, though he is said to be
looking into using tax cuts as an incentive for small-business
owners to provide health benefits to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest uncertainties the governor faces is the
response of the Republican majority in the state Senate. Its
members are closely allied with Pataki and believe there is a need
to cut health care costs. But they also want to avoid a battle with
the health care workers' unions, since they are up for re-election
next year, and given that they also want to protect hospitals,
which are among the biggest employers in most Senate districts.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Republicans in the Senate have stuck by the
governor, allowing him to try to negotiate a deal with Democrats
and the union leaders. But at the same time, some officials have
indicated that the Republican majority is prepared to step in if
the negotiations stall, possibly with a proposal to renew the
existing system of surcharges before they expire. It is not clear,
though, whether such a move would satisfy union leaders who are
calling for some changes to the current system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
