<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOME-BROKERS-REAL-107     11-27 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BROKERS-REAL-1075(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOME SALES, A WORD WITH MANY MEANINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the language of real estate, in which phrases such
as ``needs TLC'' can be subject to any number of interpretations,
perhaps no other term can have as many meanings, or be as much a
misnomer, as the word ``exclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   In communities where most listings are automatically shared with
other brokerage agencies through a multiple-listing service, the
term ``exclusive broker'' has come to be synonymous with ``listing
broker.'' The same is largely true in markets without a
multiple-listing service, notably Manhattan, although in rare cases
an exclusive listing may mean that potential buyers can come only
through the agency that has the listing.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``exclusive right to sell'' listings, as well as
``exclusive agency'' listings. In the Hamptons, the terms
``co-exclusive'' and even ``tri-exclusive'' are in use.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is an exclusive, and how does it differ from the
free-for-all of what is called an open listing? And what does it
mean in terms of how a home is marketed and sold?
</P>
<P>
   At its most basic level, real estate agents say, an exclusive
listing refers to a written agreement between a seller of a
property and a brokerage concern that binds the seller for a
specified period of time, commonly three to six months, to use that
concern as the primary agency for both marketing and selling the
property.
</P>
<P>
   While an exclusive agreement never guarantees that a home will
be sold, it generally obligates the brokerage concern to not only
use its best efforts to reach that goal, but to also carry out a
multitude of tasks en route. In exchange, exclusive brokers are
guaranteed that they will receive a chunk of the commission even if
someone else ultimately brings the buyer to the home.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative to an exclusive listing is an open listing. In
an open listing, which is usually oral instead of written, no
single broker assumes responsibility for marketing a home. Instead,
the sellers can use whatever number of brokers they want, with the
stipulation that only the broker that produces a buyer will receive
a commission.
</P>
<P>
   With open listings, however, sellers are usually left with the
tasks of fielding inquiries and arranging for brokers to show their
property. And for some sellers, that can be an exhausting
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an open listing, brokers know that other firms may be
representing the property, so they don't have any sense of having a
particular commitment,'' said Deborah Beck, executive vice
president of the Real Estate Board of New York, which, among other
functions, represents 3,000 residential and commercial brokers,
mostly in Manhattan. ``With an exclusive, a broker will do
everything in their power to make sure that the property is sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive listings have been gaining popularity in most real
estate markets for the last two decades, mostly because sellers
have discovered the benefits of working with just one firm.
</P>
<P>
   And the red-hot real estate market not only has made it more
difficult for property sellers to price their homes correctly, but
has meant that in many cases sellers are having to field multiple
bids on their homes, a process that an experienced broker can help
to manage effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the past 10 years,'' said Kay Brover, executive vice
president at Douglas Elliman, ``we've gone from a system where it
used to be only the owners of a seven-room apartment on Park Avenue
that got an exclusive to studios now getting exclusives.'' Ms.
Brover estimates that 95 percent of the apartments that are
currently for sale in Manhattan are exclusive listings.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of apartment tends not to be an exclusive? ``Usually
it's not the kind of apartment, but the kind of seller,'' said Ms.
Brover. ``Believe it or not, there are sellers who have nothing to
do but sit at home and be entertained by troops of people coming
through the house.''
</P>
<P>
   In most real estate markets open listings tend to be the
exception rather than the rule. And while some consumers prefer to
sell their homes directly, without a broker (the acronym FSBO _
pronounced FIZ-bo _ means For Sale By Owner), most list their
homes, via a written contract, with a broker.
</P>
<P>
   So is an exclusive broker different from a listing broker? For
all practical purposes, the answer is no, said Gilbert Mercurio,
executive vice president of the Westchester County Board of
Realtors. The term, he said, generally refers to a listing broker
who ``has an exclusive relationship'' with the seller.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what many consumers assume, an exclusive listing
does not _ in most circumstances _ give a broker license to hog a
property entirely for himself or herself. Indeed, brokers say the
opposite is almost always true.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that because state laws mandate that brokers have
a fiduciary responsibility to the seller of a property to obtain
the best price possible, brokers who have an exclusive listing
almost always co-broke the property with their peers in an effort
to generate the widest net of potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, most of the multiple-listing services that operate in
almost all parts of the country _ with the notable exception of
Manhattan, as well as a few other small geographic areas _ will
only take exclusive listings, said Mercurio.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio said that multiple-listing services generally want to
ensure that a single broker is responsible for the property, so
that it has both an advocate as well as someone to help resolve
potential conflicts or claims.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mercurio said, most multiple-listing services will not
let a member brokerage concern keep an exclusive in-house _ that
is, circulate the listing only to other salespeople within its own
company _ unless it specifically has the written permission of the
home seller.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the misconception persists that exclusive agents almost
always work solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the word `exclusive' should be used at all. It's
misleading to the public,'' said Sona Davidian, the owner of C.S.
McClellan Real Estate in Pelham. Her concern, she said, is that
real estate brokers use the word so pointedly, in an effort to grab
buyers, that people shopping for homes often do not realize that
they can generally see the house through a firm that they may
already be working with rather than the agency that bills itself as
the exclusive broker.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At one time, exclusives that were held in house were the rule,
rather than the exception. According to Ms. Brover of Douglas
Elliman, such arrangements in New York City, for example, initially
involved the owners of large, prestigious apartments, who for
reasons of safety _ and sometimes snobbery _ tended to give their
business to just one company, often the firm that managed the
building as well.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, however, co-broking took on a new appeal.
For one thing, more real estate properties came onto the market _
spurred by factors such as the large numbers of co-op conversions
in the mid-1980s _ and more real estate companies sprouted up to
serve that market. ``Little by little, real estate agents realized
that the only way they could rationalize the market was to control
a listing through an exclusive,'' said Ms. Brover.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers often have a significant amount of time and money at
stake in a listing.
</P>
<P>
   The letter that Fox Residential Group sends to prospective
apartment sellers in New York City promises that as an exclusive
agent for the property, the firm will, among other things, help set
a market value as well as asking price for the apartment; tailor an
advertising program; hold weekly open houses to introduce the
apartment to other brokers; keep a computerized list of customers
who see the apartment, as well as their comments; regularly speak
with the seller to review the marketing program and help in the
negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
   Once a deal is struck, the Fox letter says, the firm will
immediately furnish the buyer with the co-op board's requirements
and a co-op financial statement. Additional services include
meeting with the apartment buyer to review the preparation of board
documents, as well as coordinating schedules and meeting with the
buyer to rehearse interview questions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at closing time, Fox Residential promises it will visit
the apartment one last time for a final inspection, and attend the
closing in case a last-minute problem arises.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is free, of course. In exchange for assuming
numerous responsibilities, exclusive agents are assured they will
receive a commission even if another broker finally brings a buyer
for the property. In such situations, the exclusive broker gets
half of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Different kinds of exclusives carry different sorts of
commission arrangements. Exclusive-right-to-sell listings, for
example, promise real estate brokers that they will earn a
commission if the property is sold during its listing term,
regardless of who procures the buyer. But with an exclusive-agency
listing, the broker may lose part or all of the commission if it is
the seller of the property who finds a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions might be written into the exclusive-right-to-sell
contract between the homeowner and the brokerage concern reducing
or eliminating a commission if the property is sold to a specific
individual _ for example, a named relative or neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   In most parts of New York City, as well as the surrounding
suburbs, exclusive-right-to-sell listings tend to predominate, say
real estate brokers. But in certain parts of Brooklyn where there
is generally a dearth of homes for sale, sellers of homes tend to
have more leverage, so exclusive-agency listings have become the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   In certain markets, including the Hamptons, brokers say they are
increasingly seeing co-exclusive and tri-exclusive arrangements.
With such arrangements, either two or three brokers will sign a
single contract with the seller.
</P>
<P>
   Co- and tri-exclusive arrangements are still relatively rare,
said Judi Desiderio, a partner at Cook Pony Farm, a real estate
firm that has its head office in Bridgehampton. Nevertheless, she
has seen the listings become more common over the last three to
five years from sellers who feel that their properties will receive
maximum attention with such arrangements, especially since eastern
Long Island lacks the multiple-listing service that is common
virtually everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have developed here is a modified multiple-listing
service,'' said Ms. Desiderio. ``It's a home-grown phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   In brownstone Brooklyn, the area that is made up of communities
like Brooklyn Heights and Park Slope, co-exclusives are also
popping up more frequently. According to Christopher Thomas,
director of the Brooklyn offices for William B. May Co., co-broking
arrangements in his area usually come up when two brokers have
dramatically different marketing plans, either one of which may
benefit the seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sellers can often benefit from co-exclusives because the
commission set-ups encourage competition,'' he said. ``These kinds
of listings are different from those on multiple-listing services,
where agents may feel as though they have less at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   As for commissions, while they may sometimes be split among the
listing firms, they are usually all-or-nothing arrangements, he
said, with the entire commission going to just one of the brokers.
However, if a co-broker representing a seller rather than the buyer
ends up selling the property, it is entitled to a slice of the
bounty as well.
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate brokers caution that exclusives can bring out
the worst, as well as the best, in their industry. That is because
there is a natural temptation for an agency to keep its new
exclusive listings a secret until the firm has had a chance to
bring in its own buyers _ a temptation that multiple-listing
service rules requiring prompt dissemination are designed to
control.
</P>
<P>
   If the home is sold by the firm that lists it, the entire
commission goes to that firm, rather than being split _ usually
50-50 _ with another brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   According to some brokers, like Barbara Fox, the president of
Fox Residential Group, too many firms and their agents are now
delaying the co-broking process.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fox, for one, thinks the sharing should take place
immediately after a broker receives a signed listing agreement. The
letter that her firm sends out to attract listings promises that
Fox will disseminate a co-brokerage agreement with a detailed
description within 24 hours of signing an exclusive to the
company's list of more than 150 cooperating firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a lot of greediness,'' Ms. Fox said. ``It has to do
with the shortage of properties, as well as the fact that there are
lots of buyers around.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Peters, the president of Ashforth Warburg Associates,
a Manhattan-based firm, said that he was aware of a few rare
situations in which brokers who had exclusive listings held on to
those properties right until they were sold.
</P>
<P>
   More commonly, however, he said, firms such as his may hold on
to a property for a week or so before co-broking it, in order to
give its brokers a small marketing head start. ``We always ask the
sellers before we do this,'' he said. And, he added, ``we never do
it so that it is to the seller's disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
