<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain baring medical records to combat fitness rumors
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Seeking to put to rest questions about his temperament
and fitness for the presidency, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) said
last week that he will release his voluminous medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found 350 pages, and we're looking for more,'' McCain
said during a pre-Thanksgiving Day swing through his sun-drenched
home state.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the records would not contain any psychiatric
evaluations because he did not undergo any after his release in
1973 from 5 1/2 years in captivity in North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to gather records of his many hospitalizations had
begun before published reports of a whisper campaign about McCain's
mental stability, he said. The gist of the alleged campaign is that
McCain ``took too many elbows to the head in prison,'' as the
senator himself has joked.
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists, some McCain supporters and even some of his
Republican opponents have pointed at the campaign of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush as the source of the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has closed the gap with Bush in New Hampshire, site of
the first primary Feb. 1, and is gaining on him elsewhere.
Nationally, Bush maintains a big lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot disagreements on policy with Senator McCain,
but I think this whisper campaign is outrageous. I want to call on
Governor Bush to put a stop to this. It's not only an insult to
Senator McCain, but it's an insult to all Vietnam era veterans,''
said candidate Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign aides and several senators who back the Texan have
denied raising questions about McCain's fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl (R-Ariz.), a McCain backer, said he spoke
personally to Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) and Sen. Bob Bennett
(R-Utah) and that both denied any involvement. A report had
identified both men as being part of the orchestrated effort
against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES, BAUER PITCH EFFORTS TO THE RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Bauer and magazine publisher Steve Forbes continued their battle
last week for the hearts of conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes brought together a number of prominent conservatives who
support him, including Lyn Nofziger, a former adviser to Ronald
Reagan; conservative activists Morton Blackwell, Brent Bozell,
Richard Viguerie, Armstrong Williams and Paul Weyrich; and former
U.S. Senate candidate Bruce Herschensohn of California.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer launched the first abortion ad of the campaign, telling
Iowans he would expand ``the circle of human rights and dignity''
to unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   ``From freedom of religion to the emancipation of slaves, from
civil rights to equal opportunities for women,'' Bauer says, ``I
won't stop until every one of God's children is welcomed into the
world and protected by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa holds its presidential caucuses Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY SLAMS GORE ON FUNDING REFORMS
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley leveled his sharpest attack yet on Vice President
Al Gore last week, abandoning at least for the moment his plan to
avoid the negative campaigning that Bradley says has turned off
America.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, N.H., Bradley lit into Gore on the topic of
paying for political campaigns, a sensitive topic for the vice
president given the Clinton-Gore campaign's abuses in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attended a fund-raising reception at a Buddhist temple, one
of the memorable images of the 1996 campaign. He also ran into
trouble for the fund-raising calls he made from his White House
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, there were questions about where politics ended
and government began in the Clinton-Gore fund-raising efforts. Now
we hear that Cabinet officers are structuring their schedules and
their announcements so that the vice president can finance his
political campaign when his funds run short,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning Tuesday in Iowa, chided Bradley for making a
``personal'' attack and pointed out his support for campaign
finance reform, including public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATIC LULL BOOSTS N.H.'S VOICE
</P>
<P>
   USA Today's Walter Shapiro was the first to point out a
potentially significant scheduling issue for the Democratic
presidential candidates. Bradley and Gore are battling over
caucusgoers in Iowa (Jan. 24) and voters in New Hampshire (Feb. 1).
But after those two contests, five weeks will pass before another
Democrat votes. Twelve states, including California, New York and
Georgia, hold primaries March 7.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, the Republican candidates will slog through
South Carolina, Arizona, Michigan, Virginia and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Democrats end up with such a lull? Party leaders
refused to let Democrats in some of those states move their
primaries to coincide with the GOP primaries. South Carolina's Dick
Harpootlian, the outspoken party chairman, practically begged
national Democrats for an earlier date.
</P>
<P>
   Then New Hampshire moved up its primary to Feb. 1, to avoid
getting scooped by some other publicity-hungry state.
</P>
<P>
   So the Democratic winner in New Hampshire will have five solid
weeks to savor victory and sap momentum from his opponent. New
Hampshire, already an important voice in presidential politics,
speaks loudly next year.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
