<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOME-BROKERS-REAL-3RD     11-27 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BROKERS-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: seller's disadvantage.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katy Anastasio, the founder of Anastasio Associates Inc. Realtor
in Huntington, says she has noticed that most brokers in her area
will hold a listing for about a week _ or perhaps 10 days _ and if
they can't sell a home, will then put it up as a multiple listing.
``If all the brokers in my area would just cooperate and put their
listings into our multiple-listing service, then we wouldn't have
as much of an inventory problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hamptons, said Ms. Desiderio, ``I'm seeing brokers
holding on to properties in-house, and I think their hands should
be slapped.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of what is happening, Ms. Desiderio pointed to a
firm in her area that is currently the exclusive broker on a
multimillion dollar property in Southampton. ``They've had it for
six months and they still haven't co-broked it, even though every
firm has asked them to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Elliott, a senior vice president at the firm in question,
the Southampton office of Sotheby's International Realty, said that
his section of Long Island does not have a multiple-listing service
that requires exclusives to be co-broked. Moreover, he said, his
firm would be happy to co-broke the property if another broker were
to produce a buyer that his firm had not already been in touch
with.
</P>
<P>
   While the National Association of Realtors, which mostly
represents brokers who are part of multiple-listing services,
addresses the subject of exclusives in its code of ethics, not all
multiple-listing services handle exclusives in the same manner.
Indeed, according to Mercurio of the Westchester Board of Realtors,
every multiple-listing service has its own rules regarding
exclusives.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, some multiple-listing services, such as
the one in Westchester, require that their members report exclusive
listings within 24 hours, while others allow 48 hours. ``There are
lots of variations in the handling of such data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, which has no multiple-listing service, exclusive
listings are governed under the code of ethics and resolutions
issued by the Real Estate Board of New York. And the board
specifies that its members, among other things, cannot use the term
exclusive if an exclusive listing is a verbal agreement only.
Instead, it specifies that a broker has to use the term ``ours
alone'' while it is both advertising and co-broking the property.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the relative dearth of homes for sale in the New York
area appears to have given consumers more clout when it comes to
signing an exclusive contract. Peters of Ashforth Warburg says that
he is seeing more sellers look for some sort of commission
reduction when a deal is made in-house, especially when the listing
broker and the selling broker are the same person. In cases such as
these, he added, the commission is often 5 percent rather than the
usual 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of inventory is having other effects. Roger Novatt,
a managing director at Sumitomo Real Estate, said that his agency
used to opt for a six-month listing when it signed up an exclusive.
But lately the firm has been willing to take on an exclusive for
three months only, as a result of both the general lack of
inventory and the seasonal drop in numbers of listings in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers say consumers need to do their homework when
choosing the firm that will best represent an exclusive listing.
</P>
<P>
   James Ferrari, the president of Benjamin James Associates of
Manhattan, says that brokers will ``often pitch a high-falutin'
number just to get the exclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters urges consumers not to focus on the amount of advertising
or similar promotion that a firm may be willing to put forth.
``While most sellers are looking for promotion when they sell a
home, more often than not, promotion is not the cause for selling a
home,'' Peters said. ``When choosing an exclusive broker, you need
to consider three things: their ability to network with a
community, their pricing skills and their bid management skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in today's torrid real estate market, some brokers think
the last two skills are especially important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent of the time when I'm approached by a
seller, they need help pricing an apartment,'' said Ms. Fox, adding
that she has noticed that most sellers tend to have a ``very
difficult'' time when handling multiple bids as well.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas advises sellers to consult a a lawyer before signing an
exclusive-right-to-sell contract in order to understand exactly
what the contract entails. For example, with such an exclusive, he
said, ``you are essentially giving away the right to sell your home
to your sister or some other close relative.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anastasio, meanwhile, urges consumers to stay alert in
general. She has noticed that a trick some brokers play is to mail
information into their local multiple-listing service through
regular mail, rather than through electronic mail. ``That means it
can take three days for an exclusive listing to get into the
system,'' she said. ``Consumers need to be savvy and insist that
their broker put it into their multiple-listing service
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The complexities of the business of selling homes and the
amounts of money at stake have led to a predictable outcome. ``This
is an area that has a tremendous amount of litigation,'' said David
Clurman, a Manhattan real estate lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   One cause, he said, is that consumers often don't understand the
wording in exclusive agreements; for example, the difference
between an exclusive right to sell, which means that the broker is
owed a commission no matter who buys the property, and an
exclusive-agency agreement, which gives the owner the right to sell
the property directly without paying a commission.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements themselves can be open to interpretation, he
said, citing ``when an exclusive begins and when it ends'' as an
area in which disputes can arise. ``The contracts,'' he said, ``may
have tentacles that the consumer is not aware of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
