<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT &LR;      11-27 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDS HEATS UP AND KNICKS SQUEAK PAST MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chris Childs had become the prototype player for a
New York Knicks team bloated by last season's success and sluggish
in their defense of the Eastern Conference title this year. Like a
lot of Knicks, he had stopped staying late in the gym and kept
wondering where his passion for the game had gone.
</P>
<P>
   So he spent some extra time in the gym on Friday and found joy
in the work ethic. It paid off in the way he provided the support
system the Knicks had been lacking this year.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting miserably this season, Childs hit a pivotal
3-pointer with 48.6 seconds left to help the Knicks fend off an
Orlando Magic team high on energy and low on stars, 99-96, at
Madison Square Garden Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks (7-7) made up for their injury-riddled front line by
turning to Allan Houston (30 points) and Latrell Sprewell (30
points) for the bulk of the game. They had to have more, and that
is where Childs came in. Childs, who had 15 points off the bench,
came on to give the Knicks the extra kick they needed. His big
3-pointer gave the Knicks a 93-92 lead and just enough edge to hold
up against the intense Magic (6-7).
</P>
<P>
   The Magic was not fazed by a third-quarter flurry by the Knicks
and popped out on a 6-0 run to open the fourth quarter and take a
79-78 lead on a hook shot by Chris Gatling over John Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   After Sprewell's acrobatic catch of a low alley-oop pass from
Childs, which he deftly turned it into a layup in midair, the
Knicks began a back-and-forth exchange with the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy was searching his team for a life form, for
some sign that the sluggishness his players had displayed on their
nearly monthlong road trip was just a product of the schedule and
not a factor of complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're sluggish, they'll beat us,'' Van Gundy said.
``Orlando is a hustle team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magic has been stripped off all egos _ with the departure of
Anfernee Hardaway and company _ and filled up with paycheck-starved
players either fresh out of the Continental Basketball Association
or discovered on the lonely end of other teams' benches.
</P>
<P>
   The contract-fat Knicks, loaded with eight players collecting $5
million or more this season, had to find some motivation. Or else
watch the Magic slip away. And that is almost what happened at the
start. Without three injured stars on the front line _ Marcus
Camby, Larry Johnson and Patrick Ewing _ the Knicks needed the kind
of support the Magic had.
</P>
<P>
   For most of three quarters, the Knicks leaned on their two
guards. Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell combined to score 31 of
the Knicks' 49 first-half points. But the more diverse Magic,
getting hustle plays out of Bo Outlaw and picking up points from 11
different players, held a 50-49 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks were not getting offense from anywhere
but Houston and Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they're being ignored on the floor,'' Van Gundy said
of his bevy of role players. ``We have to make teams pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs started applying that logic late in the third quarter. He
scored eight points in a three-minute stretch to awaken the Knicks
and help provide them with a 78-73 lead entering the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic took a 54-49 lead to start the third quarter, leaving
an exasperated Van Gundy to take a quick time out. It didn't help.
The Knicks were still getting outworked by the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer launched by Abdul-Wahad bounced high and long, near
the free-throw line. As Ward looked at Houston and Houston looked
at Ward, the sprite-sized Armstrong sneaked in for the rebound when
it hit the ground and shot a jumper to put the Magic up, 54-51,
with 10 minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In response, a chorus of boos echoed through the Garden and
perked up the Knicks. After that forgettable play, the Knicks
picked up their intensity and found the help they needed. Childs,
who has been shooting 32 percent, hit back-to-back long-range
jumpers to help give the Knicks a 73-67 lead with two minutes left
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Childs came right back and nailed a 3-pointer a minute later to
put the Knicks ahead, 76-67, with one minute left. Finally, there
was a lift from the bench. Finally, there was a life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
