u s BC-BOAT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT     11-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND WARY OF ITS EASY PATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearing the midway point of an uncertain and feisty America's
Cup competition that has already seen its share of raised tempers
and fallen expectations, only one particular is etched in stone.
When the 30th cup match begins in February, one of the two
contending teams will be sailing a sleek, black yacht flying the
banner of the cup's current defender, Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time in many decades that the cup holder will
advance directly to the main event without undergoing preliminary
trials. But for Team New Zealand, this coast to the finals _ the
equivalent of last season's football-champion Denver Broncos
receiving a pass through this year's regular season and playoffs,
with a guaranteed berth in the Super Bowl _ is a double-edged
sword.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, TNZ is assured of a shot to keep sailing's greatest prize.
But, without having had to hoist a single sail in meaningful
competition, will it be ready for the tested winner of the
four-month-long Louis Vuitton challenger series, the third round of
which starts Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known from Day 1 that the lack of preliminaries could be
our Achilles' heel,'' the New Zealand syndicate chief, Peter Blake,
said by telephone from Auckland. ``We don't know how fast the
challengers are going and they don't know about us. And we won't
find out, for real, until we front up on the 18th of February.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Zealand, Blake is an exception to the rule that says
sportsmen should not be placed on pedestals. He is an unabashed
hero in his sailing-crazed nation, with the knighthood to prove it.
A Whitbread race winner, and the former record-holder for the
fastest voyage around the world, Blake was the captain in 1995 when
New Zealand clinically dissected the San Diego Yacht Club, 5-0, in
the cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though he is not on board this time, he is the
undisputed leader of the first Kiwi defense. So when Blake
announced it was in the country's best interest to put its money
and talent behind a single defender, as opposed to opening the
doors for multiple efforts that would fragment the resources, there
were some low grumbles but no true opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two new boats and we're out sailing them six days a
week,'' Blake said. ``I think we're probably getting better racing
among ourselves than some of the challenger matches. When a good
team, like the Italians, comes up against a poor one, like the
Swiss, it doesn't do them any good. It just wears out sails.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake points to other advantages. ``Our racing is very
controllable,'' he said. ``If you make a change to the boat, you
can come back and analyze it and know precisely why one is faster
than the other. The challengers can't do that, because they don't
know what changes their opposition is making. So I think things are
probably fairly level.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a gauge to measure exactly where Team New Zealand
stands, Blake would like nothing better than to coax a challenger
into some unofficial racing. At least one observer, the broadcaster
and former cup-winning tactician Gary Jobson, believes the entire
regatta may hinge on whether Blake gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for the challengers to win is to make sure New Zealand
stays in the dark,'' Jobson said in a telephone interview. ``If the
Kiwis get an opportunity to sail against a challenger for any
period of time, they'll have an understanding of how they match up
against that boat and, by extension, the rest of the fleet. So if
one of the top six or seven challengers gets eliminated and spends
a week sailing against New Zealand, they'll keep the cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, in accordance to a pact made before the series, the
challengers have ignored Blake's overtures. Whether they will
remain united after the third round, when the fleet will be pared
from 11 teams to 6, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on several occasions, the New Zealand yachts could
not resist the temptation to briefly trespass on the challenger's
course, and a boatload of TNZ officials, armed with laser
range-finders and other speed-probing instruments, are regular
spectators at the top challenger races.
</P>
<P>
   If Blake thinks he sees a weakness in his rivals, he is not
talking about it. And, while he knows that his 80-odd-person team
is made up of some of the world's top competitive sailors,
sailmakers, designers and meteorologists, he retains the humble
stance that is so indicative of his countrymen's collective nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to it, it's going to be a very close
series,'' Blake said. ``The instant that we start thinking we're
good, that's when we'll lose the America's Cup.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
