<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ATP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI AND SAMPRAS EARN ATP SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ Andre Agassi and Pete Sampras won their
semifinal matches at the ATP World Championship to set up a Sunday
final pitting the year's best player against the undisputed player
of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The final of the $3.6 million tournament is the culmination of a
six-day festival in which the eight top-ranked players in the world
played in a round-robin format to determine Saturday's
semifinalists.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, ranked No. 1 in the world, earned his place in the final
by disposing of No. 2 Yevgeny Kafelnikov, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5) on
Saturday. Sampras made the dream final complete when he beat the
hometown favorite, Nicolas Kiefer, 6-3, 6-3, in the second
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Against Kafelnikov, Agassi continued the streak that propelled
him through the round-robin stage without dropping a set. He broke
Kafelnikov's serve to open the match and never looked back, easily
holding his own serve throughout the first set while keeping the
lanky Russian running from baseline to baseline.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, the 25-year-old Kafelnikov opened a 5-2 lead,
tormenting Agassi with well-placed backhanded shots down the line,
a cornerstone of his game absent in the first set. The 29-year-old
Agassi stormed back, however, capitalizing on Kafelnikov's lapses
in concentration that culminated in the flubbing of a crucial drop
shot at the end of the second-set tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, 28, took the court in the day's second semifinal where
he overwhelmed the 22-year-old Kiefer, the first German to appear
in the ATP Championship since Boris Becker in 1996. Kiefer, a
native of Hanover, was cheered on by a raucous capacity crowd of
13,000, but was never able to catch up with Sampras' serve. On
serve in the second set, Sampras broke Kiefer in the seventh game
and the German never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Merely qualifying for his sixth ATP Championship final is an
accomplishment for Sampras. Sidelined since the U.S. Open by a back
injury, he entered the ATP Championship having played only one
match in three months. During his absence, Sampras slipped to No. 5
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   After a 6-2 6-2 thrashing at the hands of Agassi in the
round-robin preliminary on Wednesday, Sampras found his form as the
tournament progressed. Nevertheless, he has concerns about his
physical readiness for the final, especially against Agassi in a
finale that has a best-of-5 format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here, I wasn't sure how I would get through these
matches,'' Sampras said. ``A five-set match will be a real
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Agassi is guaranteed to maintain his No. 1 ranking
for the year. A victory, however, would fittingly complete his
two-year resurgence from also-ran to undisputed champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm inspired by what I accomplished this year,'' Agassi said
Saturday. ``And I always look forward to playing Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is not sure he will play as well as he did when he beat
Agassi at Wimbledon this year, but he is looking forward to the
match against the man he says is playing the best possible tennis
anyone can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be two heavyweights going at it,'' Sampras
said. ``This is a fitting way to end the decade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
