<HEADER>
A2717 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOOK-TEXAS-RABBIS-TEX     11-27 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TEXAS-RABBIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBIS MADE THEIR MARK ON TEXAS HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In Texas, Yom Kippur may not be a school
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Gefilte fish may not be as common as barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers may considerably outnumber rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Jews have not been insignificant forces in the
history and culture of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite, says author and former Star-Telegram reporter
Hollace Ava Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the relatively small Jewish congregations in tiny
towns and big cities throughout the state, rabbis have played a
prominent role in Texas history, taking on civic and spiritual
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rabbis have become visible,'' said Weiner, a Fort Worth
resident. ``They are called upon for lots of things. ... They are
educated outside the region. They bring something a little exotic
or erudite here that others don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jewish Stars in Texas: Rabbis and Their Work'' (Texas A&AMP;M
Press, $24.95), Weiner tells the stories of 11 Texas rabbis who
made an impact on Texas from the 1870s until the 1980s. But in
telling those 11 stories, she is also writing about the history of
Texas, Weiner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the rabbis told us something about Texas,'' she said.
``I didn't want it just to be a Jewish book. It's a slice of
Texana.''
</P>
<P>
   The book adds to the often-neglected scholarship on Jews in the
South and Southwest, said Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, president of
Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati and former rabbi at Temple
Emanu-El in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Jewish community has not done a great job of
presenting the story of Jews in rural and smaller town around the
country,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner's book is part of a growing interest in the history of
Jews in America, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although that history stretches back to before the founding of
the country, Jews began to arrive in large numbers in the United
States at the end of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging scholarship represents a maturing of the American
Jewish community and a coming of age, Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``New communities don't look at their history,'' he said. ``They
are too busy becoming Americans. It is only when a community has a
greater sense of security, becomes part of the fabric of a
community, that it takes stock of its history.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner begins her profiles with Heinrich Schwarz of Hempstead,
Texas' first ordained rabbi. The last rabbi profiled is Levi Olan
of Dallas, who took the pulpit of Temple Emanu-El eight hours after
President John F. Kennedy was fatally shot and preached about the
``shame of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, Weiner writes about rabbis such as one in Lubbock
who presented art lectures or one in Galveston who fought the Ku
Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis Weiner profiles share some characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Many, especially in the early days, were not exactly the cream
of the crop, Weiner said. The top-notch students and teachers were
often given positions in New York or other cities with larger and
more prestigious Jewish congregations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But those who came to Texas were often rebels of sorts, she
said. They were willing to bend some of the rules to survive in a
new part of the country, she said. Some understood that it would be
difficult to keep a kosher household in Texas, for example.
Although shellfish are forbidden in a kosher diet, Sam Perl, a lay
rabbi from Brownsville, was the chaplain to the shrimp producers
association because ``what was good for the region was good for the
Jewish people who were merchants in the area,'' Weiner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas rabbis excelled at reaching out to the community
beyond the Jewish congregation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Weiner recently heard a story from a man whose
brother was killed in World War II. The family, Christians, was
informed the day before Easter. Christian preachers were too busy
on Easter Sunday to console the family, so the town's rabbi came
and sat with the family for the entire day.
</P>
<P>
   Although the complete story of Jews in the state may not be
fully told, Weiner said she expects interest from Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of curiosity about Jews,'' Weiner said. ``I
find very little prejudice and anti-Semitism, but a lot of
curiosity. Many people have never met a Jew. They'll say, `Oh, you
are a Hebrew. Tell me about your church.' They may get the
terminology wrong, but they are interested.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
