<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHICAGO-CONDO-REAL-NY     11-27 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-CONDO-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDO CONVERSIONS GAINING IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JILL SCHACHNER CHANEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Almost seven years after he moved into a two-bedroom
rental on the top floor of a downtown high-rise here, Kenneth Green
finally got what he was hoping for _ a conversion notice.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 36, had moved into his apartment on the city's Near North
Side hoping that it would be converted to a condominium. As soon as
he received the conversion notice, he signed a contract to buy his
apartment and the adjacent two-bedroom unit, which together provide
panoramic views of the city. He paid a total of $540,000 and plans
to combine the two units into one apartment this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen other popular apartment buildings go condo and
decided to stick it out because of the location, the view and the
balcony,'' said Green, a senior account manager at Merrill Corp., a
financial printer here.
</P>
<P>
   Green's story is being played out in several downtown buildings
as landlords seeking to sell rentals find once again that condo
converters are their best market. The rise in market value
``becomes enticing to people that have been in the rental apartment
building business for five or 10 years,'' said Bruce Weschler, a
principal in Wexenthaller Realty, a Chicago development and
property management firm that sold a 303-unit rental apartment
building to a condo converter in February. ``Selling to a converter
is not an unusual exit strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weschler said his company had decided to sell the 10-year-old
rental apartment building on the city's Gold Coast to American
Invsco, a national condo converter and developer, because ``you can
make 15 to 20 percent on your money now, which you could not do on
a rental building.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sellers of these rental buildings are institutional lenders,
who foreclosed on the buildings. One of them, Household
International, based in Prospect Heights, a Chicago suburb, sold
the Gold Coast Galleria building, where Green lives, to a condo
converter because the converter offered the highest price,
according to a company spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   The number of condo conversions here in recent years is still
far from the peaks that were reached in the early to mid-1980s,
when tens of thousands of rental apartments were converted.
According to Tracy Cross of Tracy Cross &AMP; Associates, real estate
consultants in Schaumburg, another Chicago suburb, since 1996 more
than 2,750 rental apartments have been converted to condos and
sold. But this year nearly 2,000 rental apartments are expected to
be converted and sold as condos, Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   The converters themselves say that Chicago's booming residential
market and skyrocketing rents downtown have combined to create a
market for these new conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conversions are popular because they allow people to buy in
locations that are otherwise unavailable because the areas are
otherwise built out,'' said Herbert Emmerman, president of Equity
Marketing Services, a Chicago company that has converted 40 rental
buildings into condos over the last 25 years. ``Also they are more
affordable,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rents in downtown high-rises are now $2 per square foot a month,
pushing many renters to buy when they learn of the tax benefits of
home ownership. Moreover, because only one new high-rise rental
apartment building has been built downtown in the last 10 years,
renters are finding their options diminishing, said Gene Stunnard
of Appraisal Research Counselors in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Venverloh, 29, a lawyer with the Chicago law firm of
Katten, Muchin &AMP; Zavis, was displaced by the conversion of her
rental building to condominiums. Her one-bedroom at 401 E. Ontario
St., which she had been renting for two years, had been offered for
sale at about $150,000, but she didn't want to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   When she began looking for a new apartment, Ms. Venverloh said,
she was surprised at how tight the rental market had become since
she had last looked. ``I was surprised at how much rents had gone
up,'' she said. Eventually, she said, she found a larger apartment
for a cheaper rent, but it did not have her preferred location or
amenities such as a dishwasher and doormen.
</P>
<P>
   According to Emmerman, the 401 E. Ontario St. building was ripe
for conversion. The eight-year-old building is just four blocks
from the Michigan Avenue shopping district and is within walking
district of the Loop. Moreover, it had also been significantly
improved before Emmerman's company purchased it in a joint venture
with Draper &AMP; Kramer, a Chicago real estate development and
management firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was virtually nothing to do except for repainting and
recarpeting,'' he said. The apartments, which range in price from
$165,000 for a 700-square-foot junior one-bedroom to $492,900 for
an 1,800-square foot three-bedroom, are not otherwise being
renovated unless buyers purchase a separate renovation package. So
far, 324 of the 394 apartments have been sold since sales started a
year ago, Emmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Following conversion, 17.5 percent of the rental tenants decided
to buy in the building. Among those who remained is Thomas Nodine,
a 38-year-old management consultant who, with his wife, Elizabeth,
a doctor, purchased a three-bedroom apartment on the building's
46th floor. When the conversion began, prior to his marriage,
Nodine had been renting one of the building's junior one-bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   After researching the condo market, he and his new wife decided
the building offered everything they were seeking for a good price.
``We wanted a low-maintenance building that was beautiful and
convenient,'' he said. ``That spelled high-rise to us. Also we
wanted to be near the lake to go running or to go to the beach. And
we like the neighborhood. It just fit in nicely with our
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Campbell, a real estate agent with Rubloff Residential
Realty here, said buyers like the Nodines were getting apartments
at cheaper per-square-foot prices than in new buildings. She said
she believed that Green could not have bought comparable space in a
new building for less than $800,000. Also, she said, there is an
added value to living in an established neighborhood such as the
Gold Coast, where most of these new conversions are occurring.
</P>
<P>
   American Invsco believed the market for condo conversions to be
so strong in Chicago that it purchased for conversion two high-rise
rental residences across the street from each other, said Nicholas
V. Gouletas, its president of sales and director of field
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gold Coast Galleria, 260 of the 332 apartments have sold
in the last year. The mixed-use building, which sits on the
southwest corner of Maple and Clark Streets , has junior
one-bedrooms and one- and two-bedrooms. Prices range from $100,000
to $144,900 for a junior one-bedroom, $150,100 to $175,000 for a
one-bedroom apartment and $242,000 to $316,000 for a two-bedroom
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The other building, the Elm at Clark Private Residences, has had
a similarly high sales rate.
</P>
<P>
   Gouletas said more than half of the building's 303 units had
sold since March when sales began. Prices for the building's junior
one-bedrooms range from $92,000 to $144,500, from $155,000 to
$191,750 for one bedrooms and $265,500 to $312,000 for two-bedroom
apartments with balconies..
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that we wanted to own both corners rather than have
someone else buy that building while we were marketing the Gold
Coast Galleria as condominiums,'' said Gouletas. ``We felt that we
would have the same kind of purchaser for both buildings and wanted
to keep them from going someplace else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
