<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BECK28-COX     11-27 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BECK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PGA Tour card out of reach for Beck
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With three rounds remaining at the PGA qualifying school
Friday, Nov. 19, Chip Beck was tied for 126th. That forecast was
gloomy even for Beck, golf's perpetual optimism machine.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, he knew he was too far behind. Only 35 or so of the
160 golfers will earn tour privileges for the 2000 season, and
Beck, who has won more than $6 million during an outstanding
career, knew he was out of it. Even if he didn't want to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as Jack Nicklaus noted while watching his son, Gary,
at the Doral Resort this week, ``Chip Beck could be falling off a
4,000-foot cliff, and on his way down he'd be saying, `There must
be some place soft to land on down here somewhere.'''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no soft landing for Beck, a former University of
Georgia player, at the annual 108-hole torture test, held this year
on Doral's Gold and Silver Courses. Even Beck has finally folded
his mental tent. At 4-over-par and tied for 120th, he went out for
Monday, Nov. 22's final round with no chance and nowhere to play
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Weary from playing nearly every week for three months at the end
of the season, Beck has even buried himself in the Tour School's
other race, where the next 50 players receive exempt status on the
Buy.com (formerly Nike) Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it the best shot I had,'' Beck said after a 66 that
came too late. ``That's what I feel happy about. I've got a better
chance of having a good year next year.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, provided there's a decent playing opportunity for Beck,
one of golf's most affable personalities. Without a tour card for
the first time since 1979, Beck must write letters to tournament
directors for sponsor exemptions. Beyond the four events sponsored
by his corporate connection, Buick, Beck must count on a few
rewards for all the goodwill he's spread on the PGA Tour for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll think I'm a good addition to their
fields,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   But does all this depress a man who went through a period of 47
missed cuts in a row _ ``cancer of the golf swing,'' he once called
his situation _ and had to sell the family's multimillion dollar
home in suburban Chicago? Not really. This is a guy who saw the
positive side of all those lost weekends without a paycheck,
appreciating the extra time to spend with his four young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have golf a long time in my life,'' Beck said in the
lobby of his Doral hotel lodge, ``but at that point in their lives,
I think it was very important to their development. ... You know,
things definitely work for the best. I wouldn't trade that for the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck always has been the master of placing things in proper
perspective. He has been forced to do it during the past three
years just to maintain any semblance of sanity. Real tragedy, he
said, isn't failing to shoot a low enough score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built a house at about the same as two other friends of
ours,'' Beck said. ``One of them lost a child in a bathtub and one
lost her husband from a heart attack. ... So my wife and I feel
fortunate. Oh, we gave our house up, but c'mon, we have healthy
children and we're healthy and just have so much to be thankful
for. ... For me, I just didn't want to have the burden of worrying
about all that, worrying about mortgages.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been approached by people out of the golf business,
including an Atlanta mortgage corporation, but he still figures it
makes more sense to spend time on his golf game rather than
learning a new trade. At least this year provided hope, if not
employment security. Laboring since Jan. 1 with Dr. Jim Suttie in
Chicago, who helped Beck stop flattening his swing plane, he earned
nearly $86,000 during the first three weeks of September. In
1997-98, he made $21,000 in 61 events.
</P>
<P>
   Beck says half-seriously that he might just play the four Buick
events next year and take the rest of the time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in my life, I don't want to just survive and
just kind of struggle along,'' he said. ``That's just not much
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Beck finished 178th on the final money list ($137,423),
more than $300,000 was needed this year to make the top 125 and
earn 2000 privileges. Clearly, the year took a physical toll on the
PGA Tour's No. 40 career money-leader (more than $6.1million).
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should be out there practicing right now,'' Beck
said, ``but, you know, my body can't go through it now. I couldn't
finish the tournament if I was out there beating balls every day. I
played three months straight almost. It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Change has been constant for Beck. He and brother Albert agreed
to end their caddie/player relationship. After a three-year famine,
Chip said, ``It was just hard on both of us trying to pull out of
the doldrums.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck's house in Lake Forest, Ill., has been sold, leaving he and
his wife, Karen, and the children renting. Beck said the house,
once listed at $5 million, carried a mortgage less than the $30,000
that had been widely reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, I'm financially secure and
independent, and I don't have to worry about what other people
think or do as far as my finances,'' Beck said. ``I can play golf
or quit tomorrow and I'll feel like I had a nice career in a lot of
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not as satisfying as I would have liked to have
been, but if somebody can go through this lifestyle without having
some ups and downs, then my hat's off to them, because they must be
tremendously gifted.''
</P>
<P>
   A black visor pushed back on head, Beck glanced back and said,
``I'll prevail. Don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
