<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-HOFSTRA-LEHIGH-NY     11-27 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOFSTRA-LEHIGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEE HOFSTRA RUN. SEE HOFSTRA RALLY. SEE LEHIGH LOSE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Hofstra overcame a 10-point deficit and its
self-destructive ways Saturday to earn its first playoff victory in
Division I-AA, a 27-15 triumph over Lehigh before a crowd of 6,770
at Hofstra Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Giovanni Carmazzi completed 22 of 30 passes for 228
yards and two touchdowns. He also rushed for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra (11-1) could run. Jimmy Jones carried 23 times for 124
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh (10-2) could not. The Mountain Hawks' star running back,
Ronald Jean, managed 52 yards on 16 carries, forcing quarterback
Phil Stambaugh into a throwing marathon. Stambaugh completed 30 of
44 passes for 323 yards and had three costly interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The last one was snagged by Hofstra's Doug Shanahan in the end
zone with 4 minutes 20 seconds remaining, and the Flying Dutchmen
holding a 27-13 lead. On Hofstra's previous possession, receiver
Steve Jackson caught the last of his 11 receptions for a 6-yard
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra closed out the scoring by taking a safety.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra will be home again, against Illinois State, in a
quarterfinal next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Four key defensive plays maintained Hofstra's lead throughout
the third quarter and into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Damon Sinicropi intercepted Stambaugh's pass as
the Lehigh quarterback was being driven to the ground early in the
final period. Hofstra took over at its 30 and eventually got a
27-yard field goal by Chad Johnson to increase its lead to 20-13.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, Hofstra's Casey Mahoney stopped Jean
on third-and-goal from the 1, and broke up a pass intended for
tight end Bruce Peltzer on fourth down. Earlier in the quarter,
cornerback Lynde Washington wrestled away an apparent touchdown
pass to Lehigh's Avon Mack for the interception.
</P>
<P>
   With Hofstra trailing, 10-0, Carmazzi directed the Flying
Dutchmen on a confidence-building 87-yard drive. It ended with
Johnson's 21-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh parlayed Stambaugh's 38-yard completion to Kody Fedorcha
into a 20-yard field goal by Jaron Taaffe on its next possession,
but showed an inability to run that would plague them all
afternoon. Jean managed only 33 yards on 11 carries in the first
half, and Stambaugh, except for the long completion to Fedorcha,
did not make any big dents, completing 11 of 17 passes for 115
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Carmazzi, meanwhile, showed the smarts and skills that have him
projected as one of the top five quarterbacks in next year's NFL
draft. Mixing in a few rushes by Jones (10 carries for 55 yards in
the first half), Carmazzi connected on 15 of 19 passes for 175
first-half yards, 104 of those coming on Jackson's eight
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson drew an interference call on Abdul Byron in the middle
of the second quarter to give Hofstra a first-and-10 at the Lehigh
7. Two plays later, Carmazzi shuffled his feet a yard into the end
zone to draw the Dutchmen to within 13-10.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays and a punt followed for Lehigh. Carmazzi hooked up
with Jackson three times on the next drive. The last completion was
an 11-yard dart to Jackson to pull Hofstra ahead, 17-13, late in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra put itself in a hole at the beginning. Jones fumbled on
the Flying Dutchmen's first play from scrimmage, giving Lehigh the
ball at the Hofstra 33. Despite a penalty on third down that
prolonged Lehigh's drive, Hofstra kept Lehigh out of the end zone.
The Mountain Hawks settled for a 22-yard field goal by Taaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra's next possession gave Lehigh excellent field position
again. Dan Zorger's snap sailed over the head of punter James
McClary. McClary ran back to retrieve the ball and passed it to
Robert Levites, who was stopped at the Hofstra 35. This time,
Lehigh fully capitalized. Jean eventually plowed in for a 1-yard
touchdown to make the score 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Flying Dutchmen could have crumbled, but Carmazzi and their
defense would not let them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
