<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 11/27/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) FARMINGVILLE, N.Y. -- Nov. 27, 1999 --
NY-IMMIGRANT-LABORERS, 11-27 -- Day laborers like these in
Farmingville who gather on street corners in the hopes of being
hired for construction and gardening jobs have opposed a plan to
limit the number of renters who share a home. The proposed
Neighborhood Preservation Act would outlaw dozens of houses by
limiting the number of people who can legally occupy rentals. And
it would give the town of Brookhaven, which governs the area, the
authority to enter homes, in some cases without a warrant, to
enforce the code. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) STIMLJE, Yugoslavia -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REVIEW,
11-27 -- A Serbian man looks out at a Swedish armored vehicle
protecting civilians commuting in and around the chaos in Kosovo.
In Kosovo's ethnically mixed areas, the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees runs local transportation. The office of
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees is in charge of the return
of some 850,000 refugees, their temporary housing and their food.
It coordinates the many aid agencies that work around Stimlje.
(Thomas Drowzak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- MILITARY-RACE-REVIEW,
11-27 -- Both male and female officers with a variety of racial
backgrounds salute the Tomb of the Unknowns at Arlington National
Cemetery. Nearly two-thirds of military personnel who responded to
a recent survey said they had had a racially offensive encounter
with a colleague during the 12 previous months, and there is a wide
disparity in how blacks and whites see the state of race relations.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) POLLEPEL ISLAND, N.Y. -- Nov. 27, 1999 --
ABANDONED-CASTLE-3, 11-27 -- Bannerman Castle on Pollelpel Island
has fallen into a state of disrepair over the years, and the waters
of the Hudson have encroached on one of its turrets. In addition to
natural erosion, a number of incidents have led to its increasing
state of decrepitude. One such incident occurred in 1920 when a
powder house explosion injured three people and catapulted a
25-foot-long piece of stone wall onto the eastern shore of the
Hudson. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) POLLEPEL ISLAND, N.Y. -- Nov. 27, 1999 --
ABANDONED-CASTLE-2, 11-27 -- Bannerman's Castle, a Scottish
fortress, sits on Pollepel Island in the Husdon River. The island
is being restored by a fledging non-profit group, the Bannerman
Castle Trust. This year, for the first time, the state parks
department allocated some money to help restore the island. The
island could be opened to the public within the next year. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) POLLEPEL ISLAND, N.Y. -- Nov. 27, 1999 --
ABANDONED-CASTLE-1, 11-27 -- Frank Bannerman VIII, a furniture
salesman, is the grandson of Frank Bannerman VI, the former owner
of Bannerman's castle on Pollepel Island. The castle's structure
has deteriorated so badly that the island has been declared
hazardous and off limits by its current owner, New York State.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KIPTOPEKE, Va. -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- BIRD-WATCHERS-2, 11-27
-- Jamie Cameron, a field biologist, releases a hawk after banding,
weighing and measuring in Kiptopeke State Park. On the one hand,
the Kiptopeke watch is a place of serious business as Cameron and
other scientists run careful seasonal tallies on the state of the
species. But at the same time, the watch is a shared joy for the
many nonprofessional birders who stop by, the sharpest of them with
decades of valued experience. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KIPTOPEKE, Va. -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- BIRD-WATCHERS-1, 11-27
-- Jamie Cameron, a field biologist, watches from his bird blind in
Kiptopeke State Park. He captures raptors like sharp-shinned hawks
and American Gold Finch's, in hand below, for banding. On the one
hand, the Kiptopeke watch is a place of serious business as Cameron
and other scientists run careful seasonal tallies on the state of
the species. But at the same time, the watch is a shared joy for
the many nonprofessional birders who stop by, the sharpest of them
with decades of valued experience. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES, Nov. 27, 1999 -- L.A.-PARKING-2, 11-27 -- At
the Century City Shopping Center, valet parking service is free
with a $25 purchase of groceries at Gelson's, an upscale
supermarket. Residents of Los Angeles have come to expect valet
parking just about everywhere. Valet parking is so common in
Southern California that drivers of $70,000 luxury cars who would
not entrust them to their own teen-agers routinely hand them over
to complete strangers and sometimes assume that restaurants offer
the service, even if they do not. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- L.A.-PARKING-1, 11-27 --
In the region that perfected drive-through banking, drive-in
restaurants and where people do almost everything with their cars,
everything, that is, except park them, Jeanette Karnes of Valettes
valet parking gives a driver a customary rose at a party in Los
Angeles. Valet parking is so common in Southern California that
drivers of $70,000 luxury cars who would not entrust them to their
own teen-agers routinely hand them over to complete strangers and
sometimes assume that restaurants offer the service, even if they
do not. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MILWAUKEE -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- WELFARE-WOMEN-3, 11-27 --
Tanya Moore, 25, a former university student on welfare for the
first time, pictured with her daughter, decided to discuss her past
with other victims of domestic violence, ``so they would know that
they are not alone.'' ``I have a hard time trusting people,
particularly authority figures,'' says Ms. Moore. Ms. Morre,
molested by a relative during their grade-school years, continues
to struggle with storms of depression that interfere with her
ability to hold jobs and form relationships. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILWAUKEE -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- WELFARE-WOMEN-2, 11-27 --
At a ``Take Back the Night'' rally in Milwaukee, women protest
violence against women. One participant, Tanya Moore, said the
presence of ``everyday people, like you see in the streets, makes
me think, O.K., I'm not the only one.'' Without recognition of the
sexual abuse in the early lives of many women on welfare, it is
difficult for caseworkers to understand how such women arrive on
welfare or the multiple problems that persist as they leave the
rolls. Many never even consider raising such an intimate subject
with their caseworkers. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MILWAUKEE -- Nov. 27, 1999 -- WELFARE-WOMEN-1, 11-27 -- A
hidden history of childhood abuse helps explain the struggles of
Mary Rhoden, 35, who began the year as a promising student in a
motivation class mandated by Wisconsin's welfare program. Ms.
Rhoden never told caseworkers she had been molested as a child.
``Oh, like they care if I'm a happy person,'' she says. Ms. Rhoden
even went as far as to lie on a questionnaire meant to detect
depression, which has plagued her for decades. ``I just told them
what they wanted to hear.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
