<P>
   DEBATES _ WASHINGTON _ With a quote borrowed from an old movie _
``I paid for this microphone, Mr. Green!'' _ Ronald Reagan stole
the stage from his Republican opponents at a 1980 New Hampshire
debate. The tide began flowing against front-runner George Bush,
and didn't stop until it had swept Reagan into the White House. As
he prepares for his first confrontation with his GOP opponents Dec.
2, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas must face the fact that debates
have the power to dramatically shift a campaign's momentum.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday in (w) Washington and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHBRAIN _ WASHINGTON _ Is Texas Gov. George W. Bush smart and
does it matter? His Yale grades weren't great and he flunked the
pop quiz, but he's got a platoon of advisors and his supporters say
that's good enough. A look at a would-be president's intellect _
and at how he stacks up against the competition _ as a prelude to
the Dec. 2 debate. (Heath, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story will be moved by the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-NOTES _ Mark Sherman's political notes. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ANESTHESIA-WAR _ WASHINGTON _ Who will put you to sleep? The
controversy over the use of specially-trained nurses to administer
anesthesia at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Md.,
is part of a larger struggle between physician-anesthesiologists
and certified registered nurse anesthetists (CRNAs). The nurses
argue that they were administering anesthesia before the medical
speciality of anesthesiology even existed and say they are fully
trained to give patients the pain-blocking and sleep-inducing
drugs. Anesthesiologists say the science is much more complex than
it was 100 years ago and the danger of sudden complications
requires the presence of a physician specialist. Not only military
medicine but Medicare and Medicaid payments are at stake. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH _ WASHINGTON _ When European and U.S. trade negotiators
square off next week over the issue of genetically modified crops,
much will be riding on the outcome for a third group with very
little influence _ poor countries. Consumers in Europe and the
United States are up in arms over the fact that U.S.-produced food
items often contain undisclosed ingredients that come from
genetically-manipulated crops, and U.S. corporate interests argue
that there is no difference in these products and traditional
foods. But in places like Sierra Leone and India, the hope of more
productive crops from genetically altered plants could spell the
difference between hunger and famine. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUTO _ WASHINGTON _ An exhibit titled ``See the USA:
Automobile Travel and the American Landscape'' has just opened at
the National Building Museum. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIVIDE _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ In the spring, the Serbs
sought to drive ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. Since NATO troops
rolled into the province, the Albanians have been returning the
favor, killing hundreds of Serbs and burning their houses and
driving them out. Now the Serbs as well as Gypsies are a vulnerable
population who live in fear of constant reprisals. Aid workers
worry that the international community made a fatal error by
treating the end of the war as a triumph of the Albanians over the
Serbs, thus creating an environment that emboldened revenge seeking
Albanians. They also worry that the outside world - particularly
the donor community - will lose sympathy for the Albanians.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTO and information for
locator map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tues., Nov. 23, in (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Murder, arson and
jail time. These are not the sort of credentials that make for a
successful political career. But this is Russia and, more
specifically St. Petersburg, where the politics is not just
bare-knuckled, it is deadly. Yuri Shutov, a member of the local
city council, wants to be elected to the national parliament, the
Duma, in the Dec. 19 elections. He's running for office from a grim
prison cell. A political maverick, Shutov was been arrested for
murder and arson last February. He claims that he has been framed
by political enemies. Until he is formally charged and a trial date
has been set, he's free to hold his local office and run for a seat
in Moscow. A look at the rough world of Russia's democracy in
action. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SAINT _ About 60,000 people visited the remains of St. Therese
at St. Jude in suburban Boca Raton, double what church
</P>
<P>
   officials had predicted. Her remains were moved from the church
to Hollywood without event Saturday after Bishop Anthony J.
O'Connell said
</P>
<P>
   the mass. (Shannon, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   HATE _ Nationwide, the American Jewish Committee is pushing
anti-hate posters and bumper stickers to remind us all that hate is
a bad thing. There are some notable local educators pledging their
support and the information will be distributed in local schools
starting Monday. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   SANTA-TRAIN _ DANTE, Va. _ She always wanted to ride the Santa
Train. Growing up a coal miner's daughter, she stood beside the
tracks every year awaiting the caboose carrying the jolly bearded
man who tossed out candy and early Christmas presents to the
children of Appalachia. But Vickie Addington didn't live to realize
her dream. She died the night before the train made its annual
trip. (Dart, Cox News Service). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NORAP _ NEW ORLEANS _ The newest, hottest rappers live in a New
Orleans subdivision called English Turn (Mike Ditka is there too).
Cash Money Records and its top rapper Juvenile filmed a mini movie
in the housing project where he grew up. Juvenile has a CD coming
out in December and Cash Money's movie will go straight to video in
December as well. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
