<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRISH-UNIONISTS-BOS &LR;      11-27 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-UNIONISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER UNIONISTS RATIFY POWER-SHARING PLAN, WITH A CAVEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Ending a century during which they were seen as
Europe's most steadfast rejectionists, Ulster Unionists Saturday
approved a compromise that will usher in a new era of power sharing
with Irish nationalists and could end the political stalemate in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprise move, the Ulster Unionist Party Council and
its leader David Trimble added a condition to the endorsement:
Unless the party has evidence that its adversary, the Irish
Republican Army, is turning in its arms by sometime in February,
Trimble and three Unionist members will resign from the new
coalition local government, collapsing it.
</P>
<P>
   By adding the last-minute amendment, Trimble defers until
February the party's final decision on whether to stay in the
power-sharing government, which is expected to be formed next week
with the IRA's political ally, Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 829 delegates who voted Saturday, 480, or 58 percent,
endorsed the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's supporters said the amendment was needed to reassure
delegates who were reluctant to drop the party's policy of refusing
to form a power-sharing government until the IRA had begun to
disarm.
</P>
<P>
   If the compromise was supposed to be an example of trust
developing between the Ulster Unionists, who represent most
Protestants in Northern Ireland, and Irish republicans, who
supported the IRA's violent campaign to end British control of
Northern Ireland, the condition on disarmament underscored the
remaining gulf between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said the February
deadline amounted to a precondition that is not part of the Good
Friday Agreement of 1998, which calls for the decommissioning of
paramilitary weapons by May but does not dictate when the
decommissioning should start. Nor was the deadline a subject of
negotiations led by George Mitchell, the former US senator from
Maine who brokered the original agreement, then spent most of the
last three months fashioning a compromise to implement it.
</P>
<P>
   Adams told the BBC the deadline ``will fuel the uncertainty, and
it will also keep alive the hope of the rejectionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Sinn Fein officials said Satgurday night the deadline will
appear to the IRA as a unilateral demand from unionists, which the
IRA would reject.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were also miffed by the terse challenge Trimble
aimed at Adams after Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clears the stalemate we've had in terms of process,''
Trimble said. ``We've done our bit. And Mr. Adams, it's over to
you. We've jumped. You follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over IRA weapons has stalled the implementation of
the Good Friday Agreement, and the peace process in general, for
more than a year. Under the compromise, Trimble agreed to drop his
party's demand for IRA weapons before forming the power-sharing
government in exchange for the IRA's commitment to have one of its
members begin meeting with retired Canadian General John de
Chastelain, who is in charge of an international body overseeing
the disarming of paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member Cabinet that will run that government, including
two from Sinn Fein, is expected to be nominated on Monday. On
Tuesday, the British Parliament will begin the process of
devolution, or returning power to the Belfast assembly, which was
created last year under the Good Friday Agreement but suspended in
July because of the weapons dispute. By Thursday, the process is
expected to be complete and local government would be returned to
Northern Ireland for the first time since 1972, when direct rule
from London was imposed at the height of the battles between the
minority Catholics and ruling Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, who had been hoping for at least 60 percent of
Saturday's vote, called the 58 percent ``a clear endorsement.'' He
got the backing he needed after three hours of debate, some of it
emotional, inside the Waterfront Hall, a riverside auditorium that
is a symbol of a new, prosperous, and relatively peaceful Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a heckler suggested Trimble had disgraced the
memory of Robert Bradford, an Ulster Unionist member of Parliament
who was murdered by the IRA in 1981. In a dramatic response,
Trimble quoted from a letter he said Bradford's widow had written
him, encouraging him to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a surreal moment when a delegate opposed to the
compromise, Jean Coulter, rose and said she wanted to refer to
``the greatest family of resistance in the world _ the Von
Trapps.'' She then quoted from the song ``Edelweiss,'' from the
film ``The Sound of Music,'' which includes the line, ``Bless my
homeland forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's deputy leader, John Taylor, reversed himself and
backed Trimble after being assured the February deadline would be
added. Party insiders say Taylor's conversion clinched the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One delegate, Tom Walton, 79, said the Ulster Unionists had
succeeded by dispelling claims they were inflexible and by
pressuring the republican movement to prove it was sincere in
wanting to transform the debate over Northern Ireland's status to
one that is exclusively political.
</P>
<P>
   Walton, who served in the British Army, said he believed Adams
was sincere in wanting to use only politics to advance the cause of
a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the IRA can prove whether they're sincere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sinn Fein officials privately said the new deadline
undermines all the diplomacy that has sought to defuse the dispute
over unionist demands for weapons and to make the relinquishing of
weapons voluntary. Many in the IRA equate turning in guns with
surrender, something they insist they did not do when they called a
cease-fire to help the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trimble's taken down one hurdle and put up another,'' one
senior Sinn Fein official complained, speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, whose high-pressure efforts to secure a compromise in
July failed, welcomed the Ulster Unionist endorsement, but steered
clear of the controversy surrounding the February deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who spent nearly three months getting Trimble and
Adams to talk to each other in private and fashion a compromise,
said Saturday's vote was encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction is the correct one,'' Mitchell said, using
language meant to praise Trimble without directly challenging
Adams's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA and Sinn Fein will be under intense pressure, including
from the White House, to make at least a token gesture on weapons.
President Clinton had urged Trimble to break the impasse and form
the power-sharing government, saying Trimble could ``walk away'' if
the IRA reneges on commitments to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   As he ducked into a car amid both cheers and jeers outside the
Waterfront Hall, Trimble had survived a near revolt in his party,
but he might have only put off the day of reckoning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
