<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSHBRAIN28-COX     11-27 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHBRAIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A look at Bush's approach to intellect
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He flunked a foreign leaders pop quiz, doesn't know
a Greek from a ``Grecian,'' was a C-average college student, can't
remember what, if anything, he liked to read as a boy and admits
that, even today, he doesn't care to read weighty books on public
policy, a subject that would seem a natural for the governor of the
second most-populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, educated at Yale and Harvard, doesn't
purport to be ``any great genius, but I'm plenty smart,'' as he
told Time magazine this month. On the campaign trail and in
interviews, Bush is self-assured, often cocky, bent on showing that
he's a decisive man of action, not an egghead.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bush travels to New Hampshire, site of the first
primary on Feb. 1, to debate his GOP rivals for the first time. He
enters as the front-runner, but with his foreign policy gaffes,
publication of his Yale grades in The New Yorker magazine and a
spate of news stories probing his intelligence, some political
pundits say Bush needs to prove that he has the depth to lead the
world's most powerful nation.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't show he's got that, they say, he should stay calm
and exude a sense of confidence instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to do a treatise on the State of the Union or
address the hot spots of the world,'' said New York pollster John
Zogby. ``He merely has to in some way show that he's up to the job,
and that can be like Jack Kennedy, who was better when he didn't
know the answer than when he did. What Kennedy was able to do was
in some way poke fun at the questioner and with a wink of his eye
suggest, `Look, I may not be able to answer your question right
now, but everything's under control.'''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Bush became testy when a Boston television reporter
asked him to name the leaders of Chechnya, Taiwan, Pakistan and
India. Late-night television hosts ran with jokes and some news
stories followed asking how smart Bush is.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nonpartisan firm Zogby International's clients is the
Boston television station that popped the pop quiz. Zogby said he
plans to survey voters after the debate to determine just how much
they care about what he calls a presidential candidate's
``knowledgeability.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Republican pollster Witt Ayers said he believes
the pop quiz didn't change the way voters perceive Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only effect the pop quiz had was the same effect the
cocaine question had, and that is to damage the reputation of the
American press rather than Governor Bush,'' Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   Should he win the nomination, Bush could face Harvard graduate
Al Gore, a vice president with well-known wonkish tendencies, or
former Sen. Bill Bradley, a Princeton graduate and Rhodes Scholar
often compared with Adlai Stevenson, the intellectuals' political
poster-child from the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   DO VOTERS CARE?
</P>
<P>
   Is Bush smart enough to handle the job he so ardently seeks?
What does it mean for a president to be smart? Do voters care about
smarts at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not particularly,'' Zogby said. ``Harding was not smart.
Questions were raised about Jerry Ford, who was not elected, but he
was president. No one is going to argue that Ronald Reagan was a
rocket scientist. In fact, he beat a rocket scientist. The issue
isn't so much knowledgeability as it is being up to the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign handlers describe him as a quick study, an
active participant in briefings whose get-to-the-point questions
help them shape his stances into policies. Bush has rolled out
policy proposals on education and defense in speeches heavily
promoted by his campaign. He delivered the latest, on foreign
affairs, in California on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've dealt with some people who are afraid to say they don't
know,'' said Josh Bolten, who coordinates Bush's policy teams,
prepares briefings and sits in on sessions with the candidate and
his advisers. ``I've never seen him try to fake it. He will
interrupt the conversation any time that he doesn't know a
particular fact. He knows a lot and he is very comfortable with
what he doesn't know. This guy raises his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Armitage, a member of Bush's foreign policy team and an
assistant defense secretary under former President Reagan, said
that he occasionally recommends reading for the governor, but that
Bush prefers the give-and-take of meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all made suggestions on what he might want to look
at,'' Armitage said. ``But generally it comes in the talking about
these matters. . . . On Japan, he's got a very strong view that
Japan is our strategic partner in Asia. . . . What he wouldn't have
known and didn't know was the history of how we got to where we
are. We fill in the blanks that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Bush's eight-person defense team also advised
Presidents Reagan and Bush. The team is headed by former Stanford
University provost Condoleezza Rice. On education, Bush is getting
help from Diane Ravitch, who served as assistant education
secretary in President Bush's administration, and former Education
Secretary Bill Bennett, among others. Bush has an economics team,
too.
</P>
<P>
   AVOIDING MANIPULATION
</P>
<P>
   Critics call Bush's willingness to seek advice laudable, but
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with experts is that if the president himself is
not smart and well-informed, even a president with the best
intentions can be misled,'' said Paul Begala, a former aide to
President Clinton who said he thinks Bush is smart but
``uncurious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to vest that much power in advisers,'' said
Begala, a former Austin, Texas, resident. ``I know very well the
influence briefers may have in what they do and do not tell the
president. . . . If you want to have your finger on the
thermonuclear button, if you want to write budgets of $1.5 trillion
a year of our money, then you want to bone up a bit. It helps to be
curious.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas political scientist, says
Bush has, ``ample intellectual candle power to be president.'' He
agrees with Begala that an unprepared president runs the risk of
being manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know enough to prevent that,'' Buchanan said.
``But that's not the same as being a policy wonk or a deep student
of any particular policy area. . . . It is a job that requires a
lot of study and he's in the midst of that study right now. Other
presidents or potential presidents have had to go to school. Ronald
Reagan was going to school on foreign policy after his
inauguration, literally taking seminars on foreign policy in the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of New Hampshire voters who turned out Monday to meet
Bush during a day of campaigning said they weren't swayed by Bush's
pop quiz performance. They think he's smart enough to be president,
though they aren't quite sure how they know it.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Ellis, 75, struck out Bush's father when the two were on
rival high school baseball teams in 1942. A veteran, he said he
considered supporting Arizona Sen. John McCain, a POW in North
Vietnam who has pulled even with Bush in polls in New Hampshire and
Iowa, crucial early caucus states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because of the son and father thing,'' Ellis said,
explaining his decision to go with Bush. ``We need someone to be
honest and great for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith Guimont said Bush must be smart to have made it so far in
life. She hopes people will give him a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, although the president has the final say, he really
goes with the strength of his advisers is the way I look at it,''
she said. ``I don't think one man is totally in charge of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, still trying to decide whom to back, also will be
watching. Richard Goodman, a retired University of New Hampshire
professor, said he's leaning toward Bradley. But he came to meet
Bush at a campaign stop in Seabrook, N.H., because he's curious
about the education reforms the governor has been touting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't just be glib,'' Goodman said. ``He's really got to
show that he's got what it takes to lead us into the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
