u s BC-RAC-REMSEN-NYT &LR;      11-27 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-REMSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENWOOD LAKE FOLLOWS HIS OWN ROUTE TO WIN REMSEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Greenwood Lake continued his unusual advance on the
Kentucky Derby Saturday when he won the 86th Remsen Stakes at
Aqueduct by a head after a furious rush down the muddy homestretch.
He has become one of the early favorites for the Derby without
taking the traditional route through the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old son of Meadowlake turned out to be the star of
New York's final day of major racing this year. Greenwood Lake was
flanked in the spotlight by the filly Jostle, who won the
Demoiselle by a head, and by late starter Affirmed Success, who won
the Cigar Mile by five lengths.
</P>
<P>
   For the hero of the cast, Greenwood Lake, it was a calculated
risk not to race against the country's best juveniles in the
Breeders' Cup three weeks ago. It was won by the 30-1 long shot
Anees, who buried some highly favored young runners. Nick Zito, the
trainer of Greenwood Lake, said he would rather not push his colt
through a race that has not produced a Derby winner in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greenwood Lake wasted no time staking a claim for the
juvenile championship, which has not produced a Derby winner in 20
years. Meanwhile, the Remsen has produced five Derby winners,
including Zito's Go for Gin six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tons of class,'' Zito said Saturday in the winner's
circle. ``I think he was equally impressive as Anees was in the
Breeders' Cup Juvenile. I think my horse warrants championship
consideration. No matter how you look at it, it's going to be close
for the 2-year-old championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood Lake ran for the first time in 7 1-2 weeks and closed
a remarkably successful year, winning three of five starts with a
major score in the Champagne Stakes and a close second in the
Belmont Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the mile and an eighth Saturday under Jean-Luc Samyn in
1:50 3/5, paid $4.10 for a $2 bet to win and earned $120,000 of the
$200,000 purse. He raced at the back of the pack for most of the
route, then circled six wide into the stretch and caught Un Fino
Vino by a head in the final stride, with Polish Mine third by a
neck in a three-horse photo finish.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed Success scored after running in the Breeders' Cup _ but
he did not run much there, finishing 12th under Jerry Bailey in the
Sprint. Yet, he came back Saturday and ran away with the $350,000
Cigar Mile, a race he entered after the favored Artax was withdrawn
on Thursday with a leg injury that forced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmed Success took the lead after three-quarters of a mile
and widened it to five lengths over Adonis, the stablemate of
Artax, who had nearly a length on Honorifico. The winner ran the
mile in 1:34 under Jorge Chavez, returned $7.90 and banked
$210,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Breeders' Cup Sprint was a complete throw-out,'' said
Richie Schosberg, who trains Affirmed Success for Albert Fried Jr.
``He vindicated himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the $200,000 Demoiselle, which was run for the 78th time,
Jostle came out of Delaware and Maryland tracks to win her fourth
straight and won this one after a free-for-all down the
homestretch. At the finish, Jostle had her head in front of March
Magic, who led Shawnee Country by a length and three-quarters.
Ogden Phipps' Finder's Fee, who missed the Breeders' Cup with a
high white-cell blood count, finished fourth about one length in
front of the favorite, Regally Appealing, who vacated the
speed-favoring rail position before tiring.
</P>
<P>
   Jostle ran the mile and one-eighth in 1:51 2/5 under Stewart
Elliott, paid $18 for a $2 bet and earned $120,000 for her fourth
success in five career starts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
