<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     11-27 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S THE PLACE IN NOVEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite what seems to be a harmonic convergence, L.A. remains a
few warped factors short of earning the nomination for hub of the
NBA universe.
</P>
<P>
   But as the season's first month grinds into oblivion, we have to
admit that its stars are boldly going where they haven't gone in
light years.
</P>
<P>
   The MVP for November? Shaquille ``We Need More Orange Paint''
O'Neal. Our Rookie of the Month is Lamar ``Extend Your Elbow On
That Jumper'' Odom. Taking the coaching bow is former USC star Paul
Westphal (Seattle), who receives the nod over Phil ``Rent-A-Karma''
Jackson, because Phil coaches the MVP, remember? If you're partial
to the far Eastern Conference, cases could be made for former
Lakers sharpie Pat Riley (Miami) and Paul Silas (Charlotte), who
used to call time outs for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The most-improved-player race was won by ex-Laker Ruben
Patterson (Seattle) over mighty Clipper Brian Skinner, with A.C.
Green checking in second behind Cleveland's Bob ``Yes!'' Sura as
Comeback Player of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   Former Long Beach State hotshot Bryan Russell (Utah) almost gets
our top-sixth-man salute, losing to Seattle's Vernon Maxwell in a
competition that rates a photo finish thanks to Mad Max's
field-goal percentage (41).
</P>
<P>
   Shaq has been a fiend on the non-dunking end of the court, but
our top defender for November is Minnesota's Kevin Garnett, who's
nasty enough to prevent Brad Pitt from scoring at cheerleader camp.
</P>
<P>
   With our compulsories in the bag, we now deliver the NBA awards
that require a higher degree of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Please Come Back Player of the Month:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan generated a lot of unrequited hoo-ha in Chicago
by dropping in on a Bulls practice, the equivalent of Moses
stopping by to edit Letterman's top 10 list.
</P>
<P>
   Best Film Premise:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Curse of Sprewell.'' In a return that might even embarrass
Al Davis, Latrell encourages Oakland fans to bleep it real.
</P>
<P>
   Best CBA Rescue:
</P>
<P>
   This one goes to the Boston Celtics, who plucked Adrian Griffin
from the Connecticut Pride (yeah, we thought it was a micro-brew,
too).
</P>
<P>
   Suit Yourself Award:
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson, who thinks Giorgio Armani is a pizza joint,
injures his hand in the act of thumbing his nose at Larry Brown's
dress code. The closest event the Sixers had to a fashion play came
courtesy of Stanley Roberts, who was bounced from the league after
testing positive for a designer drug.
</P>
<P>
   Best Corn Rows:
</P>
<P>
   With the silver and bronze going to Iverson and Sprewell,
respectively, our gold is reserved for Utah coach Jerry Sloan, who
decided to pout over a lousy Jazz effort by spending an off day at
his farm in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   sub Rumor of the weak
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks usually win this one in a rout, but they deserve some
time off.
</P>
<P>
   We now aim our noses at Washington, D.C. where the latest gossip
has forward Juwan Howard packing his $15 million contract and
dragging it to Laker Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Wizards and Lakers both are miles beyond the salary
cap, Howard's alleged new team would be required to ship back
enough salary to come within 10 percent of that 15. A Glen Rice,
Robert Horry and Travis Knight package would do it, but remember
this:
</P>
<P>
   Including this season, Howard will be paid $70 million over the
next four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Smells like a deal-killer to us.
</P>
<P>
   sub Picking on the Clips
</P>
<P>
   If ya can't re-sign 'em, draft 'em.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the war cry of the Clippers, who - thanks to the
dumping of $42 million man Lorenzen Wright on Atlanta in exchange
for two selections - may have three first-round picks next June.
</P>
<P>
   With, um, only 70 games left to play, the Clips had the NBA's
ninth-worst record. The lottery has that ``come-hither'' look.
Wright's Hawks, who keep their No. 1 if it falls within the top
nine selections, were eighth. Unless J.R. Rider goes completely
cuckoo (that one's off the board), Atlanta should be able to play
itself right out of the pick.
</P>
<P>
   The second Clipper pick from the Wright deal can be traced to
Toronto and is ``lottery protected,'' a minor concern because the
Raptors should have enough juice to qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So what?
</P>
<P>
   So when your owner balks at paying market value for his own
free-agents, first-round picks are a fine alternative. They're
relatively cheap and - thanks to the new collective bargaining
agreement's team-option clause -- can produce long-term employees
of the franchises that select them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would be swell to buy a few experienced, free-agent
role players, but owner Donald T. Sterling is a bit, well, thrifty.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves his personnel crew to be creative on draft night.
Here's an optimistic reminder: Skinner was the 21st pick in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   (sub) Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who remains true to his school (LSU), eventually will be
joined in the NBA by Bayou Bengal sophomore Stromile Swift. Swift,
a 6-foot-9 forward at LSU, was a star attraction during
high-profile pickup games last summer at a camp conducted in Las
Vegas by Portland assistant coach Tim Grgurich. ``I've heard the
name,'' O'Neal said. ``Great basketball name ... Stro-mile Swift.
Like Shaquille O'Neal. When I was little, I knew I'd grow up to be
me.'' Swift did some growing as a freshman by blocking 11 shots in
a game vs. Alabama. ... The Washington Wizards rank 28th in free
throws attempted, suggesting the MCI Center presents a new version
of call-waiting. During last Saturday's game at MCI, Wizards
employees fired T-shirts into the home crowd, but the team's play
inspired most of the fans to throw them back. ... Detroit's Jerome
Williams, who was the suspect named in that rumored trade involving
Clipper Maurice Taylor, averages one rebound every 2.6 minutes.
Garnett gets one every 2.8 minutes, Shaq comes in at 2.7. But
Williams can't match Charles Barkley (2.5), who never lets defense
get in the way of grabbing a defensive rebound. ... Through
Friday's schedule, the Chicago Bulls had yet to score 100 points
(in one game); this may be proof that a shape even more important
than the three-pointed triangle is the five-pointed star. ... Laker
Kobe Bryant, still on the mend after breaking his right hand,
worked on that 3-point stroke before Wednesday's game with Utah at
Staples Center. Kobe made 8 of his first 15 attempts ...
left-handed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
