<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2739 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-GLASS-ROYALS-KAN &LR;      11-27 1877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-GLASS-ROYALS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL OWNER OF ROYALS HAS BUSINESS SAVVY AND IS A BIG BASEBALL
FAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE ROCK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By STEVE ROCK Knight-Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   BENTONVILLE, Ark. _ It is the Friday after Thanksgiving, perhaps
the busiest shopping day of the year for Wal-Mart stores across
America.
</P>
<P>
   But David Glass, the company's president and CEO, is sitting in
his rural office talking not about retail but about the Kansas City
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Over his shoulder, peering at him from the back wall, is a
baseball-clad boy in a Norman Rockwell painting. Another wall,
decorated with framed photographs and baseball cards, pays homage
to legendary players such as Honus Wagner and Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all,'' Glass says, drawing out the words with a tinge
of a southern drawl, ``I'm a baseball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for that statement is everywhere in this office, the
place where Glass oversees one of American business's greatest
success stories. It is a story Glass played a big part in writing,
according to the autobiography of late Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anybody else, he's responsible for building the
sophisticated and efficient system we use today,'' Walton wrote in
Made in America: My Story. ``David Glass has to get the lion's
share of the credit for where we are today in distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass, 64, clearly has impeccable business savvy _ and a minimum
net worth of $323 million to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of high-ranking baseball officials identifying
Glass as ``the key'' to solving Kansas City's ownership crisis, and
Glass' subsequent decision to re-enter the ownership auction,
Kansas Citians wonder whether he has just as much baseball savvy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a logical question: What kind of owner would David Glass
be?
</P>
<P>
   Glass' name is familiar in Kansas City, where he is chairman of
the Royals board of directors. But he is still something of a
mystery to Kansas Citians who yearn for the days when the Royals
were winning division titles, league pennants and a world
championship under the direction of late owner Ewing M. Kauffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what David Glass is all about,'' said Herk Robinson,
general manager of the Royals. ``I hope the people of Kansas City
get the opportunity to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this whole thing ends up with David Glass owning the club,
it would be like never having lost Mr. Kauffman.''
</P>
<P>
   An exaggeration, perhaps. But one thing is certain: Glass, like
Kauffman, is a man who commands respect among baseball's owners. To
them he's a familiar face and a proven commodity, a guy who would
doggedly fight for small-market rights and push for change in
baseball's inequitable economic system.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Giles, for one, would ``definitely'' support Glass as the
next owner of the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very well-respected,'' said Giles, chairman of the
Philadelphia Phillies. ``When we talk about the global issues in
baseball, his judgment is very well-received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the small-market people in baseball, he's probably the
most respected. People listen when he speaks.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling what will happen to small-market clubs like
the Royals when, after the 2001 season, owners and players
renegotiate their collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anyone who can get us through those unchartered
waters, it's David Glass,'' Robinson said. ``I don't think there's
a better person on the face of the earth to guide us through
this.'' Respectful leader
</P>
<P>
   People in Bentonville describe Glass in glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   They say he is in the office by 6:30 every morning, sometimes
earlier. They say he is a ``soft-shell'' leader, not at all the
screaming type but one who commands work ethic from others by
demonstrating it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, they say, neither seeks nor needs much credit. He is
quiet, unassuming, patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very biased,'' said Lee Scott, the vice chairman and chief
operating officer at Wal-Mart. ``David hired me 20 years ago. Not
once in those 20 years has there ever been a suggestion that I
should do something that would undermine my personal values. He
cares a lot about his people.''
</P>
<P>
   Over at Kauffman Stadium, they say much the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Glass was elected chairman of the Royals board of directors in
September 1993. Since that time, he has not once stepped foot in
the Royals clubhouse without first getting permission from his
front office staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very respectful of his people,'' said Robinson, who
answers directly to Glass. ``And he doesn't tell us how to do our
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   That may surprise some people who, once upon a time, labeled
Glass as the bad guy. They thought of him as a clandestine
conspirator, a guy with visions of buying the club on the cheap and
turning it into the Little Rock Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Glass scoffs at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job that I have with the Royals, my commitment
was that whatever we did, we were going to make doggone sure that
the Royals were in Kansas City for the foreseeable future,'' Glass
said. ``Can I guarantee that the Royals are going to be there
forever? No. But the fans can.
</P>
<P>
   ``My commitment is to have major-league baseball in Kansas City.
I wouldn't ever consider anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass, mind you, would not be based in Kansas City himself.
After all, he already has a job in Arkansas and people in Kansas
City whom he trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Levy, the Royals' vice president for marketing and
communications, said that Glass had been known to point the club's
marketing staff into particular target-market directions. But, as
far as hands-on interaction, that is about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, he did ask me about the business,'' Levy said. ``And
I thought, `Oh, my goodness. The CEO of Wal-Mart is asking me about
merchandising.' But for the most part we don't talk about marketing
and merchandising. We talk about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a baseball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a fan, in fact, that in a celebratory gala in the days
following George Brett's Hall of Fame induction, Glass was tracking
every last pitch as the Royals played at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Levy remembers thinking, ``is someone who has baseball
on his mind.'' Money matters
</P>
<P>
   The most recent report from Wal-Mart Stores Inc., where Glass
has worked for more than two decades, puts Glass' holding at more
than 5.2 million shares. That's $304 million worth of stock based
on Wal-Mart's closing price Friday of 58 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Glass also holds options to buy more Wal-Mart shares at prices
lower than the stock market price. The company's last estimate
showed Glass' options worth at least $19 million, when Wal-Mart
shares were trading at $43.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Wal-Mart shares have increased in value by a third.
</P>
<P>
   Glass has a hefty paycheck from Wal-Mart, too. In the last seven
years he has earned $12.5 million in salary, bonuses and other
compensation. And $4 million of that came just last year.
</P>
<P>
   All of which spells out a net worth of $323 million minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The real figure is hard to measure but likely much higher. The
minimum figure, for example, does not account for Glass
Enterprises, his company that owns commercial property and
investments, because it does not report financial information
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assets that my family has would certainly be substantial
enough to own a baseball team,'' Glass told The Star as many as six
years ago. ``That's not a question.''
</P>
<P>
   And Glass' fortunes seemingly have improved significantly since
then, with his stake in Wal-Mart alone growing by five times in
those six years.
</P>
<P>
   Glass did not make the most recent list of the Forbes 400
richest Americans, which meant having a net worth of at least $625
million. Nor did Glass show up on the magazine's ``near-miss'' list
of Americans worth $620 million.
</P>
<P>
   Glass chose not to elaborate on his net worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will meet baseball's standards,'' Glass said, chuckling.
``Beyond that, I'd rather not comment.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment was vintage Glass, coming from a man who drives a
1993 Lexus only because his wife had his old Ford station wagon
``hauled off and buried.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives no indication of the level of success he has achieved
in his business or personal life,'' said Scott, whose desk is a
fastball away from Glass' in Arkansas. ``He doesn't seem to have
the real need for people to recognize him.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which, perhaps, inspired Fortune magazine to once name
Glass its most-admired CEO.
</P>
<P>
   As for that Forbes list of the 400 richest Americans, few
major-league baseball owners were on it. Those left off include New
York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner and Baltimore Orioles owner
Peter Angelos, both of whose teams had 1999 payrolls of more than
$75 million, the price Miles Prentice and his group were set to pay
for the entire Royals franchise before baseball rejected their
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect a similar payroll from Glass, who would have no
problem meeting the Royals' $100 million net-worth requirement but
probably would exercise conservatism in running his baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, quite simply, probably would not spend $20 million for a
player who only brought in $10 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of guy who would do that,'' Glass said.
``Fiscal responsibility on the part of all the owners is one of the
first prerequisites for baseball to regain some of its competitive
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be the kind of owner who would fund major losses.
There are teams today that are losing $20 million, $30 million, $40
million. I think that's irresponsible. I don't think anyone should
look at a Major League Baseball franchise in Kansas City and
anticipate making money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the franchise should be to break even.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, does not translate into a $40 million or $50
million payroll in Kansas City. The Royals made money in 1999, for
the first time this decade, with a payroll of less than $22
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made progress this past year,'' Glass said. ``We increased
our revenue some. If we can continue to increase revenues, we can
spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year you could see this team with a $25 million payroll.
I think you can grow your revenues, and grow your payroll, beyond
that. But not at a very rapid rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Joe McGuff, a member of the Royals board of directors:
``He would be good for Kansas City. But if people think he would
have a $50 million payroll, I think they would be mistaken. He
would run a good operation, but no one is going to come in and lose
$25 million or $30 million a year. The last two years, Ewing was
tired of losing money and complained a lot about that. He said he
was not going to continue to have those kind of losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, though, that Glass would not have to run his club on
the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very competitive and despise losing,'' Glass said. ``I
would work very, very hard to make sure we have a team in Kansas
City that is competitive, that is fun to watch. The fun goes out of
it if you lose all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In major-league baseball, your chances to win don't come
around too often. So when it does come around, do whatever it takes
to try and take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mark Davis contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
