<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2741 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-1970s-ESSAY-KAN &LR;      11-27 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1970s-ESSAY-KAN </SLUG>
  
 SCANDAL, RECESSION IN 1970s BEGET CYNICISM THAT ENDURES TODAY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOTES-Here is the eighth installment of The Star's 10-part
series looking at the stamp of change that each decade of the
century left on Americans. Today: The 1970s _ ``Distrust and
Declining Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   By BRIAN BURNES Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The 1970s _ what a downer decade.
</P>
<P>
   The United States endured humiliation at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The decade's marquee milestone was Richard Nixon's Watergate
scandal and the first resignation of a president. Its legacy _ a
wholesale cynicism about politicians _ corrodes public discourse to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Kansas City Star poll, almost one in five
respondents said they trusted the federal government ``not at
all.'' No wonder voter turnout is so low.
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, Arab nations hit the United States with an oil embargo
in 1973, the country fled from Vietnam in a frenzied retreat in
1975, and America was rendered almost powerless by the Iran hostage
crisis in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, our collective confidence was shattered. The
cynicism settled on all things big: big media; big business; big
labor; big government.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? It appeared the big shots just did not know what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to economic wisdom, inflation and unemployment rose at
the same time in the 1970s. Federal Reserve Chairman Arthur Burns,
asked to explain the economy, said, ``The rules are not working the
way they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Big business just did not seem to get it. Auto companies
continued to make fuel guzzlers even as the price of gasoline
skyrocketed and lines of drivers stretched from service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp. eventually had to be bailed out _ by big
government.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 nuclear accident at Three Mile Island made us wonder
whether the safe harnessing of nuclear energy _ as an alternative
to foreign oil _ was beyond the reach of American engineers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the media, some reporters, such as Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein, got famous. But many in the public began to resent the
larger media establishment, thinking it was too liberal, too
negative, too smug and way too isolated from rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout lingers. Fifteen percent in The Star poll said they
trusted American corporations ``not at all,'' and 24 percent said
they trusted the news media ``not at all.'' Disillusionment grows
</P>
<P>
   Add it up, and today the 1970s endure as a mutt decade, an
interval of declining expectations in contrast to the oh-so-serious
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   College students in the 1970s did not demonstrate, they
streaked.
</P>
<P>
   Today the decade is played for laughs. There's the Have a Nice
Day Cafe. There's disco. The fashion legacy of the '70s _ just say
the words ``leisure suit'' out loud _ has not aged well.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disillusionment with institutions, especially big and powerful
institutions, had been growing unchecked since the middle 1960s,''
said Todd Gitlin, New York University professor and author of The
Sixties: Years of Hope, Days of Rage.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 1960s sparked skepticism in the Love Generation and
even violence among the extreme left, the 1970s bestowed cynicism
on a much larger demographic.
</P>
<P>
   And since then, much of the distrust and even violence has come
from the extreme right.
</P>
<P>
   Some especially disillusioned people formed their own militias
in response to a government they perceived to be malignant or _ in
the case of the destruction of the Branch Davidian complex in Waco,
Texas, in 1993 by federal officers _ even murderous.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors who convicted Timothy McVeigh for first-degree
murder in the bombing of the federal office building in Oklahoma
City in 1995 _ which killed 168 persons _ said the attack was
planned in retribution for Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Cozad, a Kansas City lawyer and a former chairman of the
Missouri Republican Party, points out that extreme distrust of
government goes back to the beginning of the country. Take the
Whiskey Rebellion of 1794, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in the fever swamps don't just distrust
government,'' Cozad said, ``they have a fundamental psychological
problem with the concept of authority.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that the right can feed off distrust of
government, Cozad said. George Wallace received more than 9 million
votes in the 1968 presidential election and was a significant
candidate in 1972 before being shot and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Also, distrust of Washington should not be assumed to be
unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distrust of government was a profoundly rational response to
the data,'' Cozad said. ``People began to come to the perfectly
sensible conclusion that this huge government operated in ways that
it was unwilling to describe to the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyndon Johnson was a thorough-going liar and then was followed
by Richard Nixon, who was a thorough-going liar.''
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent Watergate scandal was only the biggest downer in
a decade of full downers. The new stagflation
</P>
<P>
   Economically, times were terrible.
</P>
<P>
   The 1973-74 oil embargo ushered in a recession, the worst
economic crisis in America since Franklin D. Roosevelt was
president. Oil prices almost quadrupled between 1972 and 1974.
</P>
<P>
   By spring 1974, service station attendants _ the people who
pumped your gasoline while you sat in your car _ started carrying
guns for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices fed inflation. And while inflation rose, so did
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Economists, groping for a word, came up with ``stagflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans heard a lot about that. After 1971, when NBC News
installed the first full-time economics correspondent, Americans
became more conversant in the dismal science than ever before. The
dour Irving R. Levine became almost as familiar as Howard Cosell
and _ because of the relentlessly bad tidings he bore _ perhaps
just as beloved.
</P>
<P>
   It was no fun looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   Walk the streets for half a year, trying to find a new career,
the group Tavares sang in the 1975 disco hit, ``It Only Takes a
Minute.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gerald Ford became president in August 1974, the
unemployment rate was 5.3 percent. It reached 9.2 percent in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate personal issues such as finding a job sometimes served
to contain the spirit of the 1960s, said Ruth Shechter of Fairway,
Kan., who helped campaign for public accommodations and fair
housing measures in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Shechter co-founded the Housing Information Center in
Kansas City, which offered housing counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was unemployment, housing discrimination, sexual
discrimination and many other issues,'' Shechter said. ``People
were looking at each of these issues rather than just one single
point. So the energies were diffused, and there wasn't a single
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, politicians in power at the wrong time suffered.
</P>
<P>
   At first Democrats gained: 49 seats in the House and four in the
Senate in the 1974 off-year elections. Two years later Democrats
wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the Republicans the defeat they so richly deserve,'' said
Rep. Mo Udall of Arizona at the 1976 Democratic Convention in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Voters did, electing outsider Jimmy Carter as president. But
economic conditions remained stubbornly poor. In July 1979, Carter
startled the country when he canceled a planned energy address and
convened a national summit, calling a cross-section of American
leaders to Camp David for 10 days of soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   Carter then descended to announce that the nation was suffering
a ``crisis of confidence.'' The economic program he proposed _
repeated the next day in a Kansas City speech _ included a call for
personal energy conservation and a pledge to reduce oil imports.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Iranian demonstrators took U.S. Embassy
workers in Tehran hostage, beginning their 444 days in captivity.
American voters would boot Carter out about a year later.
Environmental concern
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s was not wall-to-wall torment.
</P>
<P>
   The first Earth Day in 1970 served as a symbolic birth for the
budding environmental movement. The apparent scarcity of resources
in the 1970s has resulted in an American citizenry more sensitive
to recycling.
</P>
<P>
   The concept had become so familiar in Kansas City that in 1992,
when local environmental activists attempted to construct a giant
trash turtle, they ran short of old newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, meanwhile _ along with the larger media
establishment _ began to re-invent themselves. Many of the larger
daily papers installed ombudsmen, or reader representatives, to
establish better accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television, which began its penetration of the American
home largely in the 1970s, led to a proliferation of viewing
choices. Although some wondered whether this only served to
fragment the American public into many more ever-smaller interest
groups, others celebrated the new diversity of programming.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of big media to re-establish its grip, meanwhile,
dovetailed with the arrival of the Apple II computer.
</P>
<P>
   As the first mass-produced computer, introduced in 1977, the
Apple II helped spark an information revolution. The widespread
commercial application of microprocessor technology allowed for a
vast amount and diversity of information, entertainment and
electronic commerce in homes, schools and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Media critics throughout the 1990s have occupied themselves by
imagining the ultimate look of the coming ``convergence'' of news,
entertainment and computer technology born in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy skepticism
</P>
<P>
   Despite the litany of plagues from the 1970s, the decade's
ultimate endowment may be positive.
</P>
<P>
   Mild distrust is not so bad if it fosters a reasonable
skepticism about large institutions and their intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have taken away naivete, you are much wiser about
people and what people actually do,'' said Frank Smist Jr.,
chairman of the political science department at Rockhurst
University.
</P>
<P>
   But true danger may wait at the place where distrust calcifies
into hardened cynicism, where voters can assume a sinister agenda
behind each act of public policy and simply disengage. Call it
``The truth is out there'' way of looking at the world
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake, Gitlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think that the lesson of Watergate or Vietnam is
that they shouldn't take politicians seriously, they are gravely
misguided,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior only allows politicians to operate largely free
from any accountability to those that they are supposed to
represent, Gitlin added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distrust by itself is an abdication of responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
