<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-FISHER-FOREIGN-KAN &LR;      11-27 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-FOREIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING BRINGS SMALL TOWN, FOREIGN STUDENTS TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER Knight Ridder Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   BURNS, Kan. _ To this town on the western edge of the Flint
Hills on Thanksgiving came Abdullah Al-Shamrani, Karen Chan, Shahid
Hussain, Wael Qassim, and Ahmed Abu Ali.
</P>
<P>
   They were from Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Pakistan and Hong Kong,
they were students from the University of Kansas, and they stayed
through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For 45 years, turkey and fixings day has meant strangers here,
so much so that a catch phrase is used to describe Burns,
population 285: ``The smallest U.S. community with the biggest
foreign diplomatic service in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, about 500 foreign students from the University
of Kansas have spent their autumn holiday here.
</P>
<P>
   For the students, among two dozen who were scattered around the
state this weekend, the respite from their studies was low-key.
They ate a big dinner on Thursday, got lots of sleep, watched the
ebb and flow of a small town, wondered at the immensity of the
surrounding land, maybe went to a church supper and visited with
their host families. It was informal, relaxed and unscripted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just treat them like they were our own kids,'' said Esta
Hall, who along with her husband, Calvin, has had one or more
foreign students for Thanksgiving dinner and a weekend stay since
1965. ``It's just as if they were home.''
</P>
<P>
   That open-handed Kansas hospitality has been indelibly stamped
in the memories of some of the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burns was the only place in the U.S.,'' wrote a woman who
became an physician in India, ``where I never felt like an animal
in a zoo,'' referring to her colorful sari, unusual looks, and the
expectation in larger venues that her well-meaning hosts would want
some kind of performance, such as a speech.
</P>
<P>
   In Burns, the woman wrote, she could relax, take part in the
town's everyday life, be herself, see part of an America so
different from the big cities or movie screen images, and make
friends with people who, at their core, were pretty much like
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Another student wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good to know you are there instead of in a big city
where life is changing so terribly fast. It is a great
accomplishment what you have done.... You gave of part of you, by
sharing your everyday life with us.''
</P>
<P>
   And another:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come back to Italy I will speak about America. I always
think (sic) Burns, and I'm sure my friends will like Burns. For us
intolerant European and Asiatic people, (Burns) was the best lesson
of tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Burns, just west of U.S. 77, about midway between El
Dorado and Florence has a made a world reputation by just being
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Mention this town and somewhere, somebody will say, ``Ah,
Burns,'' and smile, said Ed Grimwood, a retired hardware store
owner and implement dealer who has traveled to Europe and Latin
America and visited the students who have been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we meet again it's like we're just one big family,''
Grimwood said. ``Burns, to them, is special.''
</P>
<P>
   That uniqueness started in 1954 when Betty Grimwood, Ed's wife,
read a magazine article about foreign students while waiting in a
doctor's office in El Dorado. When the physician was ready for her,
Grimwood, then 29, laid the magazine aside.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't forget.
</P>
<P>
   Even in rural Kansas, 1954 was a year of uneasiness. Dien Bien
Phu in Indochina had fallen, the Cold War was headed for the deep
freeze and riots outside U.S. embassies were in the newspapers
almost every week. America, to some, had come to be seen as
heavy-handed, insensitive, even bullying.
</P>
<P>
   Grimwood talked to her friend Bonnie Lohrentz. Together the two
women broached an idea to the Women's Society of Christian Service
at the Burns Methodist church.
</P>
<P>
   What if, Grimwood and Lohrentz proposed, foreign people could
see that we're all pretty much the same? If they could come here,
we could get to know them and they could get to know us? Wouldn't
that help? At least a little?
</P>
<P>
   Members of the society agreed. But where on earth would the
students come from? U.S. 77 wasn't exactly a magnet for
international traffic. Even the Santa Fe branch line had been gone
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Grimwood, by all accounts a no-nonsense woman, figured if anyone
would know where to find foreign students, it would be the people
up at KU. So she got on the phone and explained the plan. Her
husband recalled that it wasn't quite ``Send me some kids!'' but
her thrust was essentially the same.
</P>
<P>
   KU signed on and recruited the first batch, and Thanksgiving
1954 saw the first arrivals. Others from all over the world _
Africa, Asia, South America, the Pacific Rim _ have followed,
bringing with them a multitude of cultures, languages, skin colors
and religions.
</P>
<P>
   But mainly they bring themselves _ human beings _ which sort of
evens things out, said Ed Grimwood. People are people, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go up and get them in the car,'' Grimwood said. ``Then we
drive back, and we almost always stop at the Matfield Green cattle
pens on the (Kansas) turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Lawrence is kind of eastern, lots of trees, things
close together. But when those kids get out of the car at the pens
you can tell they're looking at more land than most have ever seen
before. And that's kind of our introduction to them of Burns.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first, the goal was to treat the students just like
anybody else. They'd help out with the dinner, maybe pitch in on
the dishes, do what college kids are supposed to do. If they wanted
to milk a cow or ride on a combine, well, that could be arranged.
The whole idea was to get to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1954, that's been pretty much the way it's worked.
It's not flashy. There's been publicity, but even that has been
muted.
</P>
<P>
   Esta Hall said there have been years when a lot of students have
come and some years when just a few showed up. Bonnie Lohrentz
moved away, and others took her place. The event, known as the
Thanksgiving Homestay Program, expanded to other Kansas
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty was so proud of it,'' Hall said. ``She was our spark
plug. She got it going and stayed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year. Betty Grimwood died of cancer in May. To mark
her passing, the event from this year hence will be known as the
Betty Grimwood Thanksgiving Homestay Program, no matter where KU
foreign students spend the holiday, be it Jetmore or Eureka, Derby
or Burns, or any of a half-dozen other towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's meant just as much to us here as it has to the
students,'' said Ed Grimwood, who along with his sons, their wives,
and his grandchildren was host for a foreign student this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just became a part of our lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
