<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S PLENTY IN STORR FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last Tuesday, goalie Jamie Storr was in pain and
the Los Angeles Kings were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches spoke in hushed tones about the right groin he reinjured
in the first period of the team's 5-2 victory over Colorado.
Stephane Fiset was still a few weeks away with a bruised right hand
and minor-league goalies were being asked to fill in.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon at the Staples Center, Storr returned to the
lineup with the flair that earned him NHL Player of the Week
earlier this month. He defeated San Jose 4-1, withstanding a
19-shot second period by the Sharks and confounding a team that is
second only to the Kings in goals scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure if I was going to play today,'' said Storr, who
stopped 33 shots to raise his record against San Jose to 6-1. ``But
it was important to me to get back in there. I wanted to be a part
of what's going on. It got better in a hurry and I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Kings' fear was that Storr has had groin problems
the past few seasons. He went out in the fourth game last season
with a left groin strain and the Kings never recovered. Earlier
this season, he tweaked the right groin and was unavailable to
practice for a week. But when he was injured Tuesday trying to stop
a breakaway by Colorado's Joe Sakic, Storr first admitted it was
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact that the area already was hurt actually helped,''
he said. ``If this had been a new injury I would have been out
three to four weeks. I just knew this one could not get any
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings returned from the road Wednesday night, Storr
spent the next two days with trainer Pete Demers and the Kings
medical staff to stretch out the groin and rebuild strength, which
had dropped 80 percent according to coach Andy Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are miracle workers,'' Murray said. ``To get him
back this fast is amazing. Jamie came to me after practice (Friday)
and said he could play. I told him if he thought he could play, I
expected a great game. We certainly got that.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick whistles: Kings defenseman Aki Berg, who was benched for
two games earlier this month for poor play, was on the ice for the
Kings' first three goals.... Even though Murray gave the team the
next two days off, Luc Robitaille (broken left foot) will continue
to skate and is expected to return Friday against the Mighty Ducks
in Anaheim.
</P>
</TEXT>
