A2752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HATE28-COX     11-27 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish group launches anti-hate campaign
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The American Jewish Committee wants you
to know that no one is born hating, and they plan a public
relations blitz to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this week, as part of a national campaign against hate
crimes, various chapters are pinning up posters. The posters
feature babies of differing races and ethnicities happily rolling
together. The photo is accompanied by a list of suggestions for
political and religious leaders, lawmakers, school administrators
and members of the media interested in halting hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach, the posters are following bumper stickers that
the chapter there printed with money given by an anonymous donor
specifically to fight hate crimes. The bumper stickers were
distributed to area law enforcement agencies over the summer and
publicize a toll-free hotline used to report hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's Palm Beach County chapter also has sent a letter
to South Florida congressmen urging new laws that strengthen gun
control and protect minority groups. Many of the area's prominent
lawmakers and educators signed the letter, including Palm Beach
County Schools Superintendent Joan Kowal and Florida Atlantic
University President Anthony Catanese.
</P>
<P>
   The letter refers to several crimes that made national news in
the last year, including the slaying of a gay man in Wyoming and
the Los Angeles shooting at a Jewish Community Center. Organizers
said there are no local crimes fueling the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, not at the moment,'' said William Gralnick,
regional director for the American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Florida began categorizing hate crimes in 1989, defining them as
actions ``that in any way constitute an expression of hatred ...
based on (a victim's) personal characteristics.'' Gralnick said the
committee aims to be proactive rather than wait for additional
problems to arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to create an environment that is not conducive to
hate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
