<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PARTY28-COX     11-27 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High prices put damper on New Year's Eve plans
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The big question about New Year's Eve is
not if you'll be able to find a suitably glorious hotel room or
cruise cabin in which to greet the next 1,000 years but which of
the many still-available options you should choose.
</P>
<P>
   Only 33 days before the Big Event, the potential party-goer has
a plethora of great backdrops for singing ``Auld Lang Syne.'' A
spare cabin on the legendary Queen Elizabeth 2 is not a dream but a
reality. There are rooms aplenty at The Breakers and the
Ritz-Carltons in Palm Beach and Naples on the big night.
</P>
<P>
   You heard Disney World was booked? Surprise. Rooms are available
at Disney's Caribbean Beach Hotel, Coronado Springs Hotel and the
Polynesian. There's a three-night minimum, and you have to buy a
package that includes admissions to all four theme parks. Get out
the American Express card _ rates start at $1,122.28 for two adults
(add more for the kids).
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Fitzpatrick Manhattan Hotel in New York,
which got a lot of publicity early in the year when it offered the
entire hotel to one celebrant and 181 of his or her closest friends
for a cool $1 million? As the hotel's reservation agent says:
``There were no takers.'' The hotel has vacancies on New Year's Eve
and is offering rooms for $400 per night (a two-night minimum).
</P>
<P>
   Hotel owners, cruise line agents and airline officials are
scratching their heads, puzzling over why consumers aren't rushing
to make sure they have fantastic plans for such a
once-in-a-lifetime event.
</P>
<P>
   What, they want to know, are folks planning to be doing during
the countdown Dec. 31? Watching Dick Clark on TV, for heaven's
sake? Waving sparklers in the back yard?
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say the lack of interest probably is due to one
of two things: People are procrastinating or, more probably, they
are shocked and dismayed by the outrageous prices of rooms and
special events.
</P>
<P>
   If the first theory is true, one day in early or mid-December,
everyone will suddenly pull the trigger and pick up the phone, and
those who are a day late really will be left sitting at home.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents, the travel industry's
foremost travel barometer, is going with the second theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the prices were so high that people said, 'No way am I
paying that when I can go two weeks later and pay a third of the
price,''' says ASTA spokeswoman Kristina Rundquist. ``Suppliers
definitely overestimated the overall interest in doing something at
all costs. They think this is the event to die for, but most people
realize it's surrounded by a lot of hype.''
</P>
<P>
   She thinks there will be an upswing of reservations near the end
of the year. ``You might see people holding out for last-minute
bargains, but I think it won't be until after New Year's that
business will pick up _ when prices aren't jacked up 70 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization's 25,600-member travel agents, she says, are
not hearing Y2K fears from clients, especially about flying. In
fact, finding flights for travelers is more difficult than hotel
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem now is getting air reservations to get people to
their hotel rooms,'' she says. ``The holidays traditionally are a
busy time. We have heard some airlines are canceling flights on New
Year's Eve not because of Y2K but because people are already at
their destinations that night.''
</P>
<P>
   As the date draws closer, hotels are scrambling for big-name
entertainment to entice more business. The Ritz-Carlton Palm Beach
has booked comedian Rita Rudner to perform Dec. 31. But Rita is an
expensive date _ the price for dinner and a show in the ballroom is
$895 and that doesn't include a room. There's a three-night minimum
and room rates for those arriving Dec. 30 range from $925 to $4,485
per night. Dinner and champagne at one of the hotel's three
restaurants start at $95 for an early seating. (You'll have to
toast midnight somewhere else.)
</P>
<P>
   Rooms are available, and the hotel managers think they will
fill. ``We expect it's going to click, and people will start making
reservations,'' says Deb Hurd, Ritz-Carlton spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Lou Rawls will be one of the entertainers at the
Ritz-Carlton Naples. The price for a four-night package including
room, shows, a bottle of Taittinger champagne with two Baccarat
flutes, his and hers massages and a New Year's Eve photograph is
$6,800. A variety of rooms is still available.
</P>
<P>
   The Breakers doesn't have a big name act _ a reservations agent
said Drew Carey would perform but a hotel spokesperson said he
wouldn't _ but will have two galas. A two-night package including a
gala and a room is $2,499; a three-night package starting Dec. 30
is $2,999.
</P>
<P>
   And over in the Bahamas, Atlantis _ the mega-resort on Paradise
Island _ has been promoting its millennium events, which include
fireworks and a concert by the Steve Miller Band, for more than a
year and it still has empty rooms. Just the room is $620 per night,
but to see the band and other events plus dinner and a room for two
nights is $2,247.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of Carnival Cruise Lines' 14 ships have cabins available
on special millennium cruises. And there's room at the inns in Las
Vegas, including New York-New York Hotel, which has a three-night
minimum with room rates starting at $579 per night, and that
doesn't include any amenities or shows. The regular rate is $69.
</P>
<P>
   In London, which probably has more millennium festivities than
any other European city, the Dorchester, the city's most elegant
address, and Park Lane Hotel have rooms available on the big night.
</P>
<P>
   And that QE2 millennium cruise: The least expensive available
cabin is $11,400 per person, double, for the Dec. 20 to Jan. 4
cruise from Miami to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   With these prices, a lot of people might elect to stay home,
says ASTA's Rundquist.
</P>
<P>
   And where will she be New Year's Eve? ``At a friend's house for
a masked ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
