<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SYRACUSE-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI BEATS SYRACUSE, 45-13  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A decade so full of glorious achievement is winding to
an ignominious conclusion for Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Every Syracuse football team had a winning record in the 1990s _
81-35-3 in aggregate _ and the decade was punctuated by three Big
East Conference titles and eight bowl games, assuming the Music
City Bowl in Nashville will see a silver lining in Saturday's
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season ended for Syracuse Saturday with a 45-13 rout
by Miami before 35,208 in the Orange Bowl. It left Syracuse at 6-5,
with four losses in its last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the Hurricanes, still smarting from last season's
66-13 loss to Syracuse, raised their record to 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no clue how they made us feel last year,'' Miami
defensive tackle Matt Sweeney said of Syracuse. ``We owe them
something big.''
</P>
<P>
   In this season of collapse, the Syracuse defense has been able
to maintain some respectability, ranking ninth nationally in total
defense entering this game.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday the defense played reasonably well until the
humidity slowly sapped it of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Miami's success in the first half came on breakdowns by
Syracuse's special teams and its offense.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams' giveaways started early. Just 6 minutes 12
seconds into the game, the designated snapper Mike Bennett spotted
the hosts a 2-0 lead when, with Syracuse at its 1-yard line in a
punting situation, he hiked the ball out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Syracuse defense then held Miami to 2 yards on its next
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over at its 31, Syracuse drove 69 yards in 14 plays to
take a 7-2 advantage, its only lead of the game. Quarterback Troy
Nunes clicked on two passes to Pat Woodcock totaling 24 yards and
tailback James Mungro added an 11-yard run. Fullback Kyle Johnson
scored untouched on a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Crosland's two missed field goal attempts, from 48 and 29
yards, allowed the Orangemen to maintain their lead until midway
through the second quarter, when costly mistakes changed the
complexion of the game.
</P>
<P>
   First, a 79-yard touchdown pass from Nunes to Woodcock was wiped
out by a holding call on center P.J. Alexander. Two plays later,
Miami's Santana Moss made that mistake hurt a little more. He
returned a punt 61 yards to give the lead back to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Moss swept left, then cut back inside the 20 to score untouched.
The Hurricanes tacked on a 2-point conversion, on freshman Ken
Dorsey's pass over the middle to Andre King, to make it 10-7 with
6:26 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   On their next series, the Orangemen wasted a 29-yard run by
fullback Nick Sudano when Nate Trout's 43-yard field goal attempt
sailed wide right.
</P>
<P>
   Then Miami finally began to flex a little offensive muscle. A
73-yard drive featured Moss' 20-yard reception from Dorsey and
Clinton Portis' 29-yard run, and ended when Dorsey hit split end
Reggie Wayne on 17-yard touchdown pass for a 17-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Syracuse still in the game, Nunes then gave the Hurricanes
an enormous lift heading into halftime. Cornerback Leonard Myers
stepped in front of Woodcock on a pass by Nunes and returned it 54
yards down the left sideline to make it 24-7 Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The margin only grew in the second half as Miami scored 21
points in the third quarter. Portis scored on a 3-yard run 3:33
into the half, then Moss scored on a 16-yard pass from Dorsey and
tight end Bubba Franks scored on a 17-yard pass, even with
linebacker Morlon Greenwood tipping the ball. Miami had a 45-7 lead
entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse closed the gap on a 1-yard run by Mungro early in the
final period. But by then, it just served to make the final score
look a little less ugly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
