u a BC-NJ-PLANECRASH-NYT &LR;      11-27 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PLANECRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH INVESTIGATORS FOCUS ON INSTRUMENTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investigators focused on a pair of tiny gyroscopes on
Saturday as possible factors in the crash of a private plane in
Newark that killed a Maryland family of three and injured 25 people
on the ground as it plunged down a street, broke apart, struck
buildings and cars, and set off fires and explosions.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the single-engine Beechcraft Bonanza plowed through
the largely residential street a mile west of downtown Newark, two
badly burned victims remained in critical condition, dozens of
residents who were displaced from a devastated block faced up to a
week in temporary shelters, and others confronted the loss of their
homes as officials condemned two buildings as structurally unsound.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash that killed the plane's owner-pilot,
Itzhak Jacoby, 56, his wife, Gail, 50, and their daughter Atira,
13, remained undetermined, and officials of the National
Transportation Safety Board said it might take six to nine months
before definitive conclusions could be drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike large airliners, small planes have no flight data
recorders or cockpit voice recorders to provide clues as to why
they crashed. But investigators appeared to be making progress on
Saturday, gathering up most of the plane's wreckage, including
parts of the cockpit control panel, a fuel pump, and a wing part.
</P>
<P>
   They also found two gyroscopes _ devices that help provide
instrument readings to show a pilot how a plane is oriented in foul
weather. Like spinning tops, gyroscopes keep their position no
matter which way a plane is oriented; without them, a pilot caught
in dense fog or a cloud would be flying blind.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the wreckage was taken to a municipal garage for
reassembly, the two gyroscopes, each an inch in diameter, were sent
to the safety board's laboratory in Washington for analysis. But
even if they were faulty, it was unclear what role they might have
played because the weather at the time of the crash was not bad
enough to have disoriented the pilot, one investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby, in three exchanges with air traffic controllers recorded
minutes after his takeoff from Linden Airport eight miles south of
Newark, said he was having problems with instruments, and he
referred specifically to ``gyros.''
</P>
<P>
   Bound for home in Bethesda, Md., after spending Thanksgiving in
New York, Jacoby and his wife and daughter took off at 10:49 a.m.
Friday, despite warnings by airport officials against doing so
because of rain and dense fog that had cut visibility at times to
100 feet. The plane went down six minutes later, and all three were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   David Muzio, an investigator for the safety board, noted on
Saturday that visibility over Newark at the time of the crash was
two and a half miles, and he said there were no indications that
weather was a factor. He also said that there were no signs that
the plane's engine or structural frame were faulty.
</P>
<P>
   The path of debris laid down by the disintegrating plane
measured 600 feet from the first point of impact on a warehouse
roof to the last item of scattered fragments, Muzio added at a
briefing at the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plane's rate of descent had been measured at 7,800
feet per minute, which is a steep dive. A normal rate of descent is
about 1,500 feet per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Muzio said the yoke _ the pilot's steering wheel _ was turned
over to the Essex County Sheriff's Department for fingerprint
analysis, mainly to confirm that Jacoby was at the controls. The
investigator stressed that there was no implication that Jacoby's
wife or daughter was believed to be at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings of Jacoby's conversations with controllers at
Newark International Airport might be crucial clues. Jacoby, who
had filed a required plan for an instrument-assisted flight to
Dulles International Airport in Virginia, told controllers less
than 90 seconds after takeoff that he was having trouble. Muzio
said on Friday night that the pilot had cited difficulty with a
``gyro,'' mentioning it three times.
</P>
<P>
   Various government agencies were supporting the safety board
investigation, along with representatives of the companies that
manufactured the engine, frame, and other parts of the Beechcraft
Bonanza, a four-seat plane with a V-shaped tail, a 285-horsepower
engine, and capable of speeds up to 200 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Two people who were severely burned on the ground remained in
critical condition at University Hospital in Newark. Albert Walker,
59, had burns over 15 percent of his body, and Rhonda Acey, 29, had
extensive second- and third-degree burns.
</P>
<P>
   More than 75 residents displaced from Kent Street, where the
plane fell and broke apart, were evacuated on Friday and put up at
a Salvation Army center a mile away. They were not allowed to move
back in to homes that had been damaged by flames and blasts from
exploding cars.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James, taking reporters on a tour, said that two
buildings that had housed several families had been condemned as
structurally unsound. Temporarily, he said, some of the displaced
would be put up at a hotel in nearby Orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm homeless now,'' said Theresa Gates, 28, of 23 Kent Street,
one of the condemned buildings. ``They're tearing down my building
with most of my stuff in there. I've struggled and worked for
everything I have, and now my home is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said that other multifamily buildings on the
street would have to be cleared by city inspectors over the coming
week before any of their residents would be allowed back in.
</P>
<P>
   After city inspectors found no serious structural problems with
the four buildings at 8, 10, 12 and 14 Kent Street, the mayor said
their residents would be allowed to return as early as Monday or
Tuesday after gas, water, and electrical lines could be turned back
on.
</P>
<P>
   Workers on Saturday began to raze a three-story warehouse that
was the first structure to be hit by the plane and set afire. The
aircraft then plunged down on Kent Street, where it struck nine
cars and set them ablaze. The gas tanks of most later exploded,
damaging the multifamily homes lining the street.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the block, the plane sideswiped a KFC restaurant
and broke apart. The bodies of its occupants were hurled out onto a
parking lot, and the plane's fiery debris shot across Springfield
Avenue, a commercial thoroughfare, and came to rest on sidewalks
and side streets, in yards and vacant lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost three lives, but it could have been a lot worse,''
James said. He said that lives had undoubtedly been spared because
a nearby preschool had been closed for the long Thanksgiving
weekend, and that a fast-food restaurant struck by the plane had
not been open.
</P>
<P>
   The crash site on Saturday was a scene of terrible devastation:
the hulks of mangled, burned-out cars that had been set afire, the
shattered houses with windows and doors agape, blood spattered on
the wall of the restaurant and its parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks were cordoned off with yellow police tape to keep
out curiosity seekers, but some residents were allowed into their
homes briefly to retrieve belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Gennie Holpe, of 14 Kent Street, said as she returned for
clothing that she had spent a sleepless night on a cot at the
Salvation Army center, tormented by the recollection of the bodies
she had seen. ``I can't even sleep,'' she said. ``I'm a woman of
God, and I'm trying to be strong. But you can't even imagine
something like this. It was like a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rosella Reese, 84, the owner of 27 Kent Street, who had been
forced temporarily out of a home she had lived in for 43 years,
voiced sorrow for the dead and for her devastated street. ``This
pilot took his whole family,'' she said, ``and destroyed this
community with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
