<HEADER>
A2764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-CARCHASE-NYT &LR;      11-27 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CARCHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADCAST OF MAN'S DEATH REKINDLES A DEBATE IN LOS ANGELES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The year after a suicide broadcast on live
television prompted soul-searching and public apologies from news
directors, five Southern California stations showed a car chase on
Friday that ended with the man being shot to death by police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whose identity was not released on Saturday by the
authorities, led the police and state highway patrol officers on a
200-mile, three-hour chase from San Bernardino County to San Diego,
where he was shot after emerging from his car with a handgun aimed
at officers, the San Diego Police Department said. The department
said the chase began at 6:45 a.m. after a sheriff's deputy tried to
stop a white 1979 Datsun 280Z with expired registration tags.
</P>
<P>
   Many stations covered the chase from news helicopters as part of
their regular morning broadcasts. Three stations in Los Angeles _
NBC affiliate KNBC, Fox affiliate KTTV, and WB affiliate KTLA _ and
two stations in San Diego, KFMB and KNSD, carried the story to its
conclusion on the day after Thanksgiving, when children were out of
school.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage, which came with less than a week to go in the
November sweeps period that will be used to determine stations'
advertising rates, once again highlights the debate over ethical
standards for television news in a region that has come to rely on
helicopters as a staple of the broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, news directors from some of the stations said they
were performing a public service by informing viewers about a
dangerous chase on California highways and said they acted
responsibly by pulling away to a wide angle as the man emerged from
his car holding a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the individual got out of the car, they pulled way back
to a wide shot,'' said John Frenzel, the director of programming at
Fox. ``Given the circumstances, that seemed like using our best
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all stations in the area thought it was a large enough
story to supersede normal coverage.
</P>
<P>
   KCBS, which was broadcasting its national morning news program,
broke in with occasional reports on the chase but did not carry it
all the way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that some bad guy's running away from policemen is
not a huge surprise,'' said Roger Bell, the news director of KCBS.
``I think we know they're going to end badly.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Daniel V. Jones, apparently distraught over his
treatment by a health maintenance organization, set himself and his
dog on fire on a freeway and later shot himself in the head with a
shotgun. Stations that showed live coverage received calls from
angry viewers.
</P>
<P>
   KNBC received 2,000 complaints in that instance, but that
station had the closest image of the shooting on Friday, according
to The Los Angeles Times. Managers at the station declined to
comment on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
