<HEADLINE>
EARLY GAMES REVEAL SOME SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're almost at the quarter-pole in the 1999-2000 NBA season and
it's a good time to take a look at some of the surprising and
disappointing teams in the league. The Celtics, of course, have to
be considered something of a surprise, although Rick Pitino would
tell you he knew all along that it'd be thus.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have some company in the upside department. Here, in
no particular order, are some teams who will not want to see
November end.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Sonics have had an incredibly soft schedule in
terms of competition _ their toughest road game has been at Phoenix
_ but they've also had success on the road. They are getting a big
lift from two newcomers, Vernon Maxwell and Ruben Patterson (the
Western Conference's version of Adrian Griffin). By the end of this
week, however, they'll have played the Clippers three times, the
Warriors twice, and their early Eastern swing was hardly taxing. We
also should note that Gary Payton has brought his A game.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO: We figured the Kings would be better. They got off
to a ridiculous start in part because they've played only two
non-Japan road games so far. And those were in Texas against
Houston and Dallas. And their Arco Arena wins: Utah, Denver,
Vancouver, Houston, New Jersey, and Golden State. So we'll reserve
judgment until they come back from their Eastern swing, when they
play Miami, Orlando, Atlanta, Washington, and New Jersey. Then they
go back home and face the Lakers, Heat, and Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI: The story here is the resuscitation of Jamal Mashburn.
He's playing as well as any small forward in the league and has
responded wonderfully to the new rules and Pat Riley's Showtime II.
The big unknown is whether Mashburn can stay healthy. If he can,
the Heat will remain the East's best team and possibly make it out
of the first round of playoffs. It also doesn't hurt that Alonzo
Mourning and Tim Hardaway are playing as if they know this might be
their year.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there are teams that will be happy to move into a new
month, although for a couple, it may already be too late.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY: Maybe we had the Nets overrated coming into the
season, but two wins in their first 12 games? It'd be nice if Don
Casey had his full roster, although expectations will be huge for a
quick U-turn. And what has happened to Keith Van Horn? The guy
looks as if he went to Antoine Walker's Shot School. It'd also be
nice if Kerry Kittles sucked it up and Stephon Marbury realized
that numbers don't make the player.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: A revolution is brewing, and Rudy Tomjanovich is
sticking with his old, loyal generals instead of his new, brash
recruits. The Rockets need to decide what team they're going to be.
The one problem is that Houston has lost a lot of home games, and
it's always difficult to get it back on the road. Maybe the voters
of Houston knew what lay ahead when they rejected a new arena
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA: After their Thanksgiving loss at home to Detroit (their
second in Conseco Fieldhouse), Jalen Rose said the Pacers were
``awful.'' He said they were playing like ``garbage'' (the refuse,
not the band). They looked awful against the Celtics because they
showed up and did very little extra, including rebounding. They
have to come to grips with Rik Smits, who can't play a speed game
anymore. And what has happened to Reggie Miller's shooting eye?
These guys can't be dismissed, but they're losing games they didn't
lose in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery redux
</P>
<P>
   From the Don't Rub It In Dept.: When the Spurs were in town last
week, we asked Gregg Popovich to go back to May of 1997 when the
futures of two franchises were determined by bouncing lottery
balls. Popovich said before the Tim Duncan Lottery, he had a
special task for assistant Mike Budenholzer: make up lineups and
put them on wooden boards for the Spurs with the names of likely
draftees. Then, match those lineup boards against other teams in
the Western Conference. The Spurs figured they'd get a top three
pick; they had the third-worst record in the league behind
Vancouver and Boston. So Budenholzer put Van Horn's name on the
list and matched it up against other teams. ``There was another
guy, too,'' Popovich said. But it wasn't Duncan. ``We didn't even
bring his name up,'' Popovich said. Then came the lottery. And all
those boards that Budenholzer had painstakingly made? ``He asked me
what to do with them,'' Popovich said. ``I told him to use it as
firewood.'' The Spurs never worked out Duncan or brought him in for
the obligatory interview. Hardly anyone even bothered to call and
inquire about Duncan's availability. ``Rick (Pitino) called about
10 minutes after the lottery, which I expected,'' Popovich said.
``I would have done the same thing. He offered me his team, his
horses, anything. But there were other times when someone would
call and start talking and we both just started laughing.''
Popovich said he went to St. Croix for a week and knew what he had
when he discussed the Utah Summer League with Duncan. ``I told him
it would help him with things like illegal defenses, getting to
know our coaches, our system, and a general introduction to the
NBA. He said, `If it'll help me, I'll be there.' That's what I knew
what I had.'' Popovich also saw the no-flash, no-frills Duncan in
one game against Portland. ``He got a shot blocked by (Kelvin)
Cato, who knocked it into the 15th row, and then (Cato) did all
this jumping around and dancing,'' said Popovich. ``Tim's
expression never changed. Then, later in the game, Tim sent one of
Cato's shots into the 15th row and his expression still didn't
change. I knew he was special then.'' . . . Stanley Roberts played
with Shaquille O'Neal in college and for a handful of teams in an
otherwise uninspired NBA career. But he'll be known more for two
things: his weight and his expulsion from the league for failing a
drug test. Roberts is the first player to be banished since the NBA
and the Players Association agreed to increase the number of banned
substances. The league said Roberts was found to have an
amphetamine-based designer drug in his system. In an interview with
a Houston television station, Roberts said he never took a designer
drug and was not given a re-test. The league said he was re-tested
and failed that as well (Roberts said the same sample was used).
``This is a tragic thing,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown said. ``This
is really a disappointment.'' . . . The Sixers called up Kevin
Ollie to take the spot of the injured Allen Iverson. If nothing
else, the injury will eliminate the problem Brown faced in trying
to pair Iverson with Larry Hughes. Now he can put Hughes in at
shooting guard and the kid will get a chance to show his stuff. A
lot of people think he has a lot of stuff to show. The Celtics
considered signing Ollie before they went out and got Doug Overton
. . . Iverson, by the way, is on the cover of the latest Sporting
News. In the article, which talks about the new rules benefitting
Iverson's style, the Answer says, ``The only person who can stop me
is me, if I take bad shots'' _ which he does ``or rush things'' _
which he also does. ``But no individual in this league can stop
me.'' But a broken thumb can . . . Jim McIlvaine was on the Nets
last year when they started 2-10, and this year's team was 2-10
after a victory Wednesday over Golden State. ``I think the attitude
is better this year,'' McIlvaine said. ``We have guys who are still
doing the extra work, the lifting, things like that. That's
encouraging. But we do miss Jayson (Williams), his energy, his
enthusiasm. It's just a big, gaping hole that won't be filled until
he comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Slow time for Mullin
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McHale went out this way and didn't like it. Chris Mullin,
also one of the NBA's Top 50, is now, basically, an afterthought in
the Indiana rotation. But McHale's dwindling minutes in his final
year were due as much to injuries as declining skills. Mullin is
healthy and can still shoot, but he has been relegated to DNP
status on a number of occasions because he can't beat out Rose or
Al Harrington. ``This is something everyone goes through at some
point in their career,'' he said. ``I want to handle this thing the
same way I handled things when I was averaging 25 a game for the
Warriors and leading the league in minutes. There was someone
behind me back then and now I'm the one behind them. But the kids
are playing well, they're open to instruction and work, and that
makes it more enjoyable. It's easier when you're around guys with
that kind of attitude. Right now, it's working. But I'm in shape
and I'll be ready.'' . . . The Knicks' horrific schedule (13 of
their first 18 on the road) improves this week with roadies in
Milwaukee and across the Hudson against the Nets. They went 2-3 out
West and returned to find that Larry Johnson, who missed some of
the trip, will be out a while longer with back woes. LJ says he'll
be back in a couple weeks after undergoing steroid treatments. If
that doesn't work, he may need surgery. Patrick Ewing, meanwhile,
is hoping to be back by Christmas. The Knicks are playing the way
they did for most of last season: fractured, disjointed, aimless.
Latrell Sprewell got revenge of sorts when the Knicks won in Golden
State last weekend. But he also was fined $10,000 for swearing at
fans . . . You could have made some serious change had you walked
into a parlor in Vegas and put some money on Bob Sura and Brevin
Knight being the starting backcourt in Cleveland. Sura, of course,
was Fratello non grata but has been liberated by the new rules and
a new coach. Knight was _ and always will be _ undersized and is
entering free agency. The Cavs even drafted Andre Miller to protect
themselves in the event Knight could not be re-signed (and, of
course, because Miller was a logical pick at that spot). Knight won
the job hands-down in training camp, has improved his shooting
dramatically, and has seen his game improve with the new rules. So,
can we establish that Knight is a keeper? Not in his mind. ``I have
to prove it every year. Next year, there'll be different questions
and I'll have to do it all over again,'' he said. ``That's how I
look at it. I've been proving it all my life. You have to do that
until you become the best, or are considered one of the best. Until
that happens, you're always going to have to prove something. I
know what I need to do to make us win, to make us go. I know what I
need to do to make me successful. So that's all I worry about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
