<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BILLSADV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAVE BEEN DOWN THIS ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Something has always seemed to click in
these back-to-the-wall situations the past two seasons. The
Patriots respond to the gloom and doom with victories. They go from
bums to contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Twice they have resurrected themselves from ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Can this collection of underachievers rebound against Buffalo
and save their playoff hopes a third time in three years after the
midseason mark?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it in the past, but if we don't do it Sunday, it
won't mean anything,'' said Larry Whigham, who as an emotional
leader on the field is often a good judge of the team's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't accept losing here. We might lose for a few games,
but we don't continue it. We have too much pride. There's too much
athleticism here for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Whigham said the Patriots had an intense week of practice. Not
overly tough. Nobody was heaving buckets. He called it ``intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll said Thursday and Friday were intense, with
Thursday having a lot of ``hard hitting.'' But Wednesday's practice
didn't meet his standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look around this locker room,'' said Whigham after
Friday's practice, ``nobody is panicking. Everybody, to a man,
knows what has to happen. We know because we've been through it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. A brief history:
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Carroll era starts with amazing success, as the
Patriots roll to a 4-0 start and get to 5-1 before the tumbling
begins. A 24-19 loss to the Jets at the Meadowlands in the second
Tuna Bowl is the first of three consecutive losses. The hex is
broken by beating the Bills, 31-10, to go to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the Mosh Pit incident, which precedes a 27-7
thrashing by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. At 6-5, the Patriots are in
third place behind the 7-4 Dolphins and Jets, one game ahead of
Buffalo at 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   With backs against the wall, the Patriots respond by beating
Miami, 27-24. Then they eke out a 20-17 victory over Indianapolis.
Miami knocks off Oakland and the Jets begin their swoon with a loss
to Buffalo. There is a three-way tie for first place at 8-5 among
the Patriots, Dolphins, and Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins and Patriots keep pace the following week, the
Patriots winning at Jacksonville, 26-20. Both lose their
next-to-last games of the year, and then in the final week, the
Patriots win at Miami, 14-12, to take the division title with a
10-6 record. They beat Miami again in the wild-card game before
succumbing to Pittsburgh, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Patriots start 4-1 before sinking to 5-5 at their
lowest moment. Injuries had mounted by this time, and New England
was in fourth place. Talk of firing Carroll is at an all-time high,
but once again the Patriots save the coach and their self-respect
with three straight wins, starting with a 26-23 victory over Miami
on a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The streak ends with a loss to St. Louis, in a game they
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   With Drew Bledsoe out with a fractured index finger, the
Patriots face a desperate situation _ having to beat the 11-3 San
Francisco 49ers with Scott Zolak to qualify for the playoffs. They
win with three seconds left on Adam Vinatieri's 35-yard fied goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots finish fourth but make the playoffs. Without
Bledsoe and other injured players, they do not get past the
wild-card round, losing to Jacksonville, 25-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the same situation two years ago, against
Buffalo,'' recalled Carroll. ``Same thing. I wish we didn't do it
this way, but this is what we're faced with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The core guys around here have been through adversity and know
how to deal with it,'' said defensive end Ferric Collons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of making plays. Nobody is scared or nervous. We
had the same season last year, slowed down a little bit, and then
picked it back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we have lulls? I don't know. I think this team has the
best talent in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we can come back from terrible odds shows the talent.
Call it luck. We win games when we're supposed to and other times
we shoot each other in the foot. We go out there and self-destruct
and then we look at the film and there's no way the other team
should be able to do what they do against us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a week when the Patriots needed to be extra serious, they had
two players, Lawyer Milloy and Vincent Brisby, involved in a
scuffle at a nightclub, and another, Terry Glenn, late for practice
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to the radio and I hear people saying this team has
been torn apart by dissension,'' said defensive tackle Chad Eaton.
``Well, that's not true. Everybody in this organization wants to
win. I don't see it coming apart for us. The coaches are putting us
in position to make plays and we've just got to deliver.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
