<HEADER>
A2767 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-QUALIFY     11-27 1972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-QUALIFYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD, SWEAT AND TEARS IN THE CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On those days when he would head over to Bass River to hit
balls, Jason Caron would hope to run into Jim Hallet. ``He was my
idol. I'd watch him chip and putt for hours,'' said Caron.
</P>
<P>
   Hallet's hard work and gift for golf led to a few years of glory
on the PGA Tour until hand injuries took their toll. The pride of
South Yarmouth took a few years off, then tried to revive his pro
golf career at the PGA Tour Qualifying Tournament this fall. Though
he failed to make it through the first stage, Hallet can be given
credit for lending inspiration to one who made it all the way:
Caron.
</P>
<P>
   His was perhaps the longest of long-shot stories at last week's
final stage. Caron, 27, was just another titanium-carrying young
gun who was supposed to collapse at the first scent of pressure. He
was from the Hooters Tour. No PGA Tour experience. Heck, no Nike
Tour experience. Just how was he going to survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I got down there and told myself it was just another
tournament,'' said Caron. ``I just focused on golf, and in the back
of my mind I told myself to just play the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   His best was just good enough. He finished the six rounds at 8
under par, which was the cut line. The kid from Dennis-Yarmouth
High School was in the last group of qualifiers, one of just 40
golfers to earn a coveted PGA Tour card for next year. You could
not even have been quoted odds on that happening just a few weeks
ago, when Caron was one of nearly 2,000 young men who carried a
crazy dream in a bag along with 14 golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't think you can make it,'' said Caron.
``I'm proof that dreams come true.''
</P>
<P>
   And how truly well he played.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 40 golfers who earned their cards at the Doral Resort in
Miami, Caron was one of the few who had to play his way through the
first and second stages.
</P>
<P>
   Four rounds at Jennings Mill GC in Bogart, Ga.: 71-71-67-70_279.
Tied for sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Four rounds at Kiva Dunes in Gulf Shores, Ala.: 71-69-72-70_282.
Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Six rounds at Doral: 68-69-70-70-67-68_412. Tied for 35th.
</P>
<P>
   Toss all the numbers together and you get a ticket to the big
leagues and a chance to walk the fairways in Tiger Woods's
monstrous shadow. But before rushing forward, stop and ponder the
remarkable stretch of golf Caron just played. In 14 rounds of
tournament golf, he never once shot over par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the first group (on the final day at Doral) so when I
finished, I sat around a long time,'' said Caron, whose brother
Nate caddied for him. For much of the sixth day, it appeared that 9
under was the magic number, but nerves being what they are, the bad
shots piled up late in the day and 8 under got in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I birdied nine and 10,'' said Caron, who graduated in 1994
from Charleston Southern University in South Carolina, ``but made a
double at the 12th to fall back to 6 under.'' But birdies at the
13th and 16th got him to 8 under, and when he parred in, the long,
agonizing wait was on.
</P>
<P>
   When he had made it, Caron couldn't help but think of Hallet,
and of the people at Bass River and Bayberry, those Yarmouth
courses where he had spent so many countless hours. He was never
high-profile on the state amateur scene, but always he had the
dream, and ``there are so many people (on the Cape) who have been
very good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls came from friends and well-wishers (including
Hallet's father), and Caron will attempt to offer thanks in person
when he comes home for Christmas. The stay, however, will be short
and sweet, for duty calls and there will be long practice sessions
down South in preparation for a most improbable date with the 2000
PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy endings
</P>
<P>
   Caron's was one of the nice tales from the Q School finale, but
there were some horrors. None more disheartening than Jaxon
Brigman. He finished at 8 under thanks to a sterling 5-under 65 and
was accepting congratulations for earning his card. Then an
official asked him why he signed for a 66. Brigman was in shock.
Indeed, he had signed a scorecard that said he shot 66. Because it
was higher than what he had actually shot, he had to accept the
score, which put him at 7 under and onto the BUY.com Tour next
year. Next tale of woe belongs to Vic Wilk, who came to the tee on
his 108th hole at 9 under and probably thought he needed a par to
secure his card. But he hooked his drive into trees, and instead of
playing it safe and possibly making bogey (which would have got him
in at 8 under), Wilk gambled. He tried to hook a shot around trees
onto an island green, but it never took the big turn, landing in
the water. He made a double-bogey and missed the cut at 7 under.
Then there was Brian Tennyson, who was 10 under through 15, only to
finish bogey, three-putt bogey, double-bogey, and miss out at 6
under. Brian Claar was 9 under until a double-bogey at the 17th
left him holding a pass to the BUY.com Tour . . . It wasn't under a
blazing spotlight, but Melanie Curtin had her own challenge at a
qualifying tournament to secure a spot on the Futures Tour. The
28-year-old Weymouth native didn't know what to expect in Lakeland,
Fla., last week and she was surprised at the depth when she
arrived. ``I looked up on the putting green and said, `That looks
like Jenny Chuasiriporn,' '' said Curtin, who blossomed on the WGAM
scene the last two summers. Indeed, Chuasiriporn, like Curtin, was
trying for a spot on this training ground for future LPGA Tour
players. The 1998 US Women's Open runner-up finished in a tie for
fifth to breeze, while Curtin, after a 70-75 start, fell back to an
80-77, but still earned full-time playing status for next year.
``I'm hoping to have two good years on the Futures Tour and move
onto the LGPA Tour,'' said Curtin, who entered the tournament as an
amateur but will now turn pro. ``I'm committing myself to a full
schedule, but not expecting too much the first year.'' . . .
Remember Philip Walton? He secured the stunning Ryder Cup victory
for Europe at Oak Hill in 1995 with a singles win over Jay Haas,
but the fame was certainly short-lived. He plummeted to 92d on the
Order of Merit the next year, was 66th in 1997 and 1998, and his
best tournament finish in 1999 was 35th, which gives a hint as to
why he was back at Tour School last week. Alas, his struggles
continued as the 37-year-old Irishman finished 77th in the
six-round test at Sotogrande, Spain. Needless to say, he won't have
his card next year, thanks in large part to scores of 77, 78, and
81. Other veteran Europeans who failed at the final of Q School
included Stuart Cage and Paul Way, who as a 20-year-old made the
European Ryder Cup team in 1985. Trevor Immelman, a promising
youngster from South Africa, was another failure at the European Q
School, but 1998 British Open sensation Justin Rose prevailed with
a tie for third. Since turning pro after nearly winning that Open
at Royal Birkdale, Rose has rarely made a cut and he failed to gain
his card at last year's qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   She will be missed
</P>
<P>
   It was strictly for fun, a little game of word association with
Arnold Palmer. Pebble Beach. Augusta. The Masters. For everything
thrown out, he was quick with a reply. Then they threw at him the
words ``Winnie Palmer'' and, without missing a beat, he said: ``She
let me be Arnold Palmer.'' Indeed, his wife was the greatest part
of his life and he never hesitated to tell you that. When she died
last Saturday at 65 after a battle with cancer, it was a terrible
loss for the game's greatest ambassador, and for the many people
who had enjoyed her company through the years. People like Richard
Connolly of Concord, who has enjoyed a longtime friendship with
Palmer and was among those who attended the funeral service last
Monday. ``The theme of the service was `smile, be happy, and try to
help people,' '' said Connolly. ``That's the way she was. She was
so special.'' A few winters ago, more than a thousand people turned
out for a Ouimet Scholarship dinner to honor the King, and at a
private reception, which was wall-to-wall with Boston business
leaders, a gentleman seemed a bit frantic. A woman asked him what
was wrong, and he proceeded to tell her how busy the day had been,
what with meetings with bosses and no time for lunch. Relax and get
a drink, she said, and the man did just that. When he returned, he
discovered that the woman had retrieved some hors d'oeuvres.
Thankful, he extended his hand and introduced himself. ``Nice to
meet you,'' the woman said. ``I'm Winnie Palmer.'' . . . What many
people never realized was that while Palmer and Jack Nicklaus
carried on a heated rivalry on the golf course, their wives
developed a close friendship. Barbara Nicklaus told reporters that
recently, while sweating out a hurricane at their home in Southern
Florida, she received a call from Winnie, who, despite more
pressing concerns, was offering her wishes and prayers . . . The
Nicklauses had faithfully watched all five rounds of son Gary's
effort in the final stage of tour qualifying, but missed the sixth
when they went to Latrobe, Pa., for the funeral. What a round they
missed. Gary, 30, shot a 63, tied for 12th, and easily qualified
for his PGA Tour card in 2000. He had failed nine other years to
make it through Q School and his proud father told reporters:
``I've been telling Gary all along that he's a lot better player
than he gives himself credit for being.'' Locally, golf fans got to
see just how good the kid is when he was paired with his father in
the CVS Charity Classic at Rhode Island CC in Barrington in August.
On the first day, Gary won a skins pool and veteran PGA Tour stars
were telling observers how impressed they were with the youngster.
</P>
<P>
   The rich get richer
</P>
<P>
   You perhaps were thinking of getting Woods a Christmas present,
perhaps a golf bag emblazoned with ``Buick'' on its side? Forget
it. He's already got a bunch of them on order _ thanks to an
endorsement deal that is reportedly worth $10 million-$15 million
through 2001. Part of the deal calls for Woods to play in six of
eight Buick events over the two seasons (the company sponsors four
a year), which brings up an interesting question. Woods has been
adamant about resting the week before major tournaments, but that
will have to change this year because the Buick Classic
(Westchester, N.Y.) is the week before the US Open and the Buick
Open (Grand Blanc, Mich.) leads into the PGA Championship. Assuming
Woods plays the Buick Invitational in February (he's the defending
champ and loves Torrey Pines in San Diego) and the Buick Challenge
in September, it stands to reason that he'll have to choose between
playing before the Open or the PGA. A guess: Woods will rest before
the US Open at Pebble Beach and play the Buick Open the week prior
to the PGA at Valhalla since Michigan-to-Kentucky isn't as taxing .
. . Thomas Bjorn's playoff victory over Sergio Garcia at the Dunlop
Phoenix tournament in Japan may have barely registered on the radar
screen, but it had major implications _ as in a trip to Augusta for
the Dane. It moved Bjorn to 39th (he had been 55th) in the world
rankings, and the Top 50 get invited to play in the Masters . . .
The Golf Channel is a must for any diehard fan, but it is
especially crucial during the winter when events such as this
weekend's Holden Australian Open are shown live. Monday night, Dana
Quigley will appear on TGC's ``Golf Talk Live,'' from 8 to 9 . . .
Jim Maddalena, the assistant pro at Willowbend in Mashpee, has been
on a pretty good roll. He won three straight events in the Cape Cod
Pro-Am League and is in a tight battle with Jeff Bailey for the
Sullivan Award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
