<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALLNOTES-SCOUTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD SIGNS IN SCOUTING DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In yet another sign that all is not well within the ranks of the
Red Sox scouting department, Luke Wrenn, the scout credited with
signing Nomar Garciaparra, has resigned to take a position with the
Arizona Diamondbacks. Wrenn was hired by Mike Rizzo, a former Sox
area scout who is now the scouting director for the Diamondbacks.
Wrenn is merely the latest scout to leave the Sox fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written to the management in Boston,'' Wrenn said. ``They
know why I'm leaving. I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrenn, who will remain in the same area (scouting central and
northern Florida for the Diamondbacks), acknowledged that he was
frustrated that the Sox failed to sign players that were drafted
from his area last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated that we were unable to sign my guys we had
drafted seventh, 16th, and 26th,'' said Wrenn, who had scouted 26th
pick Marshall McDougall, the Florida State second baseman who hit
an NCAA-record six home runs in one game last season. ``But that
was this year's frustration. To me, it was just the last straw.
They knew I was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of my mind I was hoping that I could stay, and
under certain conditions I would have stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   What Wrenn would not say is that there clearly was a conflict
with Sox scouting director Wayne Britton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of guys who have left,'' Wrenn said.
``But as long as Boston keeps playing well, you're not going to
hear much about it. We are about the farthest people away from
Boston, but area scouts are some of your hardest-working people,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Headed for trouble
</P>
<P>
   Remember that head-first slide Kenny Lofton made into first base
in Game 5 of the Division Series? He suffered a dislocated left
shoulder, and now the Indians fear there may be rotator cuff damage
that could sideline him until June. That could leave the Tribe
scrambling for a leadoff man and center fielder. Lofton is
scheduled to see Dr. James Andrews for a second opinion this week .
. . It will cost more _ a lot more _ to have a good seat at Dodger
Stadium next season, to watch a team that is drawing ever closer to
having a $100 million payroll. Price of a premium seat in Chavez
Ravine has gone up 43 percent, from $28 to as much as $40. It will
still be possible to buy some seats in the upper deck and bleachers
for as little as $6 . . . The Rockies also raised ticket prices for
the third time since moving into Coors Field. The increases average
4 percent . . . The Dodgers, who probably won't know until next
month the outcome of Major League Baseball's investigation into
whether they signed third baseman Adrian Beltre as an underage
player, are distancing themselves from Tommy Lasorda's charge that
there are ``50 players in the major leagues that have been signed
illegally.'' But given the ease with which false birth documents
can be obtained in countries such as the Dominican Republic, where
such record-keeping is haphazard at best, what some may dismiss as
an emotional outburst from the volatile Lasorda may be closer to
the truth than those in the game care to acknowledge. Under current
rules, teams cannot sign a player in draft-exempt countries, like
the Dominican, until age 16, with the added provision that the
player must be 17 by the time he completes his first professional
season. There is incentive for both players from impoverished
circumstances and teams eager to grab top talents to cheat. As
difficult as it may be for MLB to verify a player's age, some sort
of monitoring system must be put in place. In Beltre's case, agent
Scott Boras is accusing the Dodgers of knowingly signing the player
before his 16th birthday and attempting to have the third baseman
declared a free agent . . . Bill Russell, who succeeded Lasorda as
Dodger manager and then was fired two years later, has made it back
to the big leagues as the third base coach of the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays. Russell managed the Devil Rays' Double A affiliate in Orlando
to the Southern League title last season . . . Blue Jays manager
Jim Fregosi is ready to take on all comers who are ripping Toronto
for its trades of outfielder Shawn Green to the Dodgers and pitcher
Pat Hentgen to the Cardinals. ``My only concern is how Raul
(Mondesi) is portrayed in this city and if they take it out on
him,'' Fregosi said of the outfielder who came to the Blue Jays
from the Dodgers. ``I don't think that's fair. Let them take it out
on me. I'll take the heat. In my estimation, Mondesi is a very
talented player who plays the game as hard as anybody.'' Meanwhile,
Blue Jays fans already barbecuing GM Gord Ash are ready to pounce
again if slugger Carlos Delgado becomes the next to leave . . .
Tuffy Rhodes, who made a cameo appearance for the Red Sox in 1995,
led the Japan Pacific League in home runs with 40, runs with 94,
and RBIs with 101 while playing for Kintetsu.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions to the number
</P>
<P>
   Clip and save: Pedro and Ramon Martinez will go 30-12 between
them next season, according to projections made by Stats Inc.,
which acknowledges that pitching projections are trickier than
those for position players. Pedro the Younger will go 19-5 with a
2.21 ER1, while Ramon will go 11-7 with a 3.44 ERA. The Stats folks
are predicting another big year for Garciaparra, too: .319, 33 home
runs, and 111 RBIs, and another sub-.300 year for Mo Vaughn (.296,
34 home runs, 106 RBIs). Vaughn hit .281 last season, only .258
against righthanders, against whom his ankle injury bothered him
most. Vaughn was still tough with runners in scoring position,
batting .348 (46 for 132), though Angels fans might be hard-pressed
to come up with one big hit during a misbegotten '99 season. Stats
also gives Mark McGwire a 32 percent chance of finishing his career
with 800 home runs, with Ken Griffey having a slightly better
chance (34 percent) . . . Randy Johnson and Pedro Martinez are the
only active pitchers averaging double figures in strikeouts per
nine innings. Johnson has 10.77 whiffs per nine innings, Martinez
10.16. Hideo Nomo, surprisingly, is third at 9.66, with Roger
Clemens fourth at 8.62. Clemens is the active leader in wins (247),
starts (479), innings (3,462 1/3), complete games (115), shutouts
(45), strikeouts (3,316), and hit batsmen (114) . . . Further ammo
for those arguing that Fenway Park's infield ranks among the worst
in the league: The Sox last season made 17 more infield errors at
home than on the road (56 to 39) and the opponents' fielding was
worse, too (42 errors in Fenway, 31 on their home fields). No AL
team made more infield errors at home last season than the Sox. In
the last three years, the Sox have made 159 infield errors at home,
131 on the road. Opponents have made 116 at Fenway, 109 in their
home parks . . . Reliever Russ Springer, who went to the World
Series with Atlanta, was happy to return last week to the team that
traded him to the Braves, the Diamondbacks. Springer, who signed a
two-year deal for slightly less than $2 million, recalled what it
was like when he was first drafted by the expansion team. ``I live
in the woods in Louisiana _ I mean, out in the woods,'' Springer
said. ``When you hear a car coming, you know it's coming to your
place. Either that, or somebody made a wrong turn. It was one of
those package-express trucks with a package of stuff from Arizona
saying, `Welcome to the Diamondbacks.' Things like that show class.
I'll always remember that.'' . . . Padres president Larry Lucchino
is back to work after undergoing surgery last month for prostate
cancer. This was his second bout with cancer. In the '80s, he
endured non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell's travels
</P>
<P>
   Alan Trammell was disappointed to end his 23-year association
with the Tigers, but wound up with a fine consolation prize when he
was hired as a coach in San Diego, the town in which he grew up.
``Down the road, I probably would like to manage,'' Trammell told
reporters. ``But I've only coached one year in the big leagues, and
one year is not enough. I need to coach.'' . . . For the second
straight winter, Giants outfielder Ellis Burks has undergone
surgery on both knees. Burks played in just 120 games last season
and never fully recovered. He said this go-round should be easier.
``Taking extra time rehabbing, I hope to have two strong legs and
not worry about taking days off after a night game,'' said Burks,
who even on gimpy knees had a good season, hitting 31 home runs,
second on the club to Barry Bonds, and driving in 96 runs . . . The
Yankees are scheduled to play an exhibition April 1 against the
Giants in new Pacific Bell Park, their first game in San Francisco
since 1962, when they beat the Giants in seven games to win the
World Series. That's the series that ended in Candlestick Park with
Yankees second baseman Bobby Richardson catching Willie McCovey's
wicked liner with runners on second and third to preserve Ralph
Terry's 1-0 win . . . The hiring of Rod Carew, deposed as Anaheim's
hitting coach, completes the first staff of new Brewers manager
Davey Lopes. Carew joins pitching coach Bob Apodaca, third base
coach Chris Speier, bench coach Jerry Royster, first base coach
Gary Allenson and the lone holdover, bullpen coach Bill Castro. ``I
thought he was still part of the Angels organization,'' Lopes said
of Carew. ``I couldn't believe we got a guy of that caliber.'' The
Brewers originally were planning to offer the job to Gary Matthews,
already on board to coach their minor league hitters. But Matthews
took a radio job with the Blue Jays instead . . . Cardinals GM Walt
Jocketty said McGwire, whose $11 million contract option was
recently exercised by St. Louis, was upset by the $84 million deal
to which the Dodgers signed Green. ``Guys are getting more and more
money,'' Jocketty said. ``He kind of wanted to make a statement by
picking up the option _ that `we don't have to have the top
dollar.' '' . . . And don't laugh, but Heathcliff Slocumb, the
Human Angioplasty, has quietly rehabilitated his career, last week
signing a two-year deal for close to $3 million with the Cardinals.
Slocumb's days as a closer are probably long over, but he was
effective as a middle- and late-inning man, compiling a 3-2 record
with a 2.36 ERA. The Cardinals are still looking hard at free agent
Mike Jackson as their closer . . . Rafael Palmeiro's rehabilitation
work on his knee is going so well that he plans to shed his
protective brace next season. ``It feels better every day,'' said
Palmeiro, who said he plans to play every day at first base next
season after starting just 28 times there for the Rangers last
season. ``I can't believe how good it feels.'' . . . Closer
Kazuhiro Sasaki has company among Japanese pitchers looking for
work on this side of the international date line. The Mariners,
among the teams interested in landing Sasaki, also were visited by
lefthanded starter Kimiyasa Kudo, who is 37 but a two-time MVP in
Japan's Pacific League. ``Kudo is a solid professional pitcher,''
said Jim Colborn, Seattle's Pacific Rim scout, who also played and
coached in Japan. ``He has been a key part of several championship
teams, including this past season, when he pitched one or two
shutouts in Daiei's win in the Japan Series.'' Kudo's courtship was
much lower key than the one the Mariners afforded Sasaki, who
stayed at the Four Seasons Hotel, dressed at Griffey's locker, and
was given a jersey with No. 22, his favorite number. Sasaki was
born on 2/22/78, reportedly at 2:22 a.m. Or so the story goes.
Sasaki also visited with the Yankees, Mets, and Diamondbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
