<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGEFOOTBAL-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE COULD BE WHIPPING UP A MIRACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ So it has begun again for the University of
Massachusetts. Another season, really, with higher stakes. Which is
the way Mark Whipple likes it.
</P>
<P>
   Make that loves it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really special,'' said the UMass coach in a locker
room filled with players who believed the gospel he had preached
all season and repeated Saturday on a postcard Southern afternoon.
``Enjoy it. Keep the faith. Just a great, great win.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was. UMass 30, Furman 23, in overtime in the Division 1-AA
playoffs, which will continue next week for the Minutemen in
Statesboro, Ga., against mighty Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   You are tempted to say this was as good as it gets for UMass.
But then you must remember that a year ago it was even better, when
the Minutemen went from worst to first and won a national
championship in Whipple's first season in Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Now another journey is under way and Whipple is leading the
Minutemen, with their three regular-season losses, on another
Southern Exposure reality tour.
</P>
<P>
   Take a good look at Whipple, UMass fans. Appreciate what you
have. The man can flat-out coach, and Saturday he and his staff
proved it.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Minutemen the better team? Questionable, especially on
the road, against a team that was good enough to not only spank
eight 1-AA opponents, but 1-A North Carolina as well.
</P>
<P>
   But UMass was tougher. Tougher at the start, tougher at the end.
And the reason was Whipple, who coaches with tough love.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple didn't know what to expect when his team got off the bus
at Paladin Stadium Saturdya morning in 60 degree sunshine. He did
know he was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating North Carolina was not a fluke,'' he said, sitting in
the tiny coaches dressing room, while his players put on their
uniforms an hour before the game. ``These guys are good. They've
got speed. I just don't know. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What concerned Whipple was that he couldn't do anything more
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of my hands,'' he said. ``I just hope . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple's concern was well-hidden. He is not one for big pregame
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never won a game yet with a pregame speech,'' he said before
walking into the locker room and delivering a simple pep talk,
telling his players to ``go out and enjoy yourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. Nothing about being better. Nothing about acting
like national champions.
</P>
<P>
   That is not Whipple's style. His words have a punch.
</P>
<P>
   Which was evident at halftime when the Minutemen came into the
locker room trailing, 14-10, the result of several defensive
breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst defense you guys have played all season,''
Whipple roared. ``What are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   But then he backed off, calm again, back in the coaches room,
while his players banged lockers, beating themselves up more than
Whipple ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, it was time to bring his team back up, to
erase the lingering doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're better than them,'' he said. ``It's going to happen.
It's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So it did, with some help, of course, as a 37-yard field goal
attempt by Jason Wells just curved wide left with 12 seconds left
in regulation, guaranteeing an overtime instead of the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It happened with kids like tailback Marcel Shipp banging away
for 170 yards and two touchdowns, including the decisive 1-yard
dive in OT; it happened with wide receiver Adrian Zullo sacrificing
his 5-foot-7-inch, 151-pound body all afternoon while making a
game-high 10 receptions for 121 yards and one touchdown; it
happened with quarterback Todd Bankhead picking apart the Furman
defense for a pair of touchdowns and 287 yards; and it happened
with the defense, which seemed to stretch nearly to the breaking
point all afternoon, making four plays when it needed to in OT.
</P>
<P>
   There was more on this magical afternoon: UMass athletic
director Bob Marcum, standing on the sideline, being as neutral as
he could throughout the game, finally heading behind the goal posts
as Wells set up for the late field goal attempt and trying to will
the ball wide; the handful of UMass fans who made the trip, wishing
to believe another miracle could happen on this afternoon and this
season; and a team that believed in itself more than anyone else
did.
</P>
<P>
   UMass entered these playoffs by a different route than a year
ago, when no one gave it the slightest chance to win one playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Minutemen fooled people then, and again Saturday, as the
10th seed in the 16-team field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We own the South,'' shouted some players as they walked off
the field amid the stunned silence of the crowd of 7,215, which
could hardly believe what it had just seen.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it. Next up is Georgia Southern, anxious to prove that
its loss to UMass in the national title game last season was some
early Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern has never lost a playoff game at home. So once
again UMass is faced with the impossible. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep the faith,'' said Whipple to his grinning, jubilant team.
``Keep the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 2127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
