</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-SMERLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN WILL HIT HOME WITH SMERLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ The prodigal son comes home Sunday, although it took a
funeral to get him here.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's Patriots-Bills game, Fred Smerlas _ along with
former teammate Reggie McKenzie _ will receive the Ralph G. Wilson
Distinguished Service Award, an honor bestowed on former Bills by
the owner himself. Considering that Smerlas fought and bled for the
Bills for 11 years and made as many Pro Bowls as O.J. Simpson
(five), that might not seem surprising, until you learn that when
the end came, it was like the bitter breakup of a long marriage.
Love was still there, but too much hurt and pain had piled on for
the end to be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Always a fighter, the Waltham native ripped the organization and
head coach Marv Levy every chance he got, because in his mind, they
had forced him out of the town he'd been born to play in. Smerlas
could never forgive the Bills for that, and so a cult hero went off
to end his career in San Francisco and back home in New England
more than $1 million richer but more aware than most that money
cannot buy happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be in San Francisco,'' Smerlas said of the
year he spent in purgatory by the Bay after Levy told him the Bills
didn't want him anymore. ``I wanted to be in Buffalo. How many
people would say that? But that's me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found a home there. I loved the town and the people, and
they loved me. I played a hard-nosed position there for 11 years.
That was my turf. I defended that turf all my life. I fought my ass
off for it, and then they were ready to just take it away from me
without a fight. What hurt was that I didn't get a shot to fight
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I didn't get my respect in high school or in college
and now in Buffalo, even after making the Pro Bowl five times and
being an alternate four more times. There's always been a rage
inside me. On the inside, I'm still the fat kid protected by a
300-pound body, so when Marv didn't give me a shot to fight for my
job, that's what hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   What Smerlas never understood was that it was hard on Levy, too.
A kind man and one of the game's great coaches, Levy determined
that a once-great player was entering his final days, but when he
began splitting playing time between Smerlas and undersized Jeff
Wright, he felt Smerlas did not take well to it.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of trying to split the position, Levy feared the
worst because Smerlas was both a team leader and a folk hero in
Buffalo. Rather than risk dividing his team over the issue of
Smerlas's slow removal, he did it in one painful swoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the hardest things I ever had to do,'' said
Levy from his home in Chicago. ``He was deeply hurt, and I
understood that. It was hurtful for us both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred was a fan favorite. He was a leader on our team. He'd
contributed a lot for many years. But when I told him we were going
to play Jeff Wright more, Fred was uncomfortable with that. I just
didn't feel he could sit behind another guy. Even mentioning it
seemed to wound him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was truly hurt by it for a long time. I knew it and that
hurt me, because I had a great regard for Fred. Fred Smerlas was
among the best to ever play his position. He was so quick they'd
call him offside sometimes when he wasn't. He had very quick hands
and he was so strong. He is among the five or six best to ever play
nose tackle and he'd always cultivated the image that he was the
toughest guy in town, which he probably was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a little showmanship, a little of that WWF persona to
him, and I think that made the way it ended harder on him. There is
only one other cut I ever made that was as difficult. I was in
Kansas City and every year we'd bring in a young kicker to compete
with Jan Stenerud and then we'd cut the guy at the end of training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one year we brought in a kid and he blew us away. He was
making 50-yard kicks and kicking off through the end zone, and
after the third preseason game I told Jan this was going to be
competitive. When I let him go, Jan was extremely bitter and hurt.
He went on and played in Minnesota and Green Bay and did fine, and
the kicker we kept was Nick Lowery and he did well. He made two
kicks of 51 and 56 yards the first game, which saved my bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years later, I'd see Jan places and he'd spin on his heels and
just walk away, but about 10 years later I was at the league
meetings and I felt this guy standing over me. It was Jan. He said,
`How are you, Marv?' and that was the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of Smerlas's feud with the Bills came under sadder
circumstances. Several years ago, ex-Bill Doug Prader was killed
when he slipped in the shower and struck his head. Smerlas returned
to Buffalo for the funeral. Levy also came back, and when he saw
Smerlas, the old memories _ good more than bad _ rushed back and
the old coach approached his old, angry player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the reconciliation began,'' said Vic Carucci, a
longtime Buffalo writer and the author of Smerlas's biography.
</P>
<P>
   That book came out in 1990, the same year Smerlas was released,
a year that coincided with the first of the Bills' four Super Bowl
teams. Carucci remembered the bitterness his subject felt in those
days and for many years thereafter, bitterness that didn't begin to
fade until Levy approached him at that funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levy saw the aging of a great player and tried to use Freddie
and Jeff both, but Fred didn't like it,'' Carucci recalled. ``San
Francisco came along and offered Fred the biggest money of his
career, and he took it because he knew if he stayed, he stayed
without any assurances anymore that he'd be on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred was just a beloved guy in this town and people took it
hard. It was not a happy time. When he came back that next season
to do a book signing people showed up with baked goods! There were
people literally with tears in their eyes, asking him to sign the
book. Nobody wanted it to end on the terms it did, but that's how
it went and Fred was bitter about it for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Smerlas once more will stand on the field he never wanted to
leave, with his wife and children, watching highlights of him in
action on the scoreboard. For just an instant those kids will have
an idea what it meant to be Fred Smerlas in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   They'll know something else, too. They'll know he's home and
glad to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back on it now and I realize Marv had his idea of how
to do it and he was 95 percent right and 5 percent wrong and it
ended up hurting both of us, but that was his assessment,'' Smerlas
said. ``It was hard for him, too. I was a volatile guy, and he was
afraid it could be an explosive situation. I was a leader and a guy
who liked to get crazy and maybe he felt the team couldn't face it
if I was there and not playing. I can see that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be great to be back. I was born in Waltham and created
in my cellar where I gained 100 pounds in three years lifting
weights without steroids, but I was formed in Buffalo. If I'd gone
anywhere else I might not have been the player I was. I was a
blue-collar guy playing in a blue-collar town, and the people there
saw that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-charging Rams
</P>
<P>
   How's this for a turnaround? Armey's Army, the St. Louis Rams
team that ex-Patriot personnel man Charley Armey helped rebuild the
last two years, could clinch the NFC West with a victory and a
Carolina loss. The Rams haven't won an NFC West title since 1985,
but if they lay claim to it Sunday, they would tie the 1985 Bears
and '97 49ers for earliest clinching of a division title since the
16-game schedule was instituted in 1978 . . . Speaking of the
Panthers, how's this for drafting consistency? Three of the four
No. 1 picks in franchise history have been arrested. Latest was
wide receiver Rae Carruth, who was charged Friday with attempted
murder of his pregnant girlfriend following a drive-by shooting. He
joins 1995 No. 1 pick Kerry Collins and 1998 selection Jason Peter
on the police blotter, both of whom were charged with drunken
driving. Collins was convicted; Peter's charges were dismissed last
summer but are being appealed by local prosecutors . . . Eagles
coach Andy Reid was so disgusted at his team's performance in last
Sunday's 44-17 loss to Indianapolis that when the team came to
Veterans Stadium Monday to watch the game film, he told them to go
home and watch soap operas instead . . . Steelers quarterback
Kordell Stewart is 4-2 on the road with an 87.3 efficiency rating;
at home, the Steelers are 1-3 and he has a 41.3 rating. This week
marks a year since the Steelers beat a team with a winning record .
. . Some wounds heal badly. As Dolphins line coach Paul Boudreau
was walking off the field after last Sunday's 27-17 victory over
his old employers, the Patriots, he grabbed a reporter and said,
``In your next report card, give the guy an F that said I couldn't
coach run blocking.'' Boudreau's comment was a slap at Pete
Carroll, who sacrificed Boudreau to help save his head coaching job
a year ago. It was the second straight year an assistant was axed
when things went bad, with offensive coordinator Larry Kennan being
the other sacrificial lamb. After the game, Boudreau said of
Carroll, ``I don't think we're going to exchange Christmas cards
this year. I wouldn't be human if I told you otherwise.'' . . .
Carroll had an interesting answer when asked why this group of
Patriots seems to start fast every year before slacking off and
putting themselves in must-win situations. ``I don't know,'' said
Carroll. ``We've been 6-4 the last three years. The fact remains
here we are again. It may just be the nature of the key guys on our
team.'' (It is a condition that preceded Carroll, in that pretty
much this same group would not have made the playoffs in 1996 had
it lost the final regular-season game to the Giants.) . . .
Wednesday's altercation between Lawyer Milloy and Vincent Brisby
during a charity party hosted by Willie McGinest may have been a
minor incident, but team owner Bob Kraft was not happy about it,
especially the fact that the night before Thanksgiving half of his
players were out partying and most of them didn't have sense enough
to hire a limousine. How many Rod Rutledge situations do they need
before they grow up in Foxborough? . . . Here's a good reason why
rookie Patriot quarterback Michael Bishop should be jumping at the
chance to get experience in NFL Europe rather than debating it:
European grads Kurt Warner, Jon Kitna, and Brad Johnson are a
combined 22-8 as NFL starters this season . . . In case you think
the recent rise of the Jets is a fluke, here's how they've done it:
In their last seven games, they have allowed 14.3 points a game
while going plus-9 in takeaway-giveaway margin. That's a formula
for winning . . . In the fourth quarter of a 17-7 victory over the
Bills last week, young Jets quarterback Ray Lucas was confronted by
Pro Bowl receiver Keyshawn Johnson after Lucas bounced a pass in
front of Johnson on a slant pattern. According to witnesses,
Johnson was cursing and told Lucas, ``What the hell are you doing?
Don't do that again!'' Lucas, making only his third professional
start, cursed right back and said, ``Here's the play. Run it!''
What followed? Lucas rolled to his right and completed a 16-yard
touchdown pass _ to Wayne Chrebet . . . Tampa head coach Tony Dungy
apparently was not impressed with the league outlawing the
throat-slashing gesture. ``I saw my son use it once,'' Dungy said.
``I think it was in a Pokemon game.'' Asked if he opposed it, Dungy
cracked, ``I do now that the league wants it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a run for it?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the Arizona Cardinals' recent two-game
winning streak. It has made them possible contenders in the awful
NFC East, but it's unlikely that they can win often enough down the
stretch to be where the preseason predictors said they'd be. Still,
there's a lesson for the Patriots in the Cardinals' recent
renaissance. Arizona has won two straight by averaging 130.5 yards
rushing. In their previous two games (one of which was a loss to
New England), the Cardinals totaled 131 yards . . . Speaking of
Arizona, don't be surprised to see quarterback Jake Plummer play
some Sunday despite the pain that persists in his thumb. Dave Brown
will start against the Giants but if he wavers, Plummer believes
he's ready to help . . . Here's what happens when people mistakenly
write off great players at the first sign of weakness. Three years
ago, much of the football world was convinced Emmitt Smith was
finished and Curtis Martin would never recover from a torn groin
and stomach muscle. Martin is third in the NFL in rushing and Smith
needs 22 more yards to become only the second back in NFL history
to rush for 1,000 yards nine consecutive seasons. Barry Sanders,
who retired this summer, did it 10 straight seasons . . . In case
you're keeping score, there have been only 34 reversals of
officials' calls through the instant replay system. Perhaps more
important to some, the average length of time it has taken for a
call to be made is 2 minutes 54 seconds. Whatever happened to that
90-second promise? . . . Old friend Kevin Turner may have played
his last NFL game. Turner has been troubled all season with neck
stingers that have caused momentary paralysis in his hand and arm,
and when he suffered another such injury last Sunday against the
Colts, the Eagles put him on injured reserve. Turner did not
dispute it this time, after earlier in the year asking to remain
active. Always a warrior, the ex-Patriot fullback played hard for a
bad team this season despite having his $1.2 million salary sliced
to $800,000. It may be the last paycheck he draws in the NFL,
although Turner would like one more shot with a winning
organization. The Patriots could do worse than giving him a shot if
he's healthy next summer . . . There are a lot of reasons a
quarterback can be benched, but Browns coach Chris Palmer may have
come up with a new one. He informed rookie Tim Couch that if he
continues to run downfield and refuses to slide for his own
protection, he will be benched . . . Matthew Hatchette has unseated
veteran Jake Reed as the Vikings' third receiver because Reed has
had a string of drops . . . The Arena League's growth will continue
now that it has signed a TV deal with TNN, ESPN, ESPN2, and ABC
beginning next season. The indoor game got a boost from the play of
Warner, whose career began in the league. There will be a Game of
the Week on TNN and playoff games on all four networks. In total,
25 games will be shown nationally . . . When Detroit defensive back
Mark Carrier was suspended for a game and fined $50,000 for
slamming his helmet into Green Bay's Antonio Freeman, it should not
have come as a surprise. Carrier has been disciplined six times
since 1992 for helmet mania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
