<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-SEASONEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S DEFINING MOMENT: THE ENTIRE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ Boston College's football team had just ended
its regular season with an 8-3 record (4-3 Big East) after Friday's
38-14 loss to second-ranked Virginia Tech before a Lane
Stadium/Worsham Field crowd of 53,150. In his postgame remarks,
third-year coach Tom O'Brien was asked to describe the defining
moments of BC's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien didn't know where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   He paused to collect his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Then he started at the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overtime win at Baylor started it all off, because if you
don't win that one, you don't know where you go,'' O'Brien said,
referring to a 30-29 victory in the Sept. 4 opener at Alumni
Stadium. ``The last-minute win against Pitt (20-16) was obviously a
big boost to this football team. Then, going to Syracuse and
winning (24-23) and then Notre Dame (31-29). Our two rivals are
Syracuse and Notre Dame. If we're going to be successful, you have
to beat your rivals some time. You can't have a rivalry if you
can't beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this point, I don't think there's a bigger victory than the
one we had last week.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's eighth triumph of the season, in South Bend, Ind., which
virtually guaranteed the No. 22 Eagles a trip to the Insight.com
Bowl Dec. 31 in Tucson, Ariz., indeed ranked as its biggest. It
would have been surpassed only by a ninth win against the Hokies
(11-0, 7-0), who clinched the Big East title outright and expect to
play top-ranked Florida State in the Sugar Bowl for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   As cubes of sugar rained down from the stands Friday, raucous
Virginia Tech fans rushed the field. The Eagles, meanwhile, trudged
off in single file, oblivious to the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But BC could take solace in one fact: The season is not over yet
for its 12 departing seniors. There remains a bowl game to be
played against a yet-to-be determined opponent. If it is indeed the
Insight.com Bowl _ a virtual certainty after Miami's victory over
Syracuse Saturday sent the Hurricanes toward the Gator Bowl _ the
foe will come from the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. The Eagles are not likely to encounter a
team that approaches the level of Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it,'' said senior free safety Pedro Cirino. ``There's
not too many Michael Vicks around.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick, Virginia Tech's amazing redshirt freshman quarterback,
outgained BC in total offense, 366 yards to 319. He threw for 290
yards and three touchdowns (of 69, 59, and 30 yards), and rushed
for 76 yards (including a 5-yard TD). Despite facing a 24-0
halftime deficit, the Eagles distinguished themselves with a
spirited second-half effort highlighted by a gallant fourth-quarter
stand, Tim Hasselbeck's 97-yard TD pass to Dedrick Dewalt, and
William Green's impressive 45-yard TD run _ the longest of his
career _ with 46 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play hard for 60 minutes,'' O'Brien said.
``That's our signature right now. Our No. 1 (Green) took off there
at the end of the game. He may be the only guy we have on our team
who can run like some of the guys they have on their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't matter what the score is or what the clock
says, we're just going to play. That's what we've got to do in
order to be competitive, in order to have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the lesson freshmen like Green learned in their first
season at The Heights. It was a first year that differed vastly
from that of BC's seniors, who were devastated by a gambling
scandal that rocked the program in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great to have guys like Chris (Hovan) and Pedro and
all the other seniors just to show us the way,'' said Green, one of
six freshmen who saw playing time this season. ``They showed us how
to never give up and how to play hard. They showed us that this BC
team can do it, that we can play against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Brien cautioned that sustained success is not likely to
come overnight. To illustrate his point, he mentioned how it took
Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer 13 years to position his team for
a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here 10 years longer than I have (at BC) _ that's
what the difference is,'' O'Brien said. ``It's continuity, and
that's the bottom line. He keeps his assistants, they do a great
job. They're not always nationally ranked in recruiting, but they
find players and do a great job of coaching. But it's been 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Virginia (media) guys remember in his sixth year
here he was 2-8-1, and they were ready to hang him here. But the
administration stuck by him and from that point on they took off.
So you have to give a lot of people credit for his success, but
he's No. 1 at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Any successful program is built on a solid foundation, something
O'Brien and his staff were able to establish this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future has to be bright,'' said O'Brien. ``We've proven
that we can do it, and we have some good young freshmen, and we're
going to continue to recruit as well as we can so that we can
continue to get speed. That's still the bottom line. That was the
difference (against Virginia Tech). We were able to negate some of
the speed in a couple of teams this year, but we had problems with
the Miamis and the Virginia Techs of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
