<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SYLVESTE     11-27 1779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SYLVESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEAT TRICK BY PERSISTENT SYLVESTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dean Sylvester may or may not be in the National Hockey League
to stay, but based on his showing last Monday night, the former BC
High winger undoubtedly will be in Atlanta at least through the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In the true spirit of giving, the 26-year-old Sylvester gave the
Thrashers their first hat trick in a 6-3 win over the Vancouver
Canucks at Atlanta's Philips Arena. After four years of displaying
a promising scoring touch in the minor leagues _ with stops in
Mobile, Kansas City, and Rochester _ he abruptly notched his first
three NHL goals, knocking in a pair during the first period and
then completing the hat trick at 11:29 of the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting,'' said Sylvester, speaking from his
hotel room outside Atlanta, where he'll remain while the Thrashers
figure out how he fits into their plans. ``But, hey, you've got to
live life the way you're used to _ just keep your feet on the
ground and not get too carried away.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester is a model in perseverance. After graduating from high
school in '91, he was not recruited by Boston-area colleges, and he
was not selected in the NHL amateur draft at age 18. He was three
years into his scholarship at Kent State when the school folded the
hockey program. He quickly transferred to Michigan State, played
there his senior year, and picked up his undergraduate degree in
finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought of quitting,'' said Sylvester. ``Heck, I was
just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   Selected by San Jose in an early '90s supplemental draft,
Sylvester signed with Mobile in the East Coast Hockey League when
the Sharks opted not to sign him. He moved up to Kansas City
(International Hockey League) halfway through the 1995-96 season
and stayed there two more years (averaging 28 goals) before signing
with Buffalo as a free agent last October. He popped in an
impressive 35 goals with Rochester (American Hockey League) last
season, but got only a brief look with the Sabres before they
swapped him to the Thrashers just prior to the June expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got hands _ that's what made him attractive to us,'' said
Atlanta general manager Don Waddell. ``He's shown he can score
before, and if you can score 35 or 40 goals, I don't care what
level you're playing, I think that shows you at least know how to
score. We were looking at players, and asking what element they
could bring, be it toughness, skill, speed, whatever. Sylvester
brought hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't bring enough, it turned out, to convince Waddell
and head coach Curt Fraser in training camp that he was ready for
the NHL. They demoted him to the Orlando (IHL) affiliate and went
into their inaugural season with a lineup stocked with other
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sent him down, I told him, `Dean, I can't tell you
whether this is for a week or a year _ that's your decision,' ''
recalled Waddell. ``But we kept getting good reports, got into some
injury trouble, and here he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester, who grew up in Hanson, scored all three goals against
Canucks netminder Garth Snow of Wrentham (is there no end to the
NHL's Bay State connections?), and became the first NHLer in four
years to bundle his first three career goals for a hat trick. The
last: San Jose's Alexei Yegorov, who did it in the 1995-96 season
and hasn't scored an NHL goal since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to use my size as much as possible to help me score,''
said the 6-foot-2-inch, 200-pound right winger. ``I'm not what
you'd call a dangler. I usually work for my goals. The key is
positioning. I think if you put yourself in position to score, then
that's the half of it. I grew up watching Cam Neely, and he'd get
in the corners and bring it out on net. I like to try to play that
kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous Atlanta crowd, just getting reacquainted with
hockey rituals (remember, the Flames bolted in '80), even
celebrated the occasion by tossing a few hats on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, I can count them in my head . . . there were, oh,
I'd say about 10,'' said an amused Waddell. ``But there were a
couple of reasons for that. It wasn't a bang-bang goal. The puck
hit the goalie first and bounced in off Dean. By the time play
started, the PA announcer hadn't announced the goal yet, so not
everyone knew it was him and what it meant. Play was up and running
for about 30 seconds before it was announced. Our PA's not in full
stride just yet. We've got some bugs to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky to be alive
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Los Angeles said Montreal's Brian Savage could have
been killed last Saturday night when he fractured at least one
vertebra after getting clobbered by Ian Laperriere. Three days
later, Savage returned to Montreal in a body cast, and he has only
an outside chance of returning to the lineup this season. Remember,
earlier this year Dallas superstar Mike Modano had an ugly fall and
said he might have to consider retiring if players' blatant
disregard for each other isn't reined in. Laperriere is aggressive,
to the point of being chippy, but is by no means a headhunter.
Leaguewide, however, these incidents are occuring with frightening
frequency, and it does seem only a matter of time before someone is
left paralyzed or dead on the ice. The game has its inherent
dangers, but it would be in everyone's interest for the league and
the Players' Association to sit down immediately _ summer could be
too late _ and discuss ways to keep the game exciting but safer . .
. The Thrashers were quick to move ex-Bruin prospect Randy
Robitaille, in part, because they were having problems signing him.
``He's small, too,'' said Waddell, who flipped the 5-foot-11-inch
Robitaille to Nashville for veteran Denny Lambert. ``If you're
going to use him up the middle _ and that's his best position _ his
size is a factor. We also had Terry Yake, Mike Stapleton, and
Patrik Stefan projected ahead of him. So when it came to getting
someone with Lambert's grit for the lineup, we made the move.'' . .
. Correction from the big penalty box: A note here last week made
reference to former Kings owner Bruce McNall serving his sentence
in California, but he is in a federal prison in Safford, Ariz.
Sorry for that missed line change. The NHL's former chairman of the
Board of Governors still has three years to go on a 70-month
sentence, but good behavior can knock off about 11 months . . .
Again, congratulations to the Lawrence Eagle Tribune's Russ Conway,
a great one himself, who was ushered into Hockey's Hall of Fame
along with Wayne Gretzky last week. Conway's diligence led to Alan
Eagleson's decline, fall, and all-expenses-paid (would Eagle expect
less?) trip to the slammer for a variety of crimes. It took years
for Conway to get the job done, a feat in itself, but all the more
impressive when working for a 365-day-a-year product . . . The
Oilers have won five Stanley Cups, four in the nine seasons Gretzky
was there. In the 20 years since the Oilers entered the league in
'79, the Original Six clubs of Boston, New York, Montreal, Toronto,
Chicago, and Detroit have amassed five Cups. That's not something
you'll find under Gretzky's name, but it could be his most
impressive stat.
</P>
<P>
   Know when to fold 'em
</P>
<P>
   That $3 million-plus per year that Byron Dafoe finally signed
for must be looking pretty good to Nikolai Khabibulin right about
now. The Coyotes picked up Sean Burke as their No. 1 netminder last
Friday _ dishing Mikhail Shtalenkov to the Panthers _ and Phoenix
GM Bobby Smith promptly said he won't negotiate with Khabibulin
until after this season . . . Keep Dec. 13 in mind. It's Stanley
Cup ring delivery day in Dallas. The Stars endured a lethargic
first quarter (projecting to just under 80 points) and rings alone
won't pull them out of their funk. But the day should provide an
emotional boost, and that could help a few of the veterans shake
their Cup hangover. More important to the big picture in Big D: the
return of Jere Lehtinen, out since mid-October with a broken ankle.
Among the best two-way players in the game, Lehtinen makes the
Stars better on both ends of the rink . . . The Bruins will see an
improved Capitals squad in D.C. Thursday night. Virtually comatose
the first six weeks of the season, the Capitals at least have found
a pulse, thanks in large part to improved penalty killing: They
burned off 53 consecutive shorthanded situations prior to allowing
a power-play goal in Buffalo Wednesday . . . Sunday night at the
Vault, the Bruins will face their former coach, Butch Goring, for
the first time since he was sent packing at the start of the
1986-87 season. Working on Long Island with a
not-even-quite-Wal-Mart lineup, Goring has little hope of
pitchforking his bunch onto the playoff pile. Among the Islanders'
biggest disappointments: the ineffectiveness of right winger Mark
Lawrence, who showed great promise (30 points/60 games) last season
. . . Why does every team in baseball have a hitting coach, but
nowhere in hockey will you find someone on the payroll as a scoring
coach? It is, without question, the most overlooked, and yet most
significant, part of the game. Lasting image: John Bucyk in his
playing days, wrapping up each practice with a bucket of pucks,
dotting forehanders and backhanders to the top shelf. Goalies are
better today, but equally significant in the decline of scoring is
the fact that forwards need to spend more time working on: 1.
positioning; 2. release; 3. touch . . . During his Hall of Fame
news conference Monday, Gretzky delicately tiptoed around the Maple
Leafs' last-minute decision not to sign him as a free agent in '96.
The deal was nixed by Leaf ownership looking to trim salary.
Gretzky: ``Every person who grows up in Southern Ontario _ it's
such a hotbed for the Maple Leafs _ every youngster here grows up
dreaming about playing for the Maple Leafs. To be in Maple Leaf
Gardens, that's really something special. I loved when I played
there. I wish I could have been _ some way, somehow _ a Maple Leaf.
But it just wasn't in the cards.'' . . . How about those Lightning,
dropping the mighty Flyers, 4-1, last week? And they did it landing
zero shots in the second period. They also did it with only eight
guys in the lineup from the final game last season. New GM Rick
Dudley (formerly of the Vipers' and Senators' front offices) again
is pulling off an impressive turnaround . . . Hockey has gotten to
you if you look at the upcoming calendar switch to 2000 and wonder
whether they're going to play the next period running time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
