<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2773 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-27 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD HEADED QBS PAY BIG PRICE TO KEEP PLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   That's all; just why?
</P>
<P>
   If you had accomplished all Steve Young has accomplished, and
doctor after doctor told you that you were risking your health
because you've had too many concussions, you'd like to think you'd
have sense enough to quit. Correct?
</P>
<P>
   And if you were Troy Aikman, winner of three Super Bowls, and
each year you challenge the odds in the face of concussion after
concussion, wouldn't you decide it was better to quit than risk
being spoon-fed your dinner by a nurse _ all this before you're
even close to age 40?
</P>
<P>
   To you and me, there is no issue. Every rational instinct tells
us that these two great quarterbacks are foolish beyond measure for
stepping on a football field again (which Aikman did on
Thanksgiving).
</P>
<P>
   But we are not, never have been, and never will be skilled
professional football players. Only someone who has walked in their
shoes can begin to understand why these two intelligent men insist
on playing.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grogan is such a man. He played quarterback with a
kamikaze style for 16 seasons. He was fearless, daring, and
astonishingly competitive. He loved what he did. And he understands
what we can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say about Steve Young, `The guy's won a Super Bowl.
He's the top-rated quarterback of all-time. He's going to the Hall
of Fame. So why is he running around looking for just one doctor
who will tell him it's OK to keep playing?' '' muses Grogan. ``I
think I understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you love doing something as much as he does, the idea of
quitting is very hard to accept. You want to milk it as long as you
can. He feels he can still play, and he can't fathom the idea of
some game being the absolute last one, knowing that you will never
do this again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when you realize, `That's it. It's over.'
In his case he knows he will never win another Super Bowl, at least
not with that team, but that has nothing to do with it. He just
truly loves to play football. And I'm sure it's the same thing with
Aikman.''
</P>
<P>
   Just being in that arena is an irresistible high. You are doing
something that sets you apart from the mainstream, and it gives you
a rush you doubt will ever be replicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I miss it?'' Grogan asks. ``In all honesty, I do. If
someone offered me a chance to play tomorrow, I'd do it. And I'm
46.''
</P>
<P>
   Young turned 38 five weeks ago. He has been beaten up the last
couple of seasons, primarily because the 49ers' offensive line has
deteriorated. He has suffered a number of concussions, and he has
been advised by a number of doctors that he should not play again
if he wishes to live a normal life away from the gridiron.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan was no stranger to concussions, but his major medical
crisis was a ruptured disk in his neck. Oh, he had the normal
assortment of problematic knees, ankles, and elbows, but the
scariest injury was this neck business, which necessitated surgery,
and from which he recovered in time to play a little more football.
At the time, there were many people advising him to quit, but he
had no intention of doing so unless the proverbial medical gun was
placed at his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I was doing anything stupid,'' he says. ``If
the doctors had ever said to me that I'd be risking serious
permanent injury if I kept playing, I think I would have quit. But
no doctor ever told me that. They said surgery would enable me to
play, and it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Grogan's last year was 1990. If he had to do it all over again,
he would have paid a little more attention to his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was knocked out several times,'' he says. ``In those days,
nobody made a big deal out of it. You hear about guys getting
`dinged,' or something like that, and that happened frequently. I
couldn't count the number of times I was hit that way. But there
were at least two or three times I was knocked out cold, and that
concerns me now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I was out for maybe 20 minutes. But I had to go back in
because the guy who relieved me _ I think it was Matt Cavanaugh _
was knocked out of the game and I had to go back in and finish. I
think knowing what we know today I'd have done it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Football players are inherently tough. We all know that. But
quarterbacks bring an extra element. Whatever Bruce Armstrong's
level of satisfaction, for example, it simply can't be the same as
Drew Bledsoe's. Armstrong has to derive satisfaction from a hidden
job well done. A quarterback controls the agenda. Not one fan in
100,000 can name anyone on the Denver Broncos' offensive line that
played against the Cleveland Browns in the AFC Championship game
Jan. 11, 1987. But 99,999 out of 100,000 fans know that John Elway
took his team 98 yards for the game-tying touchdown on what has
been immortalized as The Drive. A Steve Young or a Troy Aikman has
a very hard time stepping away from that kind of spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that the 31-year-old Aikman won't entertain the
thought of retiring. But Young is a different matter. He at least
acknowledges the possibility that he has played his last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he wants now,'' reasons Grogan, ``is to go out on his own
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   What scares Grogan is that the damage already may have been
done. When Young finally does retire, it will be because of
multiple concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am following this story with great interest,'' Grogan says.
``I want to learn about concussions myself. I want to learn what I
have to look forward to as I get older.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grogan would play again. These guys constitute a different
species.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
