<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BUFFALO-ANTOWAINS     11-27 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUFFALO-ANTOWAINSMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORKING SMITH AN ACCOUNTABLE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Antowain Smith's job here is pushing the pile,
tracking behind his fullback _ usually former Patriot Sam Gash _
and power-slamming into a wall of flesh, muscle, and all the
assorted plastic-and-fabric protection that makes up the NFL's
big-man Sunday haberdashery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing too tricky about it,'' says Jonathan Linton,
Smith's fellow Bills running back, explaining what it's like to
work in a two-back formation. ``You just keep your head down,
follow your fullback, and run to where you see less feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, the 27-year-old Smith was pushing a vastly
different pile, reporting to work five days a week on the 3-11
shift at Gureny Manufacturing in Prattville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a job to die for, but one to dye for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clothes factory,'' Smith said the other day,
recalling the three years following high school, his voluntary
respite from football, that he spent laboring at $5.50 an hour.
``My job was to put all these clothes in a big ol' tub _ clothes
and clothes and more clothes _ and dye 'em up. That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by turf toe for almost two weeks, Smith isn't certain
how effective he'll be Sunday when the Patriots visit for a
critical (read: make or break) AFC East matchup for both squads.
This is Smith's second season as the Bills' No. 1 running threat,
which also makes it the second season that all of Western New York
has been crossing off each and every one of his rushes, wondering
how much longer it will be before he blossoms as the next Thurman
Thomas. Not that Thomas has gone anywhere, but he is 33 now, hasn't
made a single rush all season, and whenever he comes back, he will
fill the senior statesman's situational-runner's role.
</P>
<P>
   While patience may be short among Bills fans _ and perhaps
quietly likewise in the Bills' front office _ Smith is known for
not falling prey to anyone's clock of expectations. He spent those
three years out of football taking care of his ailing grandmother,
working the second shift at Gureny so he could use two or three
mornings a week to shuttle his beloved Clara Smith back and forth
for dialysis treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In order to stay close to home, Smith also passed up a
scholarship at Auburn, even after signing the papers to go there,
just to help out at his grandparents' home. He was some 36 months
away from the gridiron in '94 when he returned to school at East
Mississippi College, and even then he wasn't entertaining any idea
of playing in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth is,'' he said, ``I never took football seriously at all.
And when it came time to take care of my grandmother, that didn't
really feel like a sacrifice. I mean, hey, I was 18 years old, and
of course I wanted to be doing things with my friends. But at the
same time, I had to be there for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Lykes was 16 when she gave birth to Antowain and the
feeling that she was too young to take care of him. From infancy,
he was raised by Clara and John Smith in Millbrook, Ala., just
outside Montgomery. Both his grandparents now deceased, Smith has
marked a T-shirt with their initials, J.S. and D.S., and wears it
under his No. 23 game jersey every time he takes the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me this feeling, that they're out there with me _
somehow I feel closer,'' said Smith, who was compelled to return to
school in order to fulfill one of his grandmother's dying wishes.
``I do it because it's a way of showing I think about them every
day. My grandparents did everything they could for me, and when it
was my turn I just figured, `Hey, I'm healthy, I can get a job and
help out here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In June '93, Clara Smith died at age 70. The following spring,
with help from his high school coach, Antowain arranged a tryout at
East Mississippi Junior College in Scooba, Miss., about a
three-hour drive from Millbrook. EM's coach, Tom Goode, took Smith
out to a soaked, muddy practice field, stopwatch in hand, and
clocked the aspiring applicant at an eye-popping 4.5 in the 40-yard
dash.
</P>
<P>
   Audition complete. Smith's life was starting to play out like a
scene from ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Lord, what a deal,' '' Goode recalled for the Buffalo
News a few years later. ``I told him, `The practice is over. You
can come here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simple is as simple does.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't seem quite so simple a couple of months later when
Smith, eager to get back on the field after his three-year hiatus,
found his first day of practice overwhelming. Scooba, he quickly
discovered, didn't exactly feel like the center of the universe,
even to a kid from the little town of Millbrook. Worse, however,
was the head-to-toe pain he felt after Goode's grueling workouts.
Smith wanted to fulfill his grandma's wish, but there were limits
to his loyalty. Exhausted that first day, he made up his mind to
quit and called back to Millbrook for a lift home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit, I'm telling you, I just quit,'' Smith recalled last
week, now able to chuckle at the memory. ``I actually told the
coach, `Thanks for the opportunity and everything, but I can't do
this.' Three years with no football, and I hadn't run. I just
thought, `Man, I'm in no shape for this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Smith stay in Scooba?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he said, ``no one would come and get me.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, each day got better, and then better, and Smith went
on to become a JUCO All-American in his one year at East
Mississippi, where he gained more than 1,100 yards. The exposure
led to two years at the University of Houston, where, under the
tutelage of ex-NFL assistant coach Kim Helton, he went on to roll
up 1,239 yards and 14 TDs, helping the Cougars reach the Liberty
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Helton wooed Smith to Houston, in part by promising him that he
would use his NFL connections _ established while he was coaching
with the Buccaneers, Oilers, and Raiders _ to help him find footbal
opportunities after college. By then, Smith would be 25 years old,
of course, and not the prototypical NFL draft pick. Helton's idea
was enticing, but Smith also wasn't counting on anything other than
adding to his education and maintaining that promise to Clara
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I just never took football seriously,'' said Smith, who
was so attracted to basketball as a youngster that he didn't think
about playing football until his senior year of high school _ and
ultimately only then to win a bet with schoolmates. ``My coach at
Houston was telling me, `Son, you've got a great opportunity here,'
but, for whatever reason, I just didn't take it all that seriously.
But then I started to see other guys start to make it, guys I'd
played against, and I began to think, `Hey, I can do that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same point, I was never thinking I could be here in
the NFL. Then eventually, I started to see NFL scouts coming to our
practices, and the coach was saying they were there to see me, and
that's when I said to myself, `Damn, OK, I do have a shot here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The chance began to crystallize soon after Smith's second year
at Houston when he put up strong numbers at the NFL combine. The
Bills, only weeks from seeing Thomas complete his last of eight
consecutive 1,000-yard-plus rushing seasons, used their No. 23 pick
overall with the hope that Smith could be somewhat of a first-round
sleeper. He was, after all, three or four years past the point
where GMs typically like to harvest top talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Bills GM John Butler said at the time, ``it's not like
he's a beat-up 25. He hasn't been hit a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith now is a season and a half into full-time ball-lugging
duty. He piled up a fairly impressive 1,124 yards and eight TDs
last season, but the Bills nonetheless felt compelled over the
summer to try to woo the problematic Lawrence Phillips to their
backfield. This past week, with Phillips cut free by the 49ers,
Bills coach Wade Phillips (no relation) said the Bills had no
interest in picking up the troubled but gifted runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is set right now,'' said the coach. ``Our team is
certainly set. We aren't looking for anybody right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who suffered the turf toe injury late in Buffalo's win
over Miami two weeks ago when he collected a season-high 126 yards,
was limited to only two carries and 6 yards in last Sunday's loss
to the Jets. He has 543 yards this season, with a respectable
average of 3.7 per carry, and five TDs. Phillips figures he'll have
Smith available Sunday, but is not sure if the injured toe will
limit his effectiveness. Linton would get the majority of the
carries in Smith's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be 100 percent,'' said Smith. ``I know it's
going to hurt, but I'm going to have to block that pain out of my
mind and keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills are off next week, the bye in their schedule,
presenting an opportunity for Smith to rest and come back Dec. 12
with the chance that rest will aid his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``But another week and we might not be around,'' said Smith,
knowing the importance of Sunday's matchup. ``I'm not planning to
sit out.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, not so long ago, Smith had every Sunday to himself.
All his weekends were carefree in those years immediately after
high school. He could hang with his friends, play some pickup
basketball, and help out around the house before getting back to
the factory. All that changed dramatically when he turned pro, his
days of take-home pay of less than $200 traded in for a five-year
contract worth an average $1 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of that makes me appreciate this all the more,''
said Smith, reflecting on the trail that led him here. ``I think it
makes me that much more humble, I guess you'd say. I think it shows
you can do anything you want in life, if you're willing to work at
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started late. I was the oldest guy in the draft at 25, and
at 25 you have to come in and show you can do it. I feel I have to
make my point in a short time, because, like everyone knows, the
life of a running back isn't that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that sense, I'm already behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
