<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-OKLA.-ST.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA ROUTS RIVAL, IMPROVES BOWL STANDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Oklahoma enhanced its bowl standing while it
convincingly exacted some revenge on an old rival yesterday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With representatives of the Alamo and Independence bowls looking
on with a raucous Memorial Stadium crowd of 75,374, the Sooners
posted a 44-7 Big 12 Conference victory against] Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   By winning its seventh game, Oklahoma emerged from a pack of Big
12 teams with six victories and all in bowl contention. If the
Sooners had lost, they would have been at 6-5 with Texas Tech,
Oklahoma State and Colorado and with not enough bowl invitations to
go around.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sooners rendered that point moot with its fifth home
victory of the season and joined Texas A&AMP;M as the Big 12's other
7-4 team. Now, Oklahoma simply awaits an invitation, most likely
from the San Antonio-based Alamo or the Shreveport, La.-based
Independence, or from the Insight.com Bowl in Tucson, Ariz. _ three
of the six bowls that have tie-ins with the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pretend to know a lot how bowls make their selections,
but I told the players we didn't want to leave it to chance,'' said
first-year Sooners coach Bob Stoops. ``With seven wins, we'll get
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (5-6) never got untracked offensively against the
Sooners' defense, led by defensive backs Roy Williams and Rodney
Rideau, who had 14 tackles each. The Cowboys also were short-handed
on defense after coach Bob Simmons suspended four starters earlier
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State quarterback Tony Lindsay came in with consecutive
victories against the Sooners, but his counterpart, Oklahoma
quarterback Josh Heupel, took the upper hand this time. Heupel, who
later in the afternoon was selected the Big 12 coaches' newcomer of
the year, threw two touchdown passes, passed for 287 yards and ran
for a TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like going in for us to win we had to do some things
offensively, put points on the board, sustain drives and avoid
turnovers,'' Simmons said. ``In this ballgame, we were unable to do
any of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Heupel directed the Sooners on scoring drives of 34, 55 and 75
yards. His 3-yard TD pass to Brandon Daniels on Oklahoma's third
possession was offset by a 23-yard interception return by Oklahoma
State linebacker Tarrell Knauls in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma fullback Seth Littrell put the Sooners ahead for good
on a 4-yard scoring run. Tim Duncan's extra point gave Oklahoma a
14-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sooners' first possession of the second half, Heupel
victimized the Cowboys' new faces in the secondary _ three starters
were among those suspended _ with a 73-yard scoring strike to
freshman Curtis Fagan.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, Duncan added a field goal and Heupel
guided the Sooners on a 10-play, 43-yard drive, scoring on a 7-yard
bootleg run. Cornerback Mike Woods returned an interception 43
yards and backup punt returner J.T. Thatcher brought back a punt 81
yards for final TDs that got the home crowd roaring.
</P>
<P>
   For Littrell, a junior who had not beaten the Cowboys, it was
sweet revenge. Littrell said he heard talk this week that some
Oklahoma State players had called Memorial Stadium their second
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the way it's going to be then, hey, welcome home,''
Littrell said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
