<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     11-27 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ARE OFF; LET CRITICISM TAKE A DAY OFF, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's best the Cowboys are idle today. Perfect timing, you might
say, for a necessary mental and physical freshening, plus a
refresher course on the finer points of football.
</P>
<P>
   This is needed on a Sunday without a game. Except I'm not
talking here about the players or coaches.
</P>
<P>
   It's us. Local fans and media, plus that weird assortment of
talk-show tongues. December is coming. It's stretch-run month in
the NFL. We've got to get our act together. We've got to stop
sounding and writing like football fools. I'm guilty. You're
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the big-time national TV guys have called us a
``knowledgeable football crowd.'' Knowledgeable? Since when?
</P>
<P>
   In this strange season of ups and downs for the Cowboys, the
public emotional swings change week to week. But the whipping boy
doesn't. When something goes wrong _ meaning a loss _ it's always
Chan Gailey's fault. This comes with his territory. It's OK to
pound on Gailey, because we always pound on the offensive
coordinator around here. Only the head coach catches more grief.
Gailey is both, so he gets both barrels.
</P>
<P>
   But with the displeasure, do we really know what we're talking
about? What follows is a list of examples. See if you recognize any
of these constant screams.
</P>
<P>
   HALFTIME ADJUSTMENTS: This is the new buzz phrase around North
Texas. Lose a lead in the second half, which the Cowboys have
certainly done, and then lose the game, which they've done five
times, and the howls come rolling in about a lack of ``halftime
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's true, but when did any of us exactly become experts
on halftime adjustments? Did you immediately recognize the change
in the second half on Thursday when defensive coordinator Dave
Campo went to the ``zone blitz'' instead of the ``man blitz''
against the Dolphins? Did you?
</P>
<P>
   Fan-wise, 99.9 percent wouldn't know a halftime adjustment from
a leftover turkey sandwich. Media-wise, it would be 100 percent
except for Channel 11's Babe Laufenberg.
</P>
<P>
   TOO CONSERVATIVE: This ties in with Gailey's play-calling, which
frankly, is right out of the Jimmy Johnson book on winning
back-to-back Super Bowls in this decade. It's pretty simple. Make
the other team stop the run. And just keep running it, and running
it, and ...
</P>
<P>
   Did Emmitt Smith have a great game against the Dolphins? No,
despite 103 yards.He averaged only 3.3 yards per carry, the same as
the failed Miami running game. But because Gailey kept going to the
run, the play-action fake to Emmitt in the fourth quarter caused
cornerback Terrell Buckley to bite. Rocket Ismail blew past him,
and the 65-yard TD bomb from Troy Aikman blew open a tight game.
</P>
<P>
   If it will make you feel any better, Gailey would have made a
great offensive coordinator for Johnson in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   TOO BLAND: As in Gailey's personality. But on this subject, do
you remember a fellow by the name of Tom Landry? Or maybe you want
a clown like the last head coach.
</P>
<P>
   DUMP-OFF PASSES: What about those 5-yard throws when 10 yards
are needed? Has Gailey lost his marbles? Or could it be this is the
final desperation option on the play? Could it be that all else has
failed because the receivers couldn't get open on the primary
routes? Could it also be a ``hot read,'' meaning the blitz is in
the face of Aikman or Jason Garrett? Think about it before you
speak loudly in the press box or the stands or the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ALL THOSE SUPERSTARS AND ONLY A 6-5 RECORD: Name one current
superstar on the Cowboys. The injured Larry Allen? Probably. But
there are no others. Only the paychecks are superstar-ish.
</P>
<P>
   NINE-TOED IS ``BACK'': Did the two interceptions on Thursday
return Deion to elite status? Only in his mind. The first pick was
set up by safety George Teague tipping the pass. Teague made the
play. The second was when a Miami receiver fell down.
</P>
<P>
   Deion will be ``back'' when Campo discontinues giving him
constant safety protection, which certainly wasn't the case
Thursday. The former Nine-Toed used to be a one-man show on his
side of the field. It's the front seven making the defense work by
controlling the run without safety help. This allows the safeties
to tail the corners, including His Holiness.
</P>
<P>
   IN A LOSS, GIVE THE OTHER TEAM CREDIT: This is impossible around
here, but about three weeks after the fact it was interesting to
hear an admission that the Indy Colts are pretty darn good.
Actually, the Colts may be the best team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   LEGITIMATE CRITICISM: Ripping Gailey is actually easy. Just zero
in on the number of penalties. It doesn't matter if it's his fault
or not, the yellow flags are Gailey's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above are just something to mull over on a Sunday
without the Cowboys playing. But please mull hard. Our reputation
is at stake.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
