<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WAITING ON KOBE FOR ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Guessing when Kobe Bryant will return to the Los
Angeles Lakers' lineup has become impossible, with estimates being
pushed back weekly.
</P>
<P>
   What coach Phil Jackson does know is he won't truly have a
handle on his team's character until Bryant does come back.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, the Lakers will need another big body to help at power
forward and center no matter how much Bryant brings to the game in
other areas. And obviously, they will be improved with Bryant on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But how sufficient is the current roster? How will the starting
five function when Bryant rejoins Shaquille O'Neal and Glen Rice?
Will all the pieces fit together well enough to avoid any
significant roster moves before the February trading deadline?
</P>
<P>
   None of that will be clear until Bryant has played at least a
month, meaning those answers might not be apparent until January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to as a team assess what we're going to be like with
Kobe on the team without having him here,'' Jackson said. ``How
good can we be once he's back and increasing our team speed? Right
now we can't run, we're not a good team running or fast breaking.
Most of our best games, or the most consistent way we play, is to
slow the ballgame down a little bit, be precise with our offense.
Kobe is going to change that, but I don't know how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is defensively what does he give us, with a
guy that can hound the ball, hound the ballplayer a little bit and
get to a level where he can be a stopper? Or we can trap or do
something else differently on defense? And I don't know what Kobe's
going to bring to us at that level, because he plays with such
energy and is a good ball chaser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make kind of an assessment as to where this
team's going to go behind that kind of energy. As we look at
personnel on this club, we still have to be very flexible as
management to see what we can do to improve the team. ... We're
going to have to look at it after the New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   By January, Bryant will presumably have been playing for three
or four weeks. That's if the latest estimates hold. He's scheduled
to have his broken right hand re-examined Tuesday, and the current
expectation is he will return a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Breather: The Lakers don't play again until Tuesday at Seattle,
giving them their first three-day break between games this season.
Jackson took the opportunity to give the players the day off
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
