<SLUG> BC-FBC-UMASS-FURMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUTEMEN GET PLAYOFF WIN IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ ``Oh my God, we did it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, University of Massachusetts linebacker Kole Ayi
watched a Furman fourth-down pass fall incomplete, and then he
uttered those words. Surely they resonated in the mind of every
Minuteman player and coach as they dashed onto the field in a wild
celebration, elated that one of the most suspenseful and dramatic
games in school history had ended in victory.
</P>
<P>
   But UMass's season marches on.
</P>
<P>
   Ayi was right. UMass has done it again. After playing Furman to
a 23-23 regulation tie, the defending Division 1-AA national
champions scored on a Marcel Shipp 1-yard run, then stopped Furman
on four downs for a 30-23 overtime triumph in the first round of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   UMass, seeded 10th, improved to 9-3 and will meet second seed
Georgia Southern Saturday in Statesboro, Ga., in a rematch of last
year's 1-AA title game. Georgia Southern routed 15th-seeded
Northern Arizona, 72-29, Saturday. Furman finished 9-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous football game, maybe the best football
game we've been in in two years,'' said UMass coach Mark Whipple,
who took over the program in 1998 _ following its worst season this
century _ and led it to unprecedented heights.
</P>
<P>
   UMass has won five consecutive postseason games, including four
away from home. It has beaten four higher-seeded teams in that
span.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just tell in that overtime, our seniors didn't want
our season to end,'' said Ayi. ``They just stepped it up and came
through for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a see-saw affair, with both teams making big plays to
keep drives going or to stop them. But in OT, the Minutemen took it
to a higher level and Furman didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Credit goes to Shipp (36 carries, 170 yards, 2 touchdowns), who
redeemed himself after fumbling at the Furman 1 with 1:19 left in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of OT (which begins at the opposition's
25-yard line), UMass quarterback Todd Bankhead completed an 8-yard
pass to Pete Cariello. Then Shipp took over. He ran to the 11 for a
first down. Then he ran to the 6. Then he scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (fumble) was the worst thing that could have happened,''
said Shipp. ``It was just a case of me seeing the end zone and
trying to get extra yardage. But the guys didn't let me get down,
so I went back out there aiming to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Furman, which won the coin toss in OT but deferred to
UMass, had its chance. On first down, wide receiver Desmond
Kitchings was stopped 4 yards behind the line of scrimmage by
linebacker Matt Dawson. It seemed that a Paladin offense that had
ground out yardage all day had lost some of its sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence came on the next two downs, when quarterback
Justin Hill (15 for 25, 183 yards) was sacked for a 6-yard loss by
defensive tackle Aaron Parker, and Hill threw incomplete to split
end Zach Smerdzinski.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with his team needing 20 yards to keep its season alive,
Hill threw an incomplete pass that was intended for Kitchings. And
the UMass celebration began.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple had said before the game that even though Furman had
arguably the most talented mix of rushing and option football he
had seen this season, he hoped UMass's playoff experience would
take over. Furman had not been to the playoffs since 1996 (only
four current players suited up in that game).
</P>
<P>
   But you couldn't tell that during regulation. Furman ground out
240 yards rushing, 92 kickoff-return yards, and went 10 for 17 on
third-down conversions. It was on a third-down, 1-yard run by Derek
Russell with 8:53 left in the first quarter that gave the Paladins
a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   UMass went ahead, 10-7, on a 15-yard pass from Bankhead to Zullo
and a 34-yard field goal by Jason Cherry, but Furman, whose special
teams earned it good field position all game long, led, 14-10, at
halftime following a Russell 1-yard run that capped an eight-play,
49-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded touchdowns but both missed on conversion tries,
and UMass took a 23-20 lead on a 31-yard pass from Bankhead to Sean
Higgins with 5:01 left in the third. Then Furman kicker Jason Wells
made a 39-yard field goal with 11:12 left in regulation to tie it
at 23.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:31 left, UMass cornerback Jerard White intercepted a
pass, but UMass stalled after four downs. Furman got the ball back
at its 22 and marched to the 19-yard line. But with 12 seconds
left, Wells missed a 37-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have gone either way,'' said Furman free safety John
Keith. ``I thought it was good, but then I'm biased.''
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the overtime heroics, and the Minutemen
seemed sharper, more aggressive. After Shipp's runs, the defense
took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happened to dodge a bullet with the field goal, and
our players made plays in the overtime we hadn't made,'' said
Whipple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
