<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD QUESTIONS AWAIT USC'S HACKETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a 45-19 victory over Louisiana Tech, USC's
players were in a celebratory mood Friday night, too giddy after
containing one of the best quarterbacks in the nation to ponder how
different this season was supposed to have been.
</P>
<P>
   USC finished 6-6 and failed to qualify for a bowl game, but for
a brief moment, that was secondary to intercepting Louisiana Tech
quarterback Tim Rattay three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to look back at the negative,'' free safety
David Gibson said. ``I'm just happy we went out and got three wins
in a row (to end the season). If we'd lost those games, it could
have been a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gibson wasn't going to get too carried away. Asked if this
was finally an example of USC playing high-level football for all
four quarters, Gibson said, ``We were a little too late for that,
but we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   USC won its final three games and ended its losing streak
against UCLA at eight years, but today there are plenty of
questions going into next season.
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Who's coming back?
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett didn't rule out changes on his coaching
staff Friday night and it's something that will be addressed next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Hue Jackson is the No.1 candidate to
depart, but speculation has also focused on offensive line coach
Steve Greatwood after the season-long struggles with that unit.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the kicker?
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore David Newbury was yanked in the final game and
replaced by junior David Bell, but Hackett sounded like he was
inclined to sign another kicker. It's the most noticeable example
of how disappointing USC's special teams were.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the tailback?
</P>
<P>
   Chad Morton is gone, so the heir apparent would appear to be
Sultan McCullough. But Banning High star Chris Howard will be in
the mix and the Trojans are looking to get another back to commit.
They probably wouldn't mind signing Maurice Morris of Fresno City
College.
</P>
<P>
   How much fine-tuning will occur on defense?
</P>
<P>
   USC returns 10 of 11 starters, but outside linebacker Sultan
Abdul-Malik will probably return to defensive end, and safety
Darnell Lacy returns from an academic suspension. Lacy beat out
starter Ife Ohalete last spring and could set up an interesting
battle if the Trojans don't move one to free safety.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, USC will be better. An easy schedule and
the return of Carson Palmer guarantees that. An ill-advised attempt
to play Michigan in the Kickoff Classic could alter just how better
the Trojans will be, however.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a few questions to rethink from this season, such
as how many more games USC could have won if John Fox had started
at quarterback earlier than the ninth game?
</P>
<P>
   They definitely would have made a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   If you answer that Fox was too rusty to start sooner, then maybe
he should not have been tossed aside so casually and encouraged to
play tight end and linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is why didn't the Trojans try something
different, like the shotgun, when pass protection became such an
issue with Mike Van Raaphorst at quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   In the happy atmosphere of the locker room after defeating
Louisiana Tech, these types of issues were best put aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the stars of the day were the seniors,'' Hackett said.
``As hard a season and as down as they were, they found a way to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won three in a row, beating UCLA and stopping Tim Rattay
is a nice impetus going into the offseason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
