<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA LOOKS TO REVERSE LOSING TREND VS. TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sting from an emotional loss to their arch-rivals had yet to
diminish for the Texas Longhorns when coaches began trumpeting the
idea of following in the footsteps of players from Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies bounced back from a draining loss to Texas with a
victory over Kansas State in the 1998 Big 12 championship game. The
seventh-ranked Longhorns (9-3), in the wake of a 20-16 loss to No.
24 A&AMP;M, have a similar rebound opportunity against No. 3 Nebraska
(10-1) in Saturday's Big 12 title game in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Texas players said they plan to follow the A&AMP;M blueprint and
claim their first Big 12 championship since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches mentioned something about that right after the
game,'' said defensive tackle Casey Hampton, reflecting on the
locker-room scene Friday in College Station. ``We're a different
team from A&AMP;M, but we can do the same thing. This loss is going to
be out of our systems \Rquickly\S. It won't keep us down. I hope
we'll come back like we're supposed to and get the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike A&AMP;M, which was winless against Kansas State since the
advent of the Big 12 heading into last year's title game, Texas has
a history of success against Nebraska. The Longhorns are 3-0
against the Cornhuskers as Big 12 rivals, including a 24-20 victory
Oct. 23 in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the rematch in San Antonio _ the first Big 12
title game to feature teams that met during the regular season _
will feel like another home game for the Longhorns. Texas fans have
bought more than 42,000 tickets for Saturday's 2:30 p.m. contest in
the Alamodome, which seats 65,051.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the team goes, I'm totally confident we'll rebound
well,'' said cornerback Ahmad Brooks, who was beaten for three
pivotal completions in the second half against A&AMP;M, including the
game-winning touchdown pass with 5:02 remaining. ``We've got a
great football team. When great football teams lose, they don't
stay down. They fight back because they hate losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most players and coaches involved in Saturday's title game,
Brooks said he has never played the same team twice in one season.
Rematches happen by design in the NFL but remain a rarity in high
school or college football.
</P>
<P>
   Prevailing in such a situation, Brooks reasoned, depends on
which team makes the best adjustments to lessons learned in the
first encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever worked the first time, I'm sure the coaches would
build a game plan around that,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   During the teams' first meeting, Texas won the turnover battle,
3-0, and quarterback Major Applewhite dissected the Nebraska
secondary during a second-half rally. Applewhite connected on 8 of
9 passes for 166 yards and two touchdowns against the Cornhuskers
during the second half in Austin. His accurate arm rescued the team
from a 13-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Limited to one quarter of action because of a stomach virus
during the loss to A&AMP;M, Applewhite said he expects to be 100
percent physically by Saturday's kickoff. Applewhite attributed
bouts of dizziness and nausea that hampered him in College Station
to ``food poisoning or a 48-hour virus'' and said he is not
concerned about lingering effects.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska players, on the other hand, have a lingering desire to
heal a long-standing wound. Since the advent of the Big 12, the
Cornhuskers own a 33-5 record in conference play but are 0-3
against the Longhorns. During the waning moments of a Nov. 13
victory over Kansas State, Nebraska fans chanted, ``We want
Texas!'' The Nebraska band played a few bars of the Texas fight
song during Friday's 33-30 overtime victory over Colorado that
sealed the Huskers' spot in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the rematch with Texas, Nebraska defensive tackle
Steve Warren said: ``We've been thinking about this game for weeks.
We feel we should not have lost that first game. Now, we have a
chance to redeem that loss.''
</P>
<P>
   During the teams' Oct. 23 meeting, the Cornhuskers fell despite
a 429-275 edge in total offense because of three lost fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we controlled the game, but they came away with
the win. That's been frustrating to deal with. What we have to do
now is reverse that,'' tight end Tracey Wistrom said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to doing so, said Nebraska coach Frank Solich, is to
reverse an ongoing trend. Nebraska has more fumbles (47) and lost
fumbles (23) this season than any Division I-A team. In their past
two games, the Cornhuskers have fumbled 18 times, losing eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be 10-1 and lose that many fumbles, it seems strange,''
Solich said. ``If you don't have a great football team, you can't
overcome that statistic.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-27-99 2214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991127.0188 </DOCNO>
