<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-LEND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES FIND IT EASIER TO BUY A PHOENIX HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix has become a bright spot in getting mortgages to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The number of home loans to Hispanics and African-Americans grew
at a faster rate than mortgages to Anglos during the past four
years, unlike many other metropolitan areas. Mortgages to
African-Americans jumped nearly 92 percent from 1995 to 1998 in
Phoenix. Conventional home loans for Hispanics rose by 74 percent,
while lending to Anglos increased 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's a turnaround for Phoenix, which during the 1980s and early
1990s was considered one of the nation's worst areas for minority
lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is making strides toward helping minorities catch up
in home ownership,'' said Marty Shalloo of the Association of
Community Organizations for Reform Now.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still a lot to be done, he said. For example, Anglos
still have a disproportionate percentage of loans compared with
their percentage in the population.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's home ownership rates are coming closer to mirroring
Housing and Urban Development national statistics. Recent data from
HUD show 72 percent of Anglos own homes, compared with 46 percent
of African-Americans and 45 percent of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN recently tracked racial lending disparities nationwide. It
also found that government-backed loans, such as Federal Housing
Administration mortgages, jumped the most, 75 percent, for
Hispanics, the fastest-growing segment of Phoenix's population and
the most underserved in the housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgages to Anglos continue to dwarf those to minorities in
other big cities, such as Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Chicago and
Dallas, ACORN's study found. Nationwide, home loans to Anglos grew
twice as fast as they did to Hispanics and African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, low interest rates, a booming housing market, more
efforts by lenders and assistance from minority groups have helped
improve the minority lending record.
</P>
<P>
   All those factors helped Cathy Acero buy a home. She had rented
a house in west Phoenix for several years when her landlord gave
her the chance to buy it earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I could do it,'' said the mother of two
teenage girls.
</P>
<P>
   Acero called several lenders and was quoted rates and
requirements she couldn't manage until being referred to the
non-profit Community Housing Resources of Arizona. It works with
fledgling home buyers, mainly minority and low-income, helping with
down payments, establishing or cleaning up credit records and
finding a lender.
</P>
<P>
   Acero said she didn't feel like lenders were discriminating
against her when they talked about mortgages out of her reach. She
just felt like buying a house was beyond her means.
</P>
<P>
   Minority home buyers can face two forms of discrimination. The
first is blatant _ lenders who refuse to do business with
minorities, using such practices as red-lining, or refusing to make
mortgages in certain parts of town.
</P>
<P>
   The other is often inadvertent _ lenders' rigid requirements,
geared to Anglo buyers, that sometimes don't take into account a
diversity of lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Both have resulted in huge rejections rates of minority home
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent increases in mortgages to Hispanics and African- &QL; 
Americans, loan denials are still a huge problem for minorities
trying to buy a house in metro Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's rejection rate of Hispanic applicants is one of the
worst in the country. Hispanics were 237 percent more likely to be
denied a home loan than Anglos, ACORN found last year.
</P>
<P>
   But most advocates of minority home buying don't seem too upset
by the findings, attributing it to more people applying for
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the denials may be to people who aren't ready to buy a
house but are being tapped by real estate agents and lenders trying
to focus on the Hispanic market, said Arturo Portillo, senior vice
president of community support for Chicanos Por La Causa.
</P>
<P>
   His group helps Hispanics get into houses, counseling them on
legal and credit issues so they can get a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Most minority lending advocates such as Portillo say banks are
doing better at reaching out to Hispanic home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s and '80s, many Valley lenders were criticized for
their lack of effort in the minority markets. Some were even
accused of redlining.
</P>
<P>
   There were few Spanish-speaking loan officers or branches in
predominately African-American and Hispanic neighborhoods. Loans
were approved only if the applicants fit set criteria, which they
usually didn't because of different cultures and spending patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators enforcing banks' Community Reinvestment Act
requirements have helped, and many lenders have changed the way
they do business with minorities, lending proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to speak people's languages,'' said Carl Blunt,
regional community development manager for Norwest Mortgage. ``You
need to go to their churches, to their supermarkets and to their
neighborhoods so you can understand where they are coming from when
they apply for a home loan.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent increases in home loans, Hispanics still make
up a small portion of the home buying market considering that they
represent 20 percent of the population and that that number is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanic population is a huge market for lenders and
Realtors, but they have to reach out to them,'' said Gene Lines of
Venture Financial, which does half its business with Hispanic home
buyers in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He said Hispanics traditionally save their money at home, not in
a bank, and don't run up a lot of credit. This makes it difficult
for lenders to make them fit a standard application process.
</P>
<P>
   Matha and Cesar Castaneda have rented since they got married,
and didn't think they could afford a house. They also were afraid
of the process because of nightmare stories they heard from
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But then Matha saw an ad in Spanish for Lines' company.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we didn't want to try,'' Cesar said, ``but we got a
lot of help by people who understood where we were coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair, who work in north Scottsdale, found a home they could
afford in south Scottsdale, which is closer to their work than
where they were renting.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans, who saw the biggest jump in percentage of
home loans, are a smaller part of the market and population but
still underserved.
</P>
<P>
   And studies have shown African-Americans are the most likely to
be taken advantage of by lenders with more pricey mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said mortgage discrimination is still
driving the home ownership gap between Anglos and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The American dream of home ownership could become tougher for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Rising home prices will hurt minorities in coming years, said
Jay Butler, director of Arizona State University's Real Estate
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Also, recent changes in banking regulations could weaken
financial institutions' community reinvestment requirements, which
could cut back on the institutions' minority lending efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But many lenders say they plan to redouble their efforts with
minorities because those growing populations are the future of
their home loan business in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If minorities can't buy a home in Phoenix in this economic
climate and building boom, what is going to make their chances in
the next five years any better if banks don't have to try as hard
and home prices go up?'' ACORN's Shalloo asked. &QL; 
Catherine Reagor can be reached at (602) 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
