r a BC-TOBACCO-AZR &LR;      11-27 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU WILLING TO TAKE BIG TOBACCO MONEY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Tobacco wants to bankroll a program to teach Arizona kids
how to resist smoking, alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics might scoff. But not Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Hispanic Research Center is state coordinator for the
tobacco money and is seeking applications from school districts,
much to the dismay of anti-smoking advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have there is a university pimping _ let's say
`brokering' _ for the tobacco industry,'' said William Novelli,
president of the national Campaign for Tobacco-Free Youth.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Keller, director of the ASU center, has an answer for
that: Money is money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a need to be dogmatic and
`holier-than-thou,' '' Keller said. ``The tobacco industry is
positively motivated in the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The same controversy is cropping up in school districts across
the country, as Philip Morris and Brown &AMP; Williamson have set aside
up to $30 million for Life Skills Training. The three-year program
is a voluntary move by the companies, spokesmen say, not part of
any court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 6th- through 8th-grade students can be served the
first year, including 5,000 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Life Skills curriculum was developed years ago by educators
independent of the tobacco industry. It's aimed at instilling
self-esteem, assertiveness and the strength to resist pressures to
engage in substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Keller likes the program and sees no harm in letting tobacco
companies pay for it in a state that ranks near the bottom in
education spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want publicity out of this,'' Keller said. ``They
would prefer to be deep in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of Big Tobacco trying to get in our schools
by using the back-door approach,'' said Brad Christensen, spokesman
for the Arizona Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   And Novelli contends that the industry's largesse is simply a
public-relations ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies have embarked on a huge program to buy
respectability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Novelli said that, although they're promoting smoking-prevention
programs, the companies also are waging advertising campaigns to
recruit new smokers, 90 percent of whom are children.
</P>
<P>
   Denver and San Diego school districts have rejected the
companies' offers, he said; West Virginia said yes to $4.5 million
over the next three years, Novelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco company representatives defend their companies'
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort to address the youth smoking problem,'' said
Tom Ryan of Philip Morris. ``There is no ulterior motive.''
</P>
<P>
   Corky Newton of Brown &AMP; Williamson said, ``We produce a product
that is dangerous. It is not intended for kids, but it is falling
into the hands of kids. We should be actively involved in trying to
prevent kids from trying that product.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth McAuliffe, a junior at Mesa High School and a leader
in anti-smoking groups, is skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have their hearts in the right place, but not
really,'' she said. ``If they really want someone to not get
involved in smoking, they would stop making the product.''
</P>
<P>
   The Life Skills Training program was selected because of its
proven track record and endorsements from the Center for Disease
Control and Prevention and the American Medical Association, Newton
and Ryan said. It is expensive to implement, involving two-day
training sessions for teachers, as well as printed materials.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mike Evans, community coordinator for the Mesa
Partnership for Tobacco-Free Youth, Life Skills achieves its broad
objectives, but its tobacco component is weak when compared with
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Public Schools declined ASU's invitation to participate on
that basis, a district official said. Kyrene Elementary School
District declined because the program duplicated its existing
curriculum. Tempe Elementary Schools will meet with Keller next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Keller said ASU's Hispanic Research Center, which has long been
involved in substance-abuse programs, sought out the tobacco
companies and received a $50,000 planning grant last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Nodora, DHS administrator of Tobacco Education and
Prevention programs, said his office allocates $35 million a year
for tobacco-control programs. The tobacco industry is not working
with government agencies such as his to coordinate educational
programming, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans believes schools should reject the program simply because
of its funding source.
</P>
<P>
   ``The profits they made to do this were made on the backs of the
sick and the dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Newton said, ``What is the definition of good money
vs. bad money? Our feeling is it is good money. What makes it good
money is it is intended for a good use.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Medlyn can be reached at (602) 444-8213 or at
bev.medlyn(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
