<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2956 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AHWATUKEE-AZR &LR;      11-27 1935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AHWATUKEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHWATUKEE AREA REELING FROM UNPLANNED GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS AND BETTY BEARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ahwatukee Foothills fancied itself a suburban heaven for the
upwardly mobile _ the place to move for good schools, low crime and
mountain views.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Ahwatukee'' itself, a Crow Indian word for ``House of
Your Dreams,'' reflected what thousands hoped to find in Phoenix's
promised land south of South Mountain. But now, many residents in
this community of 98,000 wonder whether it's becoming a paradise
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not growth, but the quality of growth,'' said
Ignacio San Martin, an associate professor in Arizona State
University's School of Planning and Landscape Architecture.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 residents each year flock to Ahwatukee
Foothills. They enjoy the spacious homes, top-achieving public
schools and hiking in South Mountain Park, the country's largest
municipal park.
</P>
<P>
   But the consequences of ill-planned growth are evident
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The community has only one soccer field, which means that many
children travel to Tempe and Chandler to practice. Its booming
commercial center at 48th Street and Ray Road features a parking
lot built for 2,300 cars, yet the 24-screen movie theater alone has
about 4,000 seats. On an average day, more than 70,000 cars pass
through the 48th and Ray intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Residents complain that they have no community center, too few
fire stations, that the police substation is in a storefront, that
the single library is too small and that they face massive
rush-hour tie-ups. Violent crime rose 133 percent from 1993 to
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're drowning in traffic,'' resident Tom Bertram said. ``It
comes down to poor, poor planning. I think it's terrible the way
they're wrecking the rest of Ahwatukee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahwatukee Foothills has become a Valley-wide example of how not
to handle rapid growth. Citizens in other parts of metropolitan
Phoenix have demanded that developers pay higher impact fees to pay
for parks, schools and other amenities. Residents of north Phoenix
and Scottsdale are demanding that planners consider long-range
traffic outlooks.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix's North Gateway community (generally north of Deer
Valley Road and east of Interstate 17), residents are thinking
about planning enough parks, schools and jobs while the area is
still mostly vacant. The goal is to have 80 percent of the
residents work nearby. USAA, the country's largest insurance
company, is considering a site there that would employ up to 15,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   Developers are cooperating because they've learned that when a
community is planned correctly, the land becomes more valuable,
said Clancy Jayne, chairman of the North Gateway Village Planning
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there's no question it will be the place to come. . . .
And a lot of it is because of the mistakes made down there,'' he
said, referring to Ahwatukee Foothills.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the problems facing the community continue to occur
in suburbs from Atlanta to Los Angeles as people flee urban ills,
only to build communities that create more.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to Ahwatukee is a classic case of growth in
American cities,'' said urban planner Michael Dollin of the Joint
Urban Design Program at Arizona State. ``Initially, you want to go
to the fringe. It doesn't have the urban ills of the inner city. We
tend to think we can escape.''
</P>
<P>
   With a little foresight, many of Ahwatukee Foothills' problems
could have been prevented, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix shouldn't have rezoned so much commercial land for homes
and apartments, said San Martin, the professor. Those decisions
have forced residents to trek to jobs many miles away.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, landowners gambled and lost when they supported the
rezoning of 139 acres of commercial property near Interstate 10,
hoping that hundreds of new homes would speed the construction of a
new road. It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, residents opposed a rezoning that substituted homes for
a proposed resort. The City Council voted unanimously for homes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of achieving a balance of jobs and houses, Ahwatukee
Foothills became a bedroom community whose occupants leave to work
and shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to have more employment,'' said Joy Mee,
assistant Phoenix planning director. ``What's happening is that
people who own land and want to sell want to sell it for what's hot
at the moment. And what was hot frequently was residential.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the City Council approved rezonings that allowed some
commercial or office zoning to change to residential, over the
objections of the planning staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen growth in the job base and limited hotels and
retail. But there's not as much office space as would be
desirable,'' Mee said.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1990s, commercial development had taken off at Ray
Road and 48th Street. Retail dollars began flowing into Ahwatukee
Foothills, and the intersection became one of the most congested in
metropolitan Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The city's parking code permitted too few spaces for the
24-screen theater and surrounding stores and restaurants. The
situation led to Phoenix officials rewriting the code.
</P>
<P>
   But even more distressing, residents say, was the city's
reluctance to ask developers to help pay for police and fire
stations, libraries and parks.
</P>
<P>
   Mee said communities have failed to set aside enough land for
parks and schools, not to mention day-care centers, nursing homes,
senior centers or community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently, developers are in a hurry to get their money and
get out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the rest of the area will benefit from lessons
learned in Ahwatukee Foothills, authorities say. With proposed
impact-fee increases, planners hope to expand the uses of the money
to include streets, water, sewers and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Within Ahwatukee Foothills, the city would increase net fees
from about $900 now to $2,760 for homes east of 19th Avenue and set
them at $6,799 for homes west of 19th Avenue. The actual impact
fees would be much higher, but developers would get credits for
donating park sites and other features.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ahwatukee Foothills' difficulties were tough to avoid.
The geography of the area, featuring a mountain between it and
downtown Phoenix, made rush-hour jams inevitable, some say.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a committee studying the sparsely populated land south
of South Mountain worried that the area was a ``12-mile-long
cul-de-sac'' without a road to downtown Phoenix. Twelve years
later, there still is no easy way to get people to jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Planners believed that the state would build the South Mountain
Freeway through Ahwatukee Foothills, but the money never became
available, Mee said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, she said, developers have left incomplete roads.
And &UR; backers of a toll road concluded in early 1998 that they
couldn't attract enough traffic to make the private $360 million
project work.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid growth and bad luck also contributed to the woes. When
Phoenix voters approved $1 billion in 1988 to improve the city's
quality of life, little money went to Ahwatukee Foothills. At the
time, nobody thought the area would need parks and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The next major bond election took place this year, when voters
approved money to help pay for a regional park in Ahwatukee
Foothills. But the community already had fallen behind.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the lack of playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Edwards coordinates the Ahwatukee Foothills Soccer Club. Of
the 19 teams, six have to practice outside Ahwatukee Foothills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating. . . . We've had coaches come to
arguments because of practice space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcita Ryon and other community activists have hoped to pay for
new recreation facilities by raising private money. She and her
friends set out more than 18 months ago to raise $1 million to
equip Mountain View Park, which has a wide swath of dirt where
playing fields could be. The group has raised just $15,500.
</P>
<P>
   Schools also are experiencing a lack of space. Of two Ahwatukee
Foothills high schools, one already is over capacity. The other
doesn't have much room to spare. Five elementary schools each has
more than 800 students.
</P>
<P>
   Crime also is a concern. From 1993 to 1998, violent crime in the
area increased 133 percent, according to an analysis of Phoenix
police records by ``The Arizona Republic.'' Overall calls to police
jumped 188 percent, while property crimes climbed 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the population rose by 85 percent, faster than
the increase in property crimes but not nearly as fast as the rise
in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the flaws, longtime residents say life in Ahwatukee
Foothills has many new advantages: an increasing number of quality
restaurants, churches, movie theaters and bookstores, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a paradise,'' said Phoenix Councilman Sal DiCiccio, who
represents the area and has lived there since 1987, when it had
only one store.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few places in the city where a woman can feel
safe jogging at 1 a.m. without a dog. He contends that the
geography, and the four roads in and out, keep out criminals and
make the community relatively safe, despite the rising crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of life is tremendous,'' DiCiccio said. ``The
traffic is bad, but you feel safe, and it has good schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The area that today is Ahwatukee Foothills began as just
Ahwatukee. In the early 1970s, the Presley Development Co. built
the community in the shadow of South Mountain. A handful of other
major developments sprouted during the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, its population stood at about 36,000. During the
ensuing nine years, it has nearly tripled. In one stretch, dense,
high-end apartments line both sides of 48th Street for nearly a
mile.
</P>
<P>
   As developers keep building, ASU's San Martin questions whether
city leaders and planners are keeping a critical eye on the bigger
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never looked at the implications of fast growth,''
he said. ``Politically speaking, you don't want to slow the
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Masel, a resident and a member of the area's citizen
planning committee, agrees that officials were quick to change
course, depending on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is malleable and political,'' he said. ``Developers
tell the city, `Apartments are the only thing that's selling,' so
they get the zoning they need.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all bad, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, Ahwatukee is doing pretty well. People vote with
their dollars, and they're moving there.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is: How can Ahwatukee Foothills fix its
problems?
</P>
<P>
   Mee, the assistant planning director, points to the proposed
increase in development fees for new homes. The first public
hearing will be next month. If approved, the fees could help meet a
variety of needs, from streets to sewers.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix also plans to hire a consultant who would study current
traffic needs and examine what the demands might be in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A transit plan recently proposed for the city includes
circulator buses to help people move around Ahwatukee Foothills and
to encourage people to ride buses.
</P>
<P>
   But is it too late?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no clear solution,'' San Martin said. ``That they can
maintain the quality of life in Ahwatukee is highly questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the future, if problems aren't solved, he said,
``Anyone who has a choice won't live there.'' &QL; 
The Republic's Ryan Konig provided computer analysis for this
article. &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-7942 or at
chris.fiscus &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
