<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-27 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2957 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      11-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S `WEST WING' KEEPS US COMING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I no longer decide whether to tune in to NBC's ``The West Wing''
simply because I like or dislike the show.
</P>
<P>
   It's gone beyond that. I always catch the White House drama now
because I'm hooked. It's not a matter of taste, or even quality,
anymore. It's a matter of wanting _ needing, almost _ to know what
happens next.
</P>
<P>
   A good show works that way _ you're not just watching actors,
you're watching friends, people you feel like you know. Think about
the glory days of ``Seinfeld.'' You doubtless knew more about
George Costanza's employment misadventures than you did those of
your own relatives.
</P>
<P>
   I want to know, for instance, whether Leo, ``The West Wing's''
gruff-but-lovable chief of staff, will divorce his wife. The odds
are good, it seems _ when his wife asked him whether his marriage
wasn't more important than the work he was doing for the White
House, he said no.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``The West Wing'' isn't a show about Leo, any more than
it's a show about the president, or any of the other compelling
characters we follow each week. It's a true ensemble drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me that they feel that with every
episode, like it's over before they know it,'' John Spencer, who
plays Leo, said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good sign. Rarely does ``Providence'' seem to fly by,
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin, who created ``The West Wing,'' has a good track
record for this kind of television. His ``Sports Night'' holds a
similar sway over the few viewers who watch it. (Thanks to the low
ratings numbers, the show is on hiatus until December. Do your part
for quality TV _ when it returns, watch it. ``The West Wing,''
happily, is a hit.)
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of both shows is the dialogue _ rapid fire,
tongue-tripping, flat-out good. It works to even better effect in
the hour-long ``West Wing'' than in the half-hour ``Sports Night,''
in which characters have the occasional tendency to trip over each
other's lines. ``The West Wing'' allows for a slightly more
leisurely pace, although still quick enough that stagnation is
never a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled by the dialogue,'' Spencer said. ``I think the
gig is a hard one for many reasons, but not the words.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, almost every single one of them, are Sorkin's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron's poetry, his language, is such that it becomes acutely
necessary to learn it verbatim,'' Spencer said. ``One word throws
off his rhythms. They're sticklers there, and Aaron himself, about,
`No word must change.' There's no ad-libbing. It has to be said as
written. And he's right _ it's better said as written.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Spencer's first go-round with a writer who pens
nearly every word _ David E. Kelley hired him for ``L.A. Law.'' Not
a bad couple of jobs for a guy who rarely does television work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different ballpark,'' Spencer said of working with
writers such as Sorkin and Kelley. ``Sometimes, as an actor you're
trying to spin (excrement) into gold. When you start with a base
metal, you're 75 percent into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of actors bitch about television, but my personal
television experience has just been incredible. I've been really
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Better lucky than good, as they say. But Spencer, like the rest
of ``The West Wing'' ensemble, is plenty good, as well. Let's face
it, any writing that can make Rob Lowe seem both likeable and
believeable is right on the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, I think, is so suited to the role,'' Spencer said,
and he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer stands out as Leo, but equally good are Bradley Whitford
as Josh, Leo's deputy, and Richard Schiff as Toby, the White House
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Sheen, who plays President Josiah Bartlet, sometimes
can't help trying to chew up the scenery, but that's more amusing
than distracting _ he is, after all, playing the most powerful man
in the world, so he might as well act like it.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer has met John Podesta, President Clinton's chief of
staff. Naturally, he wondered what his real-life alter-ego thought
of ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he liked it,'' Spencer said. ``I asked him did he
think we were coming close to the mark and he said yeah. He said
what lawyers used to say about ``L.A. Law'' _ `You're showing the
more exciting parts of it, not people poring over papers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to describe the show to someone who hasn't seen it is a
tall order. White House staffers toil to get legislation passed.
Compromises are made. Feelings are hurt. Over-earnest characters
give corny speeches. Sappy music swells. No one has yet
specifically mentioned Mom and apple pie, but that's certainly the
aura the show gives off.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as cliched and hackneyed as all that sounds, ``The West
Wing'' simply works.
</P>
<P>
   That's largely because, although politics is definitely a
driving force in the show, ``The West Wing'' is really nothing more
than a good workplace drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, on one level, ``The West Wing'' is about people
going to work,'' Spencer said. ``The arena happens to be the
American government, the White House. But it's people going to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's the rest of us watching them. It's one political deal
that's easy to make. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
