<HEADLINE>
STARS' LEHTINEN COULD RETURN ON ROAD TRIP 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Anaheim's Teemu Selanne scored once, and Jere
Lehtinen sighed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Selanne scored again, and Lehtinen squirmed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Selanne scored his final goal on Friday for a game-sealing
hat trick, Lehtinen's squirms and sighs turned into full-blown
frustration. He realized he would have been playing against Selanne
... if he hadn't been waiting on his fractured ankle to heal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe,'' he says, ``maybe you help.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen will return sometime during a critical four-game road
trip that begins tonight in Atlanta. But with the Stars losing to
the Mighty Ducks on Friday, struggling to sneak close to .500 and
battling general locker-room crankiness, it can't be soon enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen fractured his ankle on Oct. 16 against Nashville, and
the Stars haven't been the same since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were 4-3-1 when Lehtinen went down. They have gone 5-7-2
since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His linemates, Brett Hull and Mike Modano, had eight goals and
five assists between them in the seven games before Lehtinen was
sidelined. He had two goals and two assists. They have had nine
goals and nine assists in the 16 games since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Jere, the Stars are banking on your return as a
last-resort way to jump-start a slumping first line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we put Lehtinen back in there when that time comes
and the chemistry is not there then we'll have to make realistic
long-term changes on that line,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``In other words, I think the assumption everybody has is when
Lehtinen comes back in that's going to mean that line gets up and
running. Well, times change.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have asked that line to be a checking line, to shut
down lines like Selanne's. Hitchcock acknowledges that's a hard way
to play, but it's a way that Lehtinen has spent his career
playing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without him, the No. 1 line hasn't embraced the role as
enthusiastically. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be looking for any loose ice. You have to be able to
compete in the tight critical areas,'' Hitchcock said. ``And I
don't think that lines has done that this year. ... It's less about
the line changing. I think the personality within the line has
changed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He attributes the change in personality to one thing:
``winning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the personality shift and subsequent struggles have
coincided with Lehtinen's stint on injured reserve isn't merely a
coincidence, Stars players say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why it isn't mere hope that his return might spark some
type of turnaround. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially important for that one line,'' Stars forward
Mike Keane said. ``If our No. 1 line is scoring, then maybe we
don't have this conversation every day, maybe we're on a three-game
winning streak instead of back to where we're battling again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars need Lehtinen like Jerry needed Jimmy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only question left to be answered is when will they get
him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Lehtinen said yesterday after skating for 25
minutes with his teammates. The only difference was he had on a
white jersey with a bright red cross on the front to remind
everybody he wasn't to be hit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Switzerland jersey,'' Lehtinen said. ``I feel OK, but
not ready. It's sore and a little weak, but still we're going
forward. There are no backups at all.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Lehtinen were just another player, he'd probably be back by
now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars can't afford for him to be just another player. So
it's imperative they wait until his ankle has healed completely,
and he has confidence in it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to have pretty good confidence to go back out and play
because I have to be ready to do everything,'' said Lehtinen, who
plays on the power- play, penalty-kill while also logging
first-line minutes. ``But, of course, it's tough. Any time when you
are out, it's tough watching games especially now when we haven't
won so many games. It's hard.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The frustration that has permeated the players in the lineup has
seeped to the players who aren't in the lineup. The lackluster loss
to the Mighty Ducks was especially frustrating, seeing that it came
on the heels of what appeared to be a corner-turning victory
against the Los Angeles Kings on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to keep turning the wheel to get around the
corner,'' Keane said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which makes this upcoming four-game road trip with games against
the Atlanta Thrashers, the New York Islanders and the Montreal
Canadiens, all struggling teams, critical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I wouldn't exactly say critical, but once we win one it
would be nice to win a couple of straight ones to give us a little
bit of air to breathe,'' Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez said.
``Right now, we win one and do all of the work to get out of the
hole, and when we're finally out instead of winning again we lose
and get right back in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to tell that to Lehtinen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars winger has watched the whole thing unfold on a
television set, powerless to do anything about it, instead left to
wait until his ankle was ready to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's like over 20 games played and we have played
good games and we still haven't won,'' Lehtinen said. ``I think the
main thing is we have to start winning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's just the guy to do it, too. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
