<HEADLINE>
IMPROVED DEFENSE WOULD BE BIG CATALYST FOR REDSKINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been said here all season that if the Washington Redskins
could find a defense to go along with their high-powered offense,
the NFC East crown would be a lock to go to the nation's capitol
for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This is not good news for the Cowboys, Giants, or Cardinals, for
if the Redskins past two games are any indication, Norv Turner
might have saved his job.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Redskins suffered a 35-28 loss in Philadelphia two
weeks ago, the defense held rookie quarterback Donovan McNabb to 60
passing yards and the Eagles to 236 total yards. Last week, in a
23-13 victory against the New York Giants, the Redskins held the
Giants to 72 rushing yards, and held an opponent to fewer than 20
points for only the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked 31st on defense for much of the season, the Redskins have
inched ahead of the expansion Cleveland Browns for 30th place. The
modest achievement brought a mock laugh from defensive coordinator
Mike Nolan, who quipped: ``What a disappointment. \ROur players\S
won't play as hard now.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, there had been nothing for Nolan to laugh at.
When the club's defensive struggles began early in the season, team
owner Daniel Snyder ordered Turner to hire an assistant to help
Nolan. The club hired Bill Arnsparger, who coached the Miami
Dolphins' 1972 ``No Name'' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the club's 38-20 loss at Dallas on Oct. 24, reports
surfaced that Snyder wanted Turner to fire Nolan. Snyder was talked
out of firing his defensive coordinator. And in the past two weeks
he is finally seeing some results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it takes time, and you never know when it's going to
come together,'' defensive tackle Dana Stubblefield said.
</P>
<P>
   With the return of pass-rush specialist Ndukwe Kalu from a
broken foot, and the promotion of defensive end Anthony Cook over
Kenard Lang, the Redskins have been able to apply more pressure on
the quarterback. Last week, Nolan rotated Lang, Cook, and starter
Marco Coleman at defensive end, and the strategy seemed to confuse
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins had four sacks, and the pressure forced the Giants'
quarterbacks into three interceptions. It was Kalu, a native of San
Antonio, whose hit on Kent Graham led to Coleman's 42-yard fumble
return for a touchdown, which proved to be the clinching points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ndukwe's our one true speed rusher on our football team, and
it showed up in a big way with the touchdown,'' Turner said. ``It
showed up on a bunch of other plays where he's close and has
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook's promotion over Lang should also be noted. Nolan said Cook
lost his job because he needs to ``play with more intensity and
continue to hustle to the ball.'' Cook, Nolan said, is ``very good
at the point of attack. He helps change the line of scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the improved play of the defensive line, Nolan
has ordered more blitzes in the past two weeks, sending cornerbacks
and safeties when the time is right. Rookie cornerback Champ Bailey
had a sack against the Eagles on Nov. 14, and strong safety Sam
Shade had a sack last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got a ways to go ... \Rbut\S we're executing
better,'' Coleman said. ``We're doing the things we were supposed
to do all along. We're getting guys to where they're supposed to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins aren't boasting too loudly. Philadelphia and the
Giants have two of the worst offenses in the league. Washington
still has games against Detroit, Indianapolis, and Miami. There is
even something to prove in today's home rematch against the Eagles
as Philadelphia running back Duce Staley had 122 of the club's 198
rushing yards last time out against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1,'' Stubblefield said, ``we have to stop Duce from
running down the middle. No. 2, if we can keep the quarterback
contained like we did the last time, we have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ...
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sakuma San Francisco 49ers general manager Bill Walsh says
the 49ers will make a substantial comeback.
Walsh says next draft critical to 49ers' future
As the 49ers tumble toward their worst season since 1980, general
manager Bill Walsh, whose savvy drafting and West Coast offense
were the backbone to the 49ers' dynasty from 1981-1998, has come
under fire. In an engaging interview with the ``San Jose Mercury
News'' last week, Walsh admitted that he's made some mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   On his perception as, ``The Genius,'' Walsh was asked if he's
lost his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably have, but I have a curveball. I'm not looking to
regain some kind of reputation. ... They don't need the original
Bill Walsh. They might have him down the hall \Rin coach Steve
Mariucci's office.\S''
</P>
<P>
   On if the Lawrence Phillips situation was a sign the 49ers were
desperate:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. We had no running back, period. We knew Charlie Garner
could break a play, but could he go 16 games? Lawrence Phillips was
the only man out there. Those are calculated moves you make in
sports, it's that simple. Miscalculation? Darned right? Did we get
more than our share of them right this year? No. Lost my fastball?
Sure. But I can't play tennis like I did, either.''
</P>
<P>
   On how long the 49ers might be down:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've run our course with a dynasty. Now we have to get it
back. Will it be a blip on the screen? No. It will be very
substantial. Will we come back. I'm sure we'll come back if we make
the right decisions in this year's draft. I'm not sure there will
be free-agent signings that will amount to that much. But it's run
its course. The salary cap has caught up to us. Two great players
\RJerry Rice and Steve Young\S are winding down quickly on their
careers. And we have an overrun of maybe $15 million for next year.
That's the reality of it.'' \Nsubheds:AFC NOTES Unhappy backup The
Patriots want backup quarterback Michael Bishop to go to NFL Europe
and get more experience, and perhaps develop as Kurt Warner or John
Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, unhappy languishing behind starter Drew Bledsoe, said
he'd rather play another sport than go to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my dream to play football in Europe, it's here,''
Bishop said. ``If I do anything, maybe I'll go play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, who played quarterback at Kansas State in 1998, was an
outfielder at Willis High School. According to Bishop's agent, Phil
Lartigue, Bishop had an invitation to try out for the Arizona
Diamondbacks last spring and has caught the eye of the Cleveland
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Tough doesn't pay One of the few things Browns fans
have had to cheer this season is the scrambling of rookie
quarterback Tim Couch, who fights for every yard and gets up
quickly after a tough tackle.
</P>
<P>
   While Browns fans cheer Couch's tenacity, Couch's coach, Chris
Palmer, worries. In fact, last week, Couch told his quarterback to
either learn to slide to avoid contact or be benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to learn to slide, or I'll take him out of the
ballgame,'' Palmer said. ``The league is trying to protect the
quarterbacks because they are so much a part of what the NFL is.
You've got to be smart. You have to slide and do the things that
are neccessary to make the next play.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Raging Cowher Steelers coahc Bill Cowher was more
animated than usual at his weekly press conference, and much of his
anger was vented at his offense, which ranks 25th overall and 29th
passing. He hinted that he'd make changes if the offense didn't
improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making a change to send a message,'' he said. ``I
would make a change if I felt it was in the best interest of this
team to get results, get it done. It's not any one person I'm
trying to pinpoint. I'm just stating facts. We're not getting it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The blame game should probably start with quarterback Kordell
Stewart, who averages a measly 5.4 yards per pass attempt, and
whose quarterback rating of 68.4 is 27th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Troubled Bills Even though Buffalo's 7-4 record would
lead two divisions in the NFC, the Bills face a must-win game
against the New England Patriots today. That's because their 7-4
record is good for just third place in the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   Bills quarterback Doug Flutie thinks it will take a team 11 wins
to make the playoffs in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go 10-6 like last year, it's rolling the dice,'' Flutie
said.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Briefly Another reason free agents hate playing in
Cincinnati? The club released punter Will Brice last week, and
according to Brice, they refused to pay for his plane ticket home.
... When Jaguars wide receiver Jimmy Smith had 220 yards against
the Saints last week, it was his first 100-plus yard receiving day
since Week 3. ``The last few weeks weren't fun for me personally,''
Smith said. ``When you are a two-time Pro Bowl wide receiver, you
don't want to spend the entire game blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:NFC NOTES `Miracle' Bucs The Tampa Bay Buccaneers have
won a game despite having six turnovers. They have won another game
despite allowing seven sacks, and they have won twice without
scoring an offensive touchdown. When asked how his team has rallied
to win three consecutive games and now finds itself, at 6-4, tied
with Detroit and Minnesota for the NFC Central lead, all Bucs coach
Tony Dungy could do was drop his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done some miraculous things,'' Dungy said. ``It's like
we're trying to set football back and show you all the ways to win
without being fundamentally sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit should go to the Bucs' fourth-ranked defense,
and rookie placekicker Martin Grammatica, who kicked four field
goals in the club's 19-10 victory against Atlanta, including two
longer than 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, though, the Bucs know they need to score to be
a serious playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious we need to score more points,'' fullback Mike
Alstott said. ``We need to be more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Birds of a feather The underdog Eagles might not win
their game against the Washington Redskins today, but at least
they'll be fresh. After the Eagles' 44-17 loss to Indianapolis last
week, coach Andy Reid gave his players last Monday off and threw
away film clips of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing we can learn from this,'' Reid said. ``Clear
your minds. Go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Eagles punter Sean Landetta agreed with Reid's decision to give
the club last Monday off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good move,'' Landetta said. ``Every player on
every team has the best chance to win every Sunday when they go in
as positive as possible. Watching this film won't help that.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Briefly The Rams can clinch the NFC West title today
if they defeat New Orleans and Carolina loses to Atlanta. But don't
expect the Rams to let up if they win their first division title
since 1985. The Rams are 8-2 for the first time since 1985, and
have a two-game lead on their nearest competitors for homefield
advantage in the playoffs. ``Homefield advantage is huge,''
quarterback Kurt Warner said. ``We want to keep winning so we can
play as many playoff games at home as possible.'' ... The Bears _
yes, the Bears _ might have one of the most dangerous set of wide
receivers in the league. Bobby Engram (56 receptions) is seventh,
and Marcus Robinson (53) is eighth in the league in receptions.
Curtis Conway was leading the NFC in receptions before he was
injured in Week 5 at Minnesota, yet he is averaging a touchdown
nearly every eight times he catches the ball. The nightmare for the
Bears' front office is that all three wide receivers are free
agents next season.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:KEY GAMES
</P>
<P>
   New England at Buffalo: In the toughest division in pro
football, this is a must-win game for both clubs. The Patriots need
this game the most, but they can't afford another five-interception
game from QB Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots 21, Bills 16
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay at Seattle: These clubs have never made the playoffs
in the same season since they both came into the league in 1976.
But both are now leading their respective divisions. Tampa Bay has
the better defense, but Seattle has a better team, and they are
playing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks 24, Buccaneers 13
</P>
<P>
   Last week: 2-1. Season: 16-15. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
