<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-SHARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BEAT SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who would have thought the Los Angeles Kings and
San Jose Sharks would not only be the hottest teams in the NHL but
the hottest ticket in town?
</P>
<P>
   How about the sellout crowd of 18,118 at Staples Center that
watched the Kings beat the Sharks 4-1 in a rare Saturday afternoon
game. Those fans remember when it was even more rare to see these
two this good.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Phoenix Coyotes, the Kings and Sharks are playing
an exciting game of Pacific Division roulette. The Kings already
have beaten the Sharks twice. The Coyotes have defeated the Kings
twice. The Sharks are 1-0 against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so long ago you couldn't imagine the Kings and San
Jose battling for the top spot in anything,'' said Glen Murray, who
scored two power-play goals. ``But this is real. These teams play
hard and have good players. This is the result.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this season, the Kings had missed the playoffs five of
the past six years, San Jose four of the past six. A Kings-Sharks
game at the Forum last November would not have drawn Murray's
family.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Kings have a new building, but it is more than
that. On a holiday weekend with beach weather outside, the Kings
played like they deserved their fourth sellout. With the victory,
they are 14-7-4 and have 33 points, one ahead of Detroit and two in
front of San Jose. The Kings also lead the league with 82 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the proof has been our power play,'' said Murray, who
ended an 0-for-29 slump with the man advantage on a first-period
goal. ``Sure we've been missing some guys, but the attitude around
here hasn't been panic. We know there is a enough talent here to
get out of any problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the 19 shots San Jose took on Kings goalie Jamie Storr in
the second period just five days after Storr suffered what appeared
to be a serious groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow through all that, the Kings emerged with a 2-1 lead on a
pretty goal by Donald Audette in front of Sharks goalie Steve
Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Murray skated past the blue line and faked a slap shot. Murray
then redirected the puck to center Bryan Smolinski on Shields'
right. His shot was stopped, but Audette collected the rebound and
scored his 10th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That ties Audette with captain Rob Blake and injured Luc
Robitaille for second on the team. The leader, Ziggy Palffy, scored
his 12th on an empty netter in the final minute of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Glen was going to take the shot, then I heard Bryan
scream at him,'' Audette said. ``The (second) line worked really
well today.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't true Wednesday when the Kings lost 3-2 in overtime
to the defending Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray met with the second unit before
Saturday's game to discuss its poor effort. The result: three goals
and five assists for the group and the next two days off for the
team. Murray now has nine goals and Smolinski leads the team with
16 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't yell; he never does,'' Smolinski said of the coach.
``But he really knows how to embarrass you. We responded to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also responded defensively. After Murray added his
second goal with 10:07 left in the game, the Kings killed off two
power plays before Palffy's goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes, Storr showed off the Kings' new bravado by
tripping Sharks center Vincent Damphousse then pushing him to the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a little trash talking that got out of hand,''
Storr said. ``It was nothing serious. I remember watching him when
I was a kid in Toronto, but I would never say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with a November game this important.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
